1. d4
{ In this course I've used the Lichess database in guiding trainable line prioritization and selection. If you see a non-qualified reference to an approximate number of games in the database, it means that this number of games is in the Lichess database restricted by the following parameters:  - Ratings: 2000 and above  - Time control: Blitz, Rapid, Classical  I've left out games in the 1600-2000 range and Bullet time controls to cut down on likely irrelevant noise.  Sometimes I'll say how frequent a line is at Master level for comparison and then I've used the Lichess Masters database which has 2 million OTB games from 1952-2019 by players rated 2200+.  
Note in May 2021: This course was mostly ready in September 2020 so a lot of the statistics have changed by now. Feel free to look up the new stats and leave a comment on the variation and I'll update them.   However, do also note that the lines are up to date and all the recent courses are covered in the repertoire clashes. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "What not to do: Juan Carlos Zamora vs. Viktor Laznicka, 2010"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ We're starting with this game to show why White shouldn't combine Nf3 with c3. This is a well-known mistake that is still overwhelmingly common among amateurs, with ~51 000 games in the database. The game was a Classical one, played in the 2010 Chess Olympiad in Khanty-Mansisk. White was rated 2564, Black 2690! }
1... d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 { White plays the triangle. } 4... Nc6
{ Black has made the classical moves. } 5. Nf3
{ At our present day and age this move deserves a double ??. Again, it's been played ~51 000 times in contrast to the correct   5.Nd2  which has only been played in ~11 000 games. Please remember not to combine Nf3 & c3! }
5... Qb6 6. Qb3 c4 7. Qc2
{ 7.Qxb6  axb6  is good for Black because they have pushed ...c4. This means that they can use the pressure on the open a-file combined with pushing the b-pawn, possibly twice, to exert a lot of pressure on White. It's exactly what we do as White in the London-Slav endgames, as you will see. The general rule about whether to resolve the Queen face-off with a capture is the following: if you have  b5  available for your bishop then the capture is good. This is obviously not the case here since Black has played ...c4 so White should retreat. }
7... Bf5
{ The star move. White can't really take the bishop because he'll lose the rook in the corner after ...Qxb2. If White had played Nd2 instead of Nf3 then this trick by Black wouldn't work and White could simply grab the bishop. }
8. Qc1
{ If   8.Qxf5?  Qxb2  9.Be2  e6!!  10.Qh3  Qxa1  and White is dead lost. The only reason White has scored decently after 9. Be2 is that clueless Black players have tried to take the rook immediately and gotten their Queen trapped afterwards  (yes, I've done this as well in the past...but it's the sort of mistake you should only make once)  .  White is therefore forced to play the necessary, but sad text move and Black has his dream position. }
8... Nh5
{ The simple  8...e6  is probably strongest, but the text move is more fighting and was also used by Magnus to defeat Kamsky in 2007, but not by using the same idea we see in this game. }
9. Bg3 f6
{ Again, the simple ...e6 is probably objectively stronger, but this is nice too preparing ...e5 to open up the position for the bishops. The rest is very unpleasant for White. }
10. Nbd2 e5 11. dxe5 Nxg3 12. hxg3 Nxe5
{ It's important for Black to take a pair of knights off. He doesn't want to allow something like  12...fxe5  13.Nh4!?  Be6  14.Ng6 }
13. Nxe5 fxe5 14. e4 { White tries to destabilize Black's center. } 14... Bg6
{ Black just retreats. } 15. exd5 Bc5
{ White's king gets stuck in the centre. It's clear who has won the opening battle here. }
16. Nxc4 { If  16.f3  Bg1!!  17.Rxg1  Qxg1 } 16... Bxf2+ 17. Ke2 Qf6 18. Nxe5
{ A blunder. } 18... O-O 19. Nxg6 Rae8+ 20. Kd3 Qxg6+ 21. Kc4 Re4+
{ Better was the immediate  21...Be3  misplacing the Queen first, and then Re4+. The rest is not as clean as it could be, but the result is never in doubt. }
22. Kb3 Qb6+ 23. Kc2 Be3 24. Qe1 Rf2+ 25. Qxf2 Bxf2 26. Rd1 Bxg3 27. Bd3 Rh4
28. Rxh4 Bxh4 29. d6 Qc6 30. Kb3 Qd7 31. a4 a6 32. c4 Bf2 33. Be4 Bc5 34. Rd5
Bxd6 35. a5 Qe7 36. Rd4 g6 37. Bd5+ Kg7 38. Re4 Qc7 39. Re6 Qc5 40. Kc2 Qb4 41.
Kb1 Bc5 { White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "2...Nf6 Two Knights: Tabiya"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ The modern London move order, also known as the Accelerated London, the Neo-London or the Mason Attack. Please see the informational file below which explains the respective pros and cons of 2. Bf4 vs. 2. Nf3 and why in this course we will prefer the former. }
2... Nf6
{ The overwhelmingly most common and most flexible move with ~250 000+ games and counting. }
3. e3
{ White should pretty much always play d4, Bf4 and e3 first in the ...d5 lines, and maintain flexibility as far as the other pieces are concerned. }
3... c5
{ The classical break, putting pressure on White's centre, again, most common with ~100 000+ games and counting. We will look at alternative ways of playing without ...c5 in later chapters. }
4. Nf3
{ This is the move that leads to the 'Two Knights' variation with Nbd2 coming next. I would go so far and say that this is the correct move even though it is far less common than the older alternative 4. c3 which leads to the 'Triangle' variation, and where one has to know to play Nbd2 before Nf3. I will explain why along the way. }
4... Nc6
{ Continuing with classical development. Black can also try   4...Qb6  , and this is one reason for starting with Nf3  since if Black plays ...c5 and ...Qb6 and you haven't developed your knight on  b1  you can meet it strongly with Nc3   4...Qb6  5.Nc3!  Notice that   4...Bf5?!  5.dxc5!  and   4...Bg4  5.Nbd2  Nc6  transposes to the line where Black plays ...Bg4 a move later. We will cover all of these lines in Chapter 5 }
5. Nbd2
{ The 'Two Knights'. This position has been reached in only ~10 000 games. From here on Black has a wide choice. In Chapter 4 we will tackle the Exchange Caro-Kann with   5...cxd4  in Chapter 5 we'll look at   5...Bf5  and   5...Bg4  in Chapter 6 at the sharp   5...Qb6  and in chapters 7-9 the main line with   5...e6  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "2...c5 Two Knights: Tabiya"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5
{ This is only the 4th most common move after ...Nf6, ...e6, and ...c6 with ~65 000 games, but it is quite an important move order since it allows Black to enter numerous interesting lines in the Exchange Caro-Kann complex. }
3. e3 Nc6
{ The most common move with ~ 34  000  games. However, Black can already enter the Exchange Caro-Kann here with  3...cxd4  . }
4. Nf3 { Again, we enter the 'Two Knights' variation. } 4... Nf6
{ The main move. As you saw in the previous variation, if   4...Qb6?!  5.Nc3!  Black can also enter the Exchange Caro-Kann here with   4...cxd4  . }
5. Nbd2 { Arriving at the 'Two Knights' Tabiya from a different move order. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "2. Bf4 vs. 2. Nf3: Pros & Cons"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ 1...d5  2.Bf4  What are the benefits and downsides of starting with this move versus Nf3 in case of 1...d5? It used to be thought that Bf4 was correct because Nf3 led to the line that should be avoided. However, it turns out that given the correct 'Two Knights' way of playing there is not as much difference as was thought.   2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Bf4  c5  4.e3  Nc6  5.Nbd2!  Two Knights.   5.c3?  This is the older way of playing and, as we already know, this would be a grave mistake.  5...Qb6  2...Nf6  3.e3  c5  4.Nf3   4.c3  If you played the Triangle then there would be a difference since now the next move must be Nbd2.  4...Nc6  5.Nd2!  Nc6  5.Nbd2  Two Knights. }
2. Bf4
{ What are the benefits and downsides of starting with this move versus Nf3 in case of 1...Nf6? Here there is actually a big difference and White should be aware of the differences in order to make an informed choice. It comes down to whether you care more about having a stronger option against ...g6 setups or the Benoni.   2.Nf3  Most of the top players like Kamsky and Sedlak who play the London play this move. The main upside is that it somewhat defangs the Benoni with 2...c5. The main downside is that it robs White of his, in my opinion, most dangerous and effective setup against ...g6 while also restricting his options against ...e6.  2...c5  The Benoni move, but after Nf3 it's just not very strong.   2...g6  This is one problem. White can't play the most effective form of the Jobava Nc3-setup since the knight gets in the way of the f-pawn in the Pirc lines, and the Queen's support of h4, in the Grünfeld lines.  3.Nc3  Let's try.   3.Bf4  London vs. the KID can be played, but I've never been a fan of these positions and would like to avoid them. Notice that neither Kamsky nor Sedlak play this either, preferring the Torre.   3.Bg5  Kamsky and Sedlak just play the Torre attack against KID.  3...d5  The Grünfeld move.   3...Bg7  The Pirc move.  4.e4  d6  5.Bf4  White can also put the bishop on e3 or g5, of course, but let's compare it with the London setup.  5...O-O  6.Qd2  Bg4  Black has this extra possibility. It's not that White's position is bad by any means. However, the other version where we get to play f3, supporting the center and g4 etc. is much stronger.  4.Bf4  With Nf3 developed this is known as the Barry Attack.  4...Bg7  5.e3  O-O  The problem is that White can't play his usual idea of h4-h5 since the knight is in the way.   2...e6  The Nimzo setup.  3.Bf4  b6  Here, Black can try this move order without being hit by Qf3.  3.d5 }
2... g6
{ 2...c5  Here the Benoni move is supposed to be the critical test of White's move order.  3.e3  White has other options, but we will study this move.  3...Qb6  Is Black's idea, since White has left b2 defenseless. However, there are several ways to play this for an advantage.  4.Nc3   4.Nf3!?  Qxb2  5.Nb5   5.Nge2!?   2...e6  The Nimzo setup.  3.e3  b6  4.Qf3!?  Here White can try this interesting move. }
3. Nc3 { This allows the Nc3 idea in its strongest form. } 3... d5
{ 3...Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Qd2  O-O  6.O-O-O  White is not going to touch the g1 knight for a while. For example...  6...c6  7.Bh6  b5  Threatening ...b5 and ...Nxe4.  8.f3±  The center is secure and White can continue with h4-h5 etc. Black is already in huge trouble. }
4. e3 Bg7 5. h4
{ White has used the tempo or e3 instead, keeping the knight back, and thus the Queen's diagonal is free to support h5. }
5... O-O 6. h5 Nxh5
{ A common mistake, demonstrating the basic idea of this line. } 7. Rxh5 gxh5
8. Qxh5
{ White is basically already winning with easy and natural attacking play against the king.   Conclusion: In the end, the choice comes down to whether you care more about having the strongest option against ...g6 systems or the Benoni. I think that given the abundance of KID and Grünfeld players and thus the statistical likelihood of facing ...g6, for non-GMs and especially for situations where your opponent can't prepare for you, Bf4 is clearly the practically correct choice! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Don't Play on Autopilot: 2...h5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 h5
{ The Rosen trap! Apparently IM Eric Rosen discovered it while analyzing with a student. It is now frequently used in online blitz  (~1500 games)  and Black scores better than White. It demonstrates nicely the importance of NOT playing the opening on autopilot. }
3. Nf3
{ Normally, White's first two moves against 1...d5 are always 2. Bf4 and 3. e3. However, here Black is trying to be tricky so White needs to take this into account and play Nf3 instead, controlling both  e5  and  g5  . The automatic e3 is what gets one in trouble after   3.e3  e5!?  4.Bxe5  f6  5.Bf4  g5  6.Bg3  h4  or   3.e3  e5!?  4.dxe5  g5  6.Bg3  h4  and the bishop is lost. This has happened in ~800 games. }
3... Nf6
{ Black's most common move. If   3...e6  4.e3  with normal play or, even better   3...e6  4.c4 }
4. e3
{ Now White can play e3 with a slightly non-standard version of the main lines, depending on how Black continues. Here c4 is always an interesting option since Black has wasted time on a flank move. }
*

