[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "London Heroes"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ To get us fired up, we'll start with some model games by our London Heroes. This is our cast and here we will take a look at one game by each, related to a particular important theme  (you will see many games by them also later)  :  
Vlatko Kovacevic  (b. 1942)  - Croatian GM who famously beat Fischer in 1970 on the Black side of the French. He played the London a lot in the 70's and 80's and published the first serious book on the London titled Win With the London System, advocating 2. Bf4  (co-authored with Sverre Johnsen, Gambit 2005)  . Current rating: 2466. We will start by taking a look at one of his classic Greek Gifts.  Eric Prie  (b. 1962)  - French GM who edited the d-Pawn Specials section for ChessPub in the 2000s and early 2010s, analyzed the London, and tested it extensively in practice. He was the first to play the specific Greek Gift later famously seen in Kamsky vs. Shankland 2014 and he was also one of the people who 'invented' the Jobava-Prie attack with Nc3. Current rating: 2435. We will study his handling of the famous London-Slav endgame.  Gata Kamsky  (b. 1974)  - Soviet-born American legend. He was ranked 4th in the world in 1995 and played Karpov for the FIDE world championship in 1996. He has also played in the Candidates in 2007 and 2011 and is a 5-time US champion. He recently published the first two volumes of his planned three-part best games collection Gata Kamsky - Chess Gamer  (Thinkers Publishing, 2019)  . Current rating: 2674. Here we will explore one of his innovations against the QID-Hedgehog setup.  Nikola Sedlak  (b. 1983)  - Serbian GM who has published the most recent up-to-date books on the London titled Winning With the Modern London System Vol. 1, on 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4  (Chess Evolution, 2016)  , and Vol. 2, on 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3  (Chess Evolution, 2017)  . Current rating: 2549. We will study one of his games with the Pillsbury plan of Ne5 & f4.  Magnus Carlsen  (b. 1990)  - No comments needed. He frequently plays his 'trusty London', especially in Blitz & Rapid. Current rating: 2863. Here we will study his use of the move Bb5.  Some other names to check out: Ferenc Berkes, Pavel Blatny, Anish Giri, Kiril Georgiev, Andrei Gorovets, Boris Grachev, Baadur Jobava, Tamir Nabaty, Daniel Naroditsky, Elisabeth Paetz, Manuel Pereyra Puebla, Eric Rosen, Antoaneta Stefanova. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Heroes: Vlatko Kovacevic (2510) vs. Hans Ree (2520), 1980"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 e6 4. Nbd2 c5 5. e3 Be7
{ The QGD style, passive move. } 6. c3 O-O 7. Bd3
{ White completes the basic setup. } 7... Nbd7
{ Again, the QGD style move. This is made possible by the bishop on  e7  . The knight fights for  e5  and sometimes finds a defensive post on  f8  . Another point is that after ...b6, Black's light-squared bishop's diagonal will be unblocked. }
8. h4
{ Kovacevic doesn't waste time and prepares for the enhanced Greek Gift with h4 and perhaps also for the Alphazero style pawn push h5 to h6.   However, perhaps it was more natural to start with  8.Ne5 }
8... b6 9. Ne5 { Thematic. } 9... Nxe5
{ There was no need to take the knight off without having completed development. If  9...Bb7  10.Qf3  Rc8  11.Rh3!  and White starts a strong attack. }
10. dxe5 { The thematic recapture, kicking away the knight. } 10... Nd7
{ If Black had already played ...Bb7 he could play ...Ne4, alas... } 11. Bxh7+
{ Here it comes! You will see this a lot in this course and you will get it a lot in your games  (I think I've played at least 50 Greek Gifts over the past couple of years)  . }
11... Kxh7 12. Qh5+
{ As I will explain later in more depth, the big part about why the London Greek Gifts are almost always better than the more standard, French etc. ones, is because the Queen can come to  h5  directly, forcing ...Kg8 as the only reply. }
12... Kg8 13. Nf3 { The other knight comes in. } 13... f6
{ This is usually the only way to defend, but here Black could've also tried inserting ...Ba6, threatening to meet O-O-O with ...Be2!!   13...Ba6  14.O-O-O?  Be2!!  This would've forced White to find the precise move Rd1 which would take away later possibilities of O-O-O:   13...Ba6  14.Rd1  g6  15.Qh6  Re8  16.Ng5  Nf8  17.h5   or  13...Ba6  14.Rd1  f6 }
14. Ng5 { A typical idea you will get to play a zillion times. } 14... fxg5 15.
hxg5 { If White is allowed to play g6 next it's lights out. } 15... Rf5
{ This frees up squares for the king and is most frequently tried, and the best move here.   If  15...Rxf4?  16.Qh8+  Kf7  17.g6+  Kxg6  18.Qh5#  is a good one to remember!   Also,  15...Bxg5  doesn't work here  16.Bxg5  Qc7  17.f4  when White's attack is too strong. }
16. Qh7+ Kf7
{ After  16...Kf8  the key move to remember is  17.Qg6!  when the Queen plays the role of the g-pawn and threatens ...Rh8#, forcing ...Kg8, and then Rh7, attacking the new focal point on g7.   For example  16...Kf8  17.Qg6!  Kg8  18.Rh7  Bf8  19.Qh5  g6  20.Qxg6+  Bg7  21.Qxg7# }
17. g6+ { The pawn lands. } 17... Ke8 { 17...Kf8  18.Qh8# } 18. Qxg7
{ Taking the g-pawn and making room for the rook. } 18... Bf8 19. Qh8
{ Even better was the immediate  19.Rh8  , pinning the bishop and making  19...Rg5  impossible due to  20.Qf7# }
19... Rg5 { Trying to prevent g7. } 20. Qg8
{ Defending the important pawn, threatening mate in one, and allowing the rook to enter. }
20... Nxe5 { Black has no other choice since if  20...Qe7  21.Rh7 } 21. Bxe5
Kd7 22. Rh8 Bb7 23. Qh7+
{ Black resigned since after  23...Kc6  24.g7  Rxg7  25.Bxg7  Qc7  26.Bf6  White wins due to his immense material superiority.  Main lesson of this game: the enhanced Greek Gift pattern with h4, dxe5, Bxh7+, Qh5+, Ng5 and after ...fxg6, hxg6, aiming to push g6 and mate on the h-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Heroes: Nikola Sedlak (2557) vs. Anton Brkic (2599), 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ Sedlak started with 2. Nf3, but the game has now transposed into our preferred 'Two Knights' move order. }
5... e6 6. c3 Bd6
{ The main move, challenging White's bishop and aiming to control  e5  . } 7.
Bg3 { White's best response, inviting ...Bxg3 with an opening of the h-file. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3
{ The main line   8.Bb5  We will see this move, Carlsen's preference, in the next game. }
8... b6
{ The modern main line. The two older moves are strongly met with Ne5.   8...Re8  9.Ne5   8...Qe7  9.Ne5 }
9. Ne5
{ In this game Sedlak went for the typical Pillsbury plan of Ne5 & f4. It's important to remember that even though this is common in the London this is NOT our main recommendation from this move order which is instead   9.e4! }
9... Bb7 10. f4 Rc8
{ 10...Ne7!  This remaneuvering of the knight is the reason why Ne5 & f4 isn't the best plan here }
11. Bh4
{ Very thematic. After White has played f4 the bishop is not needed on the diagonal to control  e5  anymore so it repositions itself and threatens to destroy Black's structure, as ...Qxf6 would lose to the Nd7 fork. }
11... Be7 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Ndf3
{ There is no knight jumping to  e4  anymore so White can bring the other knight in;   13.O-O  Is natural   13.Qf3  Is also typical }
13... Be7
{ Preparing ...f6. If   13...Bxe5  14.fxe5  f6  15.exf6  Qxf6  16.O-O  with a typical London position. }
14. h4 { The idea is to prevent ...f6. } 14... Nxe5
{ 14...f6?  15.Ng5!  fxg5   15...g6  16.Nxe6  Qd6  17.Nxf8  fxe5  18.fxe5  Nxe5  19.dxe5  Qxe5  20.Nd7  16.hxg5  Nxe5  17.fxe5  g6  18.Rxh7  Kxh7  19.Qh5+  Kg7  20.Qxg6+  Kh8  21.Qh7# }
15. Nxe5 f5 { 15...f6  16.Qh5  and White's attack is too strong } 16. g4
{ Very thematic, as whenever Black plays ...f5 g4 is an important lever to pry open the kingside. }
16... cxd4 17. exd4 Bxh4+
{ Black decides to take the pawn. At least he has a pawn for his suffering... }
18. Kd2 Bf6
{ White was threatening g5, trapping the bishop. With Bf6, black also plans to get rid of White's amazing knight. }
19. gxf5 Bxe5 20. fxe5 Qg5+ 21. Kc2 exf5
{ 21...Rxf5  Sedlak says he was expecting this, intending to meet it with  22.Qe2  Rcf8  23.Bxf5  Qxf5+  24.Kb3 }
22. Qf3 g6 23. Rag1
{ White's rooks are having a party on the Kingside open files. } 23... Qe7 24.
Bxf5 { Looks risky, but it works. } 24... Qf7 25. Rh5 { 25.Rg5 } 25... Kh8 26.
Rxg6
{ Now the Queens come off and White is winning in the endgame.   26.e6!  Qg7  27.Qg3  is also completely winning for White. }
26... Qxg6 27. Bxg6 Rxf3 28. Rxh7+ Kg8 29. Rxb7 Rc6 30. Be8 Rf2+ 31. Kb3 Rh6
32. Ka3 { 32.Rxa7 } 32... Rhh2 33. Bc6
{ White will take the d-pawn with check, after which the a-pawn and his king will be safe and Rxa7 and e6 are coming, so Black resigned.   Main lesson of this game: combining the Pillsbury plan of Ne5, f4, with the bishop-switch Bh4 and the exchange Bxf6, using h4 to prevent ...f6 and meeting ...f5 with g4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Heroes: Magnus Carlsen (2841) vs. Marin Bosiocic (2591), 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c3
{ Carlsen plays the 'Triangle' move order, but we'll forgive him. This was in 2016, before the 'Two Knights' was discovered. }
4... Nc6 5. Nd2 e6 6. Ngf3 Bd6 { Arguably the main line. } 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bb5
{ This is Carlsen's preference over the main line with Bd3. The idea is to play Bxc6 and create a weakness on  c6  and/or secure  e5  for White's knight. }
8... Ne7
{ The most common move is to remove the knight.   8...a6  Anand played this against Carlsen in the same tournament, but this allows White to carry out his basic threat  9.Bxc6  bxc6  10.Qa4  Rb8  11.Qa3  Bxg3  12.hxg3  cxd4  13.cxd4  a5  14.O-O  Qb6  15.b3  Ba6  16.Rfc1  Nd7??  17.Qd6  Qa7  18.Rxc6  Bb5  19.Rc7  Rb7  20.Rac1  a4  21.Rxb7  Qxb7  22.Rc7  Qb8  23.Rxd7  Bxd7  24.Qxd7  1-0 }
9. Bd3
{ The bishop returns, 'arguing' that the knight on ...e7 is now worse than it was before. }
9... b6
{ 9...Nc6  This actually gives White an extra tempo since if White played 8. Bd3 we would be in this position with Black to move. However, now it's White's move. }
10. e4
{ Thematic, threatening the e5 fork and consequently opening the center before Black gets to develop his bishop on the long diagonal. }
10... dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Rb8 13. dxc5
{ As you will see, this move is all the rage in so many lines... } 13... Bxg3
{ Forced, because of the pin on the rook. } 14. hxg3
{ White gains a tempo on the h-pawn. } 14... f5
{ Black tries to push White back with tempo, but... } 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. c6
{ Threatening the fork with c7. } 16... Nd5 17. Bxd5
{ White didn't have to retreat after all. } 17... Rxd5 18. Rd1
{ Black gets no respite. } 18... Rxd1+ 19. Kxd1
{ White's passed c-pawn is very strong. } 19... Ba6 20. Ne5 Rc8 21. c4 b5 22.
b4 bxc4 23. a4 Rd8+ 24. Kc2 Rd5 25. f4
{ Black resigns since after b5 there is nothing to be done. Notice that it's even hard to involve the king because then the h-pawn drops and White's rook enters the 7th rank. This is how you play a smooth game indeed...    Main lesson of this game: the plan of Bb5 and Bxc6, meeting ...Ne7 with e4, and using the Colle-style dxc5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Heroes: Eric Prie (2491) vs. Nanko Dobrev (2352), 2009"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Bf5
{ the Baltic Defense-style, copycat variation. In these variations White aims for the c4 break, Qb3 to attack the pawn and meeting ...Qb6 with c5, with an excellent Queenless middlegame which is a joy to play. }
3. c4
{ Prie goes for the immediate c-pawn push, not touching the e-pawn. As I will explain in the relevant chapter, this is an improvement over starting with e3 since it defangs Black's Baltic Defence style ...Bxb1 idea as in the line   3.e3  e6  4.c4  Bxb1!?  5.Qxb1  Bb4+  6.Kd1  This is not bad for White, but better not to allow it. }
3... c6 { Black wants to meet Qb3 with ...Qb6. } 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nf3
{ 5.Qb3!  It was better to proceed with immediate Queenside play  5...Qb6  6.c5!  Qxb3  7.axb3  Nd7  8.b4!  The b-pawn goes  8...a6  Black really needs to stop it  9.Nf3  Rc8  Stepping out of the pin  10.Nd2  White can go for the thematic Nd2-Nb3-Na5 maneuver faster without still having touched the e-pawn. }
5... Nf6 6. Qb3 { The Queen attacks the b-pawn, forcing the usual reply. } 6...
Qb6 7. c5 Qxb3 8. axb3
{ This endgame favors White who scores massively from these positions. } 8...
Nbd7 9. h3
{ This is very thematic, defending the bishop against ...Nh5, but objectively it's not needed yet and it's better to proceed immediately with   9.b4!  Nh5  10.Be5  White can give up his bishop on this square since Black's knight is offside  10...Nxe5  11.Nxe5  f6   11...Nf6  12.b5!  12.Nf3  g5  13.h3  Nf4  14.g4  . }
9... Be7 { 9...a6  was needed  10.b4  Rc8  11.Nd2  . } 10. b4 Ne4
{ This move is frequently tried, but almost never helps Black. } 11. e3 O-O
{ 11...Nxc3  12.bxc3  a6  13.b5 } 12. b5 { The b-pawn goes... } 12... f6
{ Black tries to prepare ...e5, but now White notices a nice tactic that makes it impossible. }
13. Nh4 Nxc3
{ 13...Bg6  14.Nxg6  hxg6  15.Nxe4  The point  15...dxe4  16.Bc4!  Black can't play ...e5  16...Kf7  17.bxc6  bxc6  18.O-O  . }
14. Nxf5 { Threatening to take the defenseless bishop. } 14... exf5 15. bxc3
{ It is only White who has benefitted from the change of structure. } 15... Nb8
16. Kd2
{ Not rushing things and activating all the pieces before the final breakthrough. Black can't do anything anyway. }
16... Bd8 17. c4 Rf7 18. Bd3 g6 19. Rhb1 Bc7
{ Better was ...Nd7 which, however, allows us to demonstrate White's basic threats   19...Nd7  20.bxc6  bxc6  21.cxd5  cxd5  22.Bb5  or Rb7. }
20. b6 { A little tactic to finish it off. } 20... Bxf4 21. Rxa7
{ Main lesson of this game: meeting the copycat ...Bf5 with the plan of c4 & Qb3, while keeping the e-pawn back. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Heroes: Gata Kamsky (2648) vs. Albert Bokros (2492), 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 { The Nimzo move. } 3. Bf4 b6 { The QID move. } 4. e3 Bb7
5. Nbd2 c5 6. h3
{ Kamsky is not interested in adventures, but here White could try the Ashwin trap with   5.Nc4  d5?!  6.Nce5  with the dual threat of Bb5+ and Ng5. More importantly, Kamsky is also keeping back the c-pawn with intention !   6.c3  This is the more standard way of playing  6...Be7  7.h3  cxd4  8.exd4  d6  9.Bd3  Nbd7  10.O-O  O-O  11.Re1  Re8  12.a4  a6  13.Bh2  Qc7   This position was reached in  Kamsky vs. Tiviakov   where the legend continued with  14.c4!? }
6... Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O cxd4 9. exd4 d6
{ Black adopts the flexible and popular Hedgehog setup. } 10. Re1 Nbd7 11. Bh2
{ Dropping back to be able to meet an eventual ...e5 with d5   11.Bg3  Sedlak suggests the bishop is even more usefully placed here }
11... Re8
{ A standard move, preparing ...e5 and vacating  f8  for a piece to enable some repositioning, e. g. ...Bf8 or ...Nf8 to ...Ng6 }
12. a4
{ A typical move, gaining space on the Queenside, aiming to push all the way to  a6  , and securing  c4  for the knight. }
12... a6
{ Black can't generally allow the pawn to reach  a6   12...Qc7  13.a5  Bf8  14.a6  Bc6  15.c4  Rac8  16.b4  as in Kamsky vs Rozum, 2016. }
13. a5 { White goes a5 anyway, not minding the obvious response... } 13... b5
{ ...preserving the pawn structure. But now... } 14. c4 { In one move! } 14...
bxc4 15. Nxc4 Nb8
{ Black shouldn't have given up the  b6  square   15...Qb8  16.Nfd2  Bc6  17.Ra3  Ra7 }
16. Nb6 Ra7 17. Nd2 { Sending the other knight to  c4  for backup. } 17... Nd5
18. Ndc4 Nxb6 19. Nxb6
{ 19.axb6!  Sedlak gives the following fantastic engine line  19...Ra8  20.Rxe6!!  fxe6  21.Qh5  h6  22.Qg6  Nd7  23.Qh7+  Kf8  24.Nxd6  Bxd6  25.Bxd6+  Re7  26.Bc7  Qc8  27.Bg6  Nf6  28.Qh8+  Ng8  29.Rc1  White has an objective edge in this crazy position. }
19... Nd7 20. Qa4 Nxb6 21. axb6 Ra8 22. Qa5 Qd7
{ 22...Bf6!  23.Ra4  Bc6  24.Rb4  Bg5  25.Rd1  h6 } 23. Rac1 Rec8
{ Another mistake in a tough position. If   23...Bd8  24.Qb4  and if   23...Bc6  24.d5!  exd5  25.Rc2  Bg5  26.Rxe8  Rxe8  27.Bg3  or   23...Bc6  24.d5!  Bxd5  25.Rc7  Qd8  26.Be4!  Bxe4  27.Rxe4  and in both cases the b-pawn will decide the game. }
24. Rc7 Rxc7 25. bxc7 Rc8 26. Rc1 Bc6 27. Bxa6 Rxc7 28. Bb5 Ra7
{ If  28...Bd8  29.Rxc6  Rxc6  30.Bxc6  Bxa5  31.Bxd7 } 29. Bxc6
{ Black resigned in view of   29...Qxc6  30.Rxc6  Rxa5  31.Rc8+  Bf8  32.Bxd6  Main lesson of this game: meeting the Hedgehog with the plan of a4 to a5 to a6 and planning to meet ...b5 with c4 in one move. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Repertoire Clashes: 1...d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ In the following two informational lines I'll give you an overview of how we respond to lines that have been recommended for Black. I mostly focused on Chessable repertoires, but I do also mention the most critical non-Chessable resources. This line covers 1...d5 and the next one covers 1...Nf6 and the rest. }
1... d5 2. Bf4 Nf6
{ 2...c6  3.e3  Qb6  This has been recommended by GM Alex Colovic in his recent LTR: Chebanenko Slav. I will recommend a novel plan Colovic doesn't cover. White is safely better in the resulting position.  4.Qc1  Bf5  5.Nf3  Nf6  6.c4  e6  7.c5  Qd8  8.b4  Nbd7  9.h3  Be7  10.Be2  O-O  11.O-O  Re8  12.Nbd2!  Our novelty, avoiding all trades after ...Ne4 - Nb3, enabling White to better protect e5 with Qb2 and giving him a free hand on the Queenside. For more, seehere.   2...c5  Many courses recommend this move order, but at least all of the Chessable ones go for a line which can also be reached from our text order. }
3. e3 c5
{ 3...e6  The early ...e6 plans are good equalizing tries by Black.  4.Nd2  After ...e6 has been played it's best to start with this knight to avoid any quick ...Ne4 & ...Nh5 ideas.  4...Bd6  From this starting point, a number of authors have recommended equalizing plans for Black.   
  For starters, this clever move order is used by Nikolaos Ntirlis in his excellent Playing 1. d4 d5: A Classical Repertoire, Quality Chess, 2017 with the idea to go for a bishop swap with ...b6 and ...Ba6 or move order us into the old main line with ...b6, ...Bb7 and, after we've committed to Ne5, ...Nc6. 
  
 Second, it has been recommended by GM Kiril Georgiev in his fantastic Fighting the London System Chess Stars, 2017, with the idea of a quick ...b6, ...Bb7 and occupying the center with ...Ne4.
  
 Third, it's been recommended by GM Pavel Eljanov in his great Database Complete Repertoire Against the Veresov, Trompowsky, and London, Modern Chess, 2019, with the idea of ...O-O, ...c5, ...Qc7, ...Nbd7!, and a quick ...e5, equalizing in the center.
  
 Finally, it's been recommended by my fried and coauthor Chessforlife in his excellent Beat 1.d4 systems with the best coverage yet.
  Even though White has semi-decent tries against all these lines, the most practical and ambitious approach is to follow Rubinstein  (!)  , Carlsen, Giri and others by cutting them all out with the No Retreat! line.  5.Ngf3!?  We simply don't retreat our bishop, winning a tempo for development, and thereby sidestep all of the above tries. Georgiev and Eljanov of course consider this plan as well, but we have a Giri-inspired surprise in store for both.  5...Bxf4  Georgiev's move. Black wants to exchange both sets of bishops. After exchanging dark-squared ones he will play ...b6 and ...Ba6.   5...O-O  Eljanov's move.  6.c3!  b6  Eljanov's move ...however...  7.Ne5!?  Eljanov doesn't cover this natural knight jump. For more, seehere.   5...O-O  6.c3!  c5!  CFL's move  7.Ne5!?  CFL does cover this best move, but we have a novelty in response, seehere.  6.exf4  O-O  The ball is in White's court. Bd3 is natural and has been played, but we will follow Giri and play the tempo-saving game by finding useful moves so as to meet ...b6 and ...Ba6 with Bxa6 from the starting square.  7.c3  b6  8.h4!?  White needed to find a useful move. So Harry goes up the board. Georgiev doesn't cover this plan  8...c5  9.h5!  Harry keeps on going up the board. Black really needs to stop it.  9...h6  10.Ne5  Another useful move. And now White has made so much progress that ...Ba6 doesn't really make much sense for Black anymore. For more, seeChapter 10. }
4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6
{ 5...cxd4  The Exchange Caro-Kann.  6.exd4  Bf5  This, the new main line, has been recommended by GM Alex Colovic in his On the Way to the Queen's Gambit Declined and LTR: Queen's Gambit Declined.   6...e6  7.c3  Nh5!?  This is the So system and it was recommended as one of the lines by NM Bryan Tillis in his Aggressive Queen's Gambit Declined. However, he gives a weird sideline that doesn't equalize.  8.Be3  g6  This is Tillis's move.  9.Be2  f6  10.g4  Ng7  11.Qc2!  Tillis doesn't cover this natural move, preparing O-O-O, Kb1, and h4, giving White an advantage.  7.Bb5!?  Colovic didn't cover this sharp move in his first course, but does in the second. However, we have an interesting idea that he didn't cover. Seehere.   5...Bf5?!  This slightly dubious move was recommended by NM Elijah Logozar in his provocatively titled Crush the London, here on Chessable. Logozar ended his coverage very early, on move 9. I show that White has an edge in all the ensuing lines after...  6.dxc5  e6  7.Nd4  Bxc5  8.Nxf5  exf5  9.c3  O-O  10.Be2  For more, seeChapter 4.   5...Qb6  This sharp move combined with the novel 8...g6 was recommended by GM Sam Shankland's excellent LTR: Semi-Slav. I recommend a new non-greedy move that sets Black novel problems and that Shankland didn't cover. Black might equalize deep down the line, but the position remains easier for White to play.  6.dxc5  Qxb2  7.Rb1  Qc3  8.Bb5  g6  9.e4!  dxe4  10.Be5  Qa5  11.O-O  exf3  12.Bxc6+  bxc6  13.Qxf3  Nd5  14.Ne4!  White removes the knight from harm's way, controls c3 and f6 and renews the threat of Bxh8. For more, seehere. }
6. c3 Bd6
{ The main line.   6...Nh5!?  This interesting move has been recommended by FM Yuriy Krykun in his recent Accelerated Queen's Indian Defense repertoire here on Chessable, though from a QID move order. I go a bit deeper than him. White has a safe edge in the resulting position.  7.Bg5  f6  8.Bh4  g6  9.Bd3  cxd4  10.cxd4  Bd6  11.O-O  O-O  12.Rc1  Qe7  13.Nb3  g5  14.Ne1  Qe8  15.Be2  Nf4  16.exf4  gxh4  17.g3  Qg6  18.Ng2  Qg7  19.Nxh4  Bxf4  20.Rc3!  Our novelty. For more, seehere. }
7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3 b6
{ The modern main line has been recommended by IM Christof Sielecki & FM Daniel Barrish in their LTR: Nimzo-Ragozin as well as NM Bryan Tillis in his Openings Oddities. }
9. e4 { Our move and the standard GM and engine choice these days. } 9... Be7
{ NM Bryan Tillis stops his coverage after this move, which is way too early. }
10. e5 { White's best choice, contrary to Sielecki&Barrish's opinion. } 10...
Nh5
{ Sielecki&Barrish give this in a comment, saying that Black should be fine after ...f5. This is not the case and White retains both a dangerous initiative and a clear practical, if not objective edge, after... }
11. Ng5
{ We go for this aggressive move which is the current GM and engine favorite, played by Alliestein in a crushing victory over Stockfish. For more seeChapter 8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Repertoire Clashes: 1...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ 1...f5  2.Bf4  Nf6  3.e3  e6   3...g6  This is covered by till in his Antidotes to Anti-Dutch Systems. We will follow his line a move deeper. White has an edge.  4.h4  h6  5.Nc3  d6  6.Qf3  Nc6  7.O-O-O  e6  8.e4  Qe7  9.exf5  gxf5  10.Bc4  Na5  11.Bb5+  Bd7  12.Bxd7+  Qxd7  13.d5  e5  14.Qe2±  b5!?  till's suggestion, sacrificing a pawn for counterplay.  15.Nxb5  Bg7  16.Nc3  O-O  17.Bd2  Rab8  18.Qa6  Nb7  19.Be3  Ng4  20.Nge2  Nxe3  21.fxe3  Nc5  This is where till stopped.  22.Qc4±  4.Nf3  b6  5.Be2  Bb7  6.O-O  Bd6!?  This move has been recommended by the fan-favorite, GM Simon Williams aka GingerGM, in his Killer Dutch.  7.c4  aiming for Bxd6 and c4  7...Bxf4  8.exf4  White has an iron grip on the e5-square  8...O-O  9.Nc3  Nc6  was given by Williams, but he didn't consider  10.Qc2  with the idea of  Rad1  . White is better here. For more seehere. }
2. Bf4 c5
{ the Benoni.   2...g6  the KID & Grünfeld move. This is recommended in GM Kiril Georgiev's Fighting the London System @@StartBracket@@Chess Stars, 2017@@EndBracket@@ and by GM Yannick Pelletier in his video course Anti-London System @@StartBracket@@Chessbase, 2019@@EndBracket@@. On Chessable it has been recommended in Theoryhack's FREE A Blitz Repertoire for Black, an underrated course, if there ever was one. He gives a good line, but not our move.  3.Nc3  d5   3...Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Qd2  c6  This way of playing has been advocated by GM Alexey Kornev in his A Practical Black Repertoire with Ng6, g6, d6 Vol. 1: English, Pirc, Reti and Other Defences @@StartBracket@@Chess Stars, 2016@@EndBracket@@. I recommend one of the sidelines he mentions and give a move he doesn't cover.  6.Bh6  Bxh6  7.Qxh6  Qa5  8.Bd3  c5  9.Nf3  cxd4  10.Nxd4  Nc6  11.Bb5  Bd7  12.O-O-O  Nxd4  13.Bxd7+  Nxd7  14.Rxd4  O-O-O  15.Rhd1  and White is simply better.   3...d6  4.e4  c6  This sort of idea, combining ...g6, ...d6, and ...c6 while keeping back the f8-bishop, is standardly advocated in books on the Pirc, including GM Mihail Marin's GM Repertoire: The Pirc Defence @@StartBracket@@Quality Chess, 2017@@EndBracket@@. I recommend a natural and logical way of playing that Marin doesn't address.  5.Qd2  Nbd7  6.Nf3  Bg7  7.Bh6!  This is our move. Surprisingly, Marin doesn't cover it.   3...d6  4.e4  a6  This newish move has been recommended by IM Christof Sielecki & Michael Gorny in their LTR: Pirc Defence here on Chessable, I was able to find a move they miss that leaves White on top, seehere  4.e3  Bg7  5.h4  c6   5...h5  The most common move and recommended by Theoryhack.  6.Nf3  O-O  7.Be2  This is our move, and it's better than the immediate Ne5 since it prepares a quick O-O.  6.Be2  Qb6  This move is recommended by Georgiev, but he covers it in a line where White has played Nf3. Be2 is much better since after Na4 and b4, driving away Black's Queen, White can continue with the strong h5!  7.Na4  Qa5+  8.c3  Nbd7  9.b4  Qd8  10.h5!  White intends h6 next and has a nice edge.   2...e6  The Nimzo-QID move. This move order is recommended by FM Yuriy Krykun to enter his line that we covered in 1...d5 Repertoire Clashes. However, our course move order doesn't allow for this at all.  3.e3  c5  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.Nc3!?  This move, threatening both Nb5 and d5, takes the game into independent waters. Krykun doesn't cover it. }
3. e3 { Our choice. } 3... Nd5
{ This unprincipled, but well-scoring move is recommended by FM Kamil Plichta in his Too Hot to Handle: The King's Indian Defense. I have found a novelty that makes this line near unplayable for Black!   3...Qb6  This, the main move, is recommended by IM Christof Sielecki in his Chessexplained's Benko Repertoire and it has also been recommended in the free course Agadmator's Anti-London System, but the latter fails to give the best continuation, seehere  4.Nc3  One of the two moves I give here.   4.Nf3!?  Our second move and my preference, intending to sacrifice the b-pawn for a development lead. Neither Sielecki nor the Agadmator course cover it.  4...d6  5.Bb5+!?  This is our move, with the idea of playing a4 next. Sielecki doesn't cover it. }
4. Bg3 Qb6 5. c4
{ Even Stockfish 12 can't find this on its own. Nor is it known the editors of the D-pawn specials section over at ChessPub which I consider to be the best source of opening theory. }
5... Qxb2
{ In the update, Plichta now gives  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  Qxb2  7.Nge2  cxd4  8.exd4  Qb4  9.Rb1  Qa5  but here we have an improvement in store as well. Seehere. }
6. cxd5 Qxa1 7. Qc2
{ This is the idea. White intends Nf3, Be2, O-O, and Nc3, trapping Black's Queen. Black is already lost. For more, seehere. }
