[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Use of Model Games"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ In this course, model games are used in three ways. If there is a particularly instructive or thematic model game that I think helps you get inspired to learn the lines, I've included it as an inspirational game at the very beginning of a chapter or section.   Second, in cases where I thought it would be most conducive to learning I've included the relevant model games right after the variations. The majority of the games fall into this category.  Finally, there are many model games in the last chapter that usually feature some deviation for White or an alternative line while being still instructive. These have been arranged in the same order as the chapters. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "1. Classical to Exchange Caro/Slav"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/3P4/2P1P3/PP3PPP/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We start in this Classical position. White has the triangle setup, Black has played ...c5 Queen's Gambit style, but also ...e6, locking in his light-squared bishop. The fight is over the e5 and e4 squares. White's main influence on the position comes from either planting a knight on e5 and playing f4 or pushing e4, and perhaps even e5. In contrast, Black really wants to push ...e5 to equalize in the center. }
1... cxd4
{ Black can always make the principled decision of using the c-pawn to capture the d-pawn.   Black could also clarify things in the center by pushing the c-pawn forward, but usually, it is a positional mistake, taking the pressure of the center and giving White a free hand in the center and kingside.  1...c4  Perhaps aiming to play for ...b5 and ...b4 and even ...b3. White should meet this by playing for b3 and/or e4.   Another option is  1...b6  Here it is best to imagine this played after White has already planted a knight to e5 and can therefore set up the Stonewall with  2.f4 }
2. exd4
{ We normally recapture with the e-pawn which leads to the Exchange Caro-Kann structure aka the Reversed Carlsbad. White has a half-open e-file, Black a half-open c-file. White has an outpost on e5, Black an outpost on c4. These are not 'forever' outposts since either side can kick the piece with b3 or ...f6, respectively, but that would considerably weaken the pawn structure.    Black's main plan is the minority attack with ...b5 to ...b4, in order to create a weakness on c3. White's main plan is to control e5 and to try to use the extra central space and the open file to start a kingside attack, perhaps with the help of a rook lift aka Rover Re3 - Rg3 / Rh3.   2.cxd4  There are some rare occasions where we recapture with the c-pawn, for example when Black has played ...Nh5 and we need the e-pawn to control f4 to prevent ...Nf4. This leads to the Exchange Slav structures where play will take place on the open c-file and the squares b4 and b5 and c4 and c5 have special significance for the pieces. Note that in these structures White would much rather have the b1-knight on c3, than d2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "2. Surrendering the Center with dxc5: b4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2b1k2r/ppq2ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/2P1PNB1/PP1N1PPP/3QKB1R w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here Black has played ...Nc6, ...Bd6, and now ...Qc7, threatening to push ...e5. White profitably meets this with... }
1. dxc5
{ Black can't recapture with the Queen since the ...Nc6 is in the way. Nor can he take with the bishop, due to the pin. }
1... Bxg3 2. hxg3 { White gets the open h-file. } 2... e5
{ Black can choose to play ...e5, but now } 3. b4
{ White gets to hold on to the pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "3. Surrendering the Center with dxc5: e4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4kb2/pp3ppp/1q2p3/2Pp2Bn/8/2P1PN2/PP3PPP/3QK3 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We're in a position where Black has played ...Nh5 and met White's Bg5 with ...Qb6. White played dxc5, with tempo. }
1... Qxc5 { 1...Bxc5  2.b4  White gains a useful tempo a la Semi-Slav. } 2. e4
{ Hoping to also play e5 or take on d5. Now, if Black takes we get the important 3-3  (White)  vs 4-2  (Black)  structure. Some important points:  - The main strategic goal for BOTH sides is control of the open d-file.  - Black's plans include a minority attack on the Queenside or activating their majority on the Kingside.  - White's plans are to activate their majority on the Queenside or use the e5 square. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "4. Doubled C-Pawns"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb1k3/p3qppp/2pbp3/2ppN3/3P4/2P1P1B1/PP1N1PPP/R2QK3 w Qq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We're in a position where White has played Bxc6 and inflicted doubled pawns on Black, creating a pair of targets on c6 and c5. We will face this position in the Classical with ...Bd6 Sidelines chapter. White now starts attacking the c6-weakness. }
1. Qa4 { Attacking c6. } 1... Bb7 2. Nd3 { Aiming for Bxd6 and Nxc5. } 2... Nd7
3. Qa3 { Pinning the c-pawn. White can increase pressure with Nb3! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "5. Rubinstein's Structure"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/3bpn2/3p4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here Black has played an early ...e6 and ...Bd6, without committing to ...c5 or ...Nc6, yet. White usually meets ...Bd6 with the retreat Bg3. However, in this position we instead go for the No Retreat! line and have developed our knight instead. }
1... Bxf4 { Black usually takes, sooner or later, doubling our f-pawns. } 2.
exf4
{ The Rubinstein structure. White has doubled f-pawns, but increased control over e5. }
2... O-O
{ One of Black's main plans in this structure is to play ...Ba6 and exchange another pair of bishops. However, he usually castles first, giving the move to White.   2...c5  3.dxc5  White plays dxc5 to avoid an IQP after c3, ...cxd4, cxd4. This was already played by Rubinstein in the London 1922 tournament after which our opening is named.  3...Qc7  Black attacks both pawns  4.g3  White defends the f-pawn, establishing a typical kingside structure in this opening  4...Qxc5  5.Bd3  O-O  6.O-O  Nc6  7.c3  White has great control over d4 &e5. }
3. c3
{ White makes a useful waiting move, to play Bxa6 from the starting square.   3.Bd3  This can be played, but it loses a tempo compared to our main line  3...b6  4.c3   4.Qe2  Can be played to discourage ...Ba6  4...Qd6  5.g3  c5  6.c3  a5  Black will get ...Ba6 in after all, but Carlsen's choice here has been to grab some Queenside space with  7.a4  Ba6  5.Bxa6  White has wasted 2 moves on this capture. }
3... b6 4. h4
{ White makes another useful move, gaining kingside space and intending h5 to h6. }
4... c5 { Black waits as well.   4...Ba6  5.Bxa6  Nxa6  6.Qe2 } 5. h5
{ White threatens h6 } 5... h6 { Black really needs to stop it } 6. Ne5
{ White makes a final useful move and awaits developments, meeting ...Ba6 with Bxa6, Qe2, O-O-O and possibly even g4-g5. Similarly, ...Bb7 will be met with Ndf3!, making possible responding to...cxd4 with Qxd4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "6. Black's IQP + Doubled F-Pawns"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pp3ppp/2nb1n2/3p1pB1/8/2P1P3/PP1N1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 3 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this position Black has given up the two bishops and accepted an IQP + doubled f-pawns. The fact that Black's d-pawn is isolated and that he doesn't have a light-squared bishop matter a lot here. }
11. g3
{ White has time to fianchetto the bishop like in the main line of the Tarrasch Defence since this way it will put maximum pressure on the IQP. }
11... Be7 12. Bxf6
{ White captures Black's knight to avoid any ...Ne4 jumps and further emphasize the weakness of the IQP. }
12... Bxf6 { Black's bishop is just staring at the wall of pawns... } 13. Bg2
{ White will castle and control the square in front of the pawn with Nb3 and then pile up the pressure by potentially doubling on the d-file. Qb3 is another thematic idea here, hitting the IQP from the other side. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "7. Slav Endgame"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn1qk3/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R2QK3 w Qq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We are in one of the Baltic-Slav endgame variations where Black has developed the light-squared bishop early, and played c6 and e6. White has pushed c4 and now plays... }
1. Qb3
{ Attacking the b-pawn. Notice the importance of the London bishop covering c7 and attacking b8. }
1... Qb6
{ Black's most natural move.   1...Qc8  2.Rc1  White intends cxd5 and in case of the natural ...exd5, Nb5!   1...b6  Black weakens his Queenside structure  2.cxd5  White immediately clarifies the central structure.  2...exd5  Now c6 is a target.   2...cxd5  Now White can use the b5 square. }
2. c5 Qxb3 3. axb3
{ All versions of this endgame are good for White due to the open a-file, strong London bishop, and the possibility of playing for b4 to b5, sometimes twice. Another idea is f3 to control the center and g4 and h4 with across-the-board domination. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "8. Chigorin-Carlsbad"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4kbn1/ppp2ppp/2n1p3/3p1b2/2PP1B2/4P3/PP3PPP/1N2KBN1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We're in a Chigorin position where Black has played ...Nc6, blocking their c-pawn. As GM Sam Shankland likes to emphasize, ...Nc6 blocking the c-pawn only makes sense for Black if he gets ...e5 in, which is indeed one of Black's main ideas in the Chigorin. However, the setup makes very little sense against the London since White has Bf4, adding extra control to  e5  . White has responded to Black's play by pushing c4 in response. We will see such positions in some lines of the Baltic/Slav chapter and of course in the Chigorin chapter. }
1. cxd5
{ White immediately clarifies the central structure, creating a Carlsbad-ish structure, except Black hasn't been able to play ...c6 yet. }
1... exd5 2. Nc3
{ White will enjoy the open c-file and the play will frequently revolve around Black's bad knight and backwards c-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "9. Kingside Expansion with f3, g4, h4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3qkb2/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p3b/3P1B1P/4PP2/PPP3P1/1N1QKB2 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We're in a structure which resembles the Classical Caro-Kann with ...Bf5. Black has developed their light-squared bishop with ...Bg4 on the second or third move and White has responded with f3, and h4! threatening to trap it with g4 and h5. Black can react in one of two ways. }
1... Bg6
{ Black cleverly retreats the bishop to be able to meet g4 with ...h5   1...h6  The more typical, Caro-Kannish move to make a hole for the bishop  2.g4  Bg6  3.Bd3  White could also play h5 first and then Bd3, but it might be better to keep the kingside pawn structure fluid.  3...Bxd3   3...e6  4.Bxg6  fxg6  Black would have serious weaknesses on both e6 and g6  5.Qd3  4.Qxd3  e6  5.Nc3  White will castle Queenside with a good game. }
2. g4 h5 3. g5
{ White pushes on, gaining kingside space and dislodging Black's knight. } 3...
Nd7 4. Nc3
{ Developing the important Queenside piece, with the aim of preparing O-O-O. }
4... e6 5. Bd3
{ White exchanges Black's time-wasting bishop which has already moved 3 times and develops his Queen with tempo. If given the chance White would like to take on g6 and inflict serious weaknesses on e6 and g6 on Black. }
5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 { White will castle Queenside with a good game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "10. Queen's Indian Hedgehog"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/p4ppp/1p1pp3/8/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is the Hedgehog Structure which can be reached from the Queen's Indian setup, after ...c5, ...cxd4, and ...d6. However, here we're looking at a version where White hasn't played c3  (remember Kamsky's game from the introduction?)  . Like in the Exchange Caro, White has a half-open e-file and Black has a half-open c-file. However, due to the difference in the placement of Black's d-pawn, the plans for both sides are quite different. Here White usually tries to play on the Queenside while Black's eyes are set on the center, his main goal being ...e5. }
1. a4
{ White grabs Queenside space, secures c4 for a piece, guarding it against ...b5, and aims for a5 and a6, kicking away Black's fianchettoed bishop.   1.c3  This is another, slower way of playing. In fact, usually White makes this move earlier. However, he will still continue with a4 and then play for an eventual c4 and b4. }
1... a6 { Black stops a5, intending to meet it with ...b5. Or does he? } 2. a5
{ Anyway! } 2... b5 3. c4 { In one move, following our hero Kamsky. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "11. Pirc Transformations"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1n1qk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/3PPB2/2N5/PPP2PPP/3QK1NR b Kk - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We're in a Pirc structure which is reached when Black plays ...g6 & ...Bg7 and White responds with Nc3 & e4, establishing the perfect center. Black now usually plays... }
1... d6
{ This is Black's main move and it is important to stop White's main central break: e5.   1...O-O?  2.e5  If e5 can be pushed we MUST do it, otherwise Black could try ...d5 in one move.  2...Ne8  3.Qe2  White gets ready for O-O-O thereby discouraging ...d6. White's kingside play is natural with h4-h5 etc.   1...d5?  This move doesn't work, but can be tricky. With ...d5 Black weakens the London bishop-s diagonal so White should first play  2.Nb5!  Na6  3.e5  Only after having moved the knight does White push since now he can meet...  Ne4  with  4.f3  The point is that Black doesn't have ...Nxc3 and is forced to retreat, leaving White on top. }
2. Qd2
{ White gets ready to exchange bishops. The general rule in these positions is that if Black castles, we respond with O-O-O. However, if Black waits by playing something like ...c6 or ...Nbd7 what we will do depends on whether Black is playing for ...b5 or ...e5. The move ...c6 prepares ...b5 so we force him to make a choice between castling or capturing with Bh6. However, the move ...Nbd7 prepares ...e5 and then we play O-O-O, discouraging the break. }
2... c6 3. Bh6
{ White forces Black to choose between protecting the bishop or capturing it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "12. GrÃ¼nfeld Transformations"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1nbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p4/3P1B1P/2N1P3/PPP2PP1/3QKBNR b k - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We're in a Grünfeld  structure which is most commonly reached after Black plays ...g6 & White plays Nc3, threatening e4, forcing Black to stop it with ...d5. After the ensuing e3, ...Bg7, and h4, threatening h5 and perhaps h6, the ball is in Black's court. }
1... O-O
{ This is not the most common move, but can lead to one of the main lines   1...Nbd7??  The quickest way to lose, completely disregarding the threat on c7.  2.Nb5  O-O  3.Bxc7   1...c5?!  A very common mistake. Black hasn't castled yet, so Nc7+ is a threat, At the same time, ...c5 weakens the b5 square and White gets a forever outpost after  2.Nb5  Na6  Forced, and this means Black also can't play ...a6  3.Be2  Taking a moment to stop ...Bg4. White will next set up a bind with a4 and c3.   1...h5  Logical and most common, stopping h5  2.Nf3  White just develops and intends Be2 next. }
2. h5 c5
{ 2...Nxh5??  3.Rxh5!  gxh5  4.Qxh5  White has a near unstoppable attack after Bd3, Nf3, O-O-O, Rh1 etc. }
3. hxg6 fxg6
{ 3...hxg6  4.Qd2  White intends O-O-O, f3 , g4,  Qh2, Bh6, Bxg7 and Qh8# } 4.
dxc5
{ The light squares are weakened so White takes on ...c5, opening the Queen on the d-pawn and intending Be5 to remove its defender. }
*

