[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "13. Good Benoni"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/1q1p1n2/2p5/3P4/2N1P3/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We're in a line from the Benoni where Black has played 1...Nf6, 2...c5, and 3...Qb6, but refrained from grabbing the b-pawn and played ...d6 instead. White uses this to his advantage by making the following moves to reach a good Benoni structure... }
1. Bb5+ Bd7 2. a4 a6
{ Black never wants to play  2...Bxb5  3.axb5  giving White the open a-file and a strong b-pawn. }
3. a5 Qd8 4. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 5. d5 g6 6. e4 Bg7 7. Nf3
{ Both sides will castle short next, after which White can claim that he has a good Benoni structure with the pawn on a5 restricting Black's typical ...b5 break. In the long run White will play for the e5 break. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Structures and Themes"]
[Black "14. Old Benoni Transformations"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1nb1kbn1/pp1ppppp/8/2pP4/8/8/PPP1PPPP/1NB1KBN1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We're in an Old Benoni where Black has played 1...c5 and White has responded by pushing the d-pawn. The Ball is in Black's court and he can play any of: }
1... d6
{ 1...e5  the Czech Benoni style move  2.e4  d6  3.Bb5+  A disruptive check  3...Bd7  Neither the Black bishop nor the knight want to be on d7  4.a4  White gets a4 in  4...a6   4...Bxb5  Black never wants to play this, giving White the open a-file and a strong b-pawn  5.axb5  5.Bd3  In the long run Black wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops via something like ...Be7 to ...Bg5 whereas White wants to avoid this and play for an eventual f4.   1...e6  2.Nc3  Nf6   2...exd5  3.Nxd5  d6  4.g3  3.e4  d6   3...exd5  A frequent blunder  4.e5  Remember this. With Queens on the board Black will lose material!  4.Bb5+  Again, the disruptive check  4...Bd7  5.a4   1...b5  The Benko move doesn't make sense here  2.e4   1...f5  The Clarendon Court doesn't make sense either  2.e4 }
2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3
{ 4.f4  Bg7  5.Bb5+  Again, the check  5...Nbd7  6.e5  Ng8  7.e6 } 4... a6
{ With ...a6 Black always prepares his main break ...b5. White should almost NEVER allow it, stopping it with... }
5. a4
{ White stops ...b5 and sometimes even wants to push a5. One of Black's plans here is ...Bg4 & ...Bxf3. If given the chance White can and should stop it with h3. }
*

