1. d4
{ Here we're going to take a look at the different moments Black can go bishop-hunting with ...Nh5 and how to react. There's a whole separate complex in the Baltic/Slav lines with 2...Bf5 or 2...c6 where Black aims for ...Nh5 down the line, but we'll talk about those in more depth inChapter 12. }
1... d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6
{ 4...Nh5??  fails to a tactical solution which I won't reveal here since I want you to try solving it in the tactics section, first. }
5. Nbd2 e6
{ 5...Nh5!?  This is Dubov's idea. Here it is best to grab the pawn and allow the bishop to be taken with...  6.dxc5  Nxf4  7.exf4  g6  8.c3  Bg7  9.Bb5  SeeChapter 6. }
6. c3 cxd4
{ Black enters Exchange Caro-Kann   6...Be7  Here Black is threatening ...Nh5 since he's now covering the g5 square. However, we don't give him a chance by playing  7.Ne5!   6...Qb6  7.Rb1  Nh5  Here, again, it is best to attack the Queen with tempo  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.b4  Be7  10.b5  Na5  11.Bd3  SeeChapter 9.   6...Nh5  This is a novel move, recommended by FM Yuryi Krykun in his Accelerated QID repertoire. Here it is best to attack the Queen with...  7.Bg5  f6  8.Bh4  g6  9.Bd3  cxd4  10.cxd4  SeeChapter 10. }
7. exd4 Nh5 { This is So's idea. Here it is best to return to e3 immediately. }
8. Be3 Bd6 9. Ne5 g6 10. g4 { SeeChapter 4  . } *

