[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ Here, we're going to take a look at all the different moments Black can go pawn-hunting with ...Qb6, and how to react. }
1... d5
{ 1...Nf6  2.Bf4  c5  Benoni.   2...e6  Queen's Indian.  3.e3  c5  4.Nf3  Qb6  5.Na3!  Here it is best to play this move so as to be able to jump to both b5 and c4. For more seeChapter 14.  3.e3  Qb6  This is probably Black's best ...Qb6-line. Here I give White two options, leading to very different sort of play. SeeChapter 17  4.Nc3  is one option 4. Nf3 is the other. }
2. Bf4 Nf6
{ 2...c6  Slav.  3.e3  Qb6  This is the line recommended by GM Alex Colovic in his Chebanenko repertoire.  4.Qc1  Here it is best to play this move. Seehere andhere. }
3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6
{ 4...Qb6?  As a general rule, whenever Black plays ...Qb6 earlier than on the 5th move and you still have Nc3 available, that's the move you should play!  5.Nc3!  Black has to choose his next move very carefully so as not to immediately lose. SeeChapter 5. }
5. Nbd2 Qb6
{ 5...cxd4  Black enters the Exchange Caro-Kann first and then goes ...Qb6  6.exd4  Qb6  7.Nb3  SeeChapter 4.   5...e6  6.c3  Qb6  This doesn't make a ton of sense, once White has  7.Rb1 }
6. dxc5 { SeeChapter 6. } *

