[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Exchange Caro-Kann: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5
{ This move and gives Black the most flexible options for Exchange Caro-Kann setups since he isn't committing to ...Nf6 yet.   2...Nf6  We will also look at two separate setups that Black can try, entering from this move order.  3.e3  c5  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.Nbd2  Two Knights.  5...cxd4  6.exd4  Bf5  Like in the New Main Line below. From this move order White is committed to Ngf3 and now the stereotypical c3 would allow Black several annoying lines which are covered in the next informational line.   6...Qb6  Idea nr. 2.  7.Nb3  Bf5   7...Bg4  8.h3  Bh5  9.a4  8.a4  The main idea in this line, going after the Queen and intending to push all the way to a6.  8...a6  9.a5  See the trainable line.  7.Bb5!?  A new and sharp idea, intending c4 in one move. }
3. e3
{ 3.e4  Black does have to keep in mind that here White could try the Norris Gambit with which is a nice surprise weapon, but won't be covered in this course. }
3... cxd4
{ The quickest way to enter the Exchange Caro @@StartBracket@@Lichess: ~6500 games@@EndBracket@@ . In practice, Black frequently enters a few moves later. The idea is to fix the central structure with a choice of further plans available.   3...Qb6  Notice that after ...c5 is played, all early, pre-fifth-move ...Qb6-s can be met with the thematic Nc3 to Nb5.  4.Nc3  We'll look at such lines in the next chapter. }
4. exd4 Nc6 { The more flexible knight development. } 5. c3 Nf6
{ The main, and most frequently played move @@StartBracket@@~4700 games@@EndBracket@@ . However, from this move order Black can try to keep back  the knight and try other moves like.   5...Bf5  intending a quick ...Bd6, ...f6 or ...Ne7.  6.Nd2  e6  7.Ngf3  Bd6  Idea nr. 1   7...f6  Idea nr. 2   7...Nge7  Idea nr. 3. See the trainable lines.   5...f6  the Apeldoorn Variation, preparing both ...e5 and ...g5.  6.Nf3  g5  7.Be3  It's important NOT to retreat to the stereotypical g3!  7...Bf5  8.c4!  The important move, playing it like the Queen's Gambit and intending to develop the knight to c3. See the trainable line. }
6. Nd2 Bf5
{ The new main line, controlling the important diagonal.   6...Bg4  The old main line.  7.Qb3  Qc8  8.Ngf3  e6  9.Bd3  Be7  10.O-O  O-O  11.Ne5  Now game continues depending on whether Black takes or retreats the bishop. See the trainable lines.   6...g6  This move makes little sense. White should focus on restricting Black's development.  7.Be2  Bg7  8.h3  Preparing to develop the knight without allowing the pin.  8...O-O  9.Ngf3  Bf5  10.O-O  Ne4  11.Re1   6...e6  This leads to the interesting and sharp So System.  7.Ngf3  Nh5   7...Bd6  This move makes zero sense. It's like the main line, but with Black having handed White the open e-file.  8.Bg3  O-O   8...Bxg3  Never a good idea...  9.hxg3  Similar to lines we'll study in a later chapter.  9.Bd3  White will play Ne5, f4, O-O, similar to the lines we'll study later.  8.Be3  Bd6  9.Ne5  g6  10.g4!?  Ng7  11.h4  For more see the trainable lines. }
7. Qb3
{ From this move order, this is the most precise move here. It's also easy to remember since we can meet both ...Bg4 and ...Bf5 with the same way. The point is to attack b7 and force Black to react to the threat somehow, making him lose valuable time. This cuts out the two annoying lines I mentioned in the introduction to the chapter. }
7... Qc8
{ 7...Qb6  A typical mistake. The rule is, this move is never good when b5 is available for the opposing side since here White can just exchange Queens and play Bb5.  8.Qxb6  axb6  Here the doubled pawns are a weakness and the open a-file won't matter that much.  9.Bb5  e6  10.Ngf3  Be7  We'll take this as the trainable line since White play is slightly more unintuitive. The better move is 11...Nd7 after which just 12. O-O and Stockfish suggest White continue with a3, h3, g4. etc.  11.Ne5  Rc8  12.f3  This dominates the knight on f6. Now White can tuck away the king on e2 or f2 and continue grabbing space all over the board.   7...Qd7  This just gets hit with a quick Ngf3 to Ne5.  8.Ngf3  e6  9.Ne5  Qc8  10.Bb5  Nothing fancy, just more pressure on c6.  10...a6  Nothing else makes much sense here since White is ready to ramp up the pressure with Qa4, e. g. 10...Be7, 10. Qa4.   Most common is actually 10...Nd7 after which 11.g4! and White can win the bishop pair and expand on the kingside.  11.Bxc6+  bxc6  12.Qa4  With thematic play against the c-pawn. }
8. Ngf3 e6 9. Nh4 { The thematic move, gaining the bishop pair. } 9... Be4
{ Black's best option is to give up the bishop on e4.   9...Bg6  Black's least interesting option is to give up the bishop on g6 without forcing any concessions from White.  10.Nxg6  hxg6  11.Bd3  White completes development.  11...Nh5  12.Be3  Bd6  13.g3  The main move, preventing ...Nf4. Kramnik preferred 13.O-O-O in Kramnik vs Sjugirov, 2015 and won in great style, but objectively this is much stronger.  13...Nf6  14.Nf3  Kamsky preferred the plan 14. Qd1 O-O 15. f4 with a clamp on e5 and a potential kingside attack in Kamsky vs Macieja, 2012. However, the current engines think the Queen is fine where it is and prefer this move, giving White a considerable advantage.  14...O-O  15.O-O  White can tuck away the king on g2. Play a4 to prevent the minority attack, if needed, and continue playing on the Queenside.   9...Bg4  Black tries to get White to play h3 and g4 before giving up the bishop.  10.h3  Bh5  11.g4  Bg6  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.Be2  Preventing ...Nxg4. This is much better than fianchettoing since White plans to castle long, play Kb1, and then continue with Rdg1, Be3 and h4 to h5 to put pressure on the kingside pawns. }
10. Nxe4 { We just take it off and don't bother with f3. } 10... dxe4
{ The most interesting continuation, trying to get White's knight on h4 into trouble. This is recommended by the famed theorist GM Boris Avrukh in his Beating 1.d4 Sidelines.   10...Nxe4  The natural recapture.  11.Nf3  White returns the knight and sees how things will develop. For example 11...Bd6 12. Bxd6 Nxd6 13. Bd3 and White can then castle and play Rc1 etc. }
11. g3 { Creating space for the knight. } 11... Be7 12. Ng2 Nd5
{ Avrukh's move. } 13. Rd1
{ White has a choice of moves here, but this is actually strongest, not retreating and simply intending d5!   13.Bd2  This is the move that theoreticians give, but I find the main line much more interesting and fresh.  13...O-O  14.Be2  Both Avrukh and Sedlak discussed this position. }
13... O-O
{ 13...Nxf4  Yes, Black gets the two bishops, but at what price...  14.Nxf4  White is intending d5!  14...O-O   14...Bg5  15.d5!  15.d5  exd5  16.Bh3  Qb8  17.Nxd5 }
14. Bc1 { Now it is time to retreat. It's best to go to c1. } 14... Qd7 15. Be2
Rac8 16. O-O
{ White will play Ne3 next, trying to dislodge Black's strong knight and potentially heading for g4 and e5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "A Line to Avoid"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5
{ 2...Nf6  3.e3  c5  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.Nbd2  Two Knights.  5...cxd4  6.exd4  Bf5  Reaches a similar position as the text, except White has already played Ngf3 and not c3. If we played c3 we would transpose to the text. However, from this move order our choice is  7.Bb5!? }
3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Nd2 Bf5 7. Ngf3
{ This position can be reached from two move orders, but it's one we would like to avoid because it allows Black the following two good lines.   7.Qb3!  From the text move order this is our move, forcing Black to react to the threat of Qxb7 immediately. }
7... e6
{ This leads to the first line.   7...a6  Graham Burgess recommends this relatively rare move in his new repertoire book.  8.Nh4  Bg4  9.Qb3  b5  10.h3  Bh5  11.Bd3  Like many other lines in the Caro complex this is near equal or slightly better for White. But we can simply sidestep it. }
8. Qb3 Bd6
{ The newest interesting try which can be quite a pain to meet @@StartBracket@@~ 160 games in the database@@EndBracket@@ . Black simply gambits the b-pawn. }
9. Qxb7 { White really has nothing better. } 9... Bxf4 10. Qxc6+ Kf8
{ The engines give equality, but Black scores quite well here. I think this line is best avoided though White can play either with g3 or Ne5 etc. }
11. g3
{ The sanest move, forcing the bishop to make a decision and allowing the recapture on d2 with the knight.   11.Ne5  The engine preference. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Old Main Line: 6...Bg4, 11...Nxe5, 13...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4
{ Black takes the earliest opportunity to enter the Exchange Caro-Kann. } 4.
exd4 Nc6 5. c3 { White protects the d-pawn with the c-pawn. } 5... Nf6
{ This is the main move. We will look at a host of other ways of playing that rely on keeping the knight back, in the end of this chapter. }
6. Nd2 Bg4 { The old main line. } 7. Qb3 { The obvious move. } 7... Qc8
{ The main response. Qd7 is met the same way with Ngf3 and then Black has to take into account the unpleasant threats of Bb5 and Ne5, followed by f3, g4 and h4.   However, if  7...Qb6?!  8.Qxb6   If  7...Na5  8.Qa4+  Bd7  9.Qc2  . }
8. Ngf3 e6 9. Bd3 { Taking the diagonal. } 9... Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne5 Nxe5
{ Black can take the knight. } 12. dxe5
{ White can also try Bxd5 like in the model game Wei Yi - Malakhov } 12... Nd7
13. Qc2 g6 { One way to protect the pawn. } 14. Nb3 Bf5 15. Bxf5 gxf5 16. Nd4
{ White has a long-term edge due to Black's pawn structure. There are actually a number of moves he could start with here, including Rfd1, g3, Qe2 etc. But centralizing the knight makes sense.   We shouldn't really aim for an immediate kingside attack since Black is likely to play ...Kh8 and ...Rg8. Instead, we should play g3 to secure the kingside and then focus on the center and queenside with Rfd1, Qe2 etc., stopping Black's minority attack. The knight can relocate to f3 and d2 as needed. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Old Main Line: 6...Bg4, 11...Nxe5, 13...h6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Nd2 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qc8 8.
Ngf3 e6 9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Qc2 h6
{ The other way to defend the pawn. } 14. Nb3 Nc5 15. Nxc5 Bxc5 16. Rae1
{ White's plan is to exchange bishops on e3 and then lift the rook with Re3 to Rg3 to start an attack. However, if Black chooses to go for ...Bf5 and exchange off the light-squared bishops White can play in the center. For example  16...Rd8  17.Qd2  Bf5  18.Bxf5  exf5  19.Be3  Bxe3  20.Rxe3  with an obvious edge. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Old Main Line: 6...Bg4, 10...Bh5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Nd2 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qc8 8.
Ngf3 e6 9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O Bh5
{ This is much less likely, but better than castling. Black intends to swap off the light-squared bishops as fast as possible to hamper White's attack. }
11. Rae1
{ Following Magnus's lead by putting the a-rook on the central half-open file immediately. It's entirely possible to also play Rfe1 here with the idea of keeping the a-Rook behind the a-pawn and possibly avoiding exchanging the light-squared bishop with Bf1. }
11... Bg6
{ Best move. If  11...Nd7  12.Re3  and White doubles rooks on the e-file and can look to move them to the g3 or h3.   If something like  11...Nd7  12.Re3  a6  13.a4  to stop the Minority Attack. }
12. Bxg6 hxg6 13. h4
{ The best move, grabbing kingside space and preparing for an attack on the kingside, given that Black is pretty much forced to castle on that side anyway. As a bonus, we can always meet ...Nh5 with Bh2, keeping the London bishop on its main diagonal. For more on how the game could go, see the model gameCarlsen vs. So. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Magnus Carlsen vs. Wesley So, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This was a Blitz game in the Chess.com Speed Chess Championship 2017. It demonstrates well the sort of kingside play White should aim for in these lines. The game starts as a Caro-Kann, but will later transpose to our course line. }
1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qc8 8. Nd2
e6 9. Ngf3 { At this point we've transposed to the course line. } 9... Be7 10.
O-O Bh5 { So plays the best move. } 11. Rae1
{ Magnus develops the a-Rook to e1, like we recommend as well. } 11... Bg6 12.
Bxg6 hxg6 13. h3 { The direct  13.h4  is our recommended move. } 13... a6 14.
a4 { Stopping ...b5. } 14... Nd7 { 14...Na5  was better  15.Qc2 } 15. Re3
{ In these lines White frequently wants to use the half-open e-file to send the rooks over to the kingside. }
15... O-O 16. h4 { Magnus goes h4 with a stutter step. } 16... Nf6
{ So just returns the knight, losing time. } 17. Qd1
{ Repositioning the Queen to help with the kingside attack.   17.Ne5  Was natural. }
17... b5 18. Ne5 { 18.b4  bxa4  19.Qxa4 } 18... b4 19. Bg5 Re8 20. Rh3
{ Now the storm clouds start gathering over Black's kingside. } 20... Qc7 21.
Ndf3 { Protecting e5.   21.f4  This was the better move. } 21... bxc3
{ Black should've taken the chance to chop the knight.   21...Nxe5!  22.Nxe5  Bd6  23.Re1  Ne4= }
22. bxc3
{ 22.Nxc6!  Was the way to go already here.  22...Qxc6  23.Ne5  Qd6  24.bxc3 }
22... Rac8
{ This slow move gives White a huge advantage.   22...Nxe5!  23.Nxe5  Bd6  and Black is even slightly better. }
23. Nxc6
{ White exchanges one knight and gets the other out of the way of play on the third rank. }
23... Qxc6 24. Ne5 Qc7 25. Qf3 Bd8 26. h5 { Breaking things open. } 26... Nxh5
{ 26...gxh5  27.Bxf6  Bxf6  28.Qxh5  Kf8  29.Rf3 } 27. Bxd8
{ 27.Bd2  It was better to just retreat the bishop and keep Black's rooks unconnected. }
27... Rexd8 28. g4 Nf6 29. Kg2 g5 30. Qe3
{ 30.Rfh1  Was the better way to go, simply doubling on the h-file. } 30... Ne4
31. f3 Nf6
{ 31...f6!  32.fxe4  fxe5  33.Qxg5  White has a minimal edge, according to the engines.  33...Rf8 }
32. Rfh1 Kf8 33. Qxg5 Qxc3 34. Rh8+ Ke7 35. Rxd8 Rxd8 36. Qxg7
{ Material is equal, but White is completely winning due to Black's weak king. See whether you can guess the moves from here. }
36... Qc2+ 37. Kg3 Rf8 38. Rh6 { Simply attacking the knight. } 38... Ne8
{ 38...Nd7?  39.Nxd7  Kxd7  40.Qxf8 } 39. Qg5+ f6 40. Qg6
{ Attacking the loose Queen and if Black captures he falls prey to a nasty fork. }
40... Qxa4 { 40...Qxg6  41.Nxg6+ } 41. Rh7+ Kd8 42. Qb1
{ Threatening mate in 1. } 42... Qb5 43. Nc6+ Qxc6 44. Qb8+ Qc8 45. Qb6+
{ Black will not only lose his Queen, but also the knight, so he resigned. } *

