[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "6...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Nd2 g6
{ A sideline which is rarely seen but still has ~800 games in the database. Black's bishop has really not much to do on  g7  . }
7. Be2
{ White's main thing to remember here is avoiding all exchanges and preventing ...e5. Be2 avoids exchanges after ...Bf5. }
7... Bg7 8. h3
{ The most precise move, stopping ...Bg4 before developing the knight and again avoiding any exchanges. }
8... O-O 9. Ngf3 Bf5 10. O-O Ne4 11. Re1
{ Black's problem is the bishops, one of which is looking at the b2-d4 wall while the other one is shooting into open space. White should swap knights at some point, play Nfd2 and f4. The key is to prevent the ...e5 break. White can play on the kingside while not worrying about the minority attack because the bishop is controlling  b8  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Tricky Move Order: 5...Bf5, 7...Bd6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6
{ Black could also start with the light-squared bishop even here, but it's not clear what he could gain by not playing ...Nc6 at some point e. g.   4...Bf5  5.c3  and eventually ...Nc6 will appear. }
5. c3 Bf5
{ Black played the most direct move order with 3... cxd4 and 4... Nc6 and now goes for a quick 5... Bf5, keeping the king's knight back. In German this sort of strategy is called with the fabulous name 'Königsspringerzüruckhaltungspolitik'. Black's idea is to either go for a quick ...Bd6 and then to develop the knight to  e7  , leaving open the possibility to potentially expand with ...f6, ...g5, ...h5 etc. or even try the direct ...f6 or ...Nge7. }
6. Nd2 e6 7. Ngf3 { Knights first. } 7... Bd6 { Played in ~650 games. } 8. Bxd6
{ White has nothing better to swap it off. } 8... Qxd6 9. Bb5
{ Pinning the knight and intending Ne5. White could also try the thematic   9.Nh4  . }
9... a6
{ Black's first interesting option is to challenge the bishop immediately. Notice that if   9...Nf6  10.Ne5  is similar to the main lines and   9...f6  10.Nh4  . }
10. Bxc6+ Qxc6 { If  10...bxc6  11.Nb3  intending to occupy the c5-outpost. }
11. Ne5 Qb6
{ Black has to put the Queen somewhere. If it goes to the b-file, White can play Nb3 and a4-a5. However, if to c7, then White can play g4. }
12. Nb3
{ This is stronger than the immediate g4 which, however, can also be tried, following Nb3 next as in   12.g4  Bg6  13.Nb3  with the idea of h4-h5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Tricky Move Order: 5...Bf5, 7...Bd6, 9...Ne7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3 Bf5 6. Nd2 e6 7. Ngf3 Bd6 8.
Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Bb5 Ne7 { Black's original plan and the best move. } 10. Nh4
{ Only 3  (!)  games have made it here. } 10... Bg6 11. O-O
{ White's most flexible option is to actually castle first and await developments. The bishop is not going anywhere and can be always taken off later. The position is rare and unexplored. However, note that if  11...a6  12.Be2  and White can even play Re1, Bf1, g3 and fianchetto the bishop later.   On the other hand, if Black tries to force the issue with  11...Nf5  12.Nxg6  is the correct move. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Black's Idea: Rudolf Spielmann vs. Aron Nimzowitsch, 1923"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Bf4
{ We've now transposed to a Londonesque position. } 5... Bf5 6. Nf3 e6 7. Qb3
Qd7 8. Nbd2 f6
{ An interesting, and, at the time, probably a non-standard idea. Nimzowitsch: 'This move secures the e5 square and prepares for a general advance on the wing. A strategic diversion here is justified, as his own center pawns appear reasonably secure, for e6 is well covered and the diagonal from f5 to b1 makes a pretty picture. That a flank attack, when your own center is insecure, is inadmissible, we have emphasized already more than once.' }
9. Be2
{ 9.c4  Nimzowitsch gave this move as best, but that's mistaken.  9...Bb4   9...dxc4  10.Nxc4  g5  11.Be3  Bb4+  12.Nfd2  Nge7∓  10.cxd5  exd5  11.Bb5   9.h4!  The only move to maintain a rough balance. }
9... g5 10. Bg3 h5 11. h3 Nge7 12. O-O { White castles into it. } 12... Bh6
{ This throws away a lot of the Black advantage.   12...g4 } 13. Ne1 { 13.Qd1 }
13... g4 14. Qd1 Bxd2
{ Nimzowitsch: 'This wins a pawn.'   14...gxh3!  This was much better, opening up the kingside immediately.  15.Bxh5+   15.gxh3  h4  Ng6 }
15. Qxd2 gxh3 16. Nd3 b6 { Stopping Nc5.   16...hxg2 } 17. Rfe1 h4 18. Bh2 Kf7
19. g4 hxg3 20. Bxg3 h2+ 21. Kg2 Be4+
{ 21...e5!  Nimzowitsch gave the following variation as a cleaner win.  22.dxe5  Be4+  23.f3  Rag8   23...Qh3+  24.e6+  Qxe6  25.Nf4  Qg4 }
22. Bf3 Nf5 { 22...Bxf3+  23.Kxf3  Rag8 } 23. Bxe4 dxe4 24. Nf4
{ 24.Rxe4  Qd5 } 24... e5 25. Ne2 Nh4+ 26. Bxh4 Qg4+ { With a mate in 6. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Tricky Move Order: 7...f6!?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3 Bf5 6. Nd2 e6 7. Ngf3 f6
{ Black can also try this idea, reminiscent of the Spielmann vs Nimzowitsch game we just looked at. It's the third most common move with ~75 games. On master level it's been played by Grandelius. }
8. Nh4
{ The logical human move, inviting complications. This has been played 15 times.   8.Nb3  This is one of the engine's top choices, but as of yet it is unplayed and it's also not particularly intuitive.  8...g5  No credit for other moves.   8...Bd6?!  9.Bxd6  Qxd6  10.Nh4  Bg6  11.Qe2!  Preparing a quick O-O-O!  9.Bg3  h5  Consistent.  10.h4  g4  11.Ng1  Intending Ne2.  11...Be4  The best move, but this is just engine chess, and practically quite irrelevant.  12.Ne2  A good place to stop. This position remains irrelevant unless we actually start seeing this in practice soon. }
8... g5
{ Black's best move, played 5 times and now...surprisingly, not a single White player has found the correct reply. Notice that if   9...Bg6  10.Nxg6  hxg6  11.Bd3  +/-  and if   9...Nge7  10.Nxf5  Nxf5  11.g4!  Nh4  12.Qe2  with a quick  O-O-O  next and a resulting nice edge. }
9. Qh5+ Kd7 10. g4 { What next? } 10... Bxg4
{ Lc0 likes this for Black.   10...Bc2  Stockfish likes this better.  11.Rc1  gxf4  12.Rxc2  Qe8  13.Qxe8+  Rxe8  14.Rg1  With a messy position. }
11. Qxg4 gxf4 12. Bb5 Qb6 13. Bxc6+ Qxc6
{ If  13...bxc6?  14.O-O-O!  Re8  15.Rhe1  Qd8  16.Nb3!  and White will put the knight into its perfect c5-outpost with a serious advantage. }
14. O-O-O
{ White will play Kb1 and then centralize the other rook and have an edge with also the practically easier position to play due to Black's king still being in the center. }
