[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Apeldoorn Variation: 5...f6!?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3 f6
{ Black can try the ...f6 idea even earlier. This is known as the Apeldoorn variation, preparing both ...e5 and expansion with ...g5 and ...h5. }
6. Nf3
{ Controlling e5. White should avoid the tempting  6.Bd3  e5!  7.Qh5+  g6  8.Bxg6  hxg6  9.Qxh8  exf4  10.Qxg8  Bf5  which leaves Black with a bishop pair and ready to go for the exposed White king at the cost of an exchange. White has not won a single game at master level in this line. }
6... g5 { If  6...Bg4  7.Bb5  Qb6  8.Qe2  g5  9.Bg3  h5  10.h3  Bxf3  11.gxf3 }
7. Be3 { It's important NOT to retreat to the stereotypical g3! } 7... Bf5
{ This is needed so as not to allow Bd3. If  7...Bg7  8.Bd3 } 8. c4
{ The key move! Not a single Lichess nor master game has reached here. } 8...
e6 { If  8...dxc4?  9.d5! } 9. Nc3 { Alternatively,  9.cxd5  followed by Nc3. }
9... Nge7 10. Be2 Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. Rc1
{ White has a nice small edge in an original and unexplored Queen's Gambit style position. He can take on d5 next and then play a3 and h3, Re1, intending to make Black's central pawns his targets one way or another. }
