[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "So System: 6.. e6, 7... Nh5!?, 11...f6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Nd2 e6
{ Black combines the exchange on d4 with e6. This is very common, even though not from this exact move order. }
7. Ngf3 Nh5
{ The 'So System', first seen in full effect in the game Giri vs So, 2012. The point is to drive away the bishop to get the diagonal for Black's own bishop. This was once recommended by GM Jan Gustafsson but he's sort of changed his mind after g4 was found. By now the excitement about this line is generally somewhat died down. Lichess: ~6000 games.   Notice that if Black plays something tame like ...Bd6 white can continue with the standard London plan of Bg3, Bd3, Ne5, f4, O-O etc. while benefitting from the open e-file. For example   7...Bd6  8.Bg3  O-O  9.Bd3  Re8  10.Ne5  with f4 next. }
8. Be3
{ It's best to retreat the bishop. If  8.Bg5  f6  and Black gets in a move he frequently wants to play in this line anyway. }
8... Bd6 9. Ne5
{ Attacking the knight with some hidden tactical points. Notice that if  9...Nxe5  10.dxe5!  and White will simply win a piece.   If  9...Bxe5  10.dxe5  g6  11.Be2  and White is dominating. }
9... g6
{ Black protects the knight. Notice that if something limp like  9...Nf6  10.f4  and White has total control over e5. }
10. g4
{ Making the game dynamic by attacking the knight and expanding on the kingside! }
10... Ng7
{ Again, if instead  10...Nf6  11.f4  and White is control of the position   or even the engine choice  10...Nf6  11.g5!?  For more see the model game Naroditsky-Smirnov }
11. h4 f6
{ Black's first option is to use the f-pawn to try to push ...e5. This is statistically the least common. }
12. Nxc6
{ We obviously do not retreat and take the opportunity to destroy Black's structure. }
12... bxc6 13. Bd3 e5 { Black follows his plan. } 14. dxe5 fxe5 15. h5
{ Threatening to take on g6. } 15... e4 { Natural, but this doesn't work. } 16.
Nxe4 dxe4 17. Bxe4 Bb7 18. hxg6 Qe7 19. Qa4
{ White has an unstoppable attack. He will take on  h7  and castle long when all of his pieces are in prime positions and Black's king is in extreme danger. }
*

