[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "So System: 11...Nxe5, 13...O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Nd2 e6 7. Ngf3 Nh5 8.
Be3 Bd6 9. Ne5 g6 10. g4 Ng7 11. h4 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. h5 O-O
{ The only alternative move. } 14. f4
{ I like this better than the also natural  14.Nf3  . } 14... Bf6
{ Black is threatening ...Bh4+, disrupting White's coordination. If instead  14...Bc7  15.Qf3  followed by hxg6, O-O-O, and Qh3, in some order. }
15. hxg6
{ An important move, setting a little trap we saw in the tactics section. If Black now wants to throw in the check he will get punished  15...Bh4+?  16.Rxh4!  Qxh4+  17.Bf2  and after the Queen moves we will open the h-file with gxh7+. }
15... fxg6 16. Nf3
{ Now we prevent the check. White has a dynamic attacking position. Perhaps the computer can equalize, but for a human it won't be easy to find the exact sequence of moves. Stockfish gives:  16...e5  17.Nxe5  Ne6  18.Qd2  Bh4+  19.Kd1  Bg3!!  20.Kc2  Qd6 =  , but I dare to say nobody will play this unless they've done their research and memorized the line. For more, see the model game Cornette vs Xu. }
*

