1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Nd2 e6 7. Ngf3 Nh5 8.
Be3 Bd6 9. Ne5 g6 10. g4 Ng7 11. h4 h5
{ The more human move, stopping h5, and also the most statistically likely with ~70 games. }
12. Bg5 { Black can react with ...Be7, ...Qc7, or ...Qb6. } 12... Be7
{ A natural reaction, but now White has all the threats and Black can make a mistake on every step. Obviously bad is   12...f6  13.Nxg6!  followed by retreating the bishop to  e3  . }
13. Bb5 { Pinning the attacked knight. } 13... Bd7
{ Black has an opportunity to go wrong by taking the pawn with  13...Bxg5  14.hxg5  Qxg5  15.Qa4  and White has a huge advantage due to the attack on  c6  and Black's issues with king safety. }
14. Bxc6 Bxc6
{ Black can make a mistake with  14...bxc6  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  16.Nb3  and White will put the other knight into the nice c5-outpost }
15. Qf3 { Threatening mate. } 15... Rf8
{ Black can go wrong by castling  15...O-O  16.gxh5!  Opening the g-file  16...Nxh5  17.O-O-O  and White will play  Rdg1  next with a strong attack }
16. gxh5 { Or  16.Bh6 } 16... Bxg5
{ Black can go wrong by taking on  h5  16...Nxh5?  17.Bh6 } 17. hxg5 Nxh5 18.
Qe3
{ Protecting the pawn. White is doing well. The knight on  e5  is dominating the  c6  -bishop and we can always consider Nxc6 or O-O-O and breaking through with Nf1 to Ng3. }
