1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Nd2 e6 7. Ngf3 Nh5 8.
Be3 g6
{ This novel move was recently recommended by NM Bryan Tillis in his Aggressive QGD course. It's been played ~150 times and Black seems to score pretty well. }
9. Be2 f6
{ Black has mostly played ...Bd6 here which can be met with just O-O, e. g.  9...Bd6  10.O-O  Nf4  11.Bb5  Only three games have reached this position. }
10. g4
{ I like this move which is similar to the main line, gaining kingside space. An alternatively good way of playing is  10.O-O  Ng7  11.Bd3  Bd6  12.Re1  O-O  13.Rc1  , followed by c4 to open up the position. }
10... Ng7 11. Qc2
{ Tillis gives instead the mysterious 11. Bf4. I suggest you play this natural move, preparing O-O-O, followed by Kb1 and h4 with a safe edge. Black has a wide choice of moves, but none of it amounts to more than maneuvering on the first two ranks so we can just continue with our plan. }
