1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 cxd4
{ Black can also play the Exchange Caro from a different move order. This is quite rare, but it does give him some extra options and needs a separate response. }
6. exd4 Bf5
{ Black attempts to transpose to the new main line with White committed to Nf3 instead of c3, without ...Qb6 available. }
7. Bb5
{ Hello! Intending c4 in one move. This is about 10x rarer than c3. Here we basically have to check 4 different moves.   7.c3  This is what would allow Black to play the annoying  7...e6  with 8...Bd6 or 7...a6. }
7... a6
{ Surely some people will try this move.   7...Rc8  This move puts no particular pressure on White.  8.O-O  e6  9.c3 }
8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. c4 dxc4 10. Nxc4
{ White accepts the IQP. In return, Black has a destroyed Queenside structure. }
10... e6 11. O-O Be7 12. Nfe5 *

