[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "2...Nf6, 6...Bf5 with ...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5 7. Bb5 e6
{ Overwhelmingly the most common move @@StartBracket@@~85 games@@EndBracket@@. This was played in Aronian vs. Inarkiev in the World Blitz Championship 2019 and has been recommended by GM Alex Colovic in his LTR: Queen's Gambit Declined. }
8. Ne5 Qb6
{ 8...Rc8?  This is a mistake that is about as popular as ...Qb6.  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.Ba6  Traps the rook. }
9. c4 { Now things get sharp. } 9... Qxd4
{ This is the critical move, but it hasn't been played in a single game.   9...dxc4  Inarkiev's move, also recommended by Colovic  10.Bxc6+  bxc6  11.Ndxc4  Qa6  12.Qe2  Bb4+  13.Bd2  Bxd2+  14.Qxd2  Keeping the Queens on for the moment with interesting play.  Colovic gives  14...O-O  and now  15.Qa5!  is a very interesting try to push the action since Black will need to find the best move so as not to be immediately worse... }
10. Nxc6 Qxf4 11. g3
{ The point is to force the Queen off away so that White gets the d4 square for the knight. }
11... Qd6 12. Nd4+ Nd7 13. O-O Be7 14. Nxf5 exf5 15. c5
{ With the simple idea to sacrifice a pawn to keep Black's king in the center or disconnect Black's Queen from his bishop and thereby prevent castling. }
15... Qc7 { 15...Qxc5  16.Bxd7+  Kxd7  17.Rc1  White is already winning. } 16.
Re1 Kf8 17. Rc1 { With a clear edge to White. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "2...Nf6 with 6...Qb6, 7...Bf5, 8...e6?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 cxd4 6. exd4 Qb6
{ Black's extra option from this move order, attacking d4 and b2, played 446 times and 41 times at master level. This wouldn't make any sense if c3 was played instead of Nf3. However, even here it's dubious since the Queen gets in the way of Black's thematic minority attack with the b-pawn. }
7. Nb3 { Natural, blocking b2 and defending d4. } 7... Bf5
{ The less common option, played ~100+ times in Lichess and about 10 times at Master level. However, it was tried against Carlsen by both Kramnik and Wang Hao in 2019. }
8. a4
{ Pieces on b6 and g6 frequently 'attract' the a- and h-pawns, due to the gained tempo. White's threat is pushing the pawn to a5 with tempo and then a6, and Black really can't allow that to happen. This move is a huge improvement over Sedlak's 8. c3 and is more similar to his line against ...Bg4. }
8... e6 { Let's see what happens when Black is clueless. } 9. a5 Qd8
{ Obviously not  9...Qb4+?  10.c3  Qe7  11.a6  . } 10. a6 Qb6
{ The Queen is forced to return. Everything else loses real fast. For example, if  10...bxa6??  11.Rxa6  is suicide due to Bb5.   If  10...b6  11.Bb5  is similarly lights out. }
11. c3 { White is in no rush to take the pawn on b7. } 11... Be7
{ A natural move but it loses. Black's best is  11...Ne4  12.axb7  Qxb7  13.Ba6  Qb6  14.O-O  and White is positionally dominant. }
12. Nc5 Bxc5 { If instead  12...bxa6  13.Rxa6  Qxb2  14.Rxc6  . } 13. dxc5 Qxb2
{ If  13...Qxc5  14.axb7!  and White is winning due to his control of  b8  . }
14. axb7 Qxb7 15. Ba6 Qb2 16. O-O O-O 17. Qa4
{ White is completely winning since the knight can't be defended and the Queen is equally in trouble. }
*

