[White "4. Exchange Caro-Kann"]
[Black "2...Nf6 with 6...Qb6, 7...Bf5, 8...a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 cxd4 6. exd4 Qb6 7. Nb3 Bf5 8.
a4 a6
{ As we have seen, Black has to stop the march of the a-pawn. However, he should do it without giving up the b5-square with  8...a5 ?!  9.Bb5 }
9. a5 Qd8 10. Ne5
{ Several master games have reached here, but nobody has played this, best move, yet, preferring to develop the bishop first. White threatens to take on c6 and Black should NOT react to this. }
10... e6
{ Best move. If  10...Nxe5?  11.dxe5  Nd7  12.Nd4  Bg6  13.e6!   Or  10...Nxe5?  11.dxe5  Nd7  12.Nd4  Be6  13.Nxe6  fxe6  14.g3  intending Bh3. }
11. Nxc6
{ It's strongest to take off the knight and ruin Black's structure first. }
11... bxc6 12. Bd3
{ White doesn't have to go for this and could instead keep the pieces on the board and play  12.c3  Be7  13.Be2  O-O  14.O-O  with a slight edge. But the text has a more concrete idea which it is nice to see. }
12... Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Be7 14. Qc3
{ White supports the knight jump to c5. If Black takes, we take with the Queen and prevent them from castling. }
