{ Trying to embarrass the bishop. } 13... Nxe5
{ A sad necessity since any move of the h-pawn will be met by Nxg6! } 14. dxe5
{ Here Black will most likely lose material. Unless they find... } 14... Qc7
{ The only move, simultaneously x-raying the bishop, in case of exf6, and attacking the c2-pawn. But who would find this without engine help? }
15. Qd4 { Protecting the bishop and renewing the threat. } 15... Nxg4 16. f3
Nh6 17. h5 Bf5 18. Qa4+ Qd7 19. Nd4
{ This was instructive, but you'll never see this in live play. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. The Tricky 4...Qb6?!, 5...Bf5, 5...Bg4"]
[Black "4...Qb6: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5
{ We'll look at the ...Qb6 lines from this move order because Black can try combining it with both ...Nc6 & ...Nf6 }
3. e3 Nf6
{ 3...Nc6  Combining ...Nc6 and ...Qb6 is even worse for Black  4.Nf3!  One of the reasons for the Two Knights is exactly that it makes an early ...Qb6 a mistake for Black.  4...Qb6?  5.Nc3!  Attacking d5 and threatening Nb5. All natural moves lose to one of these threats.  5...Qa5  This is Stockfish's choice, pinning the knight, but if moving the Queen again is best then you know something must've gone wrong for Black...   5...Nf6  Protecting d5  6.Nb5  e5  7.Nxe5  a6  Black attacks the knight and thinks it will save him, but...  8.Nc4!  The key move  8...dxc4  9.Nc7+  Ke7  10.Nxa8  Qxb2  11.Be2  Qc3+  12.Kf1  cxd4  13.Rb1  6.dxc5  Nf6  7.Bb5 }
4. Nf3 Qb6
{ Black could also try to throw in the Exchange Caro exchange first with  4...cxd4  5.exd4  Qb6  but it won't do him much good since White can choose between playing in the spirit of this chapter with  6.Nc3  or in the next with  6.Nbd2  . For more, see the model gameRosen vs. Agdestein. }
5. Nc3
{ Same remedy, though this is better for Black since the d-pawn is already protected. }
5... Qxb2
{ Consistent, but bad. Nevertheless, we'll take this as the main line since you need to know the refutation   5...c4!  Up until recently, this seemed like the only way to play this position and not be immediately worse, but see below  6.e4!?  This is the more exciting option, played only 4 times  (!)  (compared to Rb1: 261 times)  . White opens up the center and makes possible the retreat Bd2.  6...Nxe4  7.Nxd5  Qa5+  8.Nc3  Nxc3  9.bxc3  Be6   9...Qxc3+  10.Bd2  Qa3  11.Bxc4  is practically losing for Black  10.Be2   5...e6  6.Nb5  Na6  7.c3  White sets up the typical Queenside bind with a4 next   5...Bd7!?  is Nakamura's new try, see the trainable line   5...a6  is also possible. See the trainable line. }
6. Nb5 Na6 7. a3
{ A typical move in these poisoned pawn variations, taking away a3 from the Queen and threatening to trap it   7.Rb1  Objectively worse, but an easy-to-remember Blitz alternative  7...Qxa2  8.Ra1  Qb2  9.Rxa6  bxa6  10.Nc7+  Kd8  11.Ng5 }
7... Bf5 { The only move since  7...e6??  8.Rb1  Qa2  9.Qc1  traps the Queen. }
8. dxc5 { The point will soon be revealed. } 8... Bxc2 9. Qc1 Qxc1+ 10. Rxc1
Bf5
{ If  10...Bg6  11.c6  bxc6   11...b6  12.c7  12.Rxc6   If  10...Be4  11.c6 }
11. Nbd4 { Threatening Nxf5, Bb5+ and c6. White is completely winning. } *

