[White "5. The Tricky 4...Qb6?!, 5...Bf5, 5...Bg4"]
[Black "4...Nh5??"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nh5
{ This thematic bishop-hunting move can't be played this early...  ~40 games in the database  . However, the precise refutation is not totally clear cut and contains some pitfalls for White. }
5. Bxb8
{ We start with this surprising retort, removing the knight that can block the check by Bb5+. }
5... Rxb8 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. Ne5 { Discovered attack. } 8... Qf5
{ The only defense. As we saw in the tactics section, counterattacking with ...Qb5 leads to mate  8...Qb5??  9.Qxh5+  Qxb2  10.Qxf7+  Kd8  11.Qxd5+  Kc7  12.Qd7+  Kb6  13.Nc4+  Ka6  14.Qa4# }
9. c3
{ Opening the diagonal for the Queen. The only game in the database continued with the tempting  9.g4??  and White won, but should've lost after the simple  9...Qe4!  , counterattacking the rook. }
9... Nf6 10. Qa4+ Nd7 11. Qxa7 Rd8 12. Nxd7 { Simplest. } 12... Qxd7 13. Qxc5
e6 14. Qb6
{ White is up 2 pawns in a simplified position and completely winning. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. The Tricky 4...Qb6?!, 5...Bf5, 5...Bg4"]
[Black "5...Bf5: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6
{ 2...c5  3.e3  Nc6  4.Nf3  Bf5  From this move order developing the bishop early is ok and it's been played close to a 1000x. Just remember, whenever ...Bf5 appears, just take the c-pawn  5.dxc5!  e6  6.Nd4  Bxc5  7.Nxf5  exf5  8.c3  Similar to the main line since Black will not benefit from avoiding ...Nf6. }
3. e3 c5 4. Nf3
{ Against the alternative c3, ...Bf5 is much stronger, which is the second reason to prefer the two knights.   4.c3  Nc6  5.Nd2  Bf5  The most common move from this move order  6.dxc5   6.Ngf3  Qb6  This just ain't pleasant for White.   6.Qb3  Qd7  7.Ngf3  c4  Again, not pleasant for White.  e5!  White isn't controlling e5 and Black can get this break in. }
4... Nc6
{ 4...Bf5??  From this move order it's a blunder, but it's still been played a whopping 800 times.  5.dxc5  In the database White has only reacted properly here less than 100x. The point is that with the 'wrong knight' developed it'll be very hard for Black to get the pawn back because...  5...e6?   5...Nc6  6.Bb5  Bd7  7.c3  e6  8.b4  6.Bxb8!  Rxb8  7.Bb5+  Ke7  8.b4 }
5. Nbd2 Bf5
{ The second most common move in the position, with 2000 games. It was recommended by Logozar in his Crush the London @@StartBracket@@Chessable, 2019@@EndBracket@@ , but I think it's quite dubious. }
6. dxc5
{ White can grab the pawn due to the Nf3 providing extra control over and thereby preventing the reply ...e5. Again, White has reacted correctly like this in only 1/4th of the games  (~500x)  . }
6... e6
{ 6...Qa5  This has been tried a couple of times, but just  7.Nd4!  Bg4  8.f3  Bd7  9.Nb3  White keeps the pawn  9...Qd8  10.Bg3  e5  A mistake, but will probably be tried   10...e6  11.Bd3  11.Bb5 }
7. Nd4 Bxc5
{ The only move basically not to lose   7...Nxd4?  8.exd4  White keeps the pawn.   7...Bg6?  8.Bb5  Rc8  9.b4  Again, White keeps the pawn.   7...Bg4?  8.f3  Bh5  9.Bb5  And yet again, White keeps the pawn. }
8. Nxf5 exf5 9. c3
{ Important, controlling the center. White scores much better here both in the Lichess database and on Master level, due to his better structure and two bishops. However, things can get a little tricky so there are a few things you must know. Logozar comments:      @@StartBlockQuote@@White has a static advantage, and Black has a dynamic advantage. Don't count the pawn structure only as White's positional advantage, in isolated queen pawn positions the IQP often gives space and dynamics @@StartBracket@@due to the space and possibly outposts@@EndBracket@@ which can be weighed against a possible endgame with minors traded with chances for both sides. The same is true here. White has the bishop pair, but Black has a lead in development. I don't think there is any objective reason to claim that White has an advantage here, and in the small sample size of games that have been played here, Black has a small plus score. In comments on The London System: Essential Theory. @@EndBlockQuote@@I think he's mistaken both in his evaluation and, by now, also about the statistics. }
9... O-O
{ The main move, played only 43 times...   9...Bd6  Trying to split the bishop pair into half, but we can comply  10.Bg5!  O-O  11.g3!  White is playing against the IQP and has ample time to fianchetto the bishop like in the main line of the Tarrasch Defence.  11...Be7  12.Bxf6  Bxf6  13.Bg2  The IQP is a big target.   9...Ne4  Black should castle first  10.Nxe4  fxe4   10...dxe4  11.g4!!  A beautiful novelty courtesy of Stockfish 12. For more, see the trainable line.  11.Be2  O-O  12.Qb3  Qd7  13.O-O-O  Rfd8  14.Kb1  Rac8  15.f3 }
10. Be2
{ White's best, played only 12 @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ times   10.Bd3?  One thing White needs to know is to avoid this, more common move  10...d4  11.exd4  Bxd4  12.cxd4  Qxd4  13.Qf3  Rfe8+   13...Nd5 }
10... Ne4
{ Overwhelmingly the most common move in the database, Black aims for an attack with ...g4 etc. but it simply doesn't work as long as White remembers to...   10...Qd7  This restrained move is the engine's top choice and the only one which doesn't leave him with an immediately worse position. It hasn't been played in a single game!  11.Bg5  Be7  12.Bxf6  Bxf6  13.O-O  With g3 next. For more, see the trainable line. }
11. Nxe4
{ Chop the knight! White doesn't havet to worry about fixing Black's doubled pawns since he gets an advantage elsewhere. }
11... dxe4 { 11...fxe4  12.Qb3  Transposes to above. } 12. Qb3 Qe7 13. O-O-O
Rad8 14. h4
{ This is an interesting suggestion by Stockfish, aiming to secure the bishop on f4 by pushing the pawn to h5, and not minding sacrificing it. }
14... Rxd1+ { 14...h6  15.h5 } 15. Rxd1 Qxh4 16. g3
{ This is better than Bg3, which can also be played. Let's continue the line so you see the main ideas and resources in White's position. }
16... Qe7 17. Qd5 { Centralizing the Queen with a tempo on the f-pawn. } 17...
g6 18. b4
{ Who exactly is playing dynamically here? For the rest, see the trainable line. }
