[Black "9...Ne4?!, 10...dxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bf5 6. dxc5 e6 7. Nd4 Bxc5 8.
Nxf5 exf5 9. c3 Ne4
{ The immediate knight jump doesn't work. Just remember, whenever it appears... }
10. Nxe4 { Chop it off! } 10... dxe4
{ One possible recapture, but this practically loses after the novelty... } 11.
g4
{ Oh yeah baby! This move does it all. We attack Black's pawn and likely split them in half, prepare the fianchetto, force the simplification with ...Qxd1, Rxd1, giving us control of the open file, and on top of it all we get the open g-file to work with. What more can you ask for from a single move!   11.Bc4  can also be played with the line continuing with  11...Qe7  12.Qd5!  g6  13.Bg5  f6  14.Bxf6  Qxf6  15.Qxc5  , but the text is far more powerful. }
11... Qxd1+
{ Black doesn't have any better since if  11...fxg4  12.Qxg4  and White is going to play  Rd1  and has the open g-file. If Black doesn't capture the Queen nor the pawn White will just grab it with gxf5. }
12. Rxd1 fxg4 13. Bg2
{ This is the idea. White will get the central pawn and have the open g-file and the two bishops to work with in the endgame. As we saw in the tactics section, holding on to the pawn with  13...f5??  is just met with  14.Rd5  forking the bishop and the pawn. So Black will likely play ...Rad1 after which White can play Bxe4 and then go after the g-pawn with Rg1. }
*

