[Black "5...Bg4 7. Qa4?!: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6
{ Another possible independent move order is  2...c5  3.e3  Nc6  4.Nf3  Bg4  and here White should just play  5.c3  where Black's only real independent option is  5...Qb6  6.Nbd2!  Qxb2  7.Rb1  Qxc3  8.Bb5!  Bd7  9.Ba4  and White is winning due to the threat of  Rxb7  . Black could also try 5...e6 which either leads to Exchange Caro or main line again. }
3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bg4
{ Black's other bishop development. This is the third most popular move in this position with ~2000 games from this move order. But there are more from the 'Triangle' move order. }
6. c3 e6
{ The most common move, this position has been reached in ~7200+ games. } 7.
Qa4
{ This Cambridge Springs style move is only the 6th  (!)  most popular move in this position  (2nd most common in Master play)  , but I think it is, practically speaking, the best. The idea is to build up pressure on c6 with Bb5 and Ne5 next and Black has to play very precisely so as not to get killed.   I give the more positional main move  7.Qb3  as an alternative. It's simple to play and therefore good to know and I recommend you try both. }
7... Bd6
{ The most common move and a mistake, played in ~150 games   7...Nd7  The third most common move in Lichess, but the most common move at Master level, perhaps on analogy with the old Cambridge Springs main line. Black just blocks the pin and controls e5.  8.Bb5  Amping up the pressure  8...Qb6  Black's most common move  9.Ne5  Surprisingly, not the most common White move, showing again that White players frequently don't know the lines well  9...Ndxe5  10.dxc5!  An important intermediate move, attacking the Queen and intending to recapture on e5 with an attack on the loose bishop. This has never  (!)  been played in Lichess and only once on master level  10...Bxc5  Natural, but not best   10...Nd3+!  The best move, played once on master level.  11.Bxd3  Qxb2  12.Rb1  White played 12. O-O here in Hernandez Carmenates vs Vazques, 2017 in a game which started out as a Trompowsky attack and ended in a draw  12...Qxc3  13.Bb5  Sedlak's move  13...Rc8  14.O-O  Calmly offering a piece. Black shouldn't take it, but  14...Qxd2??  15.Bxc6+  An instructive tactical sequence  15...bxc6  16.Rb8  Rxb8  17.Qxc6+  Ke7  18.Qd6+  Kf6  19.Qe5+  Ke7  20.Qxb8  Black is helpless against the march of the c-pawn.  11.Bxe5  Bh5  12.g4!  Attacking the bishop once more to force it to move, blocking the g-file.  12...Bg6  13.Bxg7  Rg8  14.Bd4  White is up a pawn and has continued pressure.   7...Bxf3!  Sedlak and and Stockfish give this as Black's best move after which it's equal. It's the second most common move. However, practically White still scores well from here.  8.Nxf3  a6  Preventing Bb5.  9.Ne5  Rc8  10.Nxc6  Qd7  11.Be2  with an equal, but playable game. }
8. Ba6
{ A famous London trap. Imagine your opponent's face if he sees this appear on the board... }
8... bxa6
{ 8...Bxf4??  16 games have seen this move and White has a 100% score :  9.Bxb7  O-O  10.Qxc6!   8...Rb8  9.Bxb7  Rxb7  10.Qxc6+  Qd7  11.Qxd6   8...Qa5  This is the best Black can do here  9.Qxa5  Nxa5  10.Bxd6  bxa6  11.Bxc5  White's up a pawn with a nice position. }
9. Qxc6+ Ke7 10. Qb7+ Qd7 11. Bxd6+ Kxd6 12. Qxa6+ Ke7 13. Ne5 Qc8 14. Qa3
{ White is simply winning. } *

