1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Qa4 Nd7 8. Bb5
Qb6 9. Ne5 Ndxe5 10. dxc5 Nd3+
{ Black's best move, but quite unlikely. It has been played once at master level. }
11. Bxd3 Qxb2
{ The only principled move. If  11...Bxc5?  12.b4  Be7  13.b5  Qa5  14.Qc2  Nb8  15.e4 }
12. Rb1
{ White played  12.O-O  here in Hernandez Carmenates vs Vazques, 2017, a game which started out as a Trompowsky attack and ended in a draw. }
12... Qxc3 13. Bb5
{ Stockfish actually likes  13.Ba6  Qa5  14.Bb5  Qxa4  15.Bxa4  O-O-O  16.Bxc6  bxc6  17.Rb8+  Kd7  18.Rb7+  Ke8  19.Bc7  Ra8  20.Nb3  and White is down a pawn, but in complete control of the position. }
13... Rc8 { If  13...Qxc5  14.O-O } 14. O-O { Calmly offering a piece. } 14...
Qxd2
{ Black shouldn't take it, but after  14...Be7  15.Nb3  White is holding the reigns. }
15. Bxc6+ { An instructive tactical sequence. } 15... bxc6 16. Rb8 Rxb8 17.
Qxc6+ Ke7 18. Qd6+ Kf6 19. Qe5+
{ Forcing the king back to e7, blocking the bishop. } 19... Ke7 20. Qxb8
{ Black is helpless against the march of the c-pawn. } *

