[White "5. The Tricky 4...Qb6?!, 5...Bf5, 5...Bg4"]
[Black "5...Bg4, 7. Qb3: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Qb3
{ Somehow this is only the second most common move in the position, but it's most common at Master level. }
7... Qc8
{ 7...Qb6  Overwhelmingly most common in Lichess with ~1100 games, but it's almost a mistake here since you can just take it off and play Bb5. A general rule: when there's a Qb3 and ...Qb6 face-off, taking is good when the opponent hasn't blocked the bishop's diagonal, bad otherwise.  8.Qxb6  axb6  9.Bb5  Bxf3  Stockfish's unintuitive move, giving up the bishop for no apparent gain.   9...Nd7  10.Ne5  Ndxe5  11.Bxe5  O-O-O  12.Bg3  10.Nxf3  Ne4!  The point ! The knight uses the tempo to go to d6 and break the pin. A human would only play this if they've prepared it at home. There are no games in the Lichess database and only one game in the master database that has reached here.  11.Bd3  Nd6  12.Ke2  c4  13.Bc2  b5  14.a3 }
8. Nh4
{ Sedlak's choice, with the idea to play h3, g4 and then win the bishop for the knight. Lichess has exactly 1  (!)  game in this line... }
8... Be7
{ This developing move illustrates how White's idea works.   8...Qd7  Several GM's have chosen this move in this position. The point is to play ...Bd6 and ...O-O-O.  9.h3  Bh5  10.g4  Bg6  11.dxc5  Shimanov's and later also Tikkanen's choice, the point is to play O-O-O  11...Bxc5  12.O-O-O  O-O-O  13.Nxg6  Shimanov went for   13.Bb5  in Shimanov - Cox, 1-0, 2016. Sedlak recommends this move instead which was later played by Tikkanen in Tikkanen - Blomqvist, 1-0, 2018.  13...hxg6  14.g5  Ne8  15.c4  Bd6  16.Bxd6  Qxd6  17.Bg2  Nc7  18.Kb1  It's +/=, but White's g2-bishop is the best minor piece on the board.   8...h6  The trickiest move, setting up the fork on , but it's never been played  9.h3  g5  10.Bh2!  Bh5  11.Nhf3  c4  12.Qd1  Be7  13.Be2  The idea is to play Ne5, trade bishops and then play e4. }
9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 { 10...Nd7  11.Ndf3 } 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Bg2 *

