1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Qb3 {  } 7...
Qb6
{ Overwhelmingly most common in Lichess with ~1100 games, but it's almost a mistake here since you can just take it off and play Bb5.    @@StartBlockQuote@@A general rule: when there's a Qb3 and ...Qb6 face-off, taking is good when the opponent hasn't blocked the bishop's diagonal, bad otherwise.@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
8. Qxb6 axb6 9. Bb5
{ White is in the driver's seat. Another way of playing is with Ne5 first, hitting the bishop. For example,  9.Ne5  Nxe5  10.dxe5  Nd7  11.Bb5  Be7  12.e4  O-O-O  13.O-O  +/=. Black can play several moves here, but the most human and most common is... }
9... Nd7
{ Blocking the pin and anticipating Ne5. Notice that if something like  9...Be7  10.Ne5  O-O-O  11.Bxc6  bxc6  12.f3  Bf5  13.g4  Bg6  14.Nxc6  with taking on  e7  next. }
10. Ne5 { Hitting the knight and the bishop. } 10... Ndxe5 11. Bxe5
{ White gets the two bishops and has an eye on  g7  preventing ...Be7. He also has a target on b6. E. g. if  11...f6  12.Bc7! }
11... O-O-O 12. Bg3 *

