1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Qb3 Qb6 8. Qxb6
axb6 9. Bb5 Bxf3
{ Stockfish's unintuitive move, giving up the bishop for no apparent gain. }
10. Nxf3 Ne4
{ The point! The knight uses e4 to go to d6 and break the pin. A human would only play this if they've prepared it at home and no games in the Lichess database and only one game in the master database have reached here. }
11. Bd3 { Best to retreat the bishop immediately. } 11... Nd6 12. Ke2
{ Activating the king. } 12... c4
{ Gaining a tempo for the Queenside expansion. If  12...Be7  13.a4  . } 13. Bc2
b5 14. a3
{ Stopping ...b4. White is still a bit better and has to figure out how to use his bishop pair. }
