[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. The Tricky 4...Qb6?!, 5...Bf5, 5...Bg4"]
[Black "7. Qb3, Qc8, 8...Be7, 10...Bg6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Qb3 Qc8
{ The better way to protect b7, played only ~240 times. } 8. Nh4
{ Sedlak's choice, with the idea to play  h3  ,  g4  and then win the bishop for the knight. He warns against changing things up with  8.h3  Bh5  9.g4  Bg6  10.Nh4  Ne4!  .   Barrish & Bartholomew give  8.h3  Bh5  9.Nh4  which is similar to what we have.   However, it does allow  8.h3  Bf5!?  9.g4  Bg6  10.Nh4  Be4  11.f3! }
8... Be7
{ This developing move illustrates how White's idea works. Notice that if Black inserts  8...c4  9.Qa4  not much changes and we can still continue with our thematic idea of h3, g4, and Nxg6. }
9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Bg2
{ This position is reminiscent of a one which we've seen in the Exchange Caro-Kann chapterhere. The only difference is that here the central exchange hasn't taken place yet and ...c4 is also a possibility for Black, while White could even hope to play e4 in some variations. Due to these differences, it's better here to fianchetto the bishop, though Be2 can also, of course, be played. In any case, White has an advantage due to his bishop pair. }
