h6 { The trickiest move, setting up the fork on g5. } 9. h3
{ Not minding the fork. } 9... g5
{ Notice that  9...Bxh3  with the idea of taking a pawn and then playing g5 doesn't work due to  10.gxh3  g5  11.Be5! }
10. Bh2 Bh5
{ Again,  10...Bxh3  doesn't work due to  11.gxh3  gxh4  12.dxc5  Bxc5  13.O-O-O  . }
11. Nhf3
{ Sedlak thinks that White has easier play because his pawn structure is healthier. Play could continue... }
11... c4 12. Qd1 Be7 13. Be2
{ The idea is to play Ne5, trade bishops and then play e4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. The Sharp 5...Qb6 and 5...Nh5"]
[Black "5...Qb6, 6...Qxc5?!: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6
{ The critical move and also most common with ~3500 games played  (but it's only the third most popular at master level) }
6. dxc5
{ Forcing Black to react. This is the only move worth considering. Imagine that there were at least ~1200 games where this was NOT played... }
6... Qxc5
{ This is a mistake. Black should take the b-pawn. Played in ~900 games } 7. a3
{ The key move to know. White prepares b4 and stops anything from coming to that square. However, even before we will play c4! This has been played in only 250 games, but in most master-level games which have reached here. }
7... Bg4
{ The most common and best move with ~100 games   7...a5  Stopping b4, but this is way too slow  8.c4  The rook will come to c1 next and Black's Queen is not happy   7...e6  This just let's White carry out his plan e. g.  8.c4  Be7  9.b4   7...Nh5?  This just drops a pawn  8.Nb3  Qb6  9.Qxd5  Nxf4  10.exf4  g6  11.Bc4  Be6  12.Qd3   7...g6  Only 7 games and White has won 6 of them while allowing one draw  8.c4  Bg7  9.b4  Qb6  10.c5  Qd8  11.b5!  No lichess game has featured this move, but there is one master game...  11...Na5  12.Be5  Taking control of the long diagonal  12...O-O  13.Rc1  The only master game in the database continued with  13...a6  14.a4  axb5  15.axb5  Bg4  16.Be2  Ne4  17.Bxg7  Kxg7  18.h3  White played Nxe4 instead, threw away most of his advantage and the game ended in a draw in Rahman - Ragunandhan, 2016   7...Bf5  The second most common option ~70 games. Again, this just lets White carry out his plan  8.c4  e6  9.b4  Qe7   9...Qb6  10.c5  Qd8  11.Bb5  10.Qa4  White wants to play Ne5 next  10...Qd7  11.b5  Ne7  12.Ne5 }
8. Be2 { Natural, best, and easy to remember } 8... e6 9. c4
{ The thematic strike against the centre } 9... dxc4
{ 9...Be7  10.b4  Qb6  11.c5  Qd8  12.h3  Bh5  13.b5  Na5  14.g4  White expands all over the board  14...Bg6  15.c6!  The breakthrough comes before Black can castle   9...a5  10.cxd5   9...Bxf3  10.Bxf3  dxc4  11.Rc1 }
10. Nxc4 Bxf3
{ 10...Rd8  Is actually the only move here that's been played  11.Qb3   10...Be7  11.b4 }
11. gxf3 Rd8
{ 11...Be7  12.b4  Qd5  13.b5  Nd8  14.Nd6+   14.Qb3  14...Bxd6  15.Bxd6 } 12.
Qc2 Be7 13. Rc1
{ White has a nice advantage with the two bishops, a lead in development, and control of the c-file compensating for his damaged structure. He can eventually even hope to use the open g-file. However, in the short run he will castle kingside and expand with b4, play Bg3, and tries to use the extra f-pawn to control the center with f4. }
*

