{ Black attacks both  d4  and  b2  and White has to gambit the b-pawn. } 6.
dxc5 { Forcing Black to react. } 6... Qxc5
{ I'm sure many who don't think about the position deeply will feel like taking this pawn rather than the usually poisoned b-pawn. However, this is a mistake. }
7. a3
{ Preparing b4 and stopping anything from coming to the square. Black can try a multitude of moves here, among which 7... g6 and 7...Bf5 and 7... Bg4 are the most interesting. }
7... Nh5 { This just drops a pawn. } 8. Nb3 Qb6 9. Qxd5 Nxf4 10. exf4 g6
