1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxc5 7. a3 Bg4
{ The most common and best move. } 8. Be2
{ Natural, best, and easy to remember. White could also play as follows  8.c4  e5  9.b4  Qe7  10.Bg5  dxc4  11.h3  Bxf3  12.Qxf3  , but the text seems better. }
8... e6
{ If  8...g6  9.Rc1  Bg7  10.c4  and White is better, and Black better not play  10...O-O  11.b4!  like always. }
9. c4 { The thematic strike against the centre. } 9... dxc4
{ What else can Black do here?   If  9...Be7  10.b4  The usual move  10...Qb6  11.c5  Qd8  12.h3  Bh5  13.O-O  and White has nice space advantage.   If  9...a5  10.Rc1   If  9...Bxf3  10.Bxf3  dxc4  11.Rc1 }
10. Nxc4 Bxf3
{ If instead  10...Rd8  11.Qb3!  is strong.   If  10...Be7  11.b4!  like usual. }
11. gxf3 Rd8
{ One of my games continued with 11...Be7, but this is strongly met by 11. b4   11...Be7?!  12.b4!  Qd5  13.b5!  Nd8  14.Nd6+  Bxd6  15.Bxd6  or just 14. Qb3 }
12. Qc2 Be7 13. Rc1
{ White has a nice advantage with the two bishops, a lead in development, and control of the c-file compensating for his damaged structure. He can eventually even hope to use the open g-file. However, in the short run he will castle kingside and expand with b4, play Bg3, and try to use the extra f-pawn to control the center with f4. }
