[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. The Sharp 5...Qb6 and 5...Nh5"]
[Black "5...Qb6, 6...Qxb2: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2
{ The main move, played ~1500 times and ~160 times at master level } 7. Rb1
{ The only move worth considering, games drop to ~1100 } 7... Qc3
{ The best defense, blocking the c-pawn. The games drop to ~600   7...Qxa2?!  This is far too greedy, but has been played ~400x  8.Bb5  Bd7  Most common   8...e6  Second most common, but now  9.Nb3!!  Black's Queen is never getting out. Here's a funky-looking line where Black tries to use the only square available  9...Qa3  10.Qd4  Qa6  Whoa  11.Qd3  Qa3  12.O-O  Ra1 to Ra4 comes next and the Queen is gone   8...a6  9.Bxc6+  bxc6  10.O-O  White will try to trap Black's Queen  9.c4  e6  10.O-O  Bxc5  Most common  11.Nb3  Bb4  Retreating to e7 loses the Queen on the spot   11...Be7?  12.Bxc6  Bxc6  13.Ra1  12.Bxc6  Removing the defender of e5  12...Bxc6  13.Ra1  Qb2  14.Be5  Bc3  15.Rb1  Black is going to lose something  15...Bxe5   15...Qa3  16.Bxc3  16.Rxb2  Bxb2  17.Na5  White will take on c6 and then d5 with a nice advantage   7...Qa3  This move makes no sense, yet has been played ~150x  8.Bb5  You just play it like usual }
8. Bb5
{ Interestingly, in his 2012 GM Repertoire on the D-Pawn Specials the famous theoretician Boris Avrukh mentioned only Rb3 here and concluded that White is struggling to prove compensation. Subsequently Bb5 was found and he was proven wrong }
8... e6
{ Most common move with ~200 games and overwhelmingly most common at master level with 100+ games compared to less than 10 games in each of the alternative lines   8...Bg4?  This loses  9.Ba4!  We will take on b7. White is already winning. For example  9...Qxc5  10.Rxb7   8...Bf5?  This loses as well  9.O-O !  We don't have to protect the c-pawn !  9...Qxc2   9...Bxc2?  10.Qc1  Qxc5  11.Rb2  10.Qxc2  Bxc2  11.Rb2  Bf5  12.Ba4  We will take on b7 again   8...Bd7  Third most common move with 50 games  9.O-O  e6   9...Qxc5  10.c4  Thematic, but Be2 is also strong  10.Bd3  Again, threatening to take on b7.  10...Bxc5?   10...Bc8  Sad but best. White has a choice here between developing with Qe2, Re1 etc. or breaking with  11.e4  Qxc5  12.c4  dxe4  13.Rb5  Qa3  14.Nxe4  White has excellent compensation  11.Rb3  Qa5  12.Rb5  Qd8  13.Rxc5   8...Qxc5  Second most common move with slightly over 200 games  9.O-O  Completing development first  9...e6  10.c4  The typical break. Black has a variety of moves here.  10...Be7   10...Bd6  11.cxd5  exd5  Black can't allow Ne4  12.Rc1  Qxb5  13.Bxd6  White's down a pawn, but winning   10...Bd7  11.cxd5  exd5  12.Ba4  With Rb5 next   10...a6  11.Bxc6+  bxc6   11...Qxc6  12.Ne5  Qc5  13.Qa4+  Nd7  14.Rfc1  12.Qa4  Or Ne5  12...Bd7  13.Ne5  Qa3  14.Qc2  Rd8  15.Rb7  Be7  16.Rc1!  O-O  17.c5!  The lonely Black Queen is a goner after something like Nb1, e4, and Bd2 or Nd3, Be5, and Bd2  11.Nb3  Qa3   11...Qb6?  12.Nbd4  12.Nbd4  O-O  13.Nxc6  bxc6  14.Bxc6  Ba6  15.Bxa8  Rxa8  16.Qc2  dxc4  17.e4   8...g6  Shankland's recommendation and the 4th most common move  9.Be5!?  An interesting and simple move which has been tried only 8 times and wasn't covered by Shankland. It seems to have Kamsky's stamp of approval and the engines like a draw by repetition here, which might be useful to have in your back pocket   9.e4  The main move and Sedlak's recommendation. Shankland improved on his analysis, but many of his lines lead to a draw by repetition with Black having had the much harder game, which means they're practically quite unlikely to occur  9...dxe4   9...Nxe4??  10.Be5  10.Be5  Qa5  Shankland's move  11.O-O  exf3  White has two options here Qxf3 and Bxc6. The first leads to a draw by repetition which is good to know, if you need it. The second leads to an unbalanced, if equal endgame.  12.Qxf3   12.Bxc6+  bxc6  13.Qxf3  Nd5  14.Bxh8  Qxd2  15.c4  f6  16.Rfd1  Qc3  17.cxd5  Qxf3  18.gxf3  Bf5  19.Rb7  O-O-O  20.Rxa7  Kb8  21.Ra6  cxd5  22.c6  Engines show equality, but both sides can obviously play on. It's hard to imagine Black players learning all of this just to end up here.  12...Qxb5  If Black makes it here it's clear they've memorized the line  13.Bxf6  Qxb1  14.Rxb1  exf6  15.Qxf6  Rg8  16.Ne4  Be7  17.Nd6+  Bxd6  18.cxd6  Rb8  19.Re1+  Be6  20.Rxe6+  fxe6  21.Qxe6+  Kf8  22.Qf6+  9...Qxc5  What else ?  10.c4  Bg7   10...dxc4  11.Bd4  Qd5  12.Bxc4  Qd8  13.Qb3  e6  14.Bb5  Be7  15.O-O  White has enough activity for the pawn  11.Nb3  Qb4+   11...Qb6  12.Bd4   12.Nfd4!?  Bd7  13.Bxf6  Bxf6  14.cxd5  Nxd4  15.Bxd7+  Kxd7  16.exd4   11...Qa3?  12.cxd5  12.Nbd2  Qc5  Leads to a draw by repetition }
9. O-O Be7
{ The main move. ~100 games   9...Bxc5  Second most common with 30 games  10.Be5  Qa5   10...Qa3  11.Bb2  Qa5   11...Qxa2?  12.Nb3  Be7  13.Qc1  12.c4  11.c4  Be7  12.Nb3  Qd8  13.cxd5  exd5  14.Nbd4  Bd7  15.Qa4 }
10. e4
{ This is Alphazero's & Leelazero's novelty which will likely throw off even the most prepared opponents. If Black doesn't go wrong immediately then this line will lead to thematic attacking play. There are only 18 games in Lichess with this move and 6 games at master level. White intends e5. In contrast, Bartholomew&Barrish recommended   10.Ne5  and Sedlak suggested the trickier   10.Nd4  I will give the bare bones here. For more, see the trainable lines. }
10... O-O
{ 10...dxe4?  Completely natural and completely losing. But I can't really imagine Black seeing the next move that'll get him in trouble without knowing it ahead.  11.Nc4!!  exf3   11...O-O  12.Bd2  Rd8  13.Bxc3  Rxd1  14.Rfxd1  exf3  15.Bxf6  12.Rb3   10...Nxe4  11.Nxe4  dxe4  12.Bxc6+  bxc6  13.Bd6  exf3  14.Bxe7  Kxe7  15.Qd6+  Kf6   15...Ke8  16.Qxc6+  16.Rb3   10...a6  11.Rb3  Qxc5  12.Be3  Qxb5   12...Qd6  13.e5  13.Rxb5 }
11. e5 Nd7
{ 11...Ne4  12.Rb3  Qxc5  13.Be3  Qxb5  14.Rxb5  Nc3  15.Qa1  Nxb5  16.a4  Nc7  17.Rb1 }
12. Nb3 { Protecting c5 and preparing Bd2, trapping the queen. } 12... Qb4
{ 12...Bxc5?  13.Bd2   12...Ncxe5  13.Nxe5  Nxe5  14.Bd2  Nf3+  15.Qxf3  Qxf3  16.gxf3 }
13. Nbd4 Qxc5 14. Re1 Nxd4 { If  14...a6  15.Bd3 } 15. Nxd4 a6 16. Bd3 g6 17.
Nf3 *

