[Black " 8...e6, 9...Bxc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8.
Bb5 e6 9. O-O Bxc5
{ This is very natural, but not best. After this Black will lose many tempos and White will get a serious initiative. }
10. Be5
{ Best move. White could also try 10. Bc7, intending Rb3. Sadler gives the following example of how this can get Black into trouble:  10.Bc7  Qa3  11.Nc4  dxc4  12.Qd8#  . However, both 10...Be7 and 10...Nd7 create room for the Queen, either on  c5  or  f6  . }
10... Qa5
{ If  10...Qa3  11.Bb2!  Qa5  12.c4  threatening Nb3 and intending to meet  12...O-O  with the forcing sequence  13.Bxf6  which will transpose to the text line. }
11. c4 O-O
{ This is the best move, though Black has to accept the structural damage to his kingside to play this. Sedlak considered the prophylactic retreat  11...Be7  to be the best, but then White gets a simple edge after  12.Nb3  Qd8  13.Nbd4!  playing this first cuts down on Black's options as to what to capture on d5 with  13...Bd7  14.cxd5  exd5  15.Qa4  and White has an edge. For more, see the model game Pert-D'Costa. }
12. Bxf6
{ White initiates a forcing sequence that leaves him with two knights vs. two bishops, but an edge nevertheless. }
12... gxf6 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Bxc6 bxc6 { Black's structure is a mess. } 15. Nb3
Qb6
{ Black has to retreat the Queen while protecting the bishop and this is the best square. If  15...Qb4?!  16.Nbd4  Qa3  17.Nxc6   If  15...Qa3  16.Rc1  Bb6  17.Rxc6 }
16. Qc2 Bd6 17. Nbd4 Qa6 18. Nxc6
{ White is better due to his activity and Black's weaknesses. White's knights have a nice outpost on d4. Still, Black has some compensation due to his bishops. }
*

