1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8.
Bb5 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. e4 O-O 11. e5 Nd7 12. Nb3 Qb4 13. Nbd4 Qxc5 14. Re1 a6
15. Bd3 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 g6 17. Nf3
{ This is our theoretical position.   17.Nb3  Alphazero's choice.  17...Qc7  18.Qg4  Kg7  19.Qg3  h5  20.h4  Qd8  21.Bg5  Bxg5  22.hxg5  b6  23.Qf4  With the aim to play g4. Stockfish 12 evaluates this as 0.00, but it's obviously much easier for White to play.  23...Bb7  24.Nd4  The game eventually ended a draw. Check out GM Sadler's & WIM Regan's great video on the game. }
17... b5 18. Qd2 Re8 19. h4 { Harry goes. } 19... Bb7 20. Bg5 Bf8 21. Nh2
{ A very interesting maneuvre, preparing to meet ...h5 with g4. } 21... h5 22.
g4 Bg7 23. gxh5 Nxe5 24. h6
{ The thorn pawn is installed. It will play a key role in this game. } 24...
Nxd3 25. cxd3 Bc3
{ Stockfish 12 considers this a complete blunder...after this it's all downhill for Black. It's almost if Lc0 set a trap for a materialistic human. }
26. Qf4 Qd4
{ 26...Bxe1??  27.h7+!  This is how you mate.  27...Kh8  28.Qf6+  Kxh7  29.Qxf7+  Kh8  30.Bf6 }
27. Qc7 { A very nice Queen maneuvre. } 27... Bxe1 28. Rxe1 Rab8 29. Kg2
{ 29.Rxe6!?  Rxe6   29...fxe6  30.Bf4  With the idea of Be4.  30.Qxb8+   29.h7+  This is Stock 12's initial choice, before you show it Rxe6. The following engine line illustrates the ideas.  29...Kxh7  30.h5  Kg7  31.Bf4  Kg8  32.Ng4  gxh5  33.Nh6+  Kh7  34.Nxf7  Qg7+  35.Kh2  Rf8  36.Rxe6  Rxf7  37.Qxb8  d4  38.Rh6+  Qxh6  39.Bxh6 }
29... Rf8 30. Kg3 { The king can support both Rf3 and Ng4! } 30... Qxd3+
{ 30...Rfc8  31.Qe7  Re8  32.Qd6 } 31. Re3 Qf5 32. Rf3
{ White is completely winning here. } 32... Rbc8 33. Qxb7 Qe5+ 34. Bf4 Qa1 35.
Bd6 b4 36. Kg2 Qd4 37. Rf4 Qh8 38. Ng4
{ White's two pieces together with the thorn pawn totally dominate Black. }
38... f5 39. Be5 Rb8 { 39...Qh7  40.Bg7  fxg4  41.Qe7 } 40. Qd7 Qh7 41. Bg7
{ 41.Qxe6+  Qf7  42.Nf6+  Kh8  43.Ne4+  Kg8  44.Ng5  Qxe6  45.h7 } 41... Rf7
{ 41...fxg4  42.Qxe6+  Rf7  43.Qxf7 } 42. Qxe6 { Threatening Nf6#. } 42... Qxg7
{ The rest is just delaying mate.   42...a5  43.Nf6 } 43. hxg7 Rb7 44. Nh6+
Kxg7 45. Nxf7 Rxf7 46. Rxb4 f4 47. Rb8 Rf8 48. Rb7+ Kh6 49. Qe7 Rf7 50. Qxf7
