[Black "8...g6, 9. e4 a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8.
Bb5 g6 { Shankland's recommendation. } 9. e4
{ This was recommended by Sedlak and leads to sharp play. I like it not only because it is good, but also because it's also consistent with our move in the 8... e6 line. Notice however that Carlsen was happy to just play  9.O-O  Bg7  10.Nb3  here against Ding Liren when the game continued  10...O-O  11.Bxc6  bxc6  12.Be5  Qc4  13.Nfd4  and the game eventually ended in a draw. }
9... a6
{ Sedlak thought this was the best move, but Shankland goes for ...dxe4 instead. If  9...Nxe4?  10.Be5   Black doesn't have time for  9...Bg7  10.Be5  Qa5  11.exd5  .  The following sequence is practically completely unlikely but illustrates well White's possibilities. }
10. Be5
{ Let's explore this line to illustrate White's possibilities. I give the simpler Bxc6 as an alternative. }
10... Qxc5 11. Bd4 Qa3 12. Rb3 Qxa2
{ If instead  12...Qa5  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.O-O  Bg7  15.Nc4!  and if cxd4 Bb6 traps the Queen  15...Qd8  16.Nb6  Rb8  17.exd5  cxd5  18.Ne5  Bb7  19.Ned7!  Nxd7  20.Bxg7  Rg8  21.Nxd7  Qxd7  22.Qd4  f6  looks like an interesting try, notice that if 22...Rc8 then 23.Qb2!  23.Bxf6!  exf6  24.Qxf6  with a decisive attack. }
13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. O-O Bg7
{ If  14...dxe4  15.Bxf6  exf6  16.Qe2  is the simplest way, and White is a lot better. }
15. Qe2
{ If White wants he can make a draw here with  15.Nb1!?  Qa5  16.Bd6  Qa1  17.Bd4  and the Queen is not going anywhere. }
15... Qa5
{ If  15...O-O  16.Ra1  Qxc2  17.Rb2  or Ne1 etc. traps the Queen   If instead  15...Qxc2  White has to find the difficult  16.Ra1  after which the threats are like in the previous variation  16...Nh5  17.Qe3!  e5!  18.Nxe5  c5  19.Bxc5!  Bxe5  20.exd5  f6  21.Bd6  +/-. }
16. exd5 cxd5 17. Rb6 Nh5 { Stopping Ra1. } 18. Ne5
{ It has been fun, but you'll never get even here in an actual game so it's a good place to stop. }
