1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8.
Bb5 g6 9. e4 dxe4 10. Be5 Qa5 11. O-O exf3 12. Bxc6+
{ This enables White to avoid the draw. } 12... bxc6 13. Qxf3 Nd5 14. Ne4
{ Shankland didn't consider this non-greedy move which sets Black novel problems to solve. White removes the knight from harm's way, controls  c3  and  f6  and renews the threat of Bxh8. }
14... Rg8 15. c4 f5
{ Again, this looks like the only move. For example  15...Nf6??  16.Nxf6+  exf6  17.Qxc6+  leads to mate.   Another amazing line is  15...Nc7?  16.Rfd1  Qa6  19.Rb6!!  axb6  20.Nf6+  exf6  21.Qxc6+  Ke7  22.Bxf6#  . }
16. Ng3 Ba6
{ One option and Stockfish's initial choice. Other and perhaps objectively slightly better options for Black are  16...Qxc5  17.cxd5  Qxd5  18.Qe3   16...Nc7  17.Qxc6+  Bd7  18.Qxc7  Qxc7  19.Bxc7  Kf7  20.Rfe1   or  16...Be6  17.cxd5  Bxd5  18.Qe3  in all cases with "equality" or at least a 0.00 evaluation. }
17. cxd5 Bxf1 18. Nxf1 Qxc5 19. dxc6 Qxe5
{ The human move. Engines find equality also with  19...Rc8  20.Qb3  Qxe5  21.Qxg8  Rxc6  22.g3  . }
20. Qb3
{ Black has to have played very correctly to get here and even here his practical problems don't stop, despite the 0.00 engine evaluation. White is down a rook, but will get it back for sure. }
