[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Classical Setup with ...Be7"]
[Black "Vlatko Kovacevic vs. Tom O'Donnell, 1990"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a Classical game. One of our heroes, Kovacevic, was rated 2540, Black was rated 2410. }
1... d5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 Nf6 4. e3 Be7 5. Nbd2
{ Here, most precise might be the direct Ne5, pre-empting ...Nh5. } 5... O-O 6.
Bd3
{ White completes his development. Notice that Kovacevic is following here the basic and simple rule that there is no need to play c3 before Black actually puts pressure on our center with ...c5. }
6... b6 7. Ne5 Bb7
{ A quite a modern concept, keeping the knight back and developing the bishop first with the threat of ...Ne4. This is usually done with the Black bishop on d6 however. }
8. Qf3
{ Kovacevic sees Black's plan and reinforces e4. The Queen can also transfer to h3. }
8... Nbd7 9. h4
{ Again, Harry goes up the board in anticipation of ...Nxe5. However, here much stronger was the consistent  9.Qh3  and things are already quite difficult for Black since he has to weaken the kingside with ...g6 or ...h6 to defend. }
9... Nxe5 { Black promptly complies. } 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. O-O-O
{ Kovacevic finishes development, every piece is now more or less in action. Better was  11.Qg4  eyeing, g7 and e6. }
11... Nc5 { A natural move and also the computer suggestion. } 12. Bxh7+
{ Another Greek Gift. } 12... Kxh7 13. Qh5+
{ Again, the Queen comes in first, controlling g6. } 13... Kg8 14. Nf3 f6 15.
Ng5 { We've seen this before. } 15... fxg5 16. hxg5 Rf5
{ Same defensive move. The only thing that differs is the placement of Black's knight, bishop and c-pawn. Especially because of the knight, Black now has an escape path for his king so White must conduct the attack somewhat differently... }
17. g4
{ Here White must pursue this approach since entering with the Queen just allows Black's King to run away, e. g.  17.Qh8+  Kf7  18.Qh5+  g6  19.Qh7+  Ke8  20.Qxg6+  Kd7  . }
17... Rxg5
{ Taking the bishop is always a mistake because of the pattern we saw above  17...Rxf4??  18.Qh8+  Kf7  19.g6+  Kxg6  20.Qh5# }
18. Bxg5 Bxg5 19. f4
{ Let's take count. White has a rook and a pawn for three pieces so he's clearly down material, but Black's dark-squared bishop is not for long in this world. }
19... Bh6 20. g5 Qe8 21. Qh4 Kh7 22. Rdg1 Ne4 23. Rg4 d4
{ This attempt to open up the bishop is a mistake. Black needed to find  23...Qd8  . }
24. gxh6 g5 { If  24...g6  25.Rhg1  and White's, again, winning. } 25. fxg5 Qg6
26. exd4 { At the moment White is up material. } 26... Nf2
{ Fork + discovery. } 27. Rf1
{ This is a blunder, but the point isn't easy to appreciate. White could've of course played along with Black with the obvious  27.Qxf2  Bxh1  28.Qf6  Qxf6  29.exf6  Kg6  30.Kd2  .   However, the crushing move was  27.Rf4!!  with the simple point of playing Rf6 next, and the game would've been over there and then. }
27... Nxg4 28. Qxg4 { Now material is equal and it's also objectively equal. }
28... Rg8 29. Rf6 Qxg5+ 30. Qxg5 Rxg5
{ O'Donnell has said in comments to a MatoJelic video on this game on Youtube, that he was in radical time trouble between moves 30-40 and that siince this was a no-increment game he had to scramble to make time control at move 40. }
31. Rxe6 { White has three pawns for the piece. } 31... Be4 32. Re7+ Kxh6 33.
Rxc7 a5 { The immediate  33...Rg2  cutting off the king, was better. } 34. c4
Rg2 35. b3 Kg6 36. e6 Kf6 37. d5
{ What a picture. The beauty of this causes Black to immediately blunder with... }
37... Rg8
{ A blunder, ...Bg6 would've held the draw  37...Bg6  38.Rc6  a4  39.Rxb6  Rxa2  40.e7+  Kxe7  41.Rxg6  axb3  42.Kb1  Rc2  etc. }
38. Rb7 Ke5 { Black tries to go for a hail-mary mate. } 39. Rxb6 Kd4 40. e7 Kc3
41. Kd1 Kd3 42. Ke1 Ke3 43. Rf6 a4 44. b4 a3 45. b5
{ Here Rf8 would've worked, but it's not easy to see  45.Rf8  Rg2  46.e8=Q  Re2+  47.Kf1  Rc2  48.Qxe4+  Kxe4  49.d6  Rc1+  50.Kg2  Rd1  51.c5 }
45... Rc8 46. Ra6 Rh8 { Threatening mate, yet again. } 47. Rxa3+ Bd3 48. Rxd3+
Kxd3 49. Kf2
{ A pretty picture. Black has no chance of stopping the pawns so he resigned. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Classical Setup with ...Be7"]
[Black "Classical with ...Be7: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Be7
{ ...Be7 is played either by those who just want to timidly stick to a QGD setup or instead to prepare ...Nh5 because it stops Bg5 as a reply. It's the second most common move both at amateur level @@StartBracket@@~13 000 games@@EndBracket@@ and at master level. }
7. Ne5
{ The most precise move, avoiding ...Nh5.  Played only in a 1000 games. Here Black can castle or go ...Nxe5 immediately }
7... O-O
{ Most common   7...Nxe5  8.dxe5  Nd7  9.h4  Offering a poisoned pawn and preparing Qg4 without having to worry about ...g5 and ...h5  9...Bxh4  Black doesn't have to take it, of course   9...O-O  10.Bd3  10.Qg4  g5  11.Rxh4  gxh4   11...gxf4  12.exf4  12.Qg7  Rf8  13.Bg5  Qb6  14.O-O-O  White's basically winning due to the threats of Bxh4 followed by Qg5, Ne4, followed by Rxd7 and Qxf8 etc. }
8. Bd3
{ Black has a variety of options, but against most White gets a kingside attack }
8... Nxe5
{ Overwhelmingly the most common at amateur level with ~2200 games, and only a close second at master level so we'll spend most of our time with it. The only other real alternative that needs to be studied is ...Nd7. Limp moves like ...Qb6, ...Re8, ...h6, ...a6 etc. allow White to continue with his thematic play.   8...cxd4  9.exd4  Doesn't change much except White gets the open e-file to work with   8...Qb6  9.Rb1   8...Nd7  The most serious move  9.Ndf3  Perhaps the best move, bringing the other knight in. Qh5 doesn't work as well here. However, White can always try h4, after which the knight captures transpose and f-pawn moves can be met with Nxc6  9...f6  Most common in Lichess, masters prefer Ndxe5   9...Ndxe5  10.dxe5  f5   10...f6  11.h4  Nxe5   11...fxe5  12.Bxh7+  Kxh7  13.Ng5+  Kg6  The worse, but more interesting move here  14.h5+  Kf5  15.Nf7  An amazing mating net idea, taking away f7 from the king  15...Rxf7  16.g4+  Kf6  17.g5+  Kf5  18.Rh4  d4  19.Qf3  Qd5  20.Qh3+  Ke4  21.f3+  Kd3  22.Qf1+  Kc2  23.Rh2  12.Bxe5  fxe5  13.Nxe5  Qe8  14.Qb1  Qh5  15.f4  Bd6  16.g4  Qh6  17.Qd1  11.h4  c4   11...d4  12.Qe2  12.Bc2  White has a nice attacking position. See the game Gorovets vs Yjonosa Apointe, 2015  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.O-O  c4  12.Bc2  The plan is to open the position with b3 }
9. dxe5 { We always take with the pawn to kick the knight away } 9... Nd7 10.
h4 { This move prepares the Greek Gift. The pawn is obviously poisoned. } 10...
c4
{ Only the 4th most common move, but in some ways most interesting. Black intends ...Nc5 to ...Nd3 and so White has to strike immediately   10...g6  This is the sort of move that just plays into White's hands  11.Nf3  Controlling g5 first and intending Bh6  11...h5  12.g4  hxg4  13.h5  Ripping it all open. Black is lost whether he takes or doesn't take the offered knight   10...f5  The most common move, but White gets an advantage after  11.g4  Black players have tried everything here, but most moves are bad. For example ...c4 is met by Bc2, ...Bxh4 loses on the spot to gxf5, g6 can be met with Rg1. The only interesting moves are ...Qc7 and ...d4  11...Qc7   11...d4  Aiming to open the center with a counterattack and asking White where he's going to put his king. Things can get messy, but White comes out on top with precise play  12.Nf3  The safer and saner move, protecting the e-pawn and the loose bishop on d3. As an upside this also hasn't been played   12.gxf5  Leads to a mess along the lines of  12...dxc3  13.bxc3  Nxe5  14.Bxe5  Qxd3  15.Qg4  Bf6  16.Bxf6  Rxf6  17.Rg1  g6  18.Ne4  exf5  19.Nxf6+  Kf7  20.Qf4  Qxc3+  21.Ke2  Qxf6  22.Rad1  12...dxc3  13.bxc3  12.Nf3  Protecting the pawn and threatening gxf5  12...fxg4  13.Ng5  Double attack  13...Bxg5  14.hxg5  Only one game in the database has ever reached here. Black has to defend precisely to not get killed on the h-file  14...g6  15.Qxg4  Nxe5  16.Bxe5  Qxe5  17.Rh6  An important improvement, intending to double rooks on the h-file   10...f6  Second most common move, but it's not good  11.Qh5  f5   11...g6  Suicide  12.Bxg6  hxg6  13.Qxg6+  Kh8  14.Qh6+  Kg8  15.Rh3  With a mate in 5 starting with Rg3+  12.g4  White won a tempo   10...Qc7  11.Nf3 }
11. Bxh7+ { Obviously. Surprisingly, Bc2 has been played slightly more. } 11...
Kxh7 12. Qh5+
{ The paradigmatic feature of London Gifts is that the Queen gets to enter before the knight, forcing the king inevitably back to g8 }
12... Kg8 13. Nf3 f6
{ The only defence. Everything else just loses   13...f5  14.Ng5  Bxg5  15.hxg5  Black has to give up his Queen to stop g6   13...g6  14.Qh6  Re8  15.Ng5  Nf8  16.h5  Bxg5  17.Bxg5  Again, Black has to give up his Queen so as not to get mated immediately }
14. Ng5 fxg5 15. hxg5
{ White's basic threat is g6. Here Black has tried ...Rf5, ...Rxf4?, ...Bxg5. The former leads to a win, but ...Bxg5 gives White more options of making a mistake }
15... Bxg5
{ Played in only 8 games   15...Rf5  Most common, pinning the Queen  16.Qh7+  Kf7   16...Kf8  This loses to  17.Qg6  Kg8   17...Bc5  18.Qxe6  18.Rh7  Rf7  19.Qh5  17.g6+  Ke8  18.Qxg7  With Rh8 coming and the g-pawn close to promotion Black won't last long   15...Rxf4  Second most common, but this loses immediately to  16.Qh8+  Kf7  17.g6+  Kxg6  18.Qh5 }
16. Bxg5 Qb6
{ Now the b-pawn, e-pawn, and f-pawn are all hanging. But Stockfish simply doesn't care and finds a nice tactical solution it couldn't find a few years ago   16...Qc7  17.f4 }
17. O-O-O { White castles and defends the b-pawn } 17... Rxf2
{ Looks natural and strong, but now...   17...Nxe5  Perhaps the better try  18.Qh7+  Kf7  19.Rh6!! }
18. Rd2 Rxd2 19. Qh7+ Kf8 20. Qh8+ Kf7 21. Rf1+ Nf6 22. b4
{ There is no perpetual } 22... Rxg2 23. exf6 Rxg5 24. fxg7+ Ke7 25. Qf8+ Kd7
26. Rf7+ Kc6 27. Qe8+ Kd6 28. Qe7+ Kc6 29. Qxg5
{ White gets his rook back and a new Queen to boot. This is real engine chess. }
