Nd7 9. Ndf3 Ndxe5 10. dxe5 f6 11. h4 Nxe5 { Taking with the knight is better. }
12. Bxe5 fxe5 13. Nxe5 Qe8 14. f4
{ This is a big improvement over Sedlak's immediate  14.Qb1  Qh5  15.f4  Bd6  16.g4  Qh6  17.Qd1  . White protects the knight first and then proceeds with the attack. }
14... Bd6
{ If  14...c4  15.Bb1  Bd6  16.Qc2  g6  17.h5  and White has a strong attack. }
15. Qc2 { A rare case where we go Qc2. ...c4 is prevented by tactical means. }
15... g6 { If  15...Qh5  16.g4! } 16. h5 c4 17. Bxg6 hxg6
{ The engines think Black shouldn't actually accept the sacrifice, but let's see how to play when he does.   If  17...Qe7  18.O-O-O  with a continued attack. }
18. hxg6 Bxe5 19. fxe5 { White is threatening g7 and Qh7. } 19... Qe7
{ Just to demonstrate  19...Bd7  20.g7  Kxg7  21.Qh7# } 20. O-O-O Qg7
{ Black's best defence and now White's best is a bit unintuitive. } 21. Qe2
{ The point is to control g4 to be able to meet ...Qxg6 with Rd4-Rg4. } 21...
Bd7
{ Apparently, best play. The problem is other moves are just met with rook lifts like in   21...Qxg6  22.Rd4  with the rook going to  g4  .   21...Qxe5  22.Rh3  with  Rdh1  next. }
22. Rh7 Qxg6 23. Rxd7
{ And now White's just a pawn up with a continued attack. } *

