1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Be7 7. Ne5 O-O 8. Bd3
Nxe5
{ Overwhelmingly the most common at amateur level with ~2200 games, and only a close second at master level so we'll spend most of our time with it. Limp moves like ...Qb6, ...Re8, ...h6, ...a6 etc. allow White to continue with his thematic play. }
9. dxe5 { We always take with the pawn to kick the knight away. } 9... Nd7 10.
h4 { This move prepares the Greek Gift. The pawn is obviously poisoned. } 10...
g6
{ This is the sort of move that just plays into White's hands. Even worse is of course  10...Bxh4??  11.Bxh7+  Kxh7  12.Qh5+ }
11. Nf3 { Controlling g5 first and intending Bh6. } 11... h5
{ A common reaction. } 12. g4 { Ripping it all open! } 12... hxg4 13. h5
{ A typical attacking idea. Black is lost whether he takes or doesn't take the offered knight. Let's continue the line with the sharpest option. }
13... gxf3
{ Black grabs the material. If  13...g5  14.Nxg5  Bxg5  15.Qxg4  Kh8  16.Rg1  and White wins a lot of material.   If  13...gxh5  14.Rxh5  gxf3  16.Qxf3  leads to mate.   If  13...gxh5  14.Rxh5  f5  15.exf6  Bxf6  16.Ng5!  Bxg5  17.Qxg4  and White has many ways to win. }
14. hxg6
{ This is an important move, opening the h-file and blowing up Black king's cover. }
14... fxg6 { If  14...f5  15.Qxf3  with a mate to follow. } 15. Bxg6
{ White is now threatening Qxf3. To demonstrate the idea  15...b6  16.Qxf3  Nxe5  17.Bxe5!  Rxf3  18.Rh8#  . }
15... Bh4 { Blocking the h-file, but now. } 16. Bc2
{ White retreats the bishop and unclogs the g-file. } 16... Rf7
{ Trying to defend on the 7th rank. } 17. Qxf3
{ Black can't survive this. If  17...Qg5  18.Qh3  Rxf4  19.exf4  Qxf4  20.Qxh4  Qxh4  21.Rxh4  Nxe5  22.O-O-O  and White is winning both on material and due to the weak Black king.   If  17...Nxe5  18.Qh5  and everything falls. }
