[Black "7...Bxg3: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 Bxg3
{ Black frequently exchanges bishops. This is the second most common both at amateur and master level though about 6 times rarer than the main ...O-O  (~5000 games)  . It is frequently seen online at faster time controls though, even though it's not very good, developing White's rook for free and giving him an extra g-pawn. Black's plan is ...Qd6 or ...Qe7 and push ...e5, but White can stop this. }
8. hxg3 { Where is Black going to put his king? } 8... Qd6
{ No other plan makes sense for Black, even though amateurs play everything here. Here White can choose between Kamsky's good knight vs. bad bishop plan  (also played by Carlsen)  or Sedlak's endgame plan. The former tends to score better at master level, but it's about the same at amateur level. I prefer the former with very thematic ideas. }
9. Bb5
{ the Kamsky plan, stopping ...e5, compared to the 5k games 2 moves ago, only ~400 games have reached here.   9.Bd3  the Sedlak plan, allowing e5  9...e5  Critical test of Bd3  10.dxe5  Nxe5  11.Nxe5  Qxe5  12.Qa4+!  Bd7  13.Qf4  This endgame is White's idea, but I prefer the Kamsky plan  13...Qxf4   13...Qe7  The engines tell you to actually avoid the Queen trade  14.O-O-O  O-O-O  15.e4  Be6  16.exd5  Nxd5  17.Qe5  Qf6 =  14.gxf4  White has a small pull with an open h-file and more pawns in the center. }
9... Bd7
{ Most common move   9...O-O  Second most common  10.Bxc6  bxc6  White has several options here, playing against Black's damaged structure such as  11.Qc2   11.Qa4  11...h6  12.Nb3!  c4   12...cxd4  13.cxd4   12...Ne4!?  13.Nxc5  Nxc5  14.dxc5  Qxc5  15.O-O-O !  White will go for a kingside attack with g4-g5 etc.  13.Nc5 }
10. Bxc6 Bxc6 11. Ne5
{ Classical good knight vs. bad bishop situation. White would love to get a pair of knights off so only these two key pieces remain. }
11... Nd7
{ Most logical and overwhelmingly most common   11...h6  Perhaps best  12.Qf3  A novelty, with the idea of going g4-g5 with a new threat on f7. For more, see the trainable line. }
12. Ndf3
{ Most logical. f4 is played more at amateur level and can be played as well. }
12... cxd4 { 12...f6?  Natural, but a mistake  13.Ng6  Rg8  14.Rxh7 } 13. exd4
h6 14. Nxd7
{ White can now achieve his goal of exchanging a pair of knights and then put the other knight to e5. }
14... Bxd7 15. Ne5
{ White can involve the Queen via g4 and go to f4 and then push the g-pawn. } *

