1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 Qc7
{ Another sideline. Here the idea is again to put pressure on  e5  , but in a different way. However, from this move order, with ...Nc6 played, it doesn't work at all due to the pin, which makes possible... }
8. dxc5 Bxg3 { The only move. } 9. hxg3 a5
{ The overwhelmingly most common move at amateur level, stopping b4, but this is strongly met with... }
10. Nd4
{ I like this move the best. We're threatening to jump to b5 to harass Black's queen. If they take then they obviously protect our extra pawn. It's also good to play with c4, Rc1, a3, Rh4 etc. }
10... e5
{ Most common, but now   10...O-O  Black commits his king  11.g4!   10...Nxd4?  11.cxd4   10...Ne7  Black retreats, but now  11.b4 }
11. Nb5 Qe7 12. Nd6+ Kf8 13. e4
{ Opening things up, but of course White is spoiled for choice here with Qa4, Bb5 also possible. }
13... Be6 14. exd5 Bxd5 15. N2c4 Rd8 16. Qa4
{ Better than Qc2, which can also be played. White intends Qb5 and O-O-O. He's already up a pawn and will get more material with the more active position. }
