1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
Re8
{ This could be considered the oldest 'Main Line'. Black wants to push ...e5. It's the second most popular move in the position, but in some way the weakest. }
9. Ne5 { We play the Pillsbury move, jumping into e5. } 9... Qc7
{ Second most common move. Trying to put more pressure on e5. } 10. f4 Nd7
{ A very common blunder, leaving the kingside bare. Black has better moves of course, but most of them can be met with the thematic Bh4 and O-O, in some order. For example, if  10...b6  11.Bh4!  switching the bishop's diagonal  11...Be7  12.O-O  with a typical London game   and if  10...Ne7  11.O-O  . }
11. Bxh7+ Kxh7 12. Qh5+ Kg8 13. Qxf7+ Kh7 14. Qh5+
{ It's important to pick everything up with check. } 14... Kg8 15. Qxe8+ Kh7
16. Qg6+ Kg8 17. Qxe6+ { Black's best move is to resign... } *

