[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Classical Setup with ...Bd6, Sidelines"]
[Black "8...Qe7: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
Qe7
{ The third most popular move in this position  (~4000 games)  . The idea is to push ...e5. }
9. Ne5 { White can play the typical Pillsbury move, blocking e5. } 9... Nd7
{ In case of moves like ...Bd7 or ...Qc7 White can just continue with the plan of f4   9...Bxe5!?  Only marginally less popular than the main move  10.dxe5  Nd7  11.f4  f6  12.Nf3  White keeps an iron grip on e5 with a great game }
10. Nxd7
{ The following counterintuitive tactical sequence is mostly why ...Qe7 was put out of practice because White either wins or has the option of edge + forcing a draw. Btw, the engines still can't find this idea on their own. }
10... Bxd7
{ What would be more natural than to capture with the bishop and connect rooks.   10...Qxd7  This is the move that doesn't fall into the trap, but White can get an edge with  11.dxc5   11.Bxd6  Qxd6  12.dxc5  Qxc5  13.Bxh7+  Kxh7  14.Qh5+  Kg8  15.Ne4  g6  Counterattacking the Queen and here White doesn't have a bishop on d7 to capture and has to accept a draw by perpetual with  16.Qg5  Qc4  17.Nf6+  Kg7  18.Nh5+  Kh7  19.Nf6+  11...Bxc5  12.Nf3 }
11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5
{ White has made three forcing and unintuitive captures in a row  (and now the engines take a while, but find it) }
13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4
{ The beautiful point. White can bring the knight in with tempo on the Queen, due to the lateral pin. }
15... Qc4
{ 15...g6  This counterattack on the Queen doesn't work because of the bishop on d7  16.Nxc5  gxh5  17.Nxd7  White's a pawn up and about to win another one with Nf6+   15...Qb5  Attacking b2  16.Ng5  Rfd8  17.Qxf7+  Kh8  18.Qh5+  Kg8  19.O-O-O  Here this is best because it protects the b2-pawn }
16. Ng5 Rfd8
{ 16...Qd3!?  17.e4  An important move, blocking the diagonal  17...Rfd8  Most natural, defending the bishop, but engines prefer ...Rfe8 or ...Rfc8 which just lets White take the bishop  18.Qxf7+  Kh8  19.Qh5+  Kg8  20.Rd1  Qb5  21.a4  White wants to castle and/or play f4 and bring the rook into play to mate on the h-file }
17. Qxf7+ { As always, we enter on f7 first. } 17... Kh8 18. Qh5+ Kg8 19. Rd1
e5
{ 19...Ne5  20.Rd4   19...Be8  20.Qh7+  Kf8  21.Qh8+  Ke7  22.Qxg7+  Kd6  Now White needs Ne4 to mate so  23.b3  Qh4  24.g3  Qg4   24...Qh5  25.Ne4#  25.Nf7+  Bxf7  26.Qxg4 }
20. Qf7+ Kh8 21. e4
{ Cutting off the Queen. For the rest see the model game Kamsky vs Shankland. The engines like insanity with   21.Qh5+  Kg8  22.f4  exf4  23.Qf7+  Kh8  24.Rxd5  Bg4  25.Rxd8+  Rxd8  26.Qxc4  Rd1+  27.Kf2  Rd2+  28.Kg1  Rd1+  29.Qf1  fxe3  30.Qxd1  Bxd1  31.h4  But I don't know why one would do this to oneself... }
