[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Classical Setup with ...Bd6, Sidelines"]
[Black "Albert Becker vs. Franz Redeleit, 1914"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a correspondence game that I accidentally happened upon while taking a glance at Tim Harding's 64 Great Chess Games: Masterpieces of Postal and E-Mail Chess Chess Mail, 2002. Albert Becker @@StartBracket@@1896-1984@@EndBracket@@ was an Austrian player who played a lot of correspondence chess, was the Austrian OTB champion in 1937, played for Germany in the 1939 Olympiad and decided to remain in Argentina thereafter, where he was awarded an IM title in 1954. Once you put aside the weird move order, White played the game amazingly accurately. }
1... d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bg3 Nc6 6. c3 Nf6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Bd3
Qe7 9. Ne5 Bxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. f4 f6 12. Nf3
{ This is where we stopped our trainable line. } 12... fxe5 13. fxe5 g6
{ 13...c4  This is a typical priyome in these positions. Black plays ...c4, ...Nc5, with the idea of ...Nd3, similarly to some lines of the Ruy Lopez.  14.Bc2  Nc5  15.O-O   15.Qb1!? }
14. O-O
{ White simply castles.   14.h4  Qg7  15.h5  gxh5  16.Bf4  Ndxe5  17.Nxe5  Was played in Schlechter-Rotlewi, 1911 where White was definitely better, but screwed it up the next move and Black eventually won.   17.Rxh5!  Wins  17...Nxe5  18.Bxh7+?  Qxh7  19.Bxe5= }
14... Qg7 15. e4
{ Opening up the center and banking on Black's awkward development. } 15...
Ndxe5
{ 15...dxe4  16.Bxe4  Ndxe5  17.Nxe5  Rxf1+  18.Kxf1!  Nxe5  19.Qd8+  Qf8+  20.Qxf8+  Kxf8  21.Bxe5   15...d4  The engine preference.  16.Qd2  dxc3  17.bxc3   15...Ne7  16.Qd2   16.exd5  Nxd5  17.Qd2  c4  17.Bc2   17.Ng5!  Threatening Nxe6.  dxe4  18.Ng5  Nc5  19.Qd4   19.Rxf8+!  b6  20.Rxf8+   20.Bxe4  Qxf8  21.Bxe4  Rb8  22.Rf1  Was seen in Becker-Hatscheck, 1914   22.Qd6! }
16. Nxe5 { Unclogging the f-file. } 16... Nxe5
{ 16...Rxf1+  17.Bxf1  Nxe5  18.exd5 } 17. Rxf8+ Kxf8 { 17...Qxf8?  18.Bxe5 }
18. Bxe5
{ This is a good forcing move, but not the best.   18.exd5  This is better.  18...Nxd3   18...exd5  19.Bc2  19.Qxd3  Bd7  20.Re1  Re8  21.Be5 }
18... Qxe5 19. Qf3+ Ke7 { 19...Kg8  20.Rf1 } 20. exd5 exd5
{ 20...Qxd5  21.Be4  Qe5  22.Rf1 } 21. Qf2 { The best move. } 21... Kd6
{ 21...Qd6  22.Qh4+  Kd7  23.Qxh7+ } 22. Re1 Qg5 23. h4
{ Again, the best move. } 23... Qd8 24. Bb5 { Threatening Re8. } 24... c4 25.
Qf4+ Kc5 26. Re8 { White carries out his threat. } 26... Qd6
{ 26...Qb6  27.a4  Threatening b4+ and Qb4#. Black has to give up the Queen to avoid mate. }
27. b4+ *

