[White "8. Classical Setup with ...Bd6, Sidelines"]
[Black "16...Rfd8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
Qe7 9. Ne5 Nd7 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14.
Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 Qc4 16. Ng5 Rfd8 { The natural move, defending the bishop. }
17. Qxf7+ { As always, we enter on f7 first. } 17... Kh8 18. Qh5+
{ It is very important to return to h5, preventing ...Qh4 and preparing to get behind the King via h7. Getting the rook on the d-file immediately with  18.Rd1??  Qh4  just loses for White. }
18... Kg8 19. Rd1 { An important move, controlling the d-file. } 19... e5
{ Shankland's choice. If  19...Ne5  20.Rd4   or  19...Be8  20.Qh7+  Kf8  21.Qh8+  Ke7  22.Qxg7+  Kd6  23.b3!  Qh4  24.g3  Qg4  25.Nf7+ }
20. Qf7+
{ It's important for the Queen to be on f7, pinning Black's Queen diagonally, when you push e4. }
20... Kh8 21. e4
{ Cutting off the Queen from any lateral defense. For the rest, see the model gameKamsky vs Shankland. }
