[White "8. Classical Setup with ...Bd6, Sidelines"]
[Black "10...Qxd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
Qe7 9. Ne5 Nd7 10. Nxd7 {  } 10... Qxd7
{ Black captures with the Queen and now going for the previous sequence yields no more than a draw. }
11. O-O
{ White can just castle here. Most sources used to give  11.dxc5  Bxc5  12.Nf3  , but the text is better.   If White wants to go for the draw by repetition then they should play  11.Bxd6  Qxd6  12.dxc5  Qxc5  13.Bxh7+  Kxh7  14.Qh5+  Kg8  15.Ne4  g6!  15.Qg5  Qc4  16.Nf6+  Kg7  17.Nh5+  etc. }
11... Bxg3
{ Black wants to engineer ...e5 and this seems like a very natural try. Lots of your opponents will try the immediate  11...e5??  12.dxe5  Bxe5  13.Bxe5  Nxe5  14.Bxh7+  Kxh7+  15.Qh5+  with a fork and an extra pawn.   If  11...Re8  12.Qf3!  attacking the d-pawn e. g.  12...e5  13.Qxd5   If  11...Qe7  going back, White can play all sorts of moves, including dxc5, Qh5, Nf3, but most principled seems to punish Black for his tempo waste with  12.Bxd6  Qxd6  13.f4  setting up a good stonewall.   If  11...b6  12.Qe2  or Qh5 }
12. hxg3 Qe7
{ Black tries to engineer ...e5. He could also play ...Qd6, with the same idea, but now... }
13. f4
{ We shut it down! With an interesting and much better position we would get after 11. dxc5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Classical Setup with ...Bd6, Main Line"]
[Black "Why Not 9. Ne5 - Sergey Karjakin vs. Michael Adams, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This is a key game for almost all the D-pawn sidelines  @@StartBracket@@esp. Stonewall, Colle-Zukertort, and London!@@EndBracket@@  because it shows how Black should maneuver to meet the Pillsbury plan of Ne5 + f4. Apparently this scheme was found by Ntirlis who showed it to Avrukh who published in his book, which Adams later confirmed he had read before this game. Let me warn you ahead of time - this is a game where Black wins so focus more on his play. }
1... Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3
{ Karjakin goes for an early Nf3. Our move here would be  4.Nd2  . } 4... c5
{ Adams goes for a quick ...c5. } 5. c3 Nc6 6. Nbd2
{ We reach the common Classical line. } 6... Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3 b6
{ The modern main line. } 9. Ne5
{ Karjakin goes for the Pillsbury plan. From this move order this is emphatically NOT our choice as White. }
9... Bb7 10. f4 { Karjakin goes for the standard Pillsbury move. } 10... Ne7
{ This is the reason. Whenever you see BOTH Ne5 & f4 as Black it always makes sense to at least consider this plan, whether you're facing the Stonewall, Colle-Zukertort, or London. The idea is to play ...Nf5, ...Be7, ...Nd6 and eventually force one of the knights to e4. After that Black can play ...Bd6 again and ...Qc8 and ...Ba6 to swap bishops. This is Step 1 of the plan. }
11. Qf3
{ White has an abysmal score from here. It would be better to play  11.Qb1  which at least forces  11...g6  first, and then the further clever prophylactic  12.Bf2  , stepping away from ...Nf5. Still, it's at best equal. }
11... Nf5 { Step 2 } 12. Bf2 Be7 { Step 3, making room for ...Nd6. } 13. g4
{ This just drives the knight where it wants to go anyway. Most common is  15.O-O  Nd6  . }
13... Nd6 { Step 4 } 14. g5 Nfe4
{ Step 5, one of the knights is forced into e4. } 15. O-O-O c4
{ The typical attacking formation on the Queenside, aiming to continue with ...b5. }
16. Bc2 { If  16.Bxe4  dxe4  17.Qe2  b5  18.h4  b4  19.cxb4  a5  . } 16... b5
17. Qh3 { White keeps dreaming of an attack. } 17... b4 18. Nxe4
{ 18.cxb4  a5 } 18... dxe4 19. Be1 Bd5
{ Strengthening the central grip, supporting ...b3, and clearing the b-file. }
20. Rg1 b3 21. axb3 cxb3 22. Bb1 f5
{ A prophylactic move, securing the kingside against any counterplay. } 23.
gxf6 Bxf6 24. Rg4 Nf5 25. Kd2 Qa5 26. Ke2 Bxe5
{ Exchanging White's most active and dangerous piece. } 27. dxe5 Rad8 28. Kf2
Qa1 29. Bd2 Bc4 30. Qh5 Qxb2 31. Ke1 Rxd2
{ Superb game by Adams. For White, the main lesson is to not to meet 8... b6 with 9. Ne5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Classical Setup with ...Bd6, Main Line"]
[Black "9. e4, dxe4 & others: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
b6 9. e4
{ Only the 4th most common move with roughly 3500 games, but the best-scoring try. The immediate threat is e5, forking Black's pieces, so Black has to react somehow. }
9... dxe4
{ Overwhelmingly most common, but not the best move @@StartBracket@@~1900 games@@EndBracket@@   9...Nh5  Very rare. White can just play  10.Bxd6  Qxd6  11.e5  Qc7  12.Qc2  Black's knight is stranded   9...cxd4  4th most common. I remember when you could first try to play Lc0 it constantly chose this line  10.e5  dxc3  11.bxc3  Nxe5  12.Nxe5  Qc7  13.Qe2  Qxc3  14.O-O  Material is now equal, but White's development lead and extra minor piece should tell after something like ...Bb7 and Rfc1.   9...Bxg3  The 3rd most common move. However, opening the h-file can only benefit White. However, White should know one thing.  10.hxg3  g6  11.e5  For the rest, see the trainable line. }
10. Nxe4 { Attacking the bishop. } 10... Nxe4
{ Most common, with ~1400 games   10...Bxg3  This is worse here than on the last move  11.hxg3  h6  12.dxc5  bxc5  13.Qe2   10...Be7  This retreat is not good  11.Qe2  Thrreatening Nxf6 and Qe4 with a double attack.  Bb7  12.dxc5  Opening the d-file.  bxc5  13.h4 }
11. Bxe4 { Attacking the knight. } 11... Bb7 12. dxc5
{ The bishop is attacked three times. } 12... Bxc5
{ 12...Bxg3  13.hxg3  Black doesn't have time to regain his pawn due to the attack on h7. }
13. Qa4
{ Attacking the knight again, but also activating the Queen on the 4th rank. Black has basically tried three moves here... }
13... Rc8
{ The only good move, but not the most common, with roughly 200 games.   13...Qc8  Natural and roughly as common as ...Rc8. However, the Queen leaves the crucial h5-d8 diagonal and this allows for the gift  14.Bxh7+  Kxh7  15.Qh4+  Kg8  16.Ng5  Rd8  17.Qh7+  Kf8  18.Qh8+  Ke7  19.Qxg7  Threatening Qxf7# and forcing.  19...Rf8  20.O-O-O  White's completely winning. Stockfish now tells Black to sac a piece on d4, and after Rxd4 and Qxd4 White is not even down material with a continued attack and a completely winning position.   13...Qe8  Complete suicide since now the king is further boxed in. This has been played in 60 games and White has won all that continued with  14.Bxh7+  Lights out!   13...Na5  Most common with 250 games but bad  14.Rd1  Qc8  This looks like a moment for the gift like in the previous line and it can be played, but since Black's bishop is open, the result is equality. Objectively strongest is to play on the d-file and on the threat of the b4 fork  15.O-O  Bxe4  16.Qxe4  Now b4 is threatened  16...Be7  17.Ne5  Nb7  18.Nc6  Bf6  19.Be5  Aiming for the Ne7 fork. }
14. Rd1 { Tempo! } 14... Qe7
{ Stepping away from the rook, but avoiding ...Qe8 which is lights out again after Bxh7+, and ...Qf6, which can get in trouble after an eventual b4-b5 and Be5. }
15. O-O
{ White completes development and threatens b4 to b5, winning the a- and b-pawns. }
15... f5 { The most common move. If  15...Rfd8  16.Rfe1 } 16. Bd3
{ Intending Bc4 or Bb5 and Rfe1. } *

