1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
b6 9. e4 Bxg3
{ The third most common move. However, opening the h-file can only benefit White. }
10. hxg3 g6
{ The best move. If instead  10...h6  11.e5  Nd7  12.g4!   If  10...dxe4  11.Nxe4  h6  12.dxc5   If  10...cxd4??  11.e5!  wins on the spot. }
11. e5
{ Natural and best. An alternative idea is  11.Ne5  Bb7  12.Nxc6  Bxc6  13.e5  Ne4  14.Nf3  with the idea of Qc1 to Qh6. }
11... Ng4
{ If  11...Nh5?!  12.g4  Nf4  13.Bb5!  attacking the loose knight  13...Nxg2+  14.Kf1  and Black will lose one of the knights.   If  11...Nd7  12.Qe2  with typical play. }
12. Nf1
{ White has a choice of moves here, but this is strongest. The idea is to go to h2 and get rid of the Black's knight and then continue with the kingside attack. This is an unexplored position, but let's continue the line for a bit longer to demonstrate White's attacking plan. }
12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Qe7 { Aiming for ...Qb4+. } 14. a3 f6 15. Rh4 f5 16. N1h2
Nxh2 17. Rxh2 Bd7 18. Qd2 Na5 19. Qh6 Nb3 20. Rd1
{ White will cotninue with Bc2 to Bxb3, Ng5, and Rc1, playing on both sides of the board. }
