1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
b6 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Bb7 12. dxc5
{ The bishop is attacked three times. } 12... Bxc5 13. Qa4
{ Attacking the knight and activating the Queen on the 4th rank. Black has basically tried three moves here. }
13... Qc8
{ Natural and roughly as common as ...Rc8. However, the Queen leaves the crucial h5-d8 diagonal and this allows for the London gift. As we saw in the tactics section, even worse is  13...Qe8??  14.Bxh7!  and lights out. }
14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Qh4+ Kg8 16. Ng5 Rd8 17. Qh7+ Kf8 18. Qh8+ Ke7 19. Qxg7
{ Threatening Qxf7# and forcing... } 19... Rf8 20. O-O-O
{ White is winning here. Stockfish now tells Black to sac a piece on d4, and after Rxd4 and Qxd4 White is not even down material with a continued attack and a completely winning position. }
