b6 9. e4 Be7 10. dxc5 bxc5 { The correct recapture. } 11. O-O
{ Interestingly White scores excellently in Lichess, but poorly at master level. Black has several continuations here, but White's general plan is to take on d5 and play Re1. }
11... Bb7
{ The most natural move   11...Re8  This slightly mysterious move is given by Barrish & Sielecki  12.Re1   11...Qb6  12.Re1   11...Nh5  12.Nd4  cxd4  13.Qxh5  dxc3  14.bxc3  d4  15.cxd4  Qxd4  16.Bb5  Bb7  17.Rfd1  . }
12. Re1
{ The best move order, though here White's point is not to play e5, but take with exd5 next. Notice that if Black takes he ends up worse after  12...dxe4  13.Nxe4  Nxe4  14.Bxe4  Qxd1  15.Raxd1  and White is better due to the more active position and the weak pawn on c5. }
