[White "9. Classical Setup with ...Bd6, Main Line"]
[Black "Alliestein (3771) vs. Stockfish (3807), 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ The annotations to this marvelous game follow GM Matthew Sadler's & WIM Natasha Regan's in their video on their fantastic Game Changer Youtube channel. It's important to realize that this was the only move prescribed to Alliestein and the rest was its own choice... }
1... Nf6 2. d4 e6
{ The Nimzo-QID setup and here the neural net chooses the London Attack! } 3.
Bf4 d5 4. e3 c5 5. Nbd2 { This is slightly non-standard, not caring about c4. }
5... Nc6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3 b6 9. e4 { Allie goes for our main line. }
9... Be7 10. e5 Nh5 11. Ng5 { Allie goes for the active Ng5. } 11... Bxg5 12.
Qxh5 g6 13. Qe2 cxd4 14. h4 Be7
{ In contrast to Svane's ...Bxd2, Stockfish chooses the defensive plan with ...Be7.   Next, we'll look at  14...Bh6  15.h5  dxc3  16.bxc3  Bg7  17.f4  Sadler says that his engines didn't want Nf3 in his engine games. Stoofvlees chose f4 with the following example line   17.Kf1!?  Stockfish's choice in the engine games, with the following example line against Stoofvlees  17...d4  18.c4  Qd7  19.Re1  Nb4  20.Be4  Bb7  21.Qf3  Bxe4  22.Nxe4  Qc6  23.h6  Bh8  24.Nf6+  With mate to follow  17...Bd7  18.Bh4  Qc7  19.O-O  Na5  20.Rac1  Qc5+  21.Kh2  Rac8  22.Rf3  Followed by Rh3 & Bf6 }
15. h5 Kg7
{ Stockfish is "following" Georgiev's recommendation...   15...g5  Sadler says he likes this better  16.O-O  dxc3  17.bxc3  f6  18.exf6  Bxf6 }
16. Rd1 dxc3 17. bxc3 Bb7
{ 17...Bd7  Sadler likes this better  18.Nf3  One idea   18.Nf1  Another idea, coming to e3 and then g4  18...Na5  19.Ne3  Ba4  20.Rc1  a6  21.Ng4 }
18. Qg4 Rg8 19. Qf4
{ Alliestein chooses this idea instead   19.f4  In this position both Stoofvlees and Stockfish chose this instead  19...Qc8  20.hxg6  Stockfish   20.Bh4  Stoofvlees  20...Ba6  21.c4  Kf8  22.O-O  Qc7  23.Nf3  20...hxg6  21.Bh4  Ba6  22.Bf6+  Kf8  23.Nf3  Bxd3  24.Rxd3  Ke8  25.Rh7  Rf8  26.Ng5  Nd8  27.Nxf7  Rxf7  28.Qxg6 }
19... Bg5 20. h6+ { The thorn pawn has been established. } 20... Kh8
{ The idea is to simply give back the f-pawn   20...Kf8  Another option for Black, but now  21.Qg4  With Nf3, Bf4, Ng5 coming  21...Rc8  22.Nf3  Be7  23.Bf4  Qd7  24.O-O  Rh8  25.Bg5  Bxg5  26.Qxg5  Qe7  27.Qf4  Rc7  28.Ng5  Na5  29.Rfe1  Ke8  30.Re3  Followed by Rf3 and Black is done because f7 or h7 falls and then it's over. }
21. Qxf7 Qe7 22. Qf3 Qa3
{ Stockfish goes pawn grabbing   22...d4!?  Sadler mentions that his engine games were investigating d4, after which Black gets at least some counterplay  23.Ne4  dxc3  24.Qg4  Bd2+  25.Nxd2  cxd2+  26.Rxd2  Nb4  27.Bc4 }
23. Qg4 Bxd2+ 24. Rxd2 Qc1+ 25. Rd1 Qxc3+ 26. Kf1 Rgf8
{ 26...Nxe5  27.Qb4!!  A beautiful deflection  27...Qxb4  28.Bxe5+  Rg7  29.hxg7+  Kg8  30.Bxg6  hxg6  31.Rc1  Qc4+   31...Qb5+!!  32.Kg1  Qc6!!  33.Rxc6  Bxc6  Now the bishop is not on b7 anymore  32.Rxc4  dxc4  33.Rh8+  Kf7  34.g8=Q+  Rxg8  35.Rh7+  Picks up the bishop. }
27. Rh4
{ The star move. The rook turns out to be very important. It stops ...Nb4 & ...Nd4. White plans Bf4-Bg5-Bf6.   27.Qxe6  Ba6!  28.Bxa6  Qxg3! }
27... Rae8 { 27...Nxe5??  28.Qb4  Qxb4  29.Bxe5+ } 28. Kg1 Qa3
{ To play ...Ba6. } 29. Qe2 Rc8
{ 29...Nb4  30.Bb5  Ba6  31.Rxb4  Qxb4  32.Bxa6 } 30. Bf4 Nd4 31. Qg4 Nf5 32.
Bg5 Qb2
{ 32...Nxh4  33.Qxe6  Rc7  34.Bf6+  Rxf6  35.Qxf6+  Kg8  36.Qd8+  Qf8  37.Qxc7 }
33. Qb4 { Allie offers a Queen exchange. } 33... Qxb4
{ 33...Qxe5  34.Rf4!  Qc3  35.g4!  Qxb4  36.Rxb4  Nd6  37.Be7  +- } 34. Rxb4
{ This endgame is great for White due to Black's knight lacking outposts. }
34... Rc7 35. Ra4 Ra8 36. Rf4 Kg8 37. g4 Ne7 38. Rf6 Nc6
{ 38...Bc8  39.Bb5!  Threatening Be8 to Bf7+ } 39. Rxe6
{ After this, f4-f5 is even more dangerous. } 39... Nd4 40. Rf6 Rf8 41. Rxf8+
{ 41.Kg2  Sadler says all his engines went for this  41...Rxf6  42.exf6 } 41...
Kxf8 42. Kg2 Ne6 43. Bd2 Kf7 44. Kg3 Nc5 45. Be3
{ Allie just gives up the two bishops and allows the opposite-colored bishop endgame. }
45... Nxd3 46. Rxd3
