1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
b6 9. e4 Be7 10. e5 Nh5 11. Ng5 Bxg5 12. Qxh5 g6 13. Qe2 cxd4 14. h4 Bh6 15. h5
dxc3 16. bxc3 Bg7 { This seems to be the main line. } 17. Nf3
{ White has at least three options here and this is the first one. This position has been reached only 11 times in the Lichess database and White scores very well. However, as GM Matthew Sadler mentioned in his video on the Alliestein vs. Stockfish game, his engines in their engine games actually prefer different moves here with Stoofvlees going for  17.f4  with the idea of Bh4 and Stockfish going for  17.Kf1!?  . I will give the other two lines as alternatives and leave the choice to you. }
17... d4
{ One of Black's most common tries. We'll look at some more in the next line. }
18. Be4 Bb7 19. Rd1 Qc7 20. h6
{ In Alphazero's footsteps! This is known as the 'thorn pawn', restricting Black's king, getting very close to promotion, and in this particular case also completely shutting out Black's bishop. }
20... Bh8 21. cxd4
{ White has a clear edge due to his thorn pawn and the position of Black's dark-squared bishop. }
