24... a6 { This is too cooperative. } 25. Ng5 Qd8 26. Be4
{ Exchanging Black's best piece. A typical Alphazero idea as well. Basically the more exchanges happen the more the absence of Black's bishop is felt. }
26... Bxe4 27. Nxe4 { The knight is headed towards d6 or even f6. } 27... b5
28. a3 Nd5 { Black literally has only one good piece. } 29. Rc6 Qa5 30. Qf3
{ Defending the a-pawn. } 30... b4 31. axb4 Qxb4
{ Black managed to create a passed pawn, but he's not going to get to do much with it. }
32. R6c4 Qe7 33. Bf2 { Activating the bishop and threatening Bc5. } 33... Rfb8
34. Nc3 { White tries to exchange Black's best piece again. } 34... Nxc3 35.
R4xc3 Re8 36. g4 { Total domination. Once White plays g5 it's over. } 36...
Rab8 37. Kg2 Qd8 38. g5 Qd7 39. Ra1
{ White can take all the time in the world to try to restore 'material equality'. }
39... Ra8 40. Rd1 Qe7 41. Bc5 Qc7 42. Bd6
{ Putting a piece on an outpost. It also keeps an eye on the potential march of the a-pawn. }
42... Qb6 43. Rdc1 Rad8 44. Kh3 { 44.R1c2  Was better, with Rc7 next. } 44...
Qb2
{ 44...Rxd6  45.Rb3!  An important intermediate move, driving the Queen away. }
45. Rc7 a5 46. R1c4 { Black decided he's had enough... } *

