[White "10. Classical Setup with 6...Nh5!?"]
[Black "6...Nh5!?: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Nh5
{ Surprise. This move resembles the Exchange Caro: So System lines, but is slightly different. Black hasn't exchanged on d4 yet and opened the e-file for White. He intends to exchange at the right time to force cxd4 with an Exchange Slav structure, instead. This has been recommended by FM Yuriy Krykun's accelerated QID course, here on Chessable, though, given our lines against QID, it can only be entered from the 1...d5 move order. It's been played ~3800x.   6...Qb6  This move doesn't make a ton of sense since Black has already locked in his bishop.  7.Rb1  Nh5!?  an independent idea  8.dxc5!?   6...h6  This move can have two independent ideas. Either to expand with ...g5 & then play ...Nh5 or just play ...Nh5, having taken away Bg5.  7.Bd3  Most likely moves are actually ...Bd6 and ...Be7.  7...g5!?  An independent move that needs to be checked.   7...Nh5!?  The other independent idea, but it doesn't quite work due to the weakening of the h5-e8 diagonal. Here White has no choice, but to go Be5.  8.Be5  Nxe5  Black invariably takes since ...f6 is met with Bg6+!   8...f6??  9.Bg6+  9.Nxe5  Nf6  Black has to return the knight and even though he did gain the bishop pair, he lost the fight over the e5 square.   9...g6??  10.Nxg6  White picks up at least a piece.  10.f4  In effect White has exchanged the dark-squared bishop for one of Black's knights that can fight for e5 and can now set up the stonewall and play like usual.  8.Bg3  Nh5  Black wants the bishop pair.  9.Be5  Nxe5  Let's see what happens if Black is consistent in carrying out his plan.   9...Nf6  10.Bb5  10.Nxe5  10...Nf6  11.f4  White breaks immediately and intends O-O and perhaps Qf3, Bb5+ with pressure on the f-file.  11...Bd7  12.O-O  Be7  13.a4 }
7. Bg5 { Best move. } 7... f6
{ This is Black's idea.   7...Be7  White never minds this exchange of his bad bishop against Black's good one.  8.Bxe7  Qxe7  9.Ne5   7...Qb6  This doesn't really work.  8.dxc5  Qxc5   8...Bxc5  9.b4  Bd6  10.Nc4   8...Qxb2?  9.Nd4  Attacking the stranded knight and intending Nb5, attacking c7.  9...g6?  Just to demonstrate.   9...Nf6  10.Nb5   9...Nxd4  10.cxd4   9...Qxc3  10.Rc1  Qa5  11.Qxh5  10.Nb5  9.e4  No game has reached here.  9...Be7  10.exd5  exd5  11.Nb3  Qd6  12.Bxe7  Qxe7+  13.Qe2  Qxe2+  14.Bxe2  Nf4  15.Bf1  Kd8  16.h4  White has an advantage in this endgame due to Black's IQP. He can play g3, Kd2, Nfd4 to blockade the pawn and eventually aim to capture it. Needless to say, the practical likelihood of getting here is close to zero. }
8. Bh4 g6 9. Bd3
{ Compared to the number above, only 187 games have reached here. } 9... cxd4
{ Black exchanges in the center only now. The point is that White is forced to recapture with the c-pawn, so as not to allow for ...Nf4. }
10. cxd4
{ This is quite non-standard, compared to all the Exchange Caro structures we have. This is also evidenced by the fact that most White players have erred with exd4 @@StartBracket@@63 games versus only 17 with cxd4@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Bd6
{ Krykun's suggested move.   10...Be7  So's and van Foreest's choice.  11.O-O  O-O  12.Rc1  Bd7   12...e5  This has been tried a few times, but doesn't do too much after  13.dxe5  fxe5  14.Bxe7  Qxe7  15.Qb3!  Pinning the d-pawn and making possible Ne4.  13.a3  Rc8  So's choice.   13...Ng7  See the model game Bluebaum - van Foreest.  14.Nb3  14.b4  With Nb3 next, is natural and good.   14.Nb1!?  Giri's move, rerouting the knight to the much more active square on c3, where it belongs in the Exchange Slav structures. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Rc1
{ Very natural, putting the rook on the open c-file. Only 8 games have reached here.   12.e4!?  An interesting dynamic try.  12...g5  13.Nxg5  Nf4  14.Nxh7  Kxh7  15.exd5+  Nxd3  16.dxc6  Nf4  17.Qf3  With best play this should be equal, but it's a real mess.  17...Nd5  18.Ne4  bxc6  19.Rac1 }
12... Qe7
{ Krykun's move, but this hasn't been played in a single game. The point is to cover the h-pawn so Black can push ...g5 without having to fear Nxg5 and Qxh5.   12...Bd7  The most common choice in other lines.  13.g4!?  Can be tried here.  13...Ng7  14.a3  White intends b4, Nb3 and Nc5.   12...Ng7  Reactivating the knight via f5 is an idea.  13.Bg3  Nf5  14.Bxf5  exf5  15.Qa4  White's threatening Rxc6.   12...Qb6  13.Nb3  This is where the knight wants to be anyway.  13...Bd7  14.a3 }
13. Nb3 { The knight wants to eventually go to c5. } 13... g5
{ Black aims for complications and now play is quite unintuitive and concrete for both sides.   13...Bd7  14.e4  White can start opening the position. }
14. Ne1 Qe8 15. Be2 Nf4 16. exf4 gxh4 17. g3
{ Not the only move, White could also try Rc3, with the idea of Rh3, or the direct Bh5.   17.Rc3   17.Bh5 }
17... Qg6 { Black is threatening ...Bxf4. } 18. Ng2 Qg7
{ This is where Krykun stops his trainable line with the following comment: 'The threat now is ...h3 followed by ...Bxf4. If White just goes Kh1, Black can simply take on g3, then play ...Bd7 and he will be perfectly fine. Instead, if White takes on h4, we take on f4 with the bishop and again our position is simply good.' Let's go a few moves further.   18...hxg3  19.fxg3  White has the f5 break.   18...h3  19.Nh4  Qg7  20.Qd2 }
19. Nxh4
{ White simply grabs the h-pawn to prevent h3 and allows black to take the f-pawn in return. }
19... Bxf4
{ This is the position about which Krykun says that Black's position is simply good. However, the engines aren't that sure... }
20. Rc3
{ White has a small objective edge, but his position is much easier to play. He intends to play Bb5, Re1 and can also play Kh1 and an eventual f4 and even f5. }
