1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Nh5
{ Surprise. This move resembles the Exchange Caro: So System lines, but is slightly different. Black hasn't exchanged on d4 yet and opened the e-file for White. He intends to exchange at the right time to force cxd4 with a Exchange Slav structure, instead. This has been recommended by FM Yuryi Krykun in his accelerated QID course, here on Chessable, though, given our lines against QID, it can only be entered from the 1...d5 move order. }
7. Bg5 { Best move. } 7... Qb6
{ This was given as an interesting alternative by Krykun, but it doesn't really work.   7...Be7  White never minds this exchange of his bad bishop against Black's good one.  8.Bxe7  Qxe7  9.Ne5  Nf6  10.Bd3  With a typical position. }
8. dxc5 Qxc5
{ 8...Bxc5  9.b4  Bd6  10.Nc4   8...Qxb2?  9.Nd4  Attacking the stranded knight and intending Nb5, attacking c7.  9...g6?  Just to demonstrate.   9...Nf6  10.Nb5   9...Nxd4  10.cxd4   9...Qxc3  10.Rc1  Qa5  11.Qxh5  10.Nb5 }
9. e4 { No game has reached here. } 9... Be7 10. exd5 exd5 11. Nb3 Qd6 12. Bxe7
Qxe7+ 13. Qe2 Qxe2+ 14. Bxe2 Nf4 15. Bf1 Kd8 16. h4
{ White has an advantage in this endgame due to Black's IQP. He can play g3, Kd2, Nfd4 to blockade the pawn and eventually aim to capture it. }
