[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Early ...e6: No Retreat! "]
[Black "Why We Don't Retreat: Black's ...b6 plans"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 e6
{ Black plays an early ...e6 which can be connected to one of four  (!)  types of equalizing ideas:  a. swap bishops with ...Ba6;   b. play ...Bb7 and ...Ne4;    c. move order us into the old main line.   Finally, Black can try to adopt a setup that allows him to get in ...e5, which is considered in the next informational line.   In general, the plans considered in this chapter are the toughest nuts to crack for White if he plays the usual moves. Instead, we will sidestep all of them with a completely different setup. }
3. e3 Bd6 4. Bg3
{ The typical retreat. From this move order White can try Bxd6 with the idea of Qg4, but this can't be relied on since Black can start with 2... Nf6. }
4... Nf6 5. Nd2 O-O
{ Black finishes developing his kingside and can now go for one of the two plans. }
6. Ngf3
{ The most standard move, but White can also try the trickier  6.Bd3  instead. It is slightly better, but doesn't change the picture all too much. }
6... b6
{ Black's first set of plans is connected to this move, recommended by Ntirlis and Georgiev. The idea is either to   a. swap bishops with ...Ba6;   b. play ...Bb7 and ...Ne4; or   c. move order us into the old main line. }
7. Bd3 Bb7
{ The first plan is  7...Ba6  to exchange the light-squared bishops and weaken White's attacking potential. The text move is connected with two plans. The idea is to control the e4-square and threaten ...Ne4 next. }
8. c3 Ne4
{ Georgiev's recommendation. The third plan is to move order us into the old main line aka bad Pillsbury with  8...c5  9.Ne5  Nc6!  10.f4  Ne7!  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Early ...e6: No Retreat! "]
[Black "Why We Don't Retreat: Black's ...Qc7 & ...e5 plan"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 e6
{ Black could also start with  2...Nf6  and play ...e6 on the next move. } 3.
e3 Bd6 4. Bg3 Nf6 5. Nd2 O-O
{ Black could try for the same idea without castling, but, as we will see, that would fail to Bb5+. }
6. Ngf3 c5
{ Having first developed the kingside, Black goes for the ...c5 break. } 7. c3
Qc7 { Black intends ...Nbd7! & ...e5, after which he equalizes comfortably. }
8. Bd3
{ A normal move, but this is what the plan is directed against. White's best chance is dxc5 but the game is still equal with best play:   8.dxc5!?  Bxg3  9.hxg3  e5!?  10.b4  b6   or  8.dxc5!?  Bxg3  9.hxg3  Qxc5  10.Bd3  h6  . }
8... Nbd7
{ Black plays ...Nbd7 and not ...Nc6 since then the Queen will control c5, making dxc5 by White less desirable. They will take on g3, get ...e5 in, and equalize. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Early ...e6: No Retreat! "]
[Black "Anish Giri vs. Nikita Vitiugov, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ This game was played at Wijk an Zee. Giri was rated 2768, Vitiugov 2747! Giri's approach to the opening has deeply influenced our lines in this chapter. }
1... d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6
{ Black goes for the early ...e6 & ...Bd6. } 5. Nbd2
{ Following Rubinstein's and Carlsen's lead, Giri does not retreat! } 5... Bxf4
{ Black captures. } 6. exf4
{ White has doubled f-pawns, but an iron grip on e5. } 6... O-O 7. c3
{ Giri makes a useful move, anticipating Black's main idea of ...b6 and ...Ba6, wanting to play Bxa6 from the starting square! }
7... b6 { Black gets ready for ...Ba6. } 8. h4
{ Another useful 'waiting' move, aiming for h5 and h6. If  8.Bd3?!  Ba6  and Black is ok. }
8... c5 { Black waits as well. } 9. h5 h6 { Black stops h6. } 10. Ne5 Bb7
{ Black changes tack and goes for ...Bb7   10...Ba6?!  One could argue that this would be too late since White could try...  11.Bxa6  Nxa6  12.Qe2  Nb8  13.O-O-O  With Kb1 and g4 next and a breakthrough imminent on the kingside with g5. }
11. Ndf3
{ The point of this precise move is to allow recapturing on d4 with a piece. White generally doesn't want an IQP in this structure.   11.Bd3  Seems natural, but is, in fact, less precise due to.  11...cxd4  12.cxd4  Nc6  Threatening ...Nb4. }
11... Nc6 { 11...cxd4  12.Qxd4 } 12. Nxc6
{ 12.Bd3  Here White could finally accept the IQP.  12...cxd4  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  14.cxd4  Rc8  15.O-O  White is more comfortable and can play for g4. }
12... Bxc6
{ White's position is easier to play, partly because he has total control over e5 and his bishop has more potential. }
13. Bd3 Rc8
{ 13...Qd6!?  14.Qe2  Setting up a trap.  14...Qxf4??  15.Ne5  cxd4  16.g3  Qg5  17.Nf3!  Qg4  18.Rh4  And the Queen is trapped. }
14. Qe2 Rc7 15. a3
{ This wasn't necessary and gives Black's bishop the a4 and b3 squares.   15.g3  White could hide away the king on g2 after Kf1-Kg2.   15.Ne5 }
15... Ba4 16. Kf1 Bb3 17. Kg1 Qd6 18. Qd2
{ 18.g3  A very natural move in this position, but Giri wanted to keep this square for his rook. }
18... a5 19. Re1 Rb8 20. Rh3 Ba4
{ 20...b5?!  21.f5   21.dxc5  Palliser gives the following.  21...Qxc5  22.f5  exf5?  23.Nd4!  White's practically winning here. }
21. Bb1 { White threatens Qd3. } 21... Ne4 { Shutting the diagonal down. } 22.
Qe3 { Threatening to win a pawn on e4. } 22... b5 23. dxc5
{ 23.Bxe4  White could've and probably should've taken on e4 here.  23...dxe4  24.Qxe4  b4  25.dxc5  Rxc5  26.axb4  axb4  27.Ne5  bxc3  28.bxc3 }
23... Qxc5 24. Nd4
{ This is ok, but White could've grabbed on e4, again.   24.Bxe4  Qxe3  25.Rxe3  dxe4  26.Rxe4  b4  27.axb4  axb4  28.Ne5!  f6  29.Ng6  Black is in some trouble since White is threatening to take on e6 and b4. }
24... b4 25. axb4 axb4 26. Bxe4 { Finally Giri takes. } 26... dxe4 27. Qxe4
{ White is still the one calling the shots, being currently a pawn up. } 27...
Bd7 28. g4
{ This was the mistake that cost Giri the win.   28.Rg3  Using the g3-square. }
28... Rbc8 { Black starts building up pressure on the c-pawn. } 29. Ree3 Qa5
30. Kh2 { The game has equalized and Giri offered a draw that was accepted. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Early ...e6: No Retreat! "]
[Black "No Retreat: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6
{ 2...e6  Black can try to challenge our bishop without developing the knights.  3.e3  Bd6  Played ~68 500x.  4.Nf3  Here we will start with this knight.   4.Bxd6  This move can be tried and we will take it as an alternative. It's a good weapon for Blitz since most Black players won't have seen this and will react with the natural, but worse ...Qxd6. See the trainable line.  4...Bxf4   4...Nf6  5.Nbd2  Transposes to the main lines.  5.exf4  From here on you might think that the game is similar to the main line, except Black has the extra option of not developing the knight to f6. However, White has extra options as well, namely a quick Nc3 and O-O-O.  5...Qd6  The main independent option. Black intends to meet the typical g3 with ...Qb4+.  6.Qd2  Nf6  7.Nc3  O-O  8.O-O-O  White is doing well here with ideas of Rg1 and h3, g4-g5. }
3. e3 e6 4. Nd2
{ Here White faces a choice between starting with Nf3 or Nd2. I prefer Nd2 which prevents Black from playing both the immediate ...Ne4 and ...Nh5. Neither of those moves is particularly good, but it still makes sense to just cut them out. However, there is nothing wrong with starting with Nf3 either. }
4... Bd6
{ Black challenges our bishop straight away.   4...c5  This doesn't quite work as an independent move, and only makes sense if Black wants to transpose back to lines with ...Nc6.  5.Ngf3  Bd6?!  This is sort of a mistake. Black should arrive at this position without ...c5 played. Here White has...   5...c4  The sort of move people will try online...  6.c3  White generally aims for a quick b3 break.  6...b5  7.Ne5  Nbd7  8.Qf3!  Controlling e4.  8...Nxe5  9.dxe5  Nd7  10.h4  6.Bb5+!  Played only 66! times.  6...Nc6  Black is forced to play ...Nc6 and now can't play any of the trendy equalizing ideas. This means White could either take the knight off, play dxc5 or simply retreat the bishop.   6...Bd7??  7.Bxd6  Bxb5  8.Bxc5   6...Nbd7??  7.Bxd6  7.Bg3  O-O  Black castles.   7...Qc7  As we know, this plan doesn't work with the knight on c6.  8.dxc5  Bxg3  9.hxg3  8.c3  Qc7  If Black does something else White will retreat the bishop to d3.   8...Ne7  9.Bd3  9.dxc5  Bxg3  10.hxg3  e5  11.b4  White is a pawn up. We've seen this before, except here White has the bishop developed already, albeit to b5 not d3. }
5. Ngf3
{ This, the Rubinstein-inspired and Carlsen-endorsed No Retreat! idea, cuts out all of Black's trendy equalizing tries. Compared to the retreat which has been played over 125 000x! this has only been played around 11 000x. Black reacts in one of two ways, either they take the bishop off immediately with ...Bxf4, or they wait by castling. Other moves can just be met with Ne5 & Bd3, with more or less standard play, though with nuances, since White has the bishop still on f4. }
5... Bxf4
{ This is slightly more common with ~4500 games. It's also GM Kiril Georgiev's recommendation.   5...O-O  This is slightly less common with ~4400 games. It's the main move at master level and GM Eljanov's recommendation.  6.c3!  White makes a useful move and offers Black another chance to take on f4. If Black doesn't soon, White will just jump with the knight to e5, having saved a tempo. He can then conceivably even conitinue with something like Qf3-Qh3.  6...b6  Eljanov's suggestion.   6...c5  This seems like the critical move here, played ~950x.  7.Ne5!?  White just jumps to e5.  7...Qc7  Black starts putting pressure on e5.  8.Bd3  Nbd7  9.Ndf3  White guards e5 with a piece, forsaking e4.  9...Ne4  Most common and perhaps also best.  10.O-O  b6   10...f6?!  Black players frequently can't resist.  11.Nxd7  Bxd7  12.Bxe4  Bxf4   12...dxe4  13.Bxd6  Qxd6  14.dxc5  Qe7  15.Nd2  13.Bxd5   13.Bxh7+  Kxh7  14.exf4  Qxf4  15.dxc5  Is another way of playing it.  Bxh2+  14.Nxh2  exd5  15.dxc5  Qxc5  16.Qb3  White's rook comes on d-file and he has good play against Black's IQP.  11.h4  Harry goes again.  7.Ne5!?  White just jumps to e5. Eljanov doesn't consider this natural move which has been played around 100x. Here we are also following the model game Naiditsch vs. Halkias.  7...c5  8.h4  Qc7  9.h5  Nbd7  Black is threatening to take on e5. No game has reached here.   9...Nc6  10.Nxc6  Was played in Naiditsch vs. Halkias.  10.h6  White starts with the pawn push, to invite Black to make a mistake.  10...g6   10...Nxe5?  11.dxe5!  Bxe5  12.hxg7  Kxg7  13.Bh6+  Kg8  14.Bd3  11.Ndf3  With a safe edge in a typical London position. White intends h6 next and will then see what Black does. }
6. exf4 O-O
{ Black's main move, played around half of the time. One of Black's main plans is ...b6 and ...Ba6. White would like to meet this with Bxa6 from the starting square.   6...c5  Second most common, played around 1000x.  7.dxc5!  It's important to realize that White almost never wants to accept the IQP in this structure!  7...Qc7  8.g3  Qxc5  9.Bd3  Nc6  10.c3  Preventing ...Nb4.  10...O-O  11.O-O  b6  Most common move, but it's not very good and not played at master level since it takes the square away from the Queen. Basically any move here, White can play Qe2 or Rfe1.   11...Re8  Second most common.  12.Re1   11...Bd7  Capablanca's and Maroczy's move.  12.Qe2  Or Rfe1.  12.Nb3  Qd6  13.Qe2  White can centralize both rooks next with a pleasant advantage.  13...Bb7  Most common, but perhaps not best.  14.Rfe1  Rfe8  15.Rad1  This position has been reached in 6 games. White can continue with h4, Nbd4 etc.   6...Qd6  Third most common move, Black attacks the f-pawn immediately.  7.g3  O-O   7...c5  8.dxc5  Likely transposes.  8.Bg2  Keeping the bishops on the board! It's not easy for Black to find a plan here.   8.Bd3  This is standardly played, but here it will just get exchanged.  8...c5  Most common move, but White can just disregard this.  9.O-O  cxd4  10.Nb3  White wants to take on d4 with the b-knight! This is an unexplored position where you can just play chess.   6...b6  Black goes for the bishop exchange immediately.  7.c3  The standard response. Black has really nothing better than to transpose.  7...Ba6??  8.Bxa6  Nxa6  9.Qa4+  Qd7  10.Qxa6 }
7. c3
{ Following Giri's lead we make a useful waiting move. This is far less common than Bd3.   7.Bd3  b6  Black will get the bishops exchanged even if White plays Qe2.  8.Qe2  c5  9.c3  a5  10.O-O  Ba6  11.Bxa6  Nxa6  12.Rfe1  With rough equality. }
7... b6 { 7...c5  Transposes after.  8.dxc5 } 8. h4
{ Following Giri, we make another useful move, gaining space on the kingside and intending h5 to h6. }
8... c5
{ 8...Ba6  9.Bxa6  Nxa6  10.Qe2  The Queen develops with tempo.  10...Nb8  11.h5  h6  White has a pleasant choice between Ne5, O-O-O and even Rg1.  12.Rg1!?  Nxh5  13.Qe3  Nf6  14.g4  White is going to play O-O-O and rip things open, in some order. }
9. h5 h6 10. Ne5 Bb7
{ 10...Ba6?!  11.Bxa6  Nxa6  12.Qe2  Nb8  White can play O-O-O and continue with g4.  13.O-O-O }
11. Ndf3
{ A very precise move, allowing recapturing on d4 with a piece and avoiding the IQP. }
