1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 e6
{ Black can try to challenge our bishop without developing the knight first. }
3. e3 Bd6 { Played ~68 500x. } 4. Nf3 { Here we will start with this knight. }
4... Bxf4 { 4...Nf6  5.Nbd2  transposes to the main lines. } 5. exf4
{ From here on you might think that the game is similar to the main line, except Black has the extra option of not developing their knight to f6. However, White has extra options as well, namely a quick Nc3 and O-O-O! }
5... Qd6
{ The main independent option. Black intends to meet the typical g3 with ...Qb4+. }
6. Qd2 { Defending the pawn and covering b4. } 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. O-O-O
{ White is doing well here with ideas of Rg1, h3, g4 to g5. } *

