1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 e6
{ Black can try to challenge our bishop without developing the knight. } 3. e3
Bd6 { Played ~68 500x. } 4. Bxd6
{ This move can be tried and we will take it as an alternative. It's a good weapon for Blitz since most Black players won't have seen this and will react with the natural, but worse ...Qxd6. }
4... Qxd6
{ About 3x as common as ...cxd6, but not as good.   4...cxd6  5.c4  White's intending cxd5, if allowed.  5...dxc4  6.Bxc4  Nf6  7.Nf3  O-O   7...Qb6  8.Qe2  8.O-O  +=  White has a slight edge. }
5. Qg4
{ White attacks g7, forcing some sort of a concession in the form of ...g6, ...Qf8, or ...Kf8, and then continues with Nc3 and O-O-O. }
5... g6 { Most common.   5...Kf8  6.Nc3   5...Qf8  6.Qg3  c6  7.Nf3 } 6. Nc3
{ White threatens Nb5. } 6... a6 { 6...Nf6  Most common.  7.Qh4  Nbd7  8.Nf3 }
7. Bd3 Nf6 8. Qh4 Nbd7 9. Nf3
{ A typical Blitz tactic follows when Black doesn't castle and White plays Ne5, for example  9...b5  10.Ne5  Nxe5?  11.Qxf6!  Nxd3+  12.cxd3  leaving White with a great position with Rc1 next. }
