1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 { This is the far more common move. } 3. e3 e6
{ Black goes for the early ...e6 with the knight already developed. } 4. Nd2
{ Here White faces a choice between starting with Nf3 or Nd2. I prefer Nd2 which prevents Black from playing both the immediate ...Ne4 and ...Nh5. Neither of those moves is particularly good, but it still makes sense to just cut them out. However, there is nothing wrong with starting with Nf3 either. }
4... c5
{ This doesn't quite work as an independent move, and only makes sense if Black wants to transpose back to lines with ...Nc6 }
5. Ngf3 { Development first. } 5... c4
{ This is the sort of move people will try in Blitz... } 6. c3
{ In these structures White generally aims for a quick b3 or sometimes even b4 break. }
6... b5 7. Ne5 Nbd7 8. Qf3 { Controlling e4. } 8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 Nd7 10. h4
{ This is a completely unexplored line, but let's look at best play, demonstrating some typical ideas  10...Be7  11.Qg3  and Black better not castle into Bh6  11...g6  12.Be2  h5  13.a3  Prophylaxis against the coming ...a5 and ...b4  13...Nc5  14.Bg5!  a typical idea that also occurs in some other lines  14...Bxg5  15.hxg5  and White's idea is Qf4 and g4  15...a5  16.Qf4  Bb7  17.Rh4  and White can always just put the king on  f1  . }
