[White "11. Early ...e6: No Retreat! "]
[Black "Akiba Rubinstein vs. Savielly Tartakower, 1922"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This game is from the London 1922 tournament. Rubinstein shows us the way. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Nbd2 { Rubinstein No Retreat! } 5...
Bxf4 6. exf4 c5
{ Black goes for the natural break. This was later repeated in Rubinstein-Capablanca in the same tournament. Capablanca deviated on the 11th move and the players agreed to a draw a few moves later. }
7. dxc5
{ Instead of protecting his d-pawn with c3 and allowing for an isolated pawn after ...cxd4, Rubinstein plays the very modern dxc5, grabbing a pawn and creating a 3-2 on the Queenside. }
7... Qc7 8. g3 Qxc5 9. Bd3 Nc6 10. c3 O-O 11. O-O h6
{ Tartakower's move, but why?   11...b5  Capablanca's move, not wasting any time with starting the minority attack.  12.Ne5   12.a3  White would have a safe edge here with Qe2 and Nb3 next.  Bb7  13.Qe2  Draw agreed. }
12. Nb3 { 12.Re1  Could've been considered. } 12... Qb6 13. Re1 Bd7 14. Qe2
Rae8 15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. fxe5
{ Now White's pawns aren't even doubled and he has a nice edge. } 16... Nh7
{ The knight is lucky that it at least has h7 to go to. } 17. h4 f5 18. Nd4
{ White is just completely dominant. } 18... Re7 19. f4 Kh8 20. h5
{ Perhaps White could've improved the king first.   20.Kh1 } 20... Rg8 21. Kf2
Nf8 22. Rh1 Be8 23. Rag1 Nd7 24. g4
{ 24.b4  White should first stop counterplay with ...Nc5 and then proceed with Nb5 to Nd6. }
24... Nc5 25. Bb1
{ 25.gxf5  Nxd3+  26.Qxd3  Qxb2+  27.Qc2  Qxc2+  28.Nxc2  exf5  29.Ke2  Rc7  30.Kd3  Is a better path for White. }
25... fxg4 26. Kg3 { 26.Rxg4 } 26... Rf8 { 26...Ne4+  27.Bxe4  dxe4  28.Rh4 }
27. Rh2 Ref7 28. Rf1 { 28.Rf2 } 28... a6
{ Black misses his chance.   28...Ne4+ } 29. Qxg4 { 29.Bg6 } 29... Bb5 30. Rf3
{ 30.Rff2 } 30... Rf5 { An inexplicable blunder. } 31. Nxf5 exf5 32. Bxf5
{ 32.Qg6!!  White threatens both Qxb6 and Bxf5.  32...Qxg6+  33.hxg6  White's completely winning. }
32... Rxf5 33. Qxf5 Ne4+ { Finally the knight check, but it's too late. } 34.
Kg2 Be2 35. Qg6 { 35.Qd7 } 35... Bxf3+ 36. Kxf3 Qb5 37. Qg2 Qd3+ 38. Kg4 g5 39.
Qf3 { 39.hxg6  Kg7  40.Qh3 } 39... Qb1 40. fxg5 hxg5 41. h6 Qg1+ 42. Rg2 Qc5
43. Qf7 Qc8+ 44. e6 Qg8 45. Qxg8+ Kxg8 46. Kf5 *

