{ After this move White is suddenly worse.   26.dxe5  fxe5  27.Rb4 } 26... exd4
27. Nxd4 Re7 { 27...Re8 } 28. Bf3
{ Now engines think White is a lot worse.   28.Nxb5  axb5  29.Rxb5  Nc8  30.f3 }
28... Qe5 { Leaving the knight undefended costs Black the game. } 29. Nxb5
{ A simple discovery. } 29... Nc8 30. Nd4 Nd6 31. Rb6
{ White puts the open file to good use. } 31... Rfe8 32. Rcb1 Bxe4 33. Nc6 Bxc6
34. Bxc6 Qxe3 35. fxe3 Rd8 36. Rb8
{ Even though material is equal White is happy to start exhanging material due to the weak Black king. Harry-6 is key here, and, in fact, White is completely winning. }
36... Nc8 37. Bb7 { 37.e4  Kf8  38.Bd5 } 37... Ree8 38. Bxc8 Rxc8 39. R8b7
{ White threatens doubling on the 7th. } 39... Kh8 40. R1b6 f5 41. Rxa6 Ra8 42.
Rc6 Rac8 43. Rcb6 { Now White is keeping the rooks on. } 43... Ra8 44. a4 g5
{ 44...Rxa4  Black can't take the pawn because White then just doubles.  45.Rc7  Ra1+  46.Kh2  Rea8  47.Rbb7 }
45. Rf6 { 45.a5 } 45... Rf8 46. Rxf8+ Rxf8 47. a5 { The a-pawn runs. } *

