[White "11. Early ...e6: No Retreat! "]
[Black "5...O-O, 6...c5, 12...dxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nd2 Bd6 5. Ngf3 O-O 6. c3 c5
{ This seems like the critical move here, played ~950x. } 7. Ne5
{ Again, I recommend White to just jump into  e5  . In a recent blitz game Carlsen played Bd3 here against Narayanan when the game continued  7.Bd3  Qc7?!  8.Bxd6  Qxd6  9.Ne5  b6  10.f4  and Carlsen had a good Stonewall and won in Carlsen - Narayanan, chess24 Banter Series Final, 2020. However, after Bd3 Black doesn't have to cooperate and can just play ...Bxf4 and then proceed with the standard idea of ...b6 & ...Ba6. }
7... Qc7 { Black starts putting pressure on e5. } 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. Ndf3
{ White guards e5 with a piece, forsaking e4. } 9... Ne4
{ Most common and perhaps also best. } 10. O-O f6
{ Black players mostly can't resist.   10...b6  Might be best.  11.h4  Harry goes again. White has a typical small edge.   10...Ndf6  11.h4  and one interesting line goes  11...Ne8  12.c4!?  f6  13.cxd5  exd5  14.Nc4  Bxf4  15.exf4  Be6  16.Ne3 }
11. Nxd7 Bxd7 12. Bxe4 dxe4
{ Black can just take back, but now White has a nice tactical sequence, netting a pawn. }
13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. dxc5
{ Black can't take the pawn since then the bishop hangs as well as the e-pawn, with check. }
14... Qe7
{ 14...Qxc5?  15.Qxd7  exf3  16.Qxe6+  Kh8  17.gxf3  White is a pawn up and in no danger. }
15. Nd2 f5 16. b4 { White is a safe pawn up. } *

