[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Baltic/Slav"]
[Black "Vlatko Kovacevic vs. Robert Byrne, 1980"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This is an excellent game by one of our heroes, Kovacevic, against the American legend GM Robert Byrne. White was rated 2510, Black 2530. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 Bf5
{ Symmetry. This is not really a position we see with our move orders. } 4. e3
c6 5. c4 { The thematic move against early ...Bf5. } 5... e6 6. Nc3
{ White could've also played down the direct  6.Qb3  . } 6... Nbd7 7. Qb3
{ White goes after the b-pawn. } 7... Qb6 8. c5 Qxb3 9. axb3
{ This is the most common version of the famous London endgame. White scores massively from here, but, as we will see, this is actually the best version for Black. By the use of clever move orders, we can always get instead a version where White has played b4 instead of Nf3, which benefits us. }
9... a6
{ The most common move. Black defends the a-pawn and intends ...Rc8, taking away the c7-square, followed by ...Nh5, killing the London monster. }
10. b4 Rc8 11. h3
{ After the previous two moves, White should indeed play h3 to preserve the bishop. }
11... Be7
{ This bishop frequently performs the defensive maneuver of ...Bd8, guarding the a5-square. }
12. Nd2
{ White's typical idea is Nd2-Nb3-Na5, putting pressure on the backward b-pawn. }
12... O-O
{ 12...Bd8  Aiming for a bishop exchange with ...Bc7 doesn't work and leads to a quick trap that Boris Grachev has had no less than 3 times  13.Nb3  Bc7  14.Bxc7  Rxc7  15.b5!  The rook on h8 is undefended so Black can't take with the a-pawn  15...O-O   15...cxb5  16.Nxb5  16.b6!  Rcc8  17.Na5  Rb8  18.Bxa6!  bxa6  19.Nxc6  White's Queenside pawns can't be stopped. }
13. g4
{ White plays on both sides of the board   13.Nb3  The more usual move and now  13...Bd8  14.Bd6!  Making sure the bishop stays in play  14...Re8  15.Na5  Bxa5  16.bxa5  e5  17.Ra4! }
13... Bg6 14. Nb3 Ra8
{ Black wants to defend the b-pawn with ...Ra7, but this is very passive .   14...Bd8  15.Na5  Bxa5  16.bxa5  Rfe8  17.Bd6  With Ra4 next, is typical. }
15. Na5 Ra7 16. f3 { White has perfect central control. } 16... Rc8 17. Kd2 b6
{ Byrne crumbles under pressure... } 18. Bxa6
{ White first sacrifices a piece for a pawn to connect rooks. } 18... Rxa6 19.
Nxc6 { The point, attacking the rook and the defenseless bishop. } 19... Rxc6
20. Rxa6
{ White has an exchange and two pawns for two pieces, but it's the open a-file that matters. }
20... Rc8 21. Rha1 bxc5 22. Ra8 Rf8 23. bxc5 Nxc5
{ Nothing else for Black to try. Passive play just loses to the Queenside pawn march. }
24. Rxf8+ Kxf8 25. Ra8+ Ne8 26. dxc5 Bxc5 27. Rc8
{ 27.Rb8  Followed by b4 was another idea. } 27... Be7 28. e4
{ 28.Nb5  to Nc7, putting pressure on the pinned knight, was another idea. }
28... dxe4 29. Nxe4 f6 30. Bd6 { Kovacevic keeps simplifying. } 30... f5 31.
Bxe7+ Kxe7 32. Nc5 Kd6 33. b4 Nc7 34. Rxc7 Kxc7 35. Nxe6+ Kd6 36. Nxg7 fxg4 37.
hxg4 Kd5 38. Ke3 Kc4 39. f4 Kxb4 40. f5 Bf7 41. Ne6 h6 42. Nd8 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Baltic/Slav"]
[Black "2...Bf5, Baltic - why not 3. e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Bf5
{ The Symmetrical, Baltic Defence move order. With this move, one must always consider whether ...Bxb1 isn't an interesting option for Black   2...Nf6  3.e3  Bf5  The 2... Nf6 move order.  4.c4  We will study these lines separately   2...c6  The Slav move order.  3.e3 }
3. e3
{ This is the most common move and the move I always used to play. In some ways, constructing a repertoire with this move might be most economical since from the 2... Nf6 move order you're committed to this move anyway and there are a lot of transpositions. However, it's actually better to play c4 here and accelerate Queenside play while avoiding certain options for Black.   3.c4!?  This is my main recommendation. It doesn't allow ...Bxb1 in its strongest form and even in the main line style of positions White benefits from the tempo gained by keeping the e-pawn back. }
3... e6
{ This independent option is the most common move and it allows for ...Bxb1 in its strongest form.   3...Nf6  Would transpose to lines we get from the 2... Nf6 move order  4.c4 }
4. c4 Bxb1
{ This has been played over 1000x and it scores really well for Black since ...e6 has been played and Black can get in the quick ...Bb4+. The resulting position can be played with White, but it's better not to allow it.   4...c6  5.Nc3  Likely transposes to the main line after something like  5...Nd7   5...Nf6  Black doesn't control e5 and hence we can go for this immediately  6.Qb3   5...Bd6  6.g4!?  6.Nf3  This is important, not to allow ...e5  6...Ngf6  7.Qb3  Qb6  8.c5  Qxb3  9.axb3 }
5. Qxb1 { Vacating d1 for the king. } 5... Bb4+ 6. Kd1
{ The position is not terrible, but I'd prefer not to allow it. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Baltic/Slav"]
[Black "2...Bf5, Baltic: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Bf5 { The Symmetrical, Baltic move order. } 3. c4
{ Here White benefits from keeping back the e-pawn. This is only the third most common option in the position with only ~6700 games. }
3... e6
{ Most common, with ~3000 games.   3...Bxb1?!  Here this capture doesn't work as well since Black hasn't played ...e6 yet.  4.Rxb1  dxc4  5.e3  e6  6.Bxc4  Bb4+  7.Ke2  White's much better due to his development lead, despite having given up castling rights.   3...dxc4  Another independent option, played ~500x, but it's not of immense interest.  4.Nc3  Threatening e4.  4...Nf6  5.e3  Nbd7  6.Bxc4  e6  7.Nge2!?  White should try this to counter the potential pin on b4 and aim to meet ...Bd6 with f3, to expand in the center with the idea of meeting ...Bxf4 with Nxf4.   3...c6  The Slav move and the second most common move with ~2000 games. Black makes possible ...Qb6, but we won't allow it.  4.Qb3  White gets there first.  4...Qb6  5.Qxb6  axb6  6.cxd5  cxd5  7.Nc3  e6  8.e3  Nf6  9.Bb5+  Nc6  10.Nge2 }
4. Nc3 c6
{ The most common move. The only real options of independent interest are the bishop developments ...Bd6 and ...Bb4, but we'll look at these sorts of positions in more depth from a different move order where they're a bit stronger.   4...Bd6  5.Bxd6  Qxd6  6.Qb3  Nc6  Black has to find this move   6...Qb6?!  7.Qxb6  axb6  8.cxd5  7.e3  Nf6  8.c5!  Qd7  9.Bb5  O-O  10.Nf3   4...Bb4  5.cxd5  exd5  6.e3  Nf6  7.Qb3  Nc6  Black is forced to block the c-pawn  8.Ne2  Protecting the knight, but also intending Ng3  8...O-O  9.Ng3  a3 doesn't make a lot of sense since Black can just retreat to d6  9...Bg6  10.Be2 }
5. Qb3 { Attacking the defenseless b-pawn } 5... Qb6
{ THe most natural and most common move.   5...b6  This anti-positional move is second most common. White should always look at the idea of Ba6 to Bb7 here, 'fianchettoing' our bishop into their spot :  6.cxd5  Basically always the right move in these situations. We use the flank pawn to capture the center on and fix the central structure  6...exd5   6...cxd5??  7.Nb5!  7.e4!!  Oh yeah. e3 can of course be played as well, but this is a way to punish Black for not developing his kingside knight  7...dxe4  The more common choice   7...Bxe4  8.Nxe4  dxe4  9.Bc4  Qe7  10.Ne2  8.Bc4  Bg6  9.d5  Bd6  10.Nge2  Developing with every move. White is basically already winning   5...Qc8  Least common. Whenever the Queen goes to c8 the thematic idea is cxd5, Rc1, and Nb5 !  6.cxd5  exd5  7.e4!!  Bxe4   7...dxe4  8.Bc4  Bg6  9.Nxe4  8.Nxe4  dxe4  9.f3  BDG-style!, with Bc4 coming next. }
6. c5 Qxb3 7. axb3
{ This is the first version of the famous London endgame which we'll look at. Here both sides are two moves short of the most common version we saw in the Kovacevic vs. Byrne game, above.  White is missing e3 which we omitted on the third move and Nf3, Black is missing ...Nd7 and ...Nf6. We benefit from this more. The themes to understand are:   1. White's pressure on the a-pawn and the threat of Bxb8 and Rxa7.   2. White's b-pawn push, potentially twice, with the threat of bxc6, Ba6 to Bb7, winning an exchange. Notice that this sometimes even works after ...a6 because of the pin on the a-file.   3. If Black sets up the defensive structure with ...Nd7, ...a6, and ...Rc8 to counter the previous ideas White has the knight maneuver Nf3-Nd2-Nb3-Na5, attacking the backward b-pawn.   4. Black's threat of ...Nf6 to ...Nh5, killing our London monster. White needs to know when this can be allowed and how to meet it, and when not.   Hint: Surprisingly, it can mostly be allowed. It is only when Black has completed the defensive structure with ...a6 & ...Rc8 that you need to play h3. }
7... Nd7
{ The most common option since it looks like White's threatening Bxb8 and Rxa7. However, even if Black allows for it we shouldn't go for it here   7...Nf6  8.e3  Transposes.   7...Na6  Another independent option  8.e4!  Bxe4  9.Nxe4  dxe4  10.Bxa6  bxa6  11.Rxa6   7...f6  Black is preparing e5  8.e3  e5  9.Bg3   7...a6  8.e3  The plan is still to continue with b4-b5. Just make sure you don't capture on c6 in a situation where Black can play ...Nxc6  8...Nd7  9.b4 }
8. b4
{ Pushing forward and incidentally also protecting the c-pawn after a potential ...e5. }
8... Ngf6
{ The most common move.   8...a6  This is the second most common move and similar to the main line from the other move order. Black protects the a-pawn and intends ...Rc8, removing himself from the pin. White usually responds to this with the knight tour Nf3-Nd2-Nb3-Na5. Here White can do this even faster due to not having touched the e-pawn yet  9.Nf3  Rc8  Black completes the defensive setup against b5  10.Nd2!  White starts the knight tour  10...Be7  Black usually tries to meet the knight tour with ...Be7 to ...Bd8 and chopping our knight  11.Nb3  Bd8  12.Na5  The thematic continuation.  12...Bxa5  13.bxa5  With Ra4 to Rb4 next. Also important is to keep the dark-squared bishop active with Bd6.   8...Be7  Somehow Black scores really well after this, but with no good reason  9.Nf3  With a transposition to lines we'll look at, after...  9...Ngf6  10.e3 }
9. f3
{ White is at a crossroads with three plausible options: 9. e3, 9. Nf3 and 9. f3. The text is a cool independent option from this move order, but it has been played only once. The idea is to take away e4 and prepare kingside expansion with g4 & h4, effectively playing on both sides of the board. It also discourages ...Nh5. Black has only one move to not be a LOT worse.   9.e3  is perhaps objectively strongest and very thematic. However, it would simply transpose to lines we'll look at from a different move order. }
9... Be7
{ Pretty much ever other move White will still go g4 & h4 first   9...Bc2  10.g4   9...h5  Black's only move to secure him a playable game.  10.h4   9...e5?  10.dxe5 }
10. g4 Bg6
{ 10...Bc2  11.h4  White will play e3 and Kd2 and then continue with the Queenside play. }
11. h4 h5 { 11...h6  12.e3  O-O  13.Bg3  White intends Nh3 to Nf4. } 12. g5 Nh7
13. e3 { 13.e4!? } 13... O-O 14. Nge2 { White will play Kf2, Bg3 and Nf4. } *

