1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Bf5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 c6 5. Qb3 Qb6
{ The most natural and most common move. } 6. c5 { The key push! } 6... Qxb3 7.
axb3
{ This is the first version of the famous London endgame which we'll look at. Here both sides are two moves short of the most common version we saw in the Kovacevic vs. Byrne game, above.  White is missing e3 which we omitted on the third move and Nf3, Black is missing ...Nd7 and ...Nf6. We benefit from this more. The themes to understand are:   1. White's pressure on the a-pawn and the threat of Bxb8 and Rxa7.   2. White's b-pawn push, potentially twice, with the threat of bxc6, Ba6 to Bb7, winning an exchange. Notice that this sometimes even works after ...a6 because of the pin on the a-file.   3. If Black sets up the defensive structure with ...Nd7, ...a6, and ...Rc8 to counter the previous ideas White has the knight maneuver Nf3-Nd2-Nb3-Na5, attacking the backward b-pawn.   4. Black's threat of ...Nf6 to ...Nh5, killing our London monster. White needs to know when this can be allowed and how to meet it, and when not.   Hint: Surprisingly, it can mostly be allowed. It is only when Black has completed the defensive structure with ...a6 & ...Rc8 that you need to play h3. }
7... Nd7
{ The most common move since it looks like White is threatening Bxb8 and Rxa7. However, even if Black allows for it, we shouldn't go for it here. If  7...Nf6  8.e3  transposes.   7...Na6?!  8.e4  opening up the center with tempo.   If  7...f6  8.e3  e5  9.Bg3   7...a6  8.e3  The plan is still to continue with b4-b5. Just make sure you don't capture on  c6  in a situation where Black can play ...Nxc6. }
8. b4
{ Pushing and incidentally also protecting the c-pawn after a potential ...e5. }
8... a6
{ This is the second most common move and similar to the main line from the other move order which we'll look at later. Black protects the a-pawn and intends ...Rc8, removing himself from the pin. }
9. Nf3
{ White has a lot of options here, but we will go for the most thematic one. In all of these lines White generally responds to ...a6 & ...Rc8 with the knight tour Nf3-Nd2-Nb3-Na5. Here White can do this even faster due to not having touched the e-pawn yet. }
9... Rc8 { Black completes the defensive setup against b5. } 10. Nd2
{ White starts the knight tour. } 10... Be7
{ Black's typical defensive idea is to play ...Be7-Bd8 and take the knight when it lands on a5. }
11. Nb3 Bd8 { Looking at a5. } 12. Na5
{ Continuing with the plan. Also good is  12.f3  . } 12... Bxa5 13. bxa5
{ It's important to keep the dark-squared bishop active with Bd6. Otherwise White intends Ra4 to Rb4 next. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Baltic/Slav"]
[Black "8...Ngf6, 9. f3!?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Bf5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 c6 5. Qb3 Qb6 6. c5 Qxb3 7. axb3 Nd7 8. b4
Ngf6 { The most common move. } 9. f3
{ White is at a crossroads with three plausible options: 9. e3, 9. Nf3 and 9. f3.   9.e3  is perhaps objectively strongest and very thematic. However, it would simply transpose to lines we'll look at from a different move order.   9.Nf3  would be logical, given that we've kept back the e-pawn until now. It's a strong move, but the lines after  9...Nh5  are a bit too much to learn when there are simpler options available.  The text is a cool independent option from this move order, but it has been played only once. The idea is to take away e4 and prepare kingside expansion with g4 & h4, effectively playing on both sides of the board. It also discourages ...Nh5. Black has only one move to not be a LOT worse. }
9... Be7
{ This is not it. Also, most other moves can be met with g4 & h4. For example  9...Bc2  10.g4  .   Black's best is  9...h5!  stopping  g4  and now White should play  10.h4  with still a good game. }
10. g4 Bg6
{ If  10...Bc2  11.h4  White will play e3 and Kd2 and then continue with the Queenside play. }
11. h4 h5 { If  11...h6  12.e3  O-O  13.Bg3  White intends Nh3 to Nf4. } 12. g5
Nh7 13. e3 { Another option is  13.e4!? } 13... O-O 14. Nge2
{ White will play Kf2, Bg3 and Nf4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Baltic/Slav"]
[Black "2...Nf6, 3...Bf5: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5
{ The last moment for Black to try playing ...Bf5 without going into any of the previous lines. It's the third most common move in the position with ~60 000 games. }
4. c4 e6
{ The most common move, with ~15 000 games, and this move order gives Black some extra options.   4...Bxb1?!  Again, since Black hasn't played ...e6, this is not dangerous. Played ~350x.  5.Rxb1  e6   5...e5?  6.dxe5  Bb4+  7.Ke2  For the rest, see the trainable line.   5...c6  6.Nf3  6.Qb3   4...c6  The second most common move with ~10 000 games. Black opens the diagonal for the Queen.  5.Nc3  The standard move, but White can also try Qb3 if he wants to. Usual moves like ...e6 or ...Nbd7 transpose. Black's only independent option is to try to develop the queen to b6 himself.  5...Qb6  ~350 games.  6.Qb3  Simplest, though Qc1 can be tried as well, followed by c5. Basically White doesn't mind the capture and just intends c5 next.  6...e6   6...dxc4  The only independent move, but it's not very good.  7.Bxc4  Free tempo.  7...Qxb3   7...e6  8.Nge2  8.Bxb3  e6  9.Nge2  Nothing super exciting, but still a typical White edge.  7.c5  Qxb3  8.axb3  Trasponses to Tabiya. }
5. Nc3
{ The main move.   5.Qb3!?  Good for blitz etc. since Black won't probably react correctly  5...Nc6!  Best move, but 10 times less likely than ...b6 and ...Qc8 combined. After those two moves you're sort of home free, having forced Black into an inferior line while cutting out his extra options.   5...b6  6.Nc3   5...Qc8  6.Nc3  6.Nd2!?  Rare. The idea is to meet ...Bb4 with Nf3, connecting the knights while having kept the bishop free.  6...Bb4  7.Nf3  Ne4   7...O-O  8.a3  8.cxd5  Qxd5  9.Qxd5  exd5  10.a3  Bd6  11.Nxe4  dxe4  12.Bxd6  cxd6  13.Nd2  White has a slight pull. }
5... c6
{ Most common and the main line   5...Bd6  First extra option and the second most common move, played in ~2200 games  6.Bxd6  Seems best, but you can always try Bg5  6...Qxd6  7.Qb3  Qb6   7...b6  8.Rc1   7...Nbd7  8.c5  8.c5  Qxb3  9.axb3  O-O  10.Bb5   5...Bb4  Second extra option, Ragozin-style, played in ~2000 games. White can try Qb3 here, but after ...Nc6 it doesn't really lead to anything.  6.Ne2  Since Black's knight is now out we can't clarify the central structure with cxd5. This was the most interesting idea I could find. The point is to continue with a3 and recapture with the knight.  6...O-O   6...dxc4  7.a3  7.a3  Bd6  8.cxd5  exd5  9.Qb3   5...c5  The Tarrasch break has been tried in ~450 games, but it doesn't work.  6.Bxb8  Rxb8  7.Qa4+  b5!?   7...Qd7  8.Qxa7   7...Nd7  8.cxd5  exd5   8...cxd4  9.Qxd4  e5  10.Qd2  Bb4  11.Nge2  8.cxb5  cxd4  9.Qxd4  Rc8  A very hard move to find.  10.Qa4  Bd6  11.Nf3 }
6. Qb3 Qb6
{ The most common response, with 10 000 games.   6...b6  With around 1800 games. White has a choice between just developing with Nf3 & Be2 or fixing the central structure first with cxd5. The choice is yours, but I'm gonna go with the latter move here  7.cxd5  exd5  8.Nf3  Bd6  The most common move  9.Be2!?  The most interesting move, allowing Bxf4 and aiming to plonk the knight to e5 and meet ...Nxd5 with dxe5.   6...Qc8  From this move order, this is the second most common move with roughly 2300 games  7.Rc1  White's threat is cxd5 followed by Nb5, but ...Black's best is ...Nxd5  7...Nbd7  The most common move   7...Be7  8.cxd5!?  Practically speaking it makes sense to play this, even though objectively it might be better to just develop with Nf3 & Be2  8...exd5  Overwhelmingly most common, but now White can play his threat   8...Nxd5  9.Nge2  An interesting option   9.Nxd5  exd5  10.Ne2  9.Nb5  O-O   9...Na6  10.Nd6+  10.Nc7   7...dxc4  8.Bxc4  White gets a free tempo, but otherwise it's a normal game  8.cxd5!?  Again, the practical choice, especially since Black is slow in developing the kingside  8...exd5  Again, most common.   8...Nxd5  9.Bg3  9.Nb5!   6...Qd7  This move makes no sense, just play a quick Nf3 to Ne5 }
7. c5 Qxb3 8. axb3
{ This is the second version of the London endgame and here both sides are missing not two moves as compared to the main line, but one. White is missing Nf3 and Black is missing ...Nd7. Again, White benefits from the absence of these moves since he can consider a quicker expansion with b4-b5 as well as f3. The themes are similar as before. Interestingly, ...Nh5 almost never works out for Black here. }
8... Nbd7
{ Overwhelmingly the most common move with 9300 games.   8...a6  9.b4  Be7  Black still tries to keep the knight back  10.f3!?  An interesting option here, aiming for g4, h4 etc.   10.Nf3  A more standard move }
9. b4
{ With this move we arrive at the most important Tabiya of the whole complex. This can be reached from all of this chapters move orders. The text is the crucial improvement over the most common version of this endgame. We push b4, rather than developing the knight with Nf3. Incidentally, this also defends against ...e5. }
9... Be7
{ The most common move, with ~2750 games.   9...Nh5!?  The second most common move, with ~2500 games.  10.Bc7  We go to c7 first, now if Black doesn't challenge our bishop then we can play h3, threatening g4, and have a hole for our bishop  10...Rc8  Black attacks our bishop. Notice the hanging a-pawn   10...Be7  11.b5  This might be strongest, but h3, taking the chance to make a hole for the bishop, is thematic.  11.Be5  We retreat to e5 now  11...a6  Best and also most common   11...f6  This takes away the square from the knight  12.Bd6!  Bxd6  13.cxd6  a7 is still attacked  13...a6?   13...e5  14.Nge2  14.Be2  Attacking the knight and threatening g4, White wins.   11...Nxe5  Some won't be able to resist  12.dxe5  White scores massively from here  12...a6   12...d4  Unintuitive, but best, the idea is to get f4 for the knight  13.exd4  a6   13...Nf4  14.Rxa7  14.g3  Well, let's deny f4. White's practically winning  13.Be2  Threatening g4  12.f3!  Nf3 can also be played, but this is better, threatening g4 yet again.  12...Nhf6  Best move, but this just shows Black's strategy didn't work at all.  13.g4  Bg6  14.Bf4  h5  The engine choice.  15.g5  Nh7  16.h4  Be7   16...f6  17.gxf6  Nhxf6  18.Nh3  17.Bh3!  Black's only source of play is ...f6 so White looks at the e-pawn and will continue with Nge2 next.   9...a6?!  The third most common move, but this doesn't stop anything because of the pin.  10.b5!?  The practically most nettlesome move. Of course, f3 and Nf3 can also be played.  10...cxb5  11.Bxb5  Rc8  12.Ba4  Be7  13.f3   9...Ne4  The fourth most common move.  10.f3  Nxc3  11.bxc3  White will continue with g4 and c4. }
10. b5
{ We just push things to the max, not caring about developing the knight. ...e5 doesn't work here because dxe5 hits the knight, giving White time for b4. }
10... O-O
{ 10...e5  11.dxe5  Nh5  12.b4  Nxf4  13.exf4  f6  14.e6!  Bxe6  15.Nf3  White is winning. }
11. Nf3 { cxb6 can be played, but now it's better to first prevent ...e5. }
11... cxb5
{ Black really can't allow for the thematic threat of cxb6 followed by Ba6 to Bb7. }
12. Bxb5 a6 13. Be2 Nh5 { 13...Ne4  14.Nxe4  Bxe4  15.b4   13...Rac8  14.b4 }
14. Bc7
{ The most thematic move, but everything works here, including Be5 and even Bg3, allowing the capture. }
14... Rfc8 15. Ba5 Nb8
{ The most interesting move, intending ...Nc6   15...Nhf6  16.O-O } 16. Ne5
{ Attacking the knight, threatening g4 and intending to meet ...Nc6 with Nxc6 }
*

