1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 4. c4 e6 5. Nc3 c6 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. c5 Qxb3 8. axb3
Nbd7 9. b4 Nh5
{ The second most common move and the only move that can't really be met with b5. }
10. Bc7
{ We go to c7 first. If Black doesn't challenge our bishop then we can play h3, threatening g4, and have a hole for our bishop. }
10... Rc8
{ Black attacks our bishop. Notice the hanging a-pawn.   10...Be7  11.b5  This might be strongest, but h3, taking the chance to make a hole for the bishop, is thematic. }
11. Be5
{ Like in the previous line, we retreat to e5 now, not minding the capture. }
11... a6
{ Black protects the a-pawn first. This is best and also the most common move.   11...f6  This takes away the square from the knight...  12.Bd6!  Bxd6  13.cxd6  a7 is still attacked.  13...a6?   13...e5  14.Nge2  14.Be2  Attacking the knight and threatening g4, White wins.   11...Nxe5  Some won't be able to resist  12.dxe5  White scores massively from here  12...a6   12...d4  Unintuitive, but best, the idea is to get f4 for the knight  13.exd4  a6  14.g3  Well, let's deny f4. White's practically winning  13.Be2  Again, attacking the knight and threatening g4. }
12. f3
{ Nf3 can also be played, but this is better, threatening g4 yet again. } 12...
Nhf6
{ Best move, but this just shows Black's strategy didn't work at all   12...f6?  13.Bd6!!  Bxd6  14.cxd6  Black has no way of preventing g4, losing a piece.   12...Nxe5?  13.dxe5  d4  Black has to sacrifice a pawn not to lose a piece to g4  14.exd4  Nf4  15.g3  Just kicking the knight. White is winning  15...Ng6  16.Ne4  Aiming for Nd6+  16...Bxe4  17.fxe4  This position is hopeless for Black. }
13. g4 { Continuing the plan. } 13... Bg6 { What else? } 14. Bf4
{ Preserving the monster bishop. } 14... h5 15. g5 Nh7 16. h4 Be7 17. Bh3
{ Black's only source of play is ...f6 so White looks at the e-pawn and will continue with Nge2 next. }
