[Black "2...c6, Slav: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c6 { The Slav move order. } 3. e3
{ Here it's better to open up the diagonal first. } 3... Bf5
{ 3...Qb6  This interesting way of playing is recommended by GM Alex Colovic in his recent Slav repertoire here on Chessable. White can play b3 or Qc1. I like the latter better. It's been played ~10 000x  4.Qc1  Protecting the b-pawn and preparing c4  4...Bf5  5.Nf3  Nf6  6.c4  e6  7.c5!  Qd8  8.b4  Nbd7  9.h3  Be7  10.Be2  O-O  11.O-O  Re8  12.Nbd2  - for the rest, see the line   3...Nf6  This is the most common move, with ~49 000 games. It gives White a choice, as we will see  4.Nf3  White can play in two ways here. First, you could play c4 and be happy to play a weird QGD after ...e6. Second, you could play the text move and stay in London waters after ...e6 while meeting bishop developments with c4. I prefer the latter option.  4...Bg4  The only move of independent interest and the second most common choice with ~33 000 games.   4...Bf5  5.c4  Again, likely transposes to the main lines after ...e6, Nc3, Qb3 etc. ...Bxb1 is not dangerous.  5...Bxb1?!  6.Rxb1  e6  7.c5   4...e6  5.Nbd2  Just play the regular London setup  5.c4  White intends to play much like against ...Bf5  5...Bxf3  Other moves can be met with Qb3  6.gxf3  Qxf3 is fine too, but this seems stronger, not wasting any time with the Queen and aiming for Qb3 while also strengthening the center, controlling e4, and opening the g-file.  6...e6  7.Qb3  Qb6  8.c5  Qxb3  9.axb3  Is like the main line except the exchange of minors  9...Nh5!?  Not a very common move, but as always, needs to be checked. Anything else and White can continue with Nc3 or b4. Normally Black doesn't dare playing it here due to Bxb8 and Rxa7   9...Nbd7  10.Nc3   9...a6  10.Nc3   9...Be7  10.b4  10.Bc7!  Stronger  10...Nd7  11.b4  Rc8  12.Bg3  a6   12...Nxg3  13.hxg3  a6  14.f4  White has an advantage due to his central pawn mass  13.Nd2  With the typical idea of Nb3 to Na5. }
4. c4
{ This will likely lead to the main version of the endgame. Bxb1 doesn't really work here. }
4... e6
{ Most common move with ~11 000 games   4...Bxb1?!  5.Rxb1  e5   5...e6  6.c5   5...Qa5+  6.b4  Qxa2  7.c5  6.dxe5  Qa5+   6...Bb4+  7.Ke2  7.Ke2   4...Nf6  5.Nc3  Transposes to the position after 2... Nf6 and 3... Bf5   4...Qb6  ~500 games  5.Qc1  Qb3 can be played, but here White can also aim for a quick c5  5...e6  6.c5  Qd8  7.Nf3   4...Nd7  Very rare with 350 games  5.cxd5  As almost always, we can clarify the central structure when we can and here we also open the c-file and the a4-e8 diagonal. White can also play Nc3 and that's likely to lead to the main version of the endgame  5...cxd5  6.Qb3  Hitting both pawns  6...Qb6  7.Nc3 }
5. Qb3
{ Throwing a spanner in the works and cutting down on Black's options.   5.Nc3  The main move. It is also good and leads to the main version of the endgame after  5...Nd7   5...Bd6  6.g4!?   5...Bb4  6.Qb3  6.Nf3!  Preventing ...e5  6...Ngf6  7.Qb3  Qb6  8.c5  Qxb3  9.axb3  We've reached the position from the Kovacevic vs Byrne game. This is the main version of the London endgame and can be played as well, but why allow Black even this much ? }
5... Qb6 6. c5 Qxb3 7. axb3
{ Third version of the endgame. It's likely to transpose after ...Nd7, ...a6, or ...Nf6, but Black has one independent move here. }
7... Bxb1
{ This is a rare independent option that has been tried ~350 times. It doesn't make a huge difference though.   7...Nd7  Overwhelmingly the most common with ~1500 games.  8.b4  Like always, pushing forward while helping to take the sting out of ...e5  8...Ngf6  9.Nc3  transposes to the main tabiya again. }
8. Rxb1
{ White will just move the rook back to a1 eventually and continue with b4. }
8... Nd7
{ 8...a6  9.Nf3  Nd7  10.b4  Ngf6  11.Ra1  Rc8  12.h3  White can play Bd3 & Ke2 next and still try Nd2-Nb3-Na5. }
9. b4 { The typical push. } 9... a6 10. Ra1
{ Putting the rook back to where it belongs and threatening b5. } 10... Rc8
{ Black removes himself from the pin   10...Ngf6  11.b5  cxb5  12.Bxb5  Be7  13.h4  O-O  14.Ba4 }
11. g4
{ What ? Once the LSB is off, the rules change a bit. Engines love this space-gaining move, intending either f3 and h4 or h4 and g5 next and playing on both sides of the board. This has never been played in practice... }
11... Ne7
{ One possible response. I'll show a few just so you can get a taste   11...Ngf6  12.f3  With h4 next. Be sure not to push g5 until ...Nh5 is not possible as a response   11...Be7  12.h4  Black is just suffering here  12...Ngf6  13.f3  O-O  14.Bd3  White will play Kf2, Ne2, h5 etc. }
12. h4 h5 13. g5
{ White's bishop will got to d3, he can play f3 and Kf2 and develop the knight to e2 or h3. Black has basically no hope in ever generating any counterplay here and will get slowly squeezed to death. }
