1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c6 3. e3 Qb6
{ This interesting way of playing is recommended by GM Alex Colovic in his recent LTR: Chebanenko Slav, here on Chessable. White can play b3 or Qc1. I like the latter better. It's been played ~10 000x. }
4. Qc1 Bf5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. c4 e6 7. c5
{ White has a very specific idea in mind, to develop the knight to d2, instead of c3. }
7... Qd8 { 7...Qb4+  8.Nbd2   7...Qa5+  8.Nbd2 } 8. b4
{ We don't need to be worried about ...Nh5 just yet. Colovic only mentions Nc3 here. }
8... Nh5 9. Be5 Nd7 10. h3 { Making an escape hole now, while threatening g4. }
10... Nxe5 { 10...Nhf6  11.Bh2 } 11. dxe5
{ Black can save the piece, but it's not gonna be pretty. } 11... Be4
{ 11...Bxb1  12.Rxb1 } 12. Nbd2 Bxf3 13. Nxf3
{ g4 is still a threat so Black is forced to play g6. } 13... g6 14. g4 Ng7
{ A fianchettoed knight is never good. } 15. Bd3
{ White can continue with Ke2 and then choose where to play. He's dominating the whole board. }
