1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c6 3. e3 Nf6
{ This is the most common move, with ~49 000 games. It gives White a choice, as we will see. }
4. Nf3
{ White can play in two ways here. First, you could play c4 and be happy to play a weird QGD after ...e6. Second, you could play the text move and stay in London waters after ...e6 while meeting bishop developments with c4. I prefer the latter option. }
4... Bg4
{ The only move of independent interest and the second most common choice with ~33 000 games   4...Bf5  5.c4  transposes to the lines after ...e6, Nc3, Qb3 etc. ...Bxb1 is not dangerous  5...Bxb1?!  6.Rxb1  e6  7.c5 }
5. c4 { White intends to play much like against ...Bf5. } 5... Bxf3
{ Other moves can be met with Qb3. } 6. gxf3
{ Qxf3 is fine too, but this is stronger, not wasting any time with the Queen and aiming for Qb3 while also strengthening the center, controlling e4, and opening the g-file. }
6... e6 7. Qb3 Qb6 8. c5 Qxb3 9. axb3
{ Is like the main line except the exchange of minors. } 9... Nh5
{ Not a very common move, but as always, needs to be checked. Anything else and White can continue with Nc3 or b4. Normally Black doesn't dare playing this move here due to Bxb8 and Rxa7, but he can still try it, of course...   9...Nbd7  10.Nc3   9...a6  10.Nc3   9...Be7  10.b4 }
10. Bc7 { Stronger than Bxb8. } 10... Nd7 11. b4 Rc8 12. Bg3 a6
{ 12...Nxg3  13.hxg3  a6  14.f4  White has an advantage due to his central pawn mass. }
13. Nd2 { With the typical idea of Nb3 to Na5. } *

