1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nc6 3. e3 Bf5
{ The most common move.   3...Nf6  The second most common move. With this Black usually goes for a plan involving ...Bg4.  4.Nf3  Bg4  5.c4  e6  6.a3  I like this thematic and easy-to-remember move, simply stopping the pin.  6...Bd6  7.Bg5  A typical diagonal switch.  7...h6   7...dxc4  8.Bxc4  8.Bxf6  A more interesting idea than the retreat with Bh4, though that's also fine.   8.Bh4  g5  9.Bg3  8...Qxf6  9.Nc3  dxc4  10.Bxc4  O-O  11.Be2  The idea is to avoid any Queen trades and play h3 next. Notice that ...e5 can just be met with d5. White will complete development by castling and playing Qb3, Rac1 etc. with a simple yet clear edge. }
4. c4 e6
{ The overwhelmingly most common move.   4...Bxb1  Crazy idea nr. 1. This is not good, but Black scores pretty well with it since White is usually shell-shocked and clueless...  5.Rxb1  e5  6.Bxe5  Taking with the bishop is better than with the pawn.  6...Bb4+  7.Ke2  Nxe5  8.dxe5  dxc4  9.g3!  As unintuitive it might be, White is already winning here and doesn't mind the Queen exchange at all. This is due to his development lead and the advanced central pawn.  9...Ne7   9...Qxd1+  10.Rxd1  Ne7  11.Bh3  10.Bg2  c6  11.Qxd8+  Rxd8  12.Nf3  O-O  13.Rhc1  b5  The only way to defend the c-pawn.  14.Nd4  a6  15.Rd1  Rc8  16.e6!   4...e5  Crazy idea nr. 2. It's not good either, but it's been tried a good ~100x and, again, Black scores pretty well.  5.Bxe5  Again, take with the bishop.  5...Bb4+  6.Nc3  Nxe5  7.dxe5  Bxc3+  8.bxc3  Ne7  9.Nf3  O-O  10.Qb3  and White still has the extra pawn. }
5. cxd5 exd5 6. Nc3 Nf6 { The most common move.   6...Bb4  7.Ne2 } 7. a3
{ Stopping the pin.   7.Nf3  Is also totally fine, but I prefer to stop the pin.  7...Bb4  8.Rc1 }
7... Bd6 8. Bg5 Be7 { 8...h6?  9.Bxf6  Qxf6  10.Nxd5 } 9. Nge2 O-O
{ The most natural move. } 10. Bxf6 { White exchanges to weaken the d5-pawn. }
10... Bxf6 11. Nf4 Re8 { 11...Be6  12.Qf3 } 12. Be2 Be6 13. O-O *

