1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6
{ 2...Bg4?!  This is only the 9th most popular move in the position, tried roughly ~3000 times @@StartBracket@@and it screams of being an anti-premove ploy@@EndBracket@@.  3.f3  It's easiest to immediately start with f3. This is the 4th most popular move with ~500 games.  3...Bf5   3...Bh5  This is more popular, but the bishop has nothing to do here, just staring at the pawn.  4.c4  Play is very similar to the Slav lines.   3...Bd7  4.e4  Here White is faster since he can meet ...Nf6 with e5.  4...e6  5.Nc3  Nf6  6.Qd2  With a quick O-O-O.  4.c4  We play c4, similarly to our Slav lines. As you saw in the last chapter. f3 is actually quite a useful move in the Slav endgames. Only 11 games have reached here.  4...Nf6   4...Bxb1  This move does nothing here and play is similar to the Chigorin lines.  5.Rxb1  5.Nc3  Nc6  The engine likes this line.   5...e6  This is overwhelmingly more common, but now  6.Qb3±  White is just better here.  6.g4!  Using the f-pawn to attack the bishop and expand all over the board.  6...Bg6  7.h4  h6   7...h5  Doesn't really work here due to  8.g5  Nd7?  9.cxd5+-  8.e3  e6  9.c5+=  White controls the whole board and can always exchange bishops via Bd3 and develop the knight via Nge2 or use the typical maneuver Bg3, Nh3 to Nf4.   9.Kf2!?  An interesting alternative.  9...dxc4  10.Bxc4  Bd6  11.Nge2  O-O  12.Rc1+= }
3. e3 Bg4
{ From this move order this is the 7th most popular move with ~7700 games. } 4.
Qd3
{ Is the new engine try. The idea is logical, we simply put the Queen to b3 like in the Slav endgames. This has been tried only ~200x.   4.f3  This can be considered the old main line. We will take it as an alternative. }
4... c6
{ The most common and most logical move. Black prepares to meet Qb3 with Qb6.   4...e6  The second most common move, but this drops the whole Queenside.  5.Qb5+  Nbd7   5...Qd7??  6.Qxb7  6.Qxb7  Rb8  Natural, but it drops both pawns.  7.Qxa7  Rxb2  8.f3  Making room for the king.  8...Bf5  9.Bxc7  Qc8?  ...Qe7 is necessary.   9...Qe7  10.a3  Stopping checks on b4. White is completely winning.  10.Ba6!   4...Nbd7  5.h3  Bh5  6.Qb3  Qc8   6...Nb6  7.Nd2  e6  8.a4   6...Rb8  7.Nc3  White can go for a quick Nb5 since ...c6 is not possible anymore.  7.c4  e6  8.Nc3  c6  9.cxd5  Nxd5  10.Bg3  Be7  11.Nf3  O-O  12.Be2  a5  13.O-O  += }
5. Qb3 Qb6
{ 5...Nbd7  6.h3  Bf5  7.Nf3  Qb6  8.c4  dxc4  9.Bxc4  Qxb3  10.Bxb3+= } 6. c4
{ We're in the Slav sort of game so White plays c4 now, intending c5. } 6... e6
7. c5 Qxb3 8. axb3
{ This is just another version of the Slav endgame. It's even better for White since Black's bishop is misplaced and White can gain some tempos with f3, g4, h4 etc. }
8... Nbd7 9. b4 Be7 10. h3 Bh5 11. b5 O-O 12. Nc3
{ White controls the whole board and is basically already winning. } *

