[White "13. Chigorin & Early ...Bg4"]
[Black "2...Bg4 with c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Bg4
{ This is only the 9th most popular move in the position, tried roughly ~3000 times, and it screams of being an anti-premove ploy. }
3. f3
{ It's easiest to immediately start with f3. This is the 4th most popular move with ~500 games. }
3... Bf5
{ 3...Bh5  This is more popular, but the bishop has nothing to do here, just staring at the pawn.  4.c4  Play is very similar to the Slav lines.   3...Bd7  4.e4  Here White is faster since he can meet ...Nf6 with e5.  4...e6  5.Nc3  Nf6  6.Qd2  With a quick O-O-O. }
4. c4
{ We play c4, similarly to our Slav lines. As you saw in the last chapter, f3 is actually quite a useful move in the Slav endgames. Only 11 games have reached here. }
4... Nf6
{ 4...Bxb1  This move does nothing here and play is similar to the Chigorin lines.  5.Rxb1. }
5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The engine likes this line.   5...e6  This is overwhelmingly more common, but now  6.Qb3±  White is just better here. }
6. g4 { Using the f-pawn to attack the bishop and expand all over the board. }
6... Bg6 7. h4 h6
{ 7...h5  Doesn't really work here due to  8.g5  Nd7?  9.cxd5+- } 8. e3 e6 9.
c5
{ The key finesse. White controls the whole board and can proceed with exchanging bishops via Bd3 and developing the knight via Nge2 or use the typical maneuver Bg3, Nh3 to Nf4.   9.Kf2!?  An interesting alternative.  9...dxc4  10.Bxc4  Bd6  11.Nge2  O-O  12.Rc1+= }
*

