[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Bg4
{ This is only the 9th most popular move in the position, tried roughly ~3000 times @@StartBracket@@and it screams of being an anti-premove ploy@@EndBracket@@. }
3. f3 Bf5
{ 3...Bh5  Doesn't really differ much.  4.Nc3  e6  5.h4  h6  6.Qd2   6.g4  Bg6  7.Qd2 }
4. Nc3
{ Instead of c4, it's also entirely logical to play Jobava-style with Nc3. The idea is to support e4 and follow up with h4 and g4. Black faces a wide choice, but most moves allow you to carry out the plan. }
4... Nf6 5. g4 Bg6 6. h4 h6
{ 6...h5?  7.g5  Ng8  So as not to drop the d-pawn.  8.e4± } 7. e3
{ 7.Qd2  White doesn't actually have to go for the bishop exchange and can rather keep it there in a precarious position. The plan is a quick O-O-O, e3, Nh3, Bg3, Nf4. etc. }
7... e6 8. Bd3 { The standard, Caro-Kannish way of playing it. } 8... Bxd3 9.
Qxd3 Nc6 { 9...c5  10.Nb5 } 10. O-O-O
{ White will play Kb1, Nge2 and eventually break with e4. } *

