[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Queen's Indian"]
[Black "QID, 2...b6!? and 3...b6: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ The most flexible Black move, signaling the intention to play a Nimzo, KID, Grünfeld, or a Benoni }
2. Bf4 e6
{ The Nimzo move is the second most popular, with ~177 000 games. Here it signals the beginning of a Queen's Indian. Black aims to set up with ...Be7, ...b6, ...Bb7, ...c5 and then goes for one of three plans 1@@EndBracket@@ a flexible setup with ...d6, 2@@EndBracket@@ a better version of ...d5 lines or 3@@EndBracket@@ a Hedgehog with ...cxd4 and ...d6. If White wants, he can always play the standard response with e3, Nf3, h3 to preserve the bishop, Nbd2, and Bd3. However, we will go down the most ambitious and tricky routes, trying to punish most Black move-orders, while basically restricting them to a Hedgehog setup.   2...b6  Accelerated QID, played ~25 000x. If this would work for Black then that would mean he can get away with pretty much anything...  3.Nc3!?  We don't have to allow Black to bully us with his tricks...  3...Bb7  4.f3!  White intends e4  4...d5  Stopping e4?  5.e4!?  White can play a version of the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit ! This has been played in 60 games and White scores massively  5...dxe4   5...e6  Black can also play ...e6 here, but this is more than 10x rarer than ...dxe4.  6.Nb5  Na6  7.e5  Nd7  8.Nh3  c6  Black should challenge our knight immediately and concede the bishop pair.  9.Nd6+  Bxd6  10.exd6  O-O  11.Bd3  c5  12.c3  The engines might consider this equal at a high depth, but White's position seems easier to play.  6.fxe4  Nxe4  7.Qf3!  A typical square for the Queen in the BDG. Another option is   7.Bb5+  7...Nd6   7...Nxc3??  8.Qxb7   7...f5  8.O-O-O  8.Bb5+  c6  A hard move to play   8...Nd7!?  9.Bc6   8...Nxb5  9.Qxb7  Nxc3  10.Qxa8  9.Bd3  Nd7  10.O-O-O  White's got massive compensation for the missing pawn and this is definitely not what Black wanted to achieve when he played 2...b6 }
3. e3 b6
{ Black's third common move with ~26 000 games. White can always play in a typical fashion with Nf3 here. However, we will immediately make Black's life hard with }
4. Qf3
{ Surprise...White occupies the long diagonal first and forces either ...Nc6 or ...d5 as a response. After that the idea is to play Nc3, O-O-O, and, eventually, g4 & h4. This has been played only in ~1100 games, but is a lovely attacking line which is still quite rare in practice. }
4... d5
{ The other option for Black and the more common choice at master level.   4...Nc6  This, and ...d5, are about equally as common with roughly 450 games.  5.Nc3  White intends a quick O-O-O. The games drop to 190.  5...Bb7  The main move, played 10x more than the closest alternative, ~170x. White just needs to keep in mind that any discoveries can simply be met with e4.   5...Bb4  This needs to be also taken into account.  6.Ne2  The most natural and healthy move, avoiding any damage to structure, though Bd3 can also be tried.  6...Bb7  Most common move, but now just...   6...Nd5  This hasn't been played in Lichess, but has been played at master level and should be checked.  7.a3  Bxc3+  8.Nxc3  Nxf4   8...Nxc3  9.bxc3  White's just better after Bd3 and e4.  9.Qxf4  Bb7  10.O-O-O  Ne7  11.h4  7.O-O-O  White's better and can continue with a3 or e4, even h4 etc.  6.O-O-O  Na5  A critical-looking try, but it's only been played 7x. Tame play can be met with Kb1, e4&d5 or g4-g5 etc.   6...Bb4  Most common move in practice, but this transposes to the previous line after  7.Nge2   6...Be7  This is one of the tame moves.  7.e4  7.e4  Bb4   7...Nxe4  Black can try for a tactical solution. This has not been played.  8.Nxe4  f5  9.Bd3  fxe4  10.Bxe4  Bxe4  11.Qxe4  If you look closely, White's threatening to win a pawn with Bxc7. So if Black plays something like ...Be7 then White can grab the pawn or just continue with Kb1, Nf3-Ng5 etc. So Black has to find the computerish...  11...Bd6  12.Nf3  O-O  13.Bg3  8.Nge2  O-O  9.d5  White's better and should meet ...exd5 with Nxd5 to exchange Black's best defender first, and only then play exd5 to cramp Black further. }
5. Nc3 Bb4
{ 5...Bb7  The most common move in Lichess.  6.O-O-O  Be7   6...Bd6  7.g4  7.g4  White starts an attack, aiming to dislodge Black's knight. The plan is simple, after a likely ...Ne4, Nxe4, White will play Qg3 or Qh3 and Bd3, Nge2 etc.   5...Bd6  6.g4  Again, White starts with kingside play. It's also fine to play O-O-O first. The point is that any trades on f4 actually benefit White since the Queen has done it's job on f3 and after ...Bxf4 and Qxf4 the f3-square is vacated for the knight.  6...Bb7  7.Bd3  We develop the bishop first and are ready to continue with O-O-O and Nge2, h4 etc. }
6. Ne2 { Natural and healthy. } 6... Ne4
{ 6...Ba6  7.O-O-O  Just avoiding structural damage. No matter which knight Black takes, White will recapture with the other one. }
7. a3 Bxc3+
{ Black can't retreat because after Nxe4, dxe4 the newly born e-pawn drops immediately to Qxe4 with an attack on the rook in the corner. }
8. Nxc3 Nxc3 9. bxc3
{ Black achieved structural damage, but gave up his bishop pair. } 9... O-O
{ 9...Ba6  10.Qg4  c4 could be played as well, but this is even stronger, attacking the g-pawn. Now ...g6 can be met with h4 and ...O-O with Bxa6 and Be5. }
10. Bd3
{ White will castle and play c4 at some point, and can also later aim to play e4. Notice that ...Ba6 can just be met with c4 due to the pin on the rook. }
*

