[Black "2...b6?! 5...dxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 b6
{ This is kind of an accelerated QID, played ~25 000x. If this would work for Black then that would mean he can get away with pretty much anything... }
3. Nc3 { We don't have to allow Black to bully us with his tricks... } 3... Bb7
{ This is most likely. If  3...e6  4.e4  Bb4  5.e5!  Nd5  6.Bd2  and White's just better. }
4. f3 { White intends e4. } 4... d5 { Stopping e4?. } 5. e4
{ White can play a very good version of the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit! This has been played in 60 games and White scores massively. }
5... dxe4 6. fxe4 Nxe4 7. Qf3
{ A typical square for the Queen in the BDG. Another option is  7.Bb5+  for which see the model game Cornette vs. Bortnyk. }
7... Nd6
{ 7...Nxc3??  8.Qxb7  just wins for White while if   7...f5  8.O-O-O  and White's got a clear edge. }
8. Bb5+ c6
{ A hard move to play. If   8...Nd7!?  9.Bc6  and if the kamikaze   8...Nxb5  9.Qxb7  Nxc3  10.Qxa8  Nd5  11.Ne2  or even just Bd2 and White's winning. }
9. Bd3 Nd7 10. O-O-O
{ White's got massive compensation for the missing pawn and this is definitely not what Black wanted to achieve when he played 2... b6. }
*

