[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Queen's Indian"]
[Black "Standard Play, 3..b6 4. Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Nf3
{ White can also play into more standard waters with Nf3. } 4... Bb7 5. Nbd2
Be7
{ The immediate  5... c5 would lead to the so-called Ashwin trap  5...c5  6.Nc4!  d5?!  7.Nce5  with the dual threats of  Bb5+  and  Ng5  . I've caught many opponents with this, but in this course, we will punish the combination of  ...c5  &  ...b6  even more harshly with the objectively stronger moves  Nc3  or  c4  .  The text is the best and most flexible response for Black at this juncture. With this move, he is threatening ...Nh5, forcing h3. After this he can then choose whether to go for a version of the ...d5-lines with White committed to h3, a flexible setup with ...c5 and ...d6 or a Hedgehog with ...c5, ...cxd4 and ...d6.    Notice that playing the current setup with White allows for all of these three options, while our main recommended move orders restrict Black to only the last of these. }
6. h3 { A necessary evil, to preserve the bishop. } 6... c5 7. c3 O-O
{ If Black wants to play ...d5 it's best to castle first to avoid the annoying Bb5+. If Black plays ...d6 instead without entering the Hedgehog then White can play on the queenside or in the center depending on Black's Queen's knight development  7...d6  8.Bd3  Nbd7  9.O-O  O-O  10.a4  a6  11.Qe2   or  7...d6  8.Bd3  Nc6  9.O-O  O-O  10.Qe2  Re8  11.Rad1   The hedgehog with  7...cxd4  8.exd4  d6  is covered at the end of this chapter from a different move order. }
8. Bd3 d5 9. O-O Nc6
{ We arrive at a position which was reached in the famous gameCarlsen vs Tomashevsky. If instead  9...Nbd7  10.Qb1  is an interesting suggestion of Bartholomew & Barrish, controlling e4, putting pressure on  h7  , and preparing b4. The main point is that Black has no active plan.   The game could continue  9...Nbd7  10.Qb1  h6  12.a4  a6  13.b4  c4  14.Bc2   Black can also try to hop into  e4  immediately, but that turns out good for White after  9...Ne4  10.Bc2!  Nd7  11.Nxe4  dxe4  12.Nd2  f5  13.Bb3  switching the diagonal and putting pressure on the backward e-pawn. }
10. Qe2 { Carlsen's move. } 10... Bd6 11. Rfe1
{ Carlsen chose to centralize one rook and aim for Rubinstein's structure with d4 & f4 after Black continues with ...Bxf4 or the standard plan of pushing e4 to e5. Here are some sample lines:   11...Bxf4  12.exf4  cxd4  13.Nxd4!  Nxd4  14.cxd4  and White controls e5 and can push  f5  at some moment.   11...Re8  12.Bxd6!  Qxd6  13.e4!  dxe4  14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.Qxe4  f5  15.Qe2  with pressure on the e6-pawn   11...Qe7  12.Bxd6!  Qxd6  13.e4!  dxe4  14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.Qxe4  g6  15.dxc5  Qxc5  16.Qh4  with pressure on the king.  For more, see the above game. }
*

