1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Qb6 5. Na3
{ This is relatively rare, but best! Compared to Nc3, the knight can go not only to b5, but also to c4, in some variations. }
5... Qxb2
{ The critical-looking move, but it loses in all variations.   5...cxd4  Second most common.  6.Nc4!?  Kamsky's suggested improvement. This has been played only 15 times.  6...Qb4+   6...Bb4+  7.Nfd2  Qc6   7...Qc5  8.c3  This position has been reached in 10 games.  8...dxc3  9.bxc3  Bxc3  10.Rc1  8.exd4  7.c3  dxc3  8.a3   8.bxc3!?  This is also a fine way of playing and better if you want to keep the Queens on the board.  8...Qc5  9.Nd6+  Bxd6  10.Bxd6  Qxc3+   10...Qd5  11.Qxd5  Nxd5  12.c4=  11.Nd2  Threatening Rc1.  11...Qa5  12.Rc1  Nc6  13.Rc5  Qd8  14.Bd3  c2+   8...Qc5  9.b4  Qd5  10.Qc2  Nc6  11.Rd1  Qh5  12.Qxc3  White can continue with developing the bishop or even the direct b5.  9.axb4  cxd1=Q+  10.Kxd1  Now, White's threatening Nb6, winning the exchange.  10...Na6  Computer defense, simply blocking the a-file. This hasn't been played in a single game. Any other move and Nb6 is coming.  11.b5  Ne4  Another unlikely computer suggestion. The point is that if the knight on  a6  (moves then Nb6 will come, with full effect.)   11...d5  Yet another engine suggestion.  12.bxa6  dxc4  13.Bxc4  bxa6  14.Ke2  White's down a pawn, but better developed and much more comfortable, and can always grab the pawn back with Bxa6.  12.bxa6  Nxf2+  13.Ke2  Activating the king.  13...Nxh1  14.Nd6+  Bxd6  15.Bxd6  bxa6  16.e4  Bb7  17.Ke3  White will pick up the knight in the corner soon and be better.   5...Qb4+  This is the only move available for Black that he can't play after Nc3. Luckily it's not very good.  6.c3  Qxb2  7.Nc4  Qxc3+  8.Nfd2  b5  Protecting a4 so the Queen can go there after Rc1 and a3.   8...d5  9.Rc1  Qb4  10.a3  The Queen is lost. Note that Qb5 is of course met by Nd6+.  9.Rc1  Qb4  10.Rb1  Qc3   10...Qa4?  11.Qxa4  bxa4  12.Bxb8  11.Rxb5  Whatever Black plays next, Rb3 will trap the Queen.   5...d5  6.Nb5  Na6  7.a4   5...d6  6.Nc4  Qc6  7.a4   5...Nc6  6.Nc4  Qd8  7.Nd6+  Bxd6  8.Bxd6  Ne4  9.dxc5  b6  10.cxb6  axb6  11.c3  Nxd6  12.Qxd6 }
6. Nb5 Nd5
{ This is a better defensive try, but here it still loses.   6...Na6  This move never works, but it's overwhelmingly most common. Roughly 550 games have reached this position from different move orders.  7.a3  This should look familiar, by now.  7...Nd5   7...cxd4  8.Be5  8.Rb1  Qa2  9.Bd6  This has been played only 13 times.  9...Bxd6  10.Bc4!!  Qxc4   10...Nc3  This is not really that much better. White can take everything with tempo.  11.Nxd6+  Ke7  12.Bxa2  Nxd1  13.Nxc8+  Rhxc8  14.Kxd1  White has a piece vs. a pawn and is threatening to enter on b7.  11.Nxd6+ }
7. Rb1 { First, we lose the a-pawn to have the a-file opened for us. } 7...
Qxa2 8. Ra1 Qb2 9. Bc4
{ Now Black is losing in all lines, but White has to be precise so it's best to learn these well. }
9... Qb4+
{ Most common, trying to save the Queen. The idea behind our previous move is best illusrated by the following lines   9...Nxf4  10.Rb1   9...a6  10.Rb1   9...Nc3  10.Nc7+  Kd8  11.Qc1  Qxc1+  12.Rxc1  b5  13.Nxa8  bxc4  14.Bc7+  Ke8  15.Bxb8  Bb7  16.Nc7+ }
10. Nd2 Na6
{ Apparently strongest. Similar is   10...Nc6  11.Rb1  Nc3  12.Rxb4  Nxd1  13.Rb1  Nc3  14.Nxc3  and White's up a a piece. }
11. Rb1 Qa4
{ Very natural, trying to save the Queen and the following variation is perhaps harder to remember than some others. Note that if Black plays ...Qa5 then White should take on d5   11...Qa5  12.Bxd5  exd5  13.Qh5  White just activates the Queen and goes after the d-pawn. He can later play Nd6+ and Bxd6 and then Qg4 to go after the g-pawn.   11...Nc3  12.Rxb4  Nxd1  13.Rb1  Is similar to a line we saw in a previous note. }
12. O-O Nxf4 { 12...Be7  13.Bd6 } 13. Ra1 Qb4 { 13...Qxa1  14.Qxa1 } 14. c3 *

