1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 c5
{ This is Black's most common, and also probably best move order. It's been played around 43 200 times.   3...Be7  4.Nf3  c5  5.dxc5  Transposes to below }
4. Nf3
{ Here White does best to develop the knight. Now Black faces a choice. } 4...
cxd4
{ Black's best move is to enter the Hedgehog setup right now. This shares the 2-4th place with ~10 000 games.   4...Nc6  This is the most common move with ~14 000 games, but it's almost a mistake... Note that it was also recommended by FM Yuryi Krykun in his Accelerated QID course to enter the ...d5-line with 6...Nh5 we covered earlier. Our next move cuts this transpositional option out...  5.Nc3!?  With this surprising move White aims for either Nb5 or d5. Most standard Black moves just lose to one of these two threats...   5.Nbd2  White could, of course, simply aim to transpose to the standard lines. Black's only independent options revolve around refraining from ...d5, but it's not clear what he can achieve by this.  5...cxd4!  The only serious move and the only one played at master level.   5...d5?  Believe it or not, this is most common with ~370 games, but it just disregards White's most basic threat and loses on the spot to...  6.Nb5  e5  This is the most played move here.  7.Nxe5  Qa5+  8.c3  c4  This is mostly tried here, but it doesn't work.  9.Nxc4  dxc4   9...Qxb5?  10.Nd6+  10.Nc7+  Kd8  11.d5  White will take on a8 next.   5...d6  This doesn't really make a lot of sense after  6.dxc5  e5  7.Bg3   5...Be7  Again, simply misses White's threat  6.Nb5   5...b6  Also misses White's threats. Both Nb5 and d5 work here.  6.Nb5   6.d5  Nb4  7.e4   5...a6  Third most common. This stops Nb5, but now...  6.d5  exd5  Most common.  7.Nxd5  Nxd5  8.Qxd5  d6  9.Ng5  Attacking f7 and controlling e6.  6.exd4  Bb4  Most common.   6...d5?  7.Nb5  7.Bd3  O-O   7...Nd5  Most common, but why...  8.Bd2  Nxc3  9.bxc3  Be7  10.O-O  d5  11.Rb1  White's got easy play with a lead in development, half-open b and e-files and an extra central pawn.  8.O-O  d5  9.Ne2  White avoids structural damage and prepares for c3 or c4 and relocating the knight to the kingside with Ng3. 38 games have reached here.  9...Nh5  The engine's top choice. Most Black tries are not very challenging, here.   9...Ne4?!  An interesting move, trying to highlight the fact that White relinquished control over e4, but it's not good.  10.c4!  With this strong move, White aims to take over the whole position with a3, b4 and c5. Obviously Black can't take the pawn because then the knight hangs.  10...Be7  11.a3   9...Bd6  10.c3   9...Be7  10.c3   9...b6  10.Ne5   9...h6  10.Qc1  An interesting idea, to sac on h6 or activate the queen after ...Bd6 to ...Bxf4 with Qxf4.  10...Bd7  11.c3  Be7  12.Ng3  10.Bd2  Bd6  11.c3  White has a version of the Exchange Caro line with the Carlsbad structure where Black has played ...e6 and locked his light-squared bishop inside the pawn chain. White plans Re1 to control e5, and then Ng3 and Ne5 to occupy it, like always in this structure.   4...b6  This is the second move in the 2-4th place category, but it's a move order mistake and White can punish it in more than one way.  5.c4  I like this move the best, simply aiming to play d5 and make Black's bishop bad.  5...Bb7  he most common reaction, but not the best.   5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  Bb4+   6...Bb7  7.Nb5   6...Nc6  7.Nb5  7.Nc3  O-O  8.Nb5  Bb7  9.Bd6  Bxd6  10.Nxd6  Bc6  11.Be2  Bxg2  12.Rg1  Bc6  13.Qd4  g6  14.h4  6.d5  exd5  Overwhelmingly most common.  7.Nc3  dxc4  Most common and also best. It's very natural for Black to take the offered pawn to prevent cxd5.  8.Nb5  Na6  9.Bxc4  d5?  This is overwhelmingly most common, having been played 35 times.   9...Be7  Objectively the best move, but it has only been played twice!  10.Nd6+  Like in many of the lines in this chapter, White grabs the two bishops.  10...Bxd6  11.Qxd6  b5  Not a super-easy move to find. Both games that reached here continued with ...Qe7 and then White could've just won with   11...Qe7  12.Ng5  12.Be2  Rc8   12...Ne4  13.Qe5+  Kf8  14.O-O  13.Qe5+  Qe7  14.O-O  Despite being down a pawn, White's slightly better due to his two bishops and safer king. However, Black does have a Queenside and central majority which has to be taken into account. The likelihood of getting here is basically zero though.  10.Qa4  This is the move Black players generally miss when they play ...d5 and after this White is winning.  10...dxc4  A further blunder.   10...Nd7  11.O-O-O  dxc4  12.Rxd7  Qxd7  13.Ne5  Qe7  14.Nxa7+  Kd8  15.Rd1+  Bd5  16.Rxd5+  Kc7  17.Rd7+  Qxd7  18.Qxd7+  Kb8  19.Nec6  11.Nd6+  Double check is always brutal and after White takes the bishop on b7, the Queen is attacked and the knight on a6 is hanging as well.  11...Ke7  12.Nxb7  Black is lost since there are too many threats to count.   4...Be7  An interesting move order. With this quite rare move Black aims for ...Nh5 next.  5.dxc5!?  Modern chess. Black moved his bishop, so we make him lose a tempo. White could also play more thematically with h3, but this would give Black a lot of flexibility as far his setup.  5...Bxc5  6.Nbd2  Giri's choice against Nepo. We'll be following their game for a while.  6...d5  Nepo's choice.   6...Be7  This sort of an idea hasn't been played, but could be tried. The point is to go for a sort of Hedgehog, but with White missing the d-pawn.  7.c4  We break with c4 immediately and stop ...d5.  7...d6  Black takes away e5 from the bishop and is now threatening ...Nh5.  8.h3  O-O  9.Be2  b6  10.O-O  Bb7  11.Rc1  White plans a3, b4 and Nd4 with a typical small edge.  7.Bd3  Nc6  8.O-O  O-O  9.c4  White breaks with c4 here.  9...b6  Nepo's move.   9...Bd6  Nakamura's move and this perhaps gets closer to equality, but White's position remains easier to play.  10.Bxd6  Here we should take the bishop. Neither Bg3 nor Bg5 lead anywhere.   10.Re1  This is another interesting idea.  10...Bxf4  11.exf4  b6  12.cxd5  Nb4  13.Bb1  Nbxd5  14.g3  10...Qxd6  11.Rc1  Rd8  12.a3  dxc4  13.Bxc4  Bd7  14.Qe2  This was played in Demchenko vs. Nakamura, 2019. The position is close to equal, but still easier to play for White. The practical likelihood of getting here is also minuscule. If you don't like it, try 10. Re1 instead.  10.Qe2  Bb7  11.Rfd1  It makes more sense to place this rook on d1 and the a-rook on the c-file, which is soon to be opened, one way or another. White has a typical small edge and plans to follow up with a3 and Rc1, with nice centralization and easier play.   4...d6  Quite rare and would only make sense if Black wants to avoid the Hedgehog and play into some ...c5 + ...d6 line.  5.c4  White does not have to play ball here with c3 @@StartBracket@@which is not bad, of course@@EndBracket@@, but can instead play c4 and Nc3. }
5. exd4 b6 6. Nbd2 Be7 { After ...Be7 Black is threatening ...Nh5, as always. }
7. h3 Bb7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O d6
{ Black completes the Hedgehog central pawn structure. } 10. Re1 Nbd7 11. Bg3
{ The start of the straightforward Kamsky plan. White keeps the c-pawn flexible in order to push a4 to a5, no matter what Black does, and then plays c4 in one move.   11.c3  This is the older, more maneuvering Bronstein plan,  11...Re8  A multi-purpose move, making possible ...Bf8 with the aim of pushing ...e5 or a later ...Nf8 to ....Ng6  12.a4  Threatening a5 and making c4 safe for the knight  12...a6  13.Nc4  Attacking the d-pawn and aiming to reroute to e3  13...Qc7  14.Bg3  Stepping away from any ...e5 breaks but maintaining control of h4  14...Rac8  15.Nfd2  Stepping away from ...Bxf3 and adding to control of e4  15...Bf8  16.Ne3  White has completed the Bronstein setup. His pieces control all the central squares. The knight on e3 also protects g2 and the bishop on g3 pressures the d6 pawn.   White will continue with the plan of b4, c4, if allowed, b5, and a5. See the model game Bronstein vs. Sokolov, for more. }
11... Re8 12. a4
{ The familiar idea, gaining Queenside space, trying to push a5 and even a6, and stopping ...b5. }
12... a6
{ Black tries to stop us by intending to meet a5 with ...b5.   12...Qc7  13.a5  Bf8  14.a6  Bc6  15.c4  Rac8  16.b4  With an initiative on the Queenside. }
13. a5 { Kamsky's new plan is to push a5 anyway. } 13... b5
{ 13...bxa5  14.Nb3 } 14. c4 { Here it comes, in one move, threatening cxb5. }
14... bxc4 15. Nxc4
{ The structure has changed and both sides have gained and lost something. White can target the fixed a6-pawn, the b6-square and the d6-pawn. Black in turn can dream of attacking White's isolated Queen's pawn and has the d5-square for his knight. }
15... Qb8
{ The best move.   15...Nb8  16.Nb6  Like in Kamsky vs Bokros, 2016 as we saw in the Heroes section. }
16. Nfd2 Bc6 17. Ra3 { A complex middlegame awaits. } *

