1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 b6
{ This is a move-order mistake, which White can punish in more than one way. }
5. c4
{ I like this move the best, simply aiming to play  d5  and make Black's bishop bad. Objectively perhaps slightly stronger might be  5.Nc3  . However, it's much more to learn. Furthermore, the text is rarer, having been played only 476 times, and leads Black down a very narrow path where he will most likely err. }
5... Bb7
{ The most common reaction, but not the best. If  5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  Bb4+  7.Nc3  O-O  8.Nb5  and White has an edge. }
6. d5 exd5
{ Overwhelmingly most common. If  6...d6  7.Nc3  and White's just better in a Benoni-ish position. }
7. Nc3 dxc4
{ Most common and also best. It's very natural for Black to take the offered pawn to prevent  cxd5  . If  7...d6  8.cxd5  and White's just better and can play  e4  next to fortify the d-pawn. }
8. Nb5 Na6
{ What else? If  8...d6  9.Bxd6   If  8...Nd5  9.Bg5!  Be7?  10.Nd6+   or  8...Nd5  9.Bg5  f6  10.Bxc4!   or  8...Nd5  9.Bg5  Nf6  10.Bxc4  . }
9. Bxc4 d5 { This is overwhelmingly most common, having been played 35 times. }
10. Qa4
{ This is the move Black players generally miss when they play ...d5 and after this White is winning. }
10... dxc4 { A further blunder. } 11. Nd6+
{ Double check is always brutal and after White takes the bishop, the Queen is attacked and the knight on a6 is hanging as well. }
11... Ke7 12. Nxb7 { Black is lost since there are too many threats to count. }
*

