[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nc3 cxd4
{ The only serious move and the only one played at master level. } 6. exd4 Bb4
{ Most common.   6...d5?  Black frequently errs here too.  7.Nb5 } 7. Bd3 O-O
{ 7...Nd5  Most common, but why...  8.Bd2  Nxc3  9.bxc3  Be7  10.O-O  d5  11.Rb1  White's got easy play with a lead in development, half-open b and e-files and an extra central pawn. }
8. O-O d5 9. Ne2
{ White avoids structural damage and prepares for c3 or c4 and relocating the knight to the kingside with Ng3. 38 games have reached here.   9.Re1  The Stockfish choice, emphasizing the fact that Black wouldn't really gain all that much from ...Bxc3.  9...Bd7  This exact position has been reached only twice.   9...h6  10.Qc1  Threatening to take on h6.  10.a3  Ba5   10...Be7  11.Ne2  White relocates the knight to g3.  11.Ne5  This is an unplayed novelty. }
9... Nh5
{ The engine's top choice. Most Black tries are not very challenging, here.   9...Ne4?!  An interesting move, trying to highlight the fact that White relinquished control over e4, but it's not good.  10.c4!  With this strong move, White aims to take over the whole position with a3, b4 and c5. Obviously Black can't take the pawn because then the knight hangs.  10...Be7   10...Bd6  11.Bxd6  Qxd6  12.c5  White just clamps down on the position with tempo and then continues with a3 and b4.   12.a3  b4 and c5 are coming next.   10...Bd7  Just to demonstrate White's idea with tempo.  11.a3  Be7  12.b4  Rc8  13.c5  11.a3   9...Bd6  This is the most played move.  10.c3   9...Be7  10.c3   9...b6  10.Ne5  White jumps into e5 immediately and is ready to continue with c3 and Ng3.   9...h6  10.Qc1!?  An interesting idea, to sac on h6 or activate the queen after ...Bd6 to ...Bxf4 with Qxf4.   9...Bd7  10.c3  Be7  11.Ng3 }
10. Bd2 Bd6 { 10...Bxd2  11.Qxd2 } 11. c3
{ White has a version of the Exchange Caro line with the Carlsbad structure where Black has played ...e6 and locked his light-squared bishop inside the pawn chain. White plans Re1 to control e5 and then Ng3 and Ne5 to occupy it, like always in this structure. }
