1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Be7
{ An interesting move order. With this move Black is always aiming for ...Nh5 next. }
5. dxc5
{ Modern chess. Black moved his bishop, so we make him lose a tempo. White could also play more thematically with h3 or Nbd2, but this would give Black a lot of flexibility as far his setup and that's something we're trying to avoid. }
5... Bxc5 6. Nbd2
{ Giri's choice against Nepo and we'll be following this game for a bit.   6.c4  Is a move here that was played by Kramnik, but this ends up in one of the main lines of the QGD after...  6...O-O  7.Nc3  Nc6  8.a3  d5  9.Qc2  This highly theoretical line is best avoided. }
6... d5 { Nepo's choice. } 7. Bd3 Nc6 8. O-O O-O 9. c4
{ White breaks with c4 here. } 9... b6
{ Nepo's move.   9...Bd6  Nakamura's move and this perhaps gets closer to equality, but White's position remains easier to play.  10.Bxd6  Here we should take the bishop. Neither Bg3 nor Bg5 lead anywhere.   10.Re1  This is another interesting idea.  10...Bxf4  11.exf4  b6  12.cxd5  Nb4  13.Bb1  Nbxd5  14.g3  10...Qxd6  11.Rc1  Rd8  12.a3  dxc4  13.Bxc4  Bd7  14.Qe2  This was played in Demchenko vs. Nakamura, 2019. The position is close to equal, but still easier to play for White. The practical likelihood of getting here is also minuscule. If you don't like it, try 10. Re1 instead. }
10. Qe2 Bb7 11. Rfd1
{ It makes more sense to place this rook on d1 and the a-rook on the c-file, which is soon to be opened, one way or another. White has a typical small edge and plans to follow up with a3 and Rc1, with nice centralization and easier play.   11.a3  Aiming for b4, is another option.  11...Bd6  12.cxd5  Nxd5  13.Bg3  Bxg3  14.hxg3  Qe7  15.e4   11.Rad1  Giri's move, but it's the wrong rook. }
