1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. exd4 b6 6. Nbd2 Be7 7. h3 Bb7 8.
Bd3 O-O 9. O-O d6 10. Re1 Nbd7 11. c3
{ The start of the more maneuvering Bronstein plan. } 11... Re8
{ A multi-purpose move, making possible a later ...Bf8 with the aim of pushing ...e5 or ...Nf8 to ...Ng6. }
12. a4
{ Starting with this familiar break is the best way to reach the desired setup. White threatens a5 and makes c4 safe for the knight. }
12... a6 { Black stops our pawn, as always. } 13. Nc4
{ Attacking the d-pawn and aiming to reroute to e3. } 13... Qc7 14. Bg3
{ Stepping away from any ...e5 breaks, but maintaining control of h4. } 14...
Rac8
{ This is one of Black's standard moves in this setup. He can also play  14...Bf8  15.Nfd2   or  14...Nf8  15.Nfd2 }
15. Nfd2 { Stepping away from ...Bxf3 and adding control to e4. } 15... Bf8
{ One of Black's standard moves. If  15...Nf8  16.Ne3  and White completes his setup. }
16. Ne3
{ White has completed the Bronstein setup. His pieces control all the central squares. The knight on e3 also protects g2 and the bishop on g3 pressures the d6-pawn. White will continue with the plan of b4, c4 and if allowed, b5, and a5. See the model gameBronstein vs. Sokolov. }
