1. d4
{ This was a Classical game. The legendary GM Bronstein was rated 2495 while Black was rated 2425. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3
{ This game doesn't start as a London system, but it soon transposes. Here White commits to a very early c3. }
3... b6 4. Bf4 Bb7 5. Nbd2 Be7 6. h3 O-O 7. e3
{ Bronstein completes the London setup. } 7... c5 8. Bd3 cxd4
{ Sokolov enters the Hedgehog. } 9. exd4 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Nc4
{ A very thematic knight jump, but better would've been to play Re1 first.   11.Re1  This is our move.  11...Re8  12.a4  First securing c4 for the knight and only then playing Nc4.  12...a6  13.Bg3  Bf8  14.Nc4  Having played Re1, a4, and Bg3 @@StartBracket@@or Bh2@@EndBracket@@, White is ready for the remaneuvering of the knights with Nc4, Nfd2 and Ne3. }
11... Qc7 12. Re1 Rfe8
{ 12...b5  Since White didn't play a4, Black could've tried pushing the b-pawn with tempo.  13.Ne3  Bc6  14.a4  bxa4?!   14...a6  15.axb5  axb5  16.Qe2  Qb7  17.Nd2  b4  18.Ndc4  15.c4!  White threatens to push d5. }
13. Bg3 Nf8
{ Instead of the more standard ...Bf8, Sokolov goes ...Nf8.   13...Bf8  14.a4  a6  15.Nfd2  With Ne3 next. }
14. Nfd2
{ In these Hedgehog structures White frequently doesn't want to allow ...Bxf3 }
14... Bc6 { The Queen wants to go to b7. } 15. a4
{ Finally. With the best move order we would play this much earlier, but we're getting closer to what we called the Bronstein setup. }
15... Ng6 16. Ne3
{ The knights have been relocated and the setup is complete. White's pieces control all the central squares. The knight on  e3  (also protects)  g2  (and the bishop on)  g3  (pressures the)  d6  (pawn. White will continue with the plan of b4, c4, if allowed, b5, and a5.) }
16... Qb7 17. b4 Rac8 { White is threatening b5 and then a5. } 18. c4 a5 19. b5
Bd7 20. Be2
{ This wasn't really needed.   20.Rc1   20.h4  Sedlak gives this, with the idea of pushing away the g6-knight with h5. }
20... e5 21. Nb3 { 21.c5!  bxc5  22.dxe5  dxe5  23.Ndc4 } 21... Qb8 22. Rc1 Ne4
23. Bg4
{ White aims to exchange the light-squared bishops, emphasizing the holes on c6 and d5. }
23... Bxg4 24. Qxg4 Nxg3 25. Qxg3 Bf8
{ 25...Nf4  26.Nf5  g6  27.dxe5  dxe5  28.Nxe7+  Rxe7  29.c5  bxc5  30.Nxa5  Qa8  31.Nc4  White's connected passed pawns should decide the game. Note that ...Qxa4 fails to the Nb6 fork. }
26. Qf3
{ It isn't entirely clear why Bronstein played this. It was natural to jump in with Nd5.   26.Nd5! }
26... Re6 27. Rcd1 { 27.g3  White should've restricted Black's knight. } 27...
Qa7 { 27...Nf4!  With the idea of ...Nd3 and ...exd4. } 28. Qg4
{ White starts to lose the thread a bit.   28.c5!  It was, again, time for this breakthrough.  28...dxc5  29.dxc5  Bxc5  30.Nxc5  bxc5   30...Rxc5  31.Rd8+  Nf8  32.Nd5  31.Nc4 }
28... Rce8 29. d5 { This loses the possibiity of the c5-breakthrough. } 29...
Rf6 30. Nd2 Rf4 31. Qe2 Rd4
{ Here the rook gets doomed after g3 and Nc2   31...Rh4  This equalizes.  32.g3  Nf4! }
32. g3 Nf4 { Too late. } 33. gxf4 exf4 34. Qg4 h5 35. Qh4 g6 36. Ng4
{ White gives back some material, but considerably simplifies the position, increasing his advantage. }
