[White "15. Pirc"]
[Black "Pirc Overview & Sidelines: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6
{ Black signals either a KID or a Grunfeld. This is the most popular move, with ~240 000 games. }
3. Nc3
{ The Jobava approach. White simply threatens e4. At top level, Black normally doesn't allow this and responds with ...d5, which we'll look at in the next chapter. However, the overwhelmingly most common move here is... }
3... Bg7
{ ...with ~55 000 games, compared to ...d5 which has been played ~19 000x   3...d6  A flexible approach, ~6000 games. We will look at these lines from the 2... d6 move order   3...c5  A delayed Benoni. Here White can play either dxc5 or d5, in both cases with thematic play. }
4. e4
{ This is now essentially a Bf4-Pirc. The current version is especially good for White since the theoretical recommendation for Black is not to commit the bishop to g7 this early.   The beautiful thing about learning this setup is that if you ever want to transition to 1.e4 you can just play this chapter's lines from the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  4.Bf4  when both Black's main moves  4...Bg7  and  4...c6  transpose to lines we cover in this chapter. }
4... d6
{ Black needs to prevent e5, if he doesn't, we will play it. Played in ~30 000 games.   4...d5  A radical idea, ~2000 games.  5.Nb5!  Only the 5th most popular and played in 50 games. Even GMs have screwed this up. The point is to remove the knight from c3 with tempo and then play e5 and f3, without allowing ...Nxc3  5...Na6   5...O-O !?  6.Bxc7  6.e5  Ne4   6...Nd7  After this White should quickly develop both knights and proceed with h4  7.Nc3  e6  8.Nf3  7.f3   4...O-O  Second most popular ~8700 games  5.e5!  This must be played, otherwise Black has ...d5  5...Ne8  Most common in practice   5...Nh5  6.Bd2  The knight is in trouble  6...Bh8  7.g4  Ng7  8.h4  d6  9.h5  dxe5  10.hxg6  fxg6  11.dxe5  White will play f4 next. Another option is Bc4+  6.Qe2!  d6  7.O-O-O  For more, see the trainable line.   4...Nh5  This move does nothing  5.Be3 }
5. Qd2
{ White has a simple plan.   Rule 1: If Black castles, we castle long and then go Bh6.   Rule 2: if Black waits, we go Bh6 immediately, forcing them to make a decision and either castle or capture. However, this one has exceptions, as you will see. }
5... O-O
{ Most common, ~25 000 games.   5...h6  Surprisingly, this is third most common, with ~4300 games  6.O-O-O  g5  7.Be3  Ng4  8.h4  Nxe3  9.Qxe3   5...h5  6.h3  c6  7.Nf3   5...Nc6  The exception  6.O-O-O  O-O  7.f3   5...c6  6.Bh6  Demonstrating rule 2. }
6. O-O-O
{ From here Black has a number of plans involving ...c6, ...Nbd7 or ...Nc6. We'll look at them in more depth in the next Roadmap file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Pirc"]
[Black "4...d5?!, 5...Na6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d5
{ Black lashes out with ...d5. Maxime Vachier-Lagrave played it successfully against Etienne Bacrot in Rapid  (2017)  . However, Bacrot didn't play the only move and later lost. What is the downside of ...d5? It weakens the h2-b8 diagonal which is where the London bishop resides. Furthermore, Black's king is still in the center. Hence, it's natural to go after  c7  . }
5. Nb5
{ The only move for an advantage. Bacrot played the natural-looking 5. e5 and later lost. The point is that after  5.e5  Ne4  white's f3 can be met with ...Nxc3. }
5... Na6 6. e5
{ After removing our own knight from  c3  and displacing Black's knight we now we play e5. }
6... Ne4
{ If ...Ng4 then Black is forced to return home after  6...Ng4  7.h3  Nh6  8.Qd2  Ng8   If  6...Nd7  then White should quickly return the knight so as not to get hit with  c6  with tempo  7.Nc3  e6  this shuts out the bishop, but if c6 then Bxa6  8.Nf3  and then continue with h4. }
7. f3 { Now Black can't play ...Nxc3. } 7... c6
{ The knight has nowhere to go so this is Black's only decent try. If ...g5 then simply Be3. }
8. fxe4 { Take it! } 8... cxb5 9. Bxb5+ { A yummy pawn. } 9... Bd7 10. Bxd7+
{ Another strong option is  10.Bxa6  with a line like  10...Qa5+  11.Qd2  Qxa6  12.exd5  , winning a pawn. }
10... Qxd7 11. Qe2
{ Getting ready to play Nf3. White can castle on either side. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
