[White "15. Pirc"]
[Black "4...d5?!, 5...O-O!?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d5 5. Nb5 O-O
{ Instead of the natural ...Na6, Black can try this sharp pawn sacrifice instead. }
6. Bxc7
{ It's better to take with the bishop, with tempo. If  6.Nxc7  Nh5  is a bit annoying. }
6... Qd7 { Or  6...Qe8  , but then White is comfortable. } 7. Bxb8
{ Luring the rook away from the defense of a7. } 7... Rxb8 8. e5 Ne4
{ If  8...Nh5  9.Nxa7 } 9. f3 a6 10. Na7 Ng5 11. Nxc8 Rbxc8 12. h4 Ne6 13. c3
{ White is just a pawn up. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Pirc"]
[Black "4...O-O?!, 5...Nh5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 O-O
{ This is the second non-standard move. Wang Yue played this against Grischuk in Blitz in 2014. Grischuk, like Bacrot, didn't play the best move, but won anyway. What's the downside of O-O? It leaves White a free hand in the centre. After all, the standard  4...d6  is played to stop e5. Hence, we must push! }
5. e5 { Grischuk played the usual  5.Qd2  and got hit with  5...d5  . } 5...
Nh5 6. Bd2 { Also fine is  6.Bc1  The threat is g4, trapping the knight. } 6...
Bh8
{ Most common in practice. Best might be  6...c5  7.g4  cxd4  8.Nce2  but it's hard to see many Black players acquiesce to the loss of a piece that easily.   If Black prevents g4 by  6...f5  7.f4  with positional domination. }
7. g4 Ng7 8. h4 d6
{ Most natural, trying to break down White's center. If  8...d5  9.h5 } 9. h5
dxe5 10. hxg6 fxg6 11. dxe5
{ White will play f4 next and have a big center and all the threats. Another option is  11.Bc4+  . }
