[Black "5...h6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 { The correct move, stopping e5. } 5.
Qd2
{ The Tabiya of our basic setup, aiming to exchange the dark-squared bishops. }
5... h6
{ Black's main options are 5... O-O,  5... c6, 5... Nbd7, and 5...Nc6. However, let's look at the two possible h-pawn moves first, starting with this one. }
6. O-O-O
{ The thematic and easy-to-remember option. There's also a host of good alternatives like   6.h3   6.Be2   6.Nf3 }
6... g5
{ This is mostly played. If Black plays a non-forcing pawn move then Be2, stopping Ng4 makes sense   6...a6  7.Be2   6...c6  7.Be2  However, let's see what happens if they go after our bishop. }
7. Be3 Ng4 8. h4
{ Striking at the kingside, trying to open the file for the rook. } 8... Nxe3
9. Qxe3
{ Black has won the bishop pair but wasted a lot of time. If Black allows, we will take on g5, exchange rooks and push e5, playing in the center. For example  9...Nc6  10.hxg5  hxg5  11.Rxh8  Bxh8  12.e5   However, if Black plays g4, we can play Nge2-g3 and then push f4 with the ultimate plan of e5. For example  9...g4  10.Nge2  Nd7  11.Ng3  h5  12.Kb1  Nb6  13.f4  . }
