[Black "Castling Lines: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Qd2 O-O
{ The main move, played ~24 000x   5...Nc6  Played ~4200x. We'll include these under castling plans since Black invariably castles after our next move  6.O-O-O  O-O  7.f3!  It's important to play this first, before Bh6  7...e5?!  The most common try, but this just wins for White with precise play   7...a6  The second most common move and the usual GM choice  8.g4  Preventing e5.  8...b5  9.h4  b4  10.Nce2  e5  11.Bh6  exd4  12.Nxd4  Ne5  13.h5  White will break through soon.   7...h5  Might be best, but it's rarely played, and White has now all the time in the world  8.Kb1  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Qxd8  Rxd8  10.Rxd8+  Nxd8  11.Bxe5  White wins a pawn, but...  11...Nxe4!  Played 114 times  12.Bxg7  Nf2  13.Bf6!  Attacking the knight. For more, see the trainable line. }
6. O-O-O c6
{ The most common and a typical Pirc move, played ~4800x. Black intends ...Qa5, ...b5, ...Be6, with pressure on a2   6...Nbd7  Second most common, with ~4500 games, but this is basically winning for White, and in more than one way too!  7.e5!  This is the novel and sharp option.   7.Bh6  We will also look at the older and slower way of playing  7...Nh5  Best move, but only third most likely   7...Ne8  Most common  8.Bh6   7...dxe5  Second most common and sharp  8.dxe5  Nh5  9.Bh6  Bxe5   9...Nxe5  10.Qxd8  Bxh6+  11.Kb1  Rxd8  12.Rxd8+  Kg7  13.h3  10.h4   7...Ng4  Black attacks e5  8.Nf3  8.Bh6  Nb6  An independent option  9.Bxg7  Nxg7  10.Bd3  White's got a clear edge   6...Nc6  Transposes   6...Re8  A radical option, intending to meet Bh6 with ...Bh8  7.Bh6  Bh8  8.f3  White just secures the center and aims to continue with g4 and h4 }
7. Bh6
{ Rule 3: Block the h-file with Bh6, preparing the expansion with h4-h5, exchange of bishops and penetration with the Queen. }
7... b5
{ Black threatens...b4, kicking the knight and leaving the e-pawn defenseless }
8. f3 { Protecting the e-pawn and preparing g4 and h4 } 8... Qa5
{ Most common. Black puts pressure on , which would be defenseless after ...b4, can hope to use the Queen laterally, and can strengthen his attack with ...Be6. }
9. h4
{ The best move, not wasting any time and not caring about the a-pawn.   9.Kb1  The older, slower, and most common way of playing  9...b4  10.Nce2  Be6  11.Nc1!  A key defensive idea }
9... b4 10. Nb1 Be6 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. h5 Nbd7 13. a3
{ Exploiting the pin and playing on both sides of the board! For more, see the trainable line. }
