1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Qd2 O-O 6. O-O-O
{ Rule number 1: as soon as Black goes O-O you go O-O-O! White has an alternative way of playing here suggested by GM Larry Kaufman in his new repertoire book, namely the immediate Bh6. Perhaps this restricts Black's options a bit more and is maybe less to learn, but it is also considerably less rich and thematic. Here's a sample line:   6.Bh6  e6  7.Bxg7  Kxg7  8.Nge2  c5  9.d5  b5  10.Ng3  b4  11.Nd1  Nbd7  12.h4  h5  13.Qg5  Nb6  14.a4  a5  15.Ne3  . }
6... Re8 { A radical option, intending to meet Bh6 with ...Bh8 } 7. Bh6 Bh8 8.
f3
{ White just secures the center and aims to continue with g4 and h4 with a clear advantage. Notice that ...e5 is not really all that good since after dxe5, Black will have to capture with the rook. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Pirc"]
[Black "5...O-O, 6...c6, 10...Qxa2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Qd2 O-O 6. O-O-O c6
{ The most common, and a typical Pirc move. Black intends ...Qa5, ...b5, ...Be6, with pressure on a2. }
7. Bh6
{ Rule number 2: Block the h-file with Bh6, preparing the expansion with h4-h5, exchange of bishops and penetration with the Queen. }
7... b5
{ Black threatens ...b4 to kick away our knight and leave the e-pawn defenseless. If  7...Ng4  8.Bxg7  Kxg7  9.f3  and White will expand fast with g4 and h4. }
8. f3
{ The key move, protecting the e4-pawn, g4-square and preparing the expansion with g4 and h4-h5. Notice that if Black makes nonsense moves he can fall in a common trap in Blitz along the lines of  8...Bb7  9.h4  Nbd7  10.h5  Nxh5??  11.Rxh5!  gxh5??  12.Qg5  and lights out. }
8... Qa5 9. h4
{ This position used to be played more slowly with the natural  9.Kb1  , intending to meet ...b4 with the important defensive maneuver Ne2 to Nc1 to Nb3. This can be played as well, but there are a few subtleties here that it is important to understand.   First, all works out nicely after  9.Kb1  b4  10.Nce2  Be6  11.Nc1  and Black has no attack and White can activate the knight with Nb3 next.   Second, after  9.Kb1  Be6?!  intending ...b4 next doesn't work at all due to the must-know  10.Nd5!!  attacking the e-pawn and the Queen  10...Qxd2  11.Nxe7+  Kh8  12.Bxd2  Re8  13.d5!  and White's knight escapes.   Black's best option is  9.Kb1  Bxh6!  10.Qxh6  Be6  11.h4!  and now things get messy after  11...b4!?  12.d5!  bxc3  13.dxe6  Qb4  threatening mate  14.exf7+  Kxf7  15.b3  a5  16.a4  and White is better, but things have been and continue to be sharp and messy.   So all in all  9.h4  is the best move, not wasting any time, and not caring about the a-pawn. It turns out the king is better on c1 since now White always has Nb1. Time matters! }
9... b4
{ Black continues with his idea. Everything else just allows White to continue with his plan, e. g.  9...Be6  10.h5! }
10. Nb1 Qxa2
{ The most natural move here is to just grab the pawn. If  10...Nbd7  11.h5!  Nxh5  12.Bxg7  Nxg7  13.Qh6  Nf6  14.g4 }
11. h5 { We're much faster! } 11... Nbd7
{ Black tries to bring in the knight. If  11...Nxh5??  you should know what to do already 🥳 }
12. hxg6 { hxg6 and Kxg7 can also be reversed. } 12... fxg6
{ 12...hxg6??  13.Bxg7  Kxg7  14.Qh6+  Kg8  15.Qh8#  . } 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qh6+
Kg8
{ The most natural move.  14...Kh8  would be an instructive mistake due to leaving the rook potentially defenseless and thereby allowing  15.e5!  dxe5  16.dxe5  Nxe5??  17.Qxf8+   14...Kf7  is better, but can just be met with  15.Nh3  Ke8  Black can try to run away, but now  16.e5!  , opening the center  16...dxe5  17.Ng5  a4  18.Nxh7  Nxh7  19.Qxg6+  Kd8  20.Qxc6!  attacking the rook before capturing the knight. }
15. e5
{ A nice pawn sacrifice with the point of opening the d-file. The direct  15.Nh3  is also good and if  15...Qf7  16.Ng5  Qg7  17.Qxg7  Kxg7  18.Ne6+  winning the exchange.   However, better is  15.Nh3  Rf7  and now White has to find a correct move after which we would transpose to the text line. }
15... dxe5 16. Nh3
{ White is completely winning with Ng5 coming next.  16...Rf7  can be met with  17.dxe5!  and  17...Nxe5??  is not possible due to  18.Rd8+  demonstrating the point of opening the d-file earlier. }
*

