1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Qd2 O-O 6. O-O-O Nbd7
{ Black's second most common, KID-style option, played in ~4500 games. } 7. Bh6
{ This is also natural and good. Black has two choices here, strike at the center with 7... c5 or 7... e5. }
7... c5
{ Frequently encountered in practice, but this is practically winning for White if he knows what he's doing. }
8. Bxg7 { Step 1: Exchange bishops. } 8... Kxg7 9. e5 { Step 2: Push e5. } 9...
dxe5 { Very natural and very common. We will also look at  9...Ne8 } 10. dxe5
Ng4 { If  10...Ne8  11.Bb5  and White wins a piece. } 11. f4 Qa5 12. h3
{ Kick away the knight and prepare the expansion with g4. } 12... Nh6 13. g4
Nb6 { If  13...Ng8  14.h4   Or  13...Ng8  14.Nf3  . } 14. f5
{ Forcing play. The obvious threat is f6+ followed by Qxh6. For example  14...Bd7  15.f6+  exf6  16.exf6+  Kxf6  17.Qxh6   Notice also that  gxf5  is not possible due to  14...gxf5?  15.Qg5+!  Kh8  16.Qxh6  . It follows that Black has to sac a piece on f5. }
14... Nxf5
{ Taking with the knight is better than the bishop, partly because then the knight isn't a target anymore. }
15. gxf5 Bxf5 16. Bd3 { Challenging the bishop immediately. } 16... Rad8 17.
Qf4 { Or  17.Qe3 } 17... Bxd3 18. cxd3
{ White is a lot better and will easily consolidate. } *

