1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Qd2 O-O 6. O-O-O Nbd7 7. Bh6 e5
{ Black's better break. } 8. dxe5
{ We almost always take on e5. White can of course play many moves here, including  8.Bxg7 }
8... Nxe5 9. Bxg7
{ Objectively best is exchanging bishops and playing f4. However, White can also play in the more thematic way with  9.f3  Be6  10.h4  . }
9... Kxg7 10. f4 Nc6
{ If  10...Neg4  then simply  11.h3  and White is a lot better. } 11. h3
{ Preventing ...Bg4 and preparing g4 and f5. White has to keep an open mind as to piece deployment. Both Bd3 and Bg2 could be useful as well as Nf3 and Nge2. Here's how the line frequently continues. }
11... Re8 12. Bd3 Nb4
{ Black goes bishop-hunting. If  12...Be6  13.Nf3  completing development.   or  12...Be6  13.g4  starting the attack at once and intending f5. }
13. Nf3 Nxd3+ 14. Qxd3 { White will play e5 soon with Rhe1 & Ne4 to follow. } *

