[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Qd2 Nc6
{ Another option. This blocks the c-pawn, but prepares ...e5. } 6. O-O-O O-O 7.
f3
{ I much prefer the standard plan with 7. f3 recommended by GM Mihail Marin and played by GM Maxim Dlugy over the GingerGM suggestion of 7. Nf3. As it turns out, ...e5 can be allowed and is in fact a mistake. }
7... e5 { The critical-looking move, but it's not good. } 8. dxe5 { Take! }
8... dxe5 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. Rxd8+ Nxd8 11. Bxe5 { White wins a pawn. } 11...
Nxe4
{ Black's only chance to try to get back into the game is to find this move. }
12. Bxg7
{ The following forced sequence represents best play. All White moves make a lot of sense. }
12... Nf2 13. Bf6 { Attacking the defenseless knight on d8. } 13... Bd7
{ This is one option, protecting the knight and getting ready for Bc6. However, Black can also try  13...Nc6  14.Bh4!  Nxh1  15.g4  with  Bg2  to come. }
14. g4
{ Preparing to fianchetto the bishop in a way that doesn't allow for Nxg3. However, g3 is actually also very good. }
14... Nxh1 15. Ne4
{ Controlling f2, but also protecting the f3 pawn by putting itself in the way. Also good is Bh4. }
15... Bc6
{ Now Black would be attacking the f-pawn, immobilizing the Nf1. However, due to having played Ne4 we're good to develop the other knight to control f2 once more. }
16. Nh3 Ne6 17. Bg2
{ White will win the knight and have a completely winning position. } *

