[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Qd2 c6
{ The second most popular move, with ~8000 games. Black delays castling.   If  5...Nbd7  Another option, played ~6200 times  6.O-O-O!  Here it's best to castle. If Black castles we transpose to earlier lines. However, it's hard for him to make a good move otherwise since the  Bf4  prevents ...e5 and any other move Black makes we go e5! ourselves. For more, see the trainable lines. }
6. Bh6 { In this line it's best to force Black to make a decision. } 6... Bxh6
{ Played ~3400 times.  6...O-O  7.O-O-O  Transposes to an earlier line. } 7.
Qxh6
{ The Queen prevents Black from castling so now we'd really like to open the center with e5. }
7... Qa5
{ Black's main move, pinning and attacking e4. It's been played ~1400x. Here the principle is to defend while developing fast.   Note that if Black plays only the slightly less popular  7...b5?!  immediately we have  8.e5  with the idea that if the knight moves we play Qg7 so  8...dxe5  9.dxe5  Nd5  10.O-O-O }
8. Bd3
{ Developing and protecting the e-pawn. If White is allowed to continue undisturbed he would just play Nf3 and O-O and play in the center. }
8... c5
{ Theory move, but only the third most common   8...b5  Black's most common move  9.Nf3  Natural, and best   9.Ne2!?  b4  10.Nb1  b3+  11.Nbc3  9...b4  Black has to try this. Simple development leaves White with a big edge after O-O  10.Ne2  b3+  11.c3  bxa2  12.e5!  For more, see the trainable line.   8...Nbd7  9.Nf3   8...Qh5 }
9. Nf3
{ Again, developing and defending. Only 11  (!)  games have reached this position. I like this much better than the mainly played d5, which allows Black to liquidate into an endgame after the clever sequence   9.d5  Nbd7  10.Nf3  c4  11.Bxc4  Qc5  12.Bd3  Qxf2+  13.Kxf2  Ng4+  14.Ke2  Nxh6  This is still better for White, but I don't see why we should go for it.   Perhaps White can improve with  9.d5  Nbd7  10.O-O-O  but then he's sort of castled into it and even though the engines like this things get practically very messy after moves like  10...a6  ,  10...Rb8  , the direct  10...b5!?  as a pawn sacrifice or even  10...Ne5  , and  10...Ng4  , with a lot to learn. }
9... cxd4
{ The most natural and common move.   If  9...Bg4?!  Natural, but a mistake  10.e5!  dxe5  11.dxe5  Nd5  12.Qg7  Rf8  13.Ng5  Nxc3  14.O-O  Nd5  15.Bc4  Be6  16.Rad1   9...Nc6  10.d5  Nd4  11.Nd2 }
10. Nxd4 Nc6 { If  10...Qb6  11.O-O-O   If  10...Qc5  11.O-O-O } 11. Bb5
{ No lichess game has reached here... } 11... Bd7 12. O-O-O
{ White intends Rhe1 next with perfect centralization. He has influence all over the board and can choose to play wherever he wants. }
