[Black "5...Nbd7, 6...c5?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Qd2 Nbd7
{ Another try, played ~5100x. However, the knight doesn't belong here and it's no good at all. }
6. O-O-O
{ Here this is the best move. The point is to keep the bishop where it is, preventing ...e5 and supporting our own e5 push. This leaves Black in quite a tough spot since there isn't much for them to do, but castle. However, if Black now castles, we can play e5 or Bh6, transposing to the line with 5...O-O and 6...Nbd7.   6.Bh6  Would follow the rule that if Black doesn't castle, we force him to make a choice. It is another way of playing it, but it's not as strong as the text.  6...Bxh6  7.Qxh6  e5  8.Nf3  exd4  Black normally captures here and now White does, indeed, get a nice advantage after.  9.Nxd4  Nc5  10.Bb5+  Bd7  11.Bxd7+  Ncxd7  12.O-O-O  Qe7  13.Ndb5  Forcing Black to give up castling. }
6... c5
{ The second most common move, but this basically loses on the spot.   6...O-O  The most common move, but now we're just transposing to previous lines after e5 or Bh6.  7.e5   6...e5  Third most common, with over 400 games, but it just drops a pawn after.  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Bxe5  O-O  9.f4  Qe8  10.Bxf6  Nxf6  Whichever way Black captures, we play e5.  11.e5 }
7. dxc5 Nxc5 8. e5 Nfe4
{ This is the most common move, but White has a crushing tactical solution here.   8...Nfd7  9.exd6  O-O  10.Nf3  White is up a pawn with a development lead. }
9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qe1
{ What is the point of Qe1, rather than the more natural-looking Qe3. Well, it attacks the knight the same, but it prevents ...Qa5, seeking counterplay, at the same time. It has been played only twice.   10.Qe3  Qa5  11.Qxe4  Bf5  Is the idea. Objectively, White is still better, but this gives Black a lot more than the text. }
10... d5
{ Black thinks he's cementing the knight.   10...Bf5  11.Bb5+  Kf8  12.g4!  The tactics flow. }
11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Rxd5 { White is just winning here. } *

