[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d6 { The flexible Pirc-Philidor move. } 3. Nc3 Nbd7
{ Black threatens ...e5, which must be prevented at all costs   3...g6  4.e4  c6  The key point! Black refrains from developing the bishop and kingside castling and accelerates central and Queenside play first. This reuires White to adopt a more center-oriented setup as well   4...Bg7  Transposes to main line  5.Qd2  This looks like practically the best way of playing since a few lines transpose to earlier and practically Black often goes wrong here. It was also given as the main line by Marin in his Pirc book. Kaufman prefers the also logical Nf3.  5...Nbd7  Marin's recommendation and the third most common move   5...b5  Most common, still delaying castling, but here White has  6.e5  Nh5  7.Be3  dxe5  8.dxe5  Qxd2+  9.Bxd2  White has the better endgame.   5...Bg7  Second most common, but it transposes to a previous line after  6.Bh6  6.Nf3  Bg7  7.Bh6!  Thematic, forcing Black to make a choice. Marin doesn't cover it  7...O-O   7...Bxh6  8.Qxh6  This is better than usual since White is already more developed to where he wants to be while Black is committed to ...Nbd7  8.h4  Bxh6  9.Qxh6  Ng4  10.Qd2  h5  11.Be2  White will castle long and attack on the kingside. }
4. Nf3 c5
{ This very interesting move was suggested by Chess.com user Firethorn15 a few years ago with the idea of meeting e3 with ...Nh5. I don't think there's any chance to avoid playing the d5 line so we should just push it.   4...g6  5.e4  Bg7  6.Qd2  We've transposed to one of the previous lines   4...c6  Black intends some sort of a Czech Pirc system with ...Qc7 or ...Qa5.  5.e4  Qa5   5...Qc7  6.e5  dxe5  7.Nxe5  Nxe5  8.dxe5  Nd7  9.Bc4  e6  10.Ne4  6.e5!?   6.Bd3  A more restrained way of playing  6...e5  7.Be3  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.h3  6...dxe5  7.dxe5  Nd5  8.Bd2 }
5. d5 b5 { Black gambits a pawn. If  5...g6  6.e4 } 6. Nxb5 Rb8
{ 6...Qa5+  Stockfish's preference  7.Nc3  Rb8  8.Bd2  Rxb2  9.e4  g6  10.Bc4 }
7. c4 a6 8. Nc3 Rxb2 9. e4 g6 10. Qc1
{ A nice multi-purpose move, with tempo. } 10... Rb4 { 10...Rb7  11.Be2 } 11.
Be2 Bg7 12. Bh6 O-O 13. O-O
{ White retains a decent edge in an interesting position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Pirc"]
[Black "2...d6, 3...g6 to Pirc with 5...b5?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d6 4. e4 c6
{ The key point! Black refrains from developing the bishop and kingside castling and accelerates central and Queenside play first. This requires White to adopt a more center-oriented setup as well. }
5. Qd2
{ This looks like practically the best way of playing since a few lines transpose to earlier and Black often goes wrong here. It was also given as the main line by Marin in his Pirc book. }
5... b5 { The most common move, with ~900 games. } 6. e5
{ Only the 5th@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ most common move with ~25 games... }
6... Nh5
{ 6...dxe5  7.dxe5  Nd5   7...Qxd2+  8.Bxd2  Transposes to the text.  8.Nxd5  Qxd5  9.Qxd5  cxd5  10.Bxb5+  White wins a pawn.   6...Nd5?  7.Nxd5  cxd5  8.Bxb5+  White wins a pawn.   6...b4  7.exf6  bxc3  8.Qxc3  exf6  9.O-O-O   6...Ng8  Good luck with that.  7.exd6  exd6  8.d5 }
7. Be3 dxe5 8. dxe5 Qxd2+ 9. Bxd2
{ White has the better endgame and can continue with f4, g4, Bg2, O-O-O etc. }
