[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Pirc"]
[Black "2...d6, 3...g6 to Pirc with 5...Nbd7 6...Qa5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d6 4. e4 c6 5. Qd2 Nbd7
{ Marin's recommendation and the third most common move.   5...Bg7  The second most common move.  6.Bh6  Transposes to a previous line.   5...Qa5  The fourth most common move.  6.Nf3  b5   6...Nbd7  Transposes.  7.e5  b4  8.exf6  bxc3  9.bxc3+-  White will just play Bd3 and O-O. }
6. Nf3 { Threatening to go e5. } 6... Qa5
{ The third most common move, but in some ways the most interesting.   6...b5  The second most common move, but this gets hit with e5 again.  7.e5  b4  8.Na4  Nh5  9.Be3  Qa5  10.b3  dxe5  11.Bc4  Bg7  12.O-O  ±  White will bring the rooks to the center.  12...O-O  13.a3  exd4  14.Bxd4  e5  15.Bb2  Qc7  16.axb4 }
7. Bc4
{ Intending to go e5 on the next move.   7.e5  White can  go for the endgame here.  7...dxe5  8.dxe5  Nd5  9.Nxd5  Qxd2+  10.Bxd2  cxd5  11.h4 }
7... e5
{ Black stops e5 by playing it himself.   7...Bg7  Allows us to demonstrate White's idea.  8.e5!   7...b5  8.Bd3 }
8. Ng5
{ The most interesting and dynamic move, setting a trap.   8.Bg3  Also entirely ok. }
8... Be7
{ Black really has to find this very unintuitive move.   8...exf4  Greedy.  9.Bxf7+  Kd8  10.Ne6+  Ke7  11.Nd5+  The point!  11...Qxd5  12.exd5  Kxf7  13.Ng5+   8...Bg7??  9.Bxf7+  Ke7  10.Bb3  exf4  11.Nd5+  cxd5  12.Qxa5 }
9. dxe5
{ 9.Bxf7+  Doesn't quite work anymore due to  9...Kf8  10.Bb3  exf4  11.Ne6+  Ke8  12.O-O-O  Probably the best move if White wants to play on. }
9... dxe5 10. Be3 O-O 11. O-O *

