1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. Nf3 c6 5. e4 Qa5 6. e5
{ The more adventurous and principled option, preventing ...e5 at all costs. If the ensuing lines are too sharp for your taste, I also gave a safer, more positional alternative in  6.Bd3  . }
6... dxe5 { If  6...Nd5  7.Bd2!  and White is better. } 7. dxe5 Nd5
{ This is mostly played. Better, and very sharp, but practically very unlikely is  7...Ne4  8.e6!  fxe6  9.Qd4  Nxc3  10.Bd2  Nb5  11.Qxd7+  Bxd7  12.Bxa5  g6  13.a4  Nd6  14.Bc3  Rg8  15.Bd3  with an advantage to White. }
8. Bd2 e6 9. Ne4 Qb6 10. c4 f5 11. exf6 N5xf6 12. Nxf6+ Nxf6 13. Bd3
{ White is a lot better here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Pirc"]
[Black "2...d6 to Czech Pirc with ...Qa5 and 6. Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. Nf3 c6 5. e4 Qa5
{ Black wants to get in ...e5, but needs the help of the Queen to do so. ...Qa5 is best, pinning the knight and thereby attacking the e4-pawn, while also supporting ...e5. }
6. Bd3
{ White can also simply disregard the threat of ...e5 and continue developing. }
6... e5 7. Be3 Be7
{ If Black gets adventurous with  7...Ng4  8.Bd2  and the knight will soon be kicked with  h3  . }
8. O-O O-O 9. h3
{ White has a classical e4-position with the center and a slight space advantage. He can continue with a4, grabbing space on the Queenside or Re1. }
