[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. Nf3 c5
{ This very interesting move was suggested by Chess.com user Firethorn15 a few years ago with the following ideas:   4...c5  5.e3  Nh5   4...c5  5.d5  b5!?  6.Nxb5  Rb8  7.c4  a6  8.Nc3  Rxb2  .  I don't think there's any chance to avoid going into the d5 line so we should just push forward and play it. }
5. d5
{ 5.e3  Nh5  6.Bc4  is actually good for White.   However  5.e3  a6   or  5.e3  g6  are not as good. }
5... b5 { Black gambits a pawn. If  5...g6  6.e4  +/= } 6. Nxb5 Rb8
{ Stockfish prefers  6...Qa5+  7.Nc3  Rb8  8.Bd2  Rxb2  9.e4  g6  10.Bc4  but White keeps an edge. }
7. c4 a6 8. Nc3 Rxb2 9. e4 { Grabbing the center. } 9... g6 10. Qc1
{ A nice multi-purpose move, with tempo. } 10... Rb4
{ Another option is  10...Rb7  11.Be2  and our plan doesn't change. } 11. Be2
{ Getting a step closer to castling. } 11... Bg7 12. Bh6
{ The most straightforward and forcing Black to make a decision whether to capture or castle. Firethorn's original idea was  12.O-O  Ng4  but then  13.h3  Nge5  14.Nxe5  Nxe5  15.Bh6  doesn't look too good for Black. }
12... O-O 13. O-O
{ White retains a decent edge in an interesting position. He could also play  13.a3  or  13.Bxg7  first. }
*

