[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 { Black stops e4 with the Grunfeld approach } 4.
e3
{ White opens the diagonal for his Queen and aims for a quick opening of the h-file with h4-h5 }
4... Bg7 5. h4
{ Shout with us: 'Harry ! Harry !'. White intends h5 and hxg6. Black's main moves are ...O-O and meet h5 with ...c5 and the immediate ...h5. However, we'll start by looking at some piece moves which are invariably bad. }
5... Nbd7
{ Blunder, played ~150x like the following moves   5...Nc6  A similar blunder  6.Nb5  O-O  7.Nxc7   5...Bg4  6.f3  This only helps White  6...Be6  7.Qd2   5...Bf5  6.Nge2  Going to g3, to bother the bishop }
6. Nb5 O-O 7. Bxc7 Qe8 8. h5
{ Stockfish is brutal here and just sacrifices the h-pawn with a concrete idea. The idea is to lure the knight away from the defense of d5. }
8... Nxh5 { 8...a6  9.h6  Bh8  10.Nc3 } 9. Bh2 { Threatening the fork } 9...
Qd8 10. Nc7 Rb8 11. Nxd5 { White takes the central pawn } 11... Qa5+ 12. Nc3
{ With Be2 next } *

