1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 c5
{ A common mistake and the third most popular move in the position with ~1500 games. If Black plays ...c5 and hasn't castled yet, White has the strong... }
6. Nb5
{ Black has to play ...Na6 which means that White's knight is secure on  b5  and White can set up the bind with a4 and c3. }
6... Na6
{ 6...Qa5+?  A losing mistake  7.b4!  A very typical pawn sacrifice  7...Qxb4+  8.c3  Qa5  9.Nc7+  Kd8  10.Rc1 }
7. Be2
{ We take a moment to prevent ...Bg4 first and then continue with a4 and c3. }
7... O-O 8. c3
{ White has a simple edge with a4 next. Black has a problem with moving any of his Queenside pieces because moving the rook drops the a-pawn. }
