[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Grünfeld"]
[Black "5...O-O: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 O-O
{ Black's first main option and the second most common move, with ~3300 games. }
6. h5 { We push on. } 6... c5
{ Second most common with ~750 games.   6...Nxh5?  A typical mistake and actually still the most common move in this position, with ~1700 games  7.Rxh5!  gxh5  8.Qxh5  White is hitting the d-pawn, even though he's not really intending to take it. With the open h-file and all the minor pieces entering the attack White's already winning and scores massively from here. See the trainable lines and model games in this chapter for more. }
7. hxg6 hxg6
{ This used to be considered worse, opening the h-file for White, but current engines like it more and it is also somewhat more common, with ~350 games.   7...fxg6  Less common, with ~250 games.  8.dxc5  Qa5  One option, aiming to recapture the pawn   8...Nc6  9.Nf3  Bg4  10.Qd2!  For more, see the trainable lines.   8...Nbd7?  9.Nxd5  9.Nf3  Nc6   9...Qxc5  10.Qd4  Qxd4  11.Nxd4  Nc6  12.f3!  10.Nd2!?  Qxc5  Black takes the pawn while he can  11.Nb3  Qb6  12.Nxd5  Nxd5  13.Qxd5+  e6  14.Qe4  Bxb2  15.Rd1  Bc3+  16.Nd2  Nb4  17.Bc4  Nd5  18.O-O  Nxf4  19.exf4  White's better despite Black's two bishops because of his development lead and safer king. }
8. Qd2 { White intends O-O-O, f3, g4, Qh2, Bh6, Bxg7 and Qh8# } 8... Nc6 9.
O-O-O Bf5 10. f3 { The best move. } 10... Nb4 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. cxd3
{ For more, see the trainable line. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Grünfeld"]
[Black "5...O-O, 6...Nxh5?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 {  } 5... O-O 6. h5
{ Harry goes forward and tempts Black to take it with his knight. } 6... Nxh5
{ Black falls for it. } 7. Rxh5
{ Don't even blink. This line is super easy and fun for White. All our pieces come to very natural squares and Black has to make many tough decisions. }
7... gxh5 8. Qxh5
{ White is hitting the d-pawn twice, even though he doesn't really even want to take it. }
8... Nd7
{ Objectively best, in order to both counter the coming attack on  c7  and to shore up the kingside with ...Nf6. However, it's only the third most common and the most played moves are ...c6 and ...e6, with ...f5 slightly trailing, all to protect the d-pawn.   For  8...c6?!  see the sample gameReiland vs Baratech Galup   For  8...e6?!  see the sample gamePiorun vs Szczurek   For  8...f5  see the sample gameGirya vs Bodnaruk. }
9. Bd3
{ White has two good choices here, but taking the d-pawn is not one of them. This developing move is simple and strong. The alternative is the tricky 9. Qh2 threatening the c-pawn and forcing Black to choose between ...c6 or ...c5. Notice that if Black neglects this with something like ...Nf6 we do take the c-pawn with tempo. For example  9.Qh2  Nf6  10.Bxc7  . }
9... f5
{ The best move, shutting down the bishop's diagonal and also protecting the d-pawn. However, the natural ...Nf6 is far more common, but then  9...Nf6  10.Qh2  is still good. }
10. Nf3
{ Developing another piece. Now White just needs to castle and bring the rook into the attack. }
10... Nf6 11. Qh2
{ This is objectively the strongest move, attacking the c7-pawn. With O-O-O and ...c6 inserted, White could also play Qh4, but here it doesn't work. }
11... c6
{ If the immediate  11...Ng4  12.Qg3  c6  13.O-O-O  transposes.   If  11...c5  12.O-O-O  . }
12. O-O-O Ng4 13. Qg3 Qe8
{ The computer choice. The problem is that the light-squared bishop doesn't really have a good, active square. If the human-looking  13...Be6  14.Ng5!  Bd7  15.Nxh7!!  Kxh7  16.Qxg4  . }
14. Rh1 Qg6
{ Defending the kingside. There are 2 games in the database that have actually reached this position, but in neither did White continue with the best move... }
15. Ne2
{ Bringing the last piece into the attack and intending to continue with Ng5, Nh4 or Ne5, depending on what Black does. Of course, the likelihood of even getting all the way here is very small. If they knew what they were doing they wouldn't have played ...Nxh5? in the first place. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Grünfeld"]
[Black "Indrek Reiland vs. Jose Manuel Baratech Galup, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 { This was my second-ever Classical game. } 1... d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 g6
4. Nc3 Bg7 5. h4 O-O 6. h5 Nxh5 7. Rxh5
{ I was very happy to get this on the board. Talk about opening study paying off! }
7... gxh5 8. Qxh5 c6
{ Black was worried about the pawn on d5, but this is too slow. Here I faced my first big decision, whether to play the obvious Bd3 immediately, causing the response ...f5 or to play Nf3 first. }
9. Nf3 { I chose this move.  8.Bd3  is objectively stronger. However... } 9...
f6
{ ...my choice caused the first definite mistake. Now, after 10. Bd3, Black loses a tempo and has to play ...f5 anyway. }
10. Bd3 f5 11. g4
{ Again, I had to figure out how to proceed. First, I considered the most forcing Ng5 to provoke ...h6, but I wasn't certain of the continuation. Second, I considered the obvious O-O-O which is the computer suggestion and objectively the strongest. However, I was also thinking about preventing ...Nd7 to ...Nf6 which would defend Black's kingside.  In the end I decided to play g4 with the idea of not taking on f5, but rather having the option of pushing g5 to prevent anything from coming to f6. }
11... Qe8 12. Qh2
{ A familiar threat in this position. Now I thought he would play ...Nd7, after which I would play g5 and then O-O-O. But... }
12... Na6
{ I definitely missed the point behind this move, which is to play ...Nb4 next. }
13. g5
{ I went forward with my plan of pushing to g5 since I realized the pawn on f5 is good for me. However, this neglects his plan. The simple a3 first would've been best. }
13... Nb4 { This is what I missed. } 14. Kd2
{ A small victory for him. I considered both O-O-O and Kd2. Computer thinks that the former is better, but I thought the king would be safer in the center. }
14... Nxd3 15. cxd3 Be6
{ I was waiting for the obvious defense ...Qg6 which would've kept things going for him for a bit. This is another definite mistake. }
16. g6
{ Here I had a long 20 min. think and considered two attacking options.   First is the obvious attacking idea down the h-file with Rh1, Qg6, Ne5 to attack the Queen, Bxe5, Bxe5. But I saw that he could play ...f4 to liberate his position and screw up my attack. This line is still playable but one has to play Ne2 first, to cover f4. But even then, he can sac the exchange and come out fighting. For example   16.Rh1  Qg6  17.Ne5  Bxe5  18.Bxe5  f4!  Then I started considering the other, much more effective idea of g6. I saw three possible responses:   16.g6  hxg6  this I planned to meet with  17.Ng5  . However, turns out that this gives me an advantage, whereas  17.Rh1  would have won on the spot.   16.g6  Qxg6  which I planned to meet with  17.Rg1  and see what happens.   16.g6  h6  which I planned to meet with  17.Bxh6   I didn't even see Black's strongest defense,  16.g6  Rf6  . }
16... hxg6 { The worst option. } 17. Ng5
{ Here I made the mental mistake of not stopping for a moment and considering the best move. I had planned to meet ...hxg6 with Ng5, and saw all sorts of mates. However, I didn't consider the best defense: ...Rf6. Perhaps if I would've seen it, I would have looked at the immediately winning Rh1 instead.   17.Rh1!  Rf6  18.Qh7+  Kf7  20.Ne5+  Kf8  21.Bh6  Qf7  22.Nxf7 }
17... Rf6
{ The best move, making room for the king. If  17...Rf7  19.Qh7+  Kf8  20.Nxe6# }
18. Be5 Kf8 19. Bxf6
{ Now I saw that  19.Bxf6  Bxf6  leads to mate or a winning advantage. But again I made the mistake of not considering the best defense,  19...exf6  . }
19... exf6
{ Here I thought for a second that I'm in trouble and have thrown away the winning advantage. But then I saw the winning move...   If  19...Bxf6?  20.Qh6+  Kg8  20.Qh7+  Kf8  21.Nxe6#   19...Bxf6?  20.Qh6  Bg7!  21.Nxe6+  Kf7  22.Ng5  Kf6  23.Qh4  . }
20. Qd6+ { Boom! } 20... Qe7 21. Nxe6+ { He must've missed this. } 21... Kf7
22. Qxe7+ Kxe7 23. Nxg7 Kf7 24. Nxf5 gxf5
{ White is up a piece and the game is effectively over. } 25. Rh1
{ Grabbing the important open file. } 25... Kg6 26. Ne2
{ The knight is going to the f4 outpost. My opponent had śeen enough. This was my first ever Classical OTB win. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Grünfeld"]
[Black "Kacper Piorun vs. Krzysztof Szczurek, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 { This was a Rapid Game. White was rated 2633, Black 2133. } 1... Nf6 2.
Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 O-O 6. h5 Nxh5 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. Qxh5 e6
{ Perhaps to protect the d-pawn, but it doesn't do anything about the coming threat to c7 and locks in the light-squared bishop. }
9. Bd3
{ Even stronger was  9.Qh2!  , attacking the pawn and x-raying the knight. }
9... f5 10. Nf3 Nc6 11. O-O-O Qe8 12. Qh2 Bd7 13. a3
{ Prophylaxis against ...Nb4. } 13... Qg6 14. g4
{ Boom. Ripping open the g-file. } 14... Qxg4 15. Be2
{ Piorun takes his time, but it was also possible to win the Queen immediately with  15.Rg1  Qxf3  16.Bh6  Rf7  17.Be2 }
15... Qg6 16. Rg1 Qf6 17. Bg5 { Even stronger was  17.Ne5  Nxe5  18.Bxe5 }
17... Qg6 18. Bh6 Rf6 19. Bxg7 Qxg1+ 20. Nxg1
{ The rest doesn't need a lot of comment. } 20... Kxg7 21. Qxc7 Rf7 22. Nh3 Rg8
23. Ng5 Re7 24. Qd6 Kh6 25. Nxd5 Reg7 26. Qh2+ Kxg5 27. Qh5# *

