[White "16. Grünfeld"]
[Black "Olga Girya vs. Anastasia Bodnaruk, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 { This was a Classical game. White was rated 2484, Black 2427. } 1... Nf6
2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 O-O 6. h5 Nxh5 7. Rxh5
{ Here we go again. } 7... gxh5 8. Qxh5 f5
{ Black chooses to protect the d-pawn and the b1-h7 diagonal by f5. } 9. Nf3
{ White has a wide choice here. Another well-known game went  9.Qh2!?  Hitting the c6-pawn and x-raying the knight  9...c6??  10.Bc7!  Qe8  11.Bxb8  and White went on to win effortlessly in Zhao Xue vs Yunshan Li, 2016. }
9... c6 { A necessary evil. If  9...Nd7?  10.Nxd5!  Nf6  11.Nxf6! } 10. Bd3
{ Natural and strong. } 10... Nd7 { Now the knight can come to help. } 11.
O-O-O { White plays the last natural move. } 11... Nf6 12. Qh4
{ Since the c-pawn has already moved 12. Qh2 doesn't make as much sense anymore and it's not good to allow ...Ng4 with a double attack on the Queen and the f-pawn. However 12. Qh3 is stronger than Qh4 and avoids any simplifying ideas with ...e5. }
12... Qe8
{ Trying to bring the Queen to the defense. However, after Qh4, Stockfish does much better with  12...e5!  13.dxe5  Ne4!  14.Qxd8  Rxd8  15.Bxe4  fxe4  16.Nxe4  and White is better, but Black has definitely more chances than after the game continuation. Of course, it's near impossible that a human will find this over the board. If they're strong enough they wouldn't have ventured into this line anyway. Still, Qh3 seems preferable. }
13. Rh1 h5
{ Best defense. The planned ...Qg6 is just met by Ne5 and Black has to give a piece to avoid mate   13...Qg6  14.Ne5!  Qh5  15.Qxh5  Nxh5  16.Rxh5  , after which White is completely winning. }
14. Ne5
{ The knight covers the important light squares. White can strengthen the attack next with Ne2 to Ng3. }
14... Ng4 15. Nxg4
{ White takes. However, perhaps strongest was bringing in the final piece with a line like:  15.Ne2  Nxe5  16.Bxe5  Bf6  17.Bxf6  Rxf6  18.Nf4  . }
15... fxg4 16. Qg5 Rf6
{ Much better was giving up some material with  16...Rxf4  17.exf4  , but White's still completely winning, of course. }
17. Be5 Qf7 18. Rxh5 Rxf2 { This is just desperation. } 19. Bg6 Rf1+ 20. Nd1
Rxd1+ 21. Kxd1 Qf1+ 22. Kd2 Qf2+ 23. Kc3 Qe1+ 24. Kb3
{ After this Stockfish gives a mate in 6. } 24... a5 25. Bh7+
{ Quicker was  25.Rh8+  Kxh8  26.Qh6+  Kg8  27.Qxg7#   Or  25.Rh8+!  Bxh8  26.Bh5+  Kf8  27.Qh6+  Bg7  28.Qxg7# }
25... Kf7
{ A few moves slower was  25...Kf8  26.Qxg7  Ke8  27.Bg6+  Kd7  28.Bf5+  Kd8  27.Qf8# }
26. Qg6+ { It's mate in after  26...Kf8  27.Bxg7# } *

