[White "16. Grünfeld"]
[Black "6...c5, 7...fxg6, 8...Qa5, 9...Qxc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 O-O 6. h5 c5
{ The better reaction and one of the main lines. Black meets a wing attack with an attack on the center. }
7. hxg6 fxg6
{ This used to be thought of as the better recapture, but current engines don't agree. }
8. dxc5 { Now that the light squares are weakened, the best move is to take. }
8... Qa5
{ A natural move, attacking the c-pawn. This is second most common. Notice that something like ...Nbd7 is not possible due to  8...Nbd7  9.Nxd5!   For  8...b6  see the model gameAronian vs Nepomniachtchi. }
9. Nf3 Qxc5 10. Qd4
{ Somewhat surprisingly, this immediate Queen exchange is the strongest move.   GingerGM has recommended  10.Bg5  putting pressure on the f6-knight and threatening Bxf6 and Qxd5+ and clearing the path for Qd4 to Qh4  10...e6  11.Qd4  Qxd4  12.exd4  Nc6  13.O-O-O  .   However, better than Bg5 is  10.Be5  with a similar idea, for example  10...Nbd7  11.Qd4  Qxd4  12.Bxd4  and White has a nice advantage. }
10... Qxd4 11. Nxd4 Nc6 12. f3 { Covering the central squares. } 12... Nxd4
{ If  12...Ne8  13.Bg5  Defending the bishop and counterattacking the e-pawn  13...Nxd4  14.exd4  Nc7  protecting the d-pawn  15.O-O-O }
13. exd4 Be6
{ One option for Black.   If  13...Bd7  still  14.Be5   If  13...Bf5  attacking the c2-pawn  14.Kd2  Nh5  15.Bh2  Bh6+  16.Ke2  Bxc7  17.g4  Nf4?!  18.Kd2  is an instructive sequence, trapping Black's bishop. }
14. Be5
{ A typical idea, challenging Black's bishop. White has also other good options here such as Bh2 or Ne2. }
14... Nh5 { If  14...Rac8  15.O-O-O  and White has a comfortable endgame. } 15.
Bxg7 Nxg7
{ If  15...Kxg7  16.Kf2!  Rad8  17.Re1  Rd6  18.Re5!  is the right idea. } 16.
Kf2
{ White has the clearly better endgame with Re1 to Re5 next and the more active king. }
*

