[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 O-O 6. h5 c5 7. hxg6 fxg6 8. dxc5
Nc6
{ This is an interesting move, disregarding the pawn for the time being. It's also the most common one. However, White retains an edge with simple play. }
9. Nf3 { Natural. A viable alternative is  9.Qd2 } 9... Bg4
{ One independent try, pinning the knight. If  9...Bf5  10.Qd2  is strong.   The also natural  9...Qa5  10.Nd2  transposes to the previous line. }
10. Qd2
{ Stepping out of the pin and getting ready to castle. We never mind ...Bxf3, giving us the bishop pair, an extra central pawn and an open g-file. }
10... Nh5
{ Black mostly plays  10...Bxf3  11.gxf3  , but after that White's just better with O-O-O next. With the text move Black abandons the d-pawn with a concrete idea. This has never been played and the practical likelihood of the following happening is close to zero. }
11. Bh2 { Preserving the bishop, but now our knight is attacked twice. } 11...
Rxf3
{ Yeah right will a human find this. Notice that if Black takes first with the bishop and then the rook, the d-pawn falls with check  11...Bxf3  12.gxf3  Rxf3  13.Qxd5+  and White's basically winning. }
12. gxf3 Bxf3 13. Rg1
{ This is as good a place to stop as any. There is no way a practical game will reach even here and even though the engines might find a forced draw after moves like ...Qf8, ...d4, ...Qf7 etc. this is not going to happen in a non-correspondence game. }
*

[Event "?"]
