[Black "6...c5, 7...hxg6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 O-O 6. h5 c5 7. hxg6 hxg6
{ This used to be considered the weaker recapture, but the current engines think it's the better one. }
8. Qd2
{ White has a host of options here, but I like the thematic Qd2 with the simple plan of O-O-O, f3, g4, Qh2, Bh6, Bxg7, Qh6+, Qh8#.   Notice that the direct Qf3?! doesn't work due to  8.Qf3?!  Bg4  9.Qg3  Qb6  hitting both b2 and d4.   Some people have recommended Nf3 but  8.Nf3  Qb6!  is given by Stockfish as equal at high depth.   The two good alternatives are  8.Nge2  with Qd2 next   and Ni Hua's  8.dxc5  . }
8... Nc6 { A logical move. } 9. O-O-O
{ The direct option. An unexplored alternative is  9.Nge2  Ne4  10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.d5  . }
9... Bf5
{ The most natural developing move with the threat of ...Nb4, but it's only been played in 2  (!)  games, which shows how low the likelihood is of getting already here.   Also natural is  9...Qa5  10.a3  stopping ...Nb4, and White can continue with Nf3, Be2 etc.   Notice that  9...cxd4?  10.exd4  gives us exactly what we want.   For  9...c4?  preparing for a Queenside attack, see the model gameKülaots vs Wan. }
10. f3
{ If you gave the previous position to Stockfish 11 then at a high enough depth it insisted on exchanging Black's bishop with  10.Bd3  Bxd3  11.Qxd3  Qa5  12.a3  where White retains a slight pull, but is without a clear attacking plan.   10.f3  is the human move, planning something like g4 to kick the bishop and control h5, followed by Bh6, Qh2 etc. It is now also approved by Stockfish 12! }
10... Nb4
{ Critical. Anything else and White goes g4. However, this position has never been reached in a Lichess game. }
11. Bd3
{ Exchanging the bishop now, with the point that since Black's knight has left c6, we can recapture with the pawn, instead of the Queen, shoring up our center. }
11... Bxd3 { If  11...Nxd3  12.cxd3  and g4 is coming soon, with tempo. } 12.
cxd3 Nh5
{ A ridiculous computer move. We are continuing the line just to see where it leads. }
13. Bh2 cxd4 14. exd4 Qa5
{ Another computer move. If Black takes the pawn with ...Bxd4 White can play  14...Bxd4  16.Nge2  Bg7  17.d4  Qb6  18.g4  and White can continue with his kingside attack after something like Kb1, Bf4, Bh6, and Qh2. }
15. Kb1 { King safety. } 15... e5
{ A final computer move. If  15...Rac8  16.g4!  sets things in motion for White. }
16. Bxe5 Bxe5 17. dxe5
{ A good place to stop. There is no point in continuing to learn the following computer line, but it does demonstrate that White actually has the easier position to play  17.dxe5  d4  18.Nge2  dxc3  is not the best for Black  19.Nxc3  Rfd8  20.d4  Rac8  21.a3!  The key move  Nd5  22.Nxd5  Rxd5  23.g4  Qxd2  24.Rxd2  Ng3  25.Rg1  Rc4  26.Rxg3  Rcxd4  27.Rxd4  Rxd4  28.Kc2  when the position has stabilized and White is just a pawn up. }
*

