[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 h5
{ Overwhelmingly most common and might also be the best move } 6. Nf3
{ The most natural and common move } 6... O-O
{ Having prevented h5, Black castles. This is the most common move with ~1500 games.   6...Bg4  The second most common move, with ~900 games  7.Qd2!?  David Navara's idea, threatening Ne5 and inviting the capture  7...Bxf3  8.gxf3  White controls the e4 and g4 squares and can aim for the e4 and f4 to f5 breaks.  8...O-O   8...c6  The most common move  9.e4!  The most precise move, for the rest, see the trainable lines.  9.O-O-O  Nc6  Stockfish likes this completely defensive plan with ...Nc6 and ...e6. This has been played only once  10.e4  e6  11.Bg5  Ne7  12.Qf4  Ne8  13.Rg1  White has a strong attack }
7. Be2 { Simple and logical, developing. } 7... c5 8. dxc5 Qa5
{ 8...Nbd7  9.Nxd5  Nxd5  10.Qxd5  Bxb2  11.O-O  White simply sacs the exchange for a strong bishop.  11...Bxa1  12.Rxa1  Qa5  13.Bh6  Qxc5  14.Qb3 }
9. O-O Qxc5 10. Nb5
{ White tries to misplace Black's knight in order to play Be5 } 10... Na6 11.
a4
{ An interesting, but natural move in such structures where White has played Nb5 and Black has blocked his a-pawn with ...Na6 and doesn't have ...c6 anymore. In this position the concrete point is that the knight is now protected by a pawn so ...Bg4 and ...Bxf3 can be met with Bxf3. White plans c3 and b4 next. However, White could equally well start with c3 and then play b4 and a4.   11.Be5  An alternative. }
11... Bg4 12. c3 { White intends b4. } 12... Rfd8 13. b4 Qb6 14. Rc1
{ White has a nice Queenside space advantage and Black's knight is still sidelined. For more, see the trainable line. }
*

[Event "?"]
