[White "16. Grünfeld"]
[Black "5. ...h5, 6... Bg4, 8...c6, 9...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 h5 6. Nf3
{ The most natural move. } 6... Bg4
{ Black takes the chance and pins the knight. If  5...c5?!  7.Nb5  is similar to our 5...c5-lines. }
7. Qd2 { Navara's idea, threatening Ne5 and allowing the capture. } 7... Bxf3
{ If Black doesn't take the knight White will just jump with Ne5 with f3 and g4 to follow. For example:   7...O-O  8.Ne5   7...Nbd7  8.Ne5 }
8. gxf3
{ White gets an extra central pawn which controls the  e4  and  g4  squares and can aim for the e4 and f4 to f5 breaks, not to mention the two bishops and the open g-file. }
8... c6 9. e4
{ Starting with the direct e4 is more precise than O-O-O, though most lines transpose. The difference is that after  9.O-O-O  b5  is stronger than here. }
9... e6
{ One option. If  9...b5  10.e5!  Nfd7  11.e6!!  A typical sacrifice  11...fxe6  12.Bh3!   If  9...O-O  10.O-O-O  e6  11.Bg5  and Black is already in trouble. }
10. O-O-O Nbd7 11. Kb1
{ King safety first. Also, it's a nice waiting move. White wants to play Bg5, but he would prefer to do it after Black plays ...Nb6. The immediate Bg5 could be met by ...Qc7. }
11... Nb6 12. Bg5
{ White threatens e4 to e5 and can regroup with Bd3, Ne2 to Nf4 and Rg1, eventually trying to break through on the g-file. }
