[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 h5 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Be2
{ Simple and logical. In a Classical OTB game against a very strong opponent, I figured I'd try the principled-looking Ne5, which was promptly met with ...c5. }
7... c5 8. dxc5 { White should grab the pawn here. } 8... Qa5
{ The most common move. If  8...Nc6  9.O-O  and White has a nice edge and a target in the form of the d-pawn. We'll look at ...Nbd7 separately. }
9. O-O { White should simply castle here and go for Nb5. } 9... Qxc5 10. Nb5
{ White tries to misplace Black's knight in order to either expand on the Queenside or play Be5. }
10... Na6 11. a4
{ An interesting, but natural move in such structures where White has played Nb5 and Black has blocked his a-pawn with ...Na6 and doesn't have ...c6 anymore. In this position the concrete point is that the knight is now protected by a pawn so ...Bg4 and ...Bxf3 can be met with Bxf3. White plans c3 and b4 next. However, White could equally well start with c3 and then play b4 and a4. }
11... Bg4
{ The most natural move. If  11...Ng4  12.c4!  dxc4  13.Rc1  Bxb2  14.Rxc4  with an advantage.   If  11...Ne4  12.Ne5 }
12. c3 { Step 2, White intends b4. } 12... Rfd8
{ If  12...Bxf3  13.Bxf3  and White is better. } 13. b4 Qb6 14. Rc1
{ White has a nice Queenside space advantage and Black's knight is still sidelined. It's not easy to play this position with Black. For example, the natural  14...Rac8  loses to  15.a5  Qc6  17.Nxa7 }
14... Ne4 15. Re1
{ Stepping out of any potential ...Nd2 forks and thereby allowing for Qb3. Another idea is Ne5. White is better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Grünfeld"]
[Black "5...h5 6...O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 h5 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Be2
{ Simple and logical. In a Classical OTB game against a very strong opponent, I figured I'd try the principled-looking Ne5, which was promptly met with ...c5. }
7... c5 8. dxc5 { White should grab the pawn here. } 8... Qa5
{ The most common move. If  8...Nc6  9.O-O  and White has a nice edge and a target in the form of the d-pawn. We'll look at ...Nbd7 separately. }
9. O-O { White should simply castle here and go for Nb5. } 9... Qxc5 10. Nb5
{ White tries to misplace Black's knight in order to either expand on the Queenside or play Be5. }
10... Na6
{ If  10...Ng4?  11.b4!  Qc6  12.Nc7  e5  13.Nxd5!  threatening the fork on e7, and White wins. }
11. Be5
{ This is one option, challenging the long diagonal and intending Bd4 with tempo, with the possibility of taking the a-pawn afterwards. This position has never been reached in Lichess and only once in a master game. }
11... Ng4
{ White's idea can be seen after  11...Bg4?!  12.Bd4  .   If  11...Bf5?!  12.Rc1   If  11...Ne4  12.Bxg7   If  11...Ne4  12.Bd4  . }
12. Bxg7
{ A simple and easy-to-remember option. In the only master game Gabor Papp played the also good  12.Bd4  Bxd4  13.exd4  Qb6  14.a4  Bf5  15.Ne5  Nxe5  16.dxe5  Qe6  and now  17.Nxg4  would've given White an edge, but Black should've preferred 16...Nxe5 with an equal position. The game Papp vs Paravanyan, 2018 eventually ended a draw. }
12... Kxg7 13. Rc1 Nf6
{ Black's best, but not an easy move to make. If the natural and developing  13...Bf5  14.a3!  with the idea of b4 and then c4. }
14. c4 dxc4 15. Bxc4 Bg4 { If  15...Bf5  16.Ng5 } 16. Qb3 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Qb6 18.
Nd4 { Offering a Queen Exchange. } 18... Nc5
{ Or  18...Qxb3  19.Nxb3!  to cover the c5-square  19...Nb4  20.a3  Nc6  21.Bb5  with an advantage. }
19. Qxb6 axb6 20. a3
{ White has a comfortable endgame, possessing the bishop, having the b5-square and the rook already on an open file. Despite the kingside pawn structure being broken down, the pawns are quite strong and Black has no way whatsoever of getting to White's h-pawn. }
