[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Grünfeld"]
[Black "5...c6, h6, a6: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7
{ 4...c6  5.Be2  Probably transposes after ...Bg7 and h4 } 5. h4 c6
{ Let's look at three one-step pawn moves now. This is 3/4 most common with about ~1150 games. It's very solid and flexible. Black protects the d-pawn, stops Nb5 and keeps open the options of ...h5 and ...Qb6.   5...a6  The rarest of the one-pawn moves. Black prevents Nb5 and could be preparing ...c5. Here White could try to punish Black with h5, intending the rook sacrifice, but it is also good to play calmly with  6.Be2  As always, we fortify the threat of h5   6.h5  Nxh5  7.Rxh5  gxh5  8.Qxh5  We take this as an alternative. See the trainable line and the model games in this chapter.  6...h5  7.Nf3  O-O  8.Ne5  c5  9.dxc5  Qa5  10.O-O  Qxc5  11.Na4  Qa5  12.c4   5...h6  This is about as popular as ...c6. Black intends meeting h5 with ...g5  6.Nf3  O-O  7.h5!!  Welcome to sactown. For more, see the trainable line. }
6. Be2
{ In these lines it's best to threaten h5, and when Black stops it we will continue with Nf3 to Ne5 }
6... h5
{ Most common   6...Qb6  Georgiev's suggestion. It's only the 5th most popular, but Black scores well. However, White usually hasn't played the best move...  7.Na4!  Qa5+  8.c3  Nbd7  9.b4  Qd8  10.h5 }
7. Nf3 O-O 8. Qd2
{ Most precise, and principled, not moving the same piece twice with Ne5, even though that's also a good move and a key idea in this line. For the rest, see the trainable line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Grünfeld"]
[Black "5...c6, 6...h5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 c6
{ A very solid and flexible move. Black protects the d-pawn, stops Nb5 and keeps open the options of ...h5 and ...Qb6. As we will see, in contrast to ...a6, this can NOT be profitably met with h5. However, with less pressure on the center, White can plan a quick Nf3 to Ne5, f3 and e4 or g4. }
6. Be2
{ Preparing h5. The immediate 6. h5!? is best left for Blitz games. After  6.h5  Nxh5  7.Rxh5  gxh5  8.Qxh5  , Black's d- and c-pawns are already secure and he can mobilize himself fast. }
6... h5 { Most common and best, stopping h5. } 7. Nf3 O-O
{ Black has secured the center, stopped h5 and can now castle. However, he has other options like  7...Bg4  8.Ne5  Bxe2  9.Qxe2  Nbd7  10.O-O-O  Nxe5  11.Bxe5  and White will attack with f3 and e4 or g4. See the sample game Esipenko - Gutenev, 2018.   Also good is  7...Bg4  8.Ng5  with a similar idea, but without an exchange of pieces.   If  7...Bf5  8.Ne5  and White can again plan f3 and g4.   If  7...Nbd7  8.Qd2 }
8. Qd2
{ Most precise, and principled, not moving the same piece twice with Ne5, even though that's also a good move and a key idea in this line. }
8... Nbd7 9. Ne5 { The knight jumps to its natural home. } 9... Nxe5
{ If  9...Ne4  10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.O-O-O  Nxe5  11.dxe5  Qxd2+  12.Rxd2  and White has an advantage in this endgame. }
10. Bxe5 b5 11. f3 a5 12. O-O-O a4
{ If  12...b4?  13.Na4  and the Queenside is closed. } 13. a3 Qa5
{ This is Black's best move, insisting on ...b4. For 13... Qb6, with the same idea, see the model game Papadopoulos vs. Theodorou, 2018. }
14. Na2 Qxd2+ 15. Rxd2
{ White has a slight pull in this endgame with all three results possible. } *

