1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 a6 6. h5
{ This direct move has been tried by many GMs, especially in faster time controls. The point is that after ...a6 White can still try to attack the c-pawn and knight with Qh4 to Qh2 which is not possible after ...c6. And if Black prevents this there's the thematic Nf3 to Ng5, attacking  f7  . }
6... Nxh5 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. Qxh5 c6
{ The most common move and Savchenko's choice.   8...e6?  Only slightly less common than ...c6  9.Qh2!  Attacking c7 and the b8-knight. See Bortnyk vs Mikhalevski, 2018   8...Be6  9.Nf3  h6  10.O-O-O  See the game Bauer vs. Apicella, 2018 }
9. Nf3
{ Threatening Ng5   9.O-O-O  Keeping the knight flexible is also interesting. }
9... h6 10. O-O-O Be6
{ 10...Nd7  Savchenko's choice, but then Jobava had the strong  11.Qh2  See the game }
11. Be5 { Here this is White's best, but it's never been tried } 11... Bxe5 12.
dxe5 Nd7 13. Nd4 Nf8 14. f4
{ With an interesting, if equal position. White plans f5 next and can even consider e6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
