[White "16. Grünfeld"]
[Black "Baadur Jobava vs. Boris Savchenko, 2014"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a Classical game. The Georgian Super-GM playing White who has inspired many of these lines was rated 2706, while Black was rated 2556. }
1... Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. Nc3 a6 4. e3 g6 5. h4
{ We arrive at the ...a6-line from a slightly non-standard move order. } 5...
Bg7 6. h5 { Jobava shows us the way. } 6... Nxh5 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. Qxh5 c6
{ Unlike many others, Savchenko sees the coming threat to  c7  and pre-empts it by playing c6. }
9. Nf3 h6 { Stopping Ng5. } 10. O-O-O Nd7 11. Qh2
{ Threatening to trap the queen with Bc7. } 11... Nf8
{ Intending ...Ne6 next. If  11...Nf6  12.Bc7  Qd7  13.Na4  going into b6 or c5 is crushing. }
12. Bc7
{ Misplacing the Queen. On  d7  it blocks the bishop and now it can never come out on its natural,  d8  to  a5  diagonal. }
12... Qd7 13. Be2 Ne6
{ Continuing with the plan, but after this White has the edge, which shows how difficult these positions practically are, for Black. Stockfish's suggestion is  13...b5  . }
14. Be5 b5 15. Rh1 f6 16. Bg3 Ng5 17. Ne1
{ Avoiding the exchange and sending the knight to c5. If  17.Qh5+  Nf7  18.Nh4  O-O  and Black can try to defend with  ...Nh8  . }
17... O-O
{ Black castles into it, thinking that the king will be safe on the kingside despite White's concentration of forces there. }
18. Nd3 Qf5 19. Bf4 a5 20. Nc5 Qh7 21. g4
{ Stopping ...Bf5 and threatening Bd3. } 21... Qg6 22. Bc7
{ The final fireworks are about to start. White prepares for f4. } 22... b4 23.
N3a4 e5 24. Nb6 Ra7 25. Bd6 Re8 26. f4 { Here it comes. } 26... Nf7 27. g5
{ White sacrifices a piece  (temporarily at least...)  , to blow open the kingside lines. }
27... Nxd6
{ Black grabs the piece, but this loses. It was necessary to play  27...fxg5  28.Bb8  Rae7  29.Bh5  Qf5  30.fxe5  with the game still on. }
28. Bh5 Qf5 29. gxh6 Ree7 30. hxg7 Rxg7 31. fxe5 fxe5 32. Nxc8 Nxc8 33. Bg6
{ The final nail in the coffin. } 33... Qxg6
{ If  33...Rxg6  34.Qh8+  Kf7  35.Rh7+  with mate to follow. } 34. Qh8+ Kf7 35.
Rf1+
{ Lights out. If  35...Ke7?  36.Qf8#   35...Qf6  36.Rxf6  Kxf6  37.Qxc8   Palliser also gives  35...Qf6  36  Rxf6  Kxf6  37.Qh6+  Rg6  39.dxe5+  Kf7  40.e6+  Kf6  41.Qf8+  however in this line 37... Kf5 is slightly better. }
