[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Benoni"]
[Black "Benoni: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5
{ The Benoni-style move is considered by many theoreticians the critical test of White's move order with 2. Bf4. However, things are actually not so simple, which is also shown by the fact that it's only the 5th most popular move with ~123 300 games and 4th most popular on master level. }
3. e3
{ At this juncture, White has three moves: - The Classical with 3. e3 - The Push 3. d5 - The Capture 3. dxc5. In my opinion, they're all interesting, but the Classical is completely underestimated by most theory and will therefore be our choice. e3 has also been the choice of Kamsky, Aronian, who scored 4-0 with it in a Blitz match with Giri, Grischuk, and others. Within this complex, White has actually a choice of tricky options to make Black's life very difficult. }
3... Qb6
{ 3...Nd5  This unprincipled knight jump is recommended by FM Kamil Plichta in his King's Indian course here on Chessable and by Andrew Martin in a YT video. It's been played ~1200 times and Black scores well. Our novelty should make this line practically unplayable for Black!  4.Bg3  Qb6  5.c4!!  Boom!  5...Qxb2  6.cxd5  Qxa1  7.Qc2  for the rest, see the trainable lines   3...cxd4  4.exd4  Qb6  5.Na3  Qxb2  6.Nb5  Nd5  7.Rb1  Qxa2  8.Ra1  Qb2  9.Bd2  a6  10.c4  Nb4  11.Bc3  Nc2+  12.Kd2  Nxa1+  13.Bxb2  axb5  14.Bxa1±   3...g6  This transpositional device could be used by a clever KID player to get their preferred sort of game while avoiding the Jobava lines. It basically forces White to choose between playing a weird Sicilian after dxc5 or Nc3, a Benoni with d5 when White would've preferred to go e4 in one move, or the Classical setup with c3. The last option is objectively best and getting move ordered into it isn't actually all too bad since Black is already committed to one particular setup, namely with ...c5.  4.Nf3  This is the most flexible move, even though White can also start with Nbd2 or h3. From here on, White should always watch out for ...Nh5. The general guideline is that it isn't something to be worried about, as long as you can meet it with Be5 and Bxb8.  4...Bg7  5.c3  O-O  6.Nbd2  d6  7.h3  b6  8.Bc4  Capablanca's move. For more, see the trainable line. }
4. Nc3
{ The most common move, intending to meet ...Qxb2 with Nb5 and the main line. In this chapter I won't give a clearly preferred move, leaving it up to you. This line with the continuation 5. Nb5, forces Black to play accurately and White has a draw in the pocket for a long while. This line with 5. Nge2 is another interesting way of playing, perhaps best used as a surprise weapon. The alternative 4. Nf3 is perhaps the objectively the best move and best way to play for a win, but it does involve a gambit.   4.Nf3!?  Our second, gambit option.  4...Qxb2  5.Nbd2  Nc6  Second most common, and not bad.   5...cxd4  Weirdly enough, overwhelmingly most common.  6.exd4  Nc6??  A very natural blunder.  7.Nc4!  Qb4+  8.c3  Qxc3+  9.Bd2+-   5...Nd5  6.Rb1  Qc3  7.Rb3  Qa5  8.Bg3  e6  9.Bd3  Nb4  10.Be2+=   5...Qc3  This is rare but might be best.  6.Rb1  Nc6  7.Rb3  Qa5  8.dxc5  Taking the pressure of d4.  8...Qxc5  9.Rb5  Qa3  10.Bd3∞  Objectively Black might have a slight 'engine advantage', but practically White has a lot of compensation and most Black moves can be met with Nc4 or O-O.  6.dxc5  e6  7.Rb1  Qc3  8.Bd3  Qxc5  9.O-O  Be7  10.Rb5  Qa3  11.Nc4  Qa4  12.Nd6+  Bxd6  13.Bxd6+-  White is winning. }
4... Qxb2
{ Continuing with the main idea, but the problem with this move is that Black can only play this if he's happy with allowing White to play with a draw in hand. Whether to draw or not is entirely up to White who also has two different ways to try to play for a win. On the other hand, it's not clear what Black achieved if he doesn't take...   4...d6  5.Bb5+  Bd7  6.a4  a6  7.a5  Qd8  8.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  9.d5  g6  10.e4  Bg7  11.Nf3  O-O  12.O-O  White has an excellent Benoni.   4...e6  5.Rb1  Be7  6.Nf3  O-O  7.Be2  Nc6  8.O-O }
5. Nb5
{ 5.Nge2!?  An interesting sideline. Played 53 times and 2 times at Master level, once by Grischuk against Adhiban and once by Aronian against Giri in Blitz. White won both games.  5...Qa3  Perhaps best, but neither Adhiban or Giri played this.  6.g4!?  d6  7.Bg2  Nxg4  8.O-O  Nf6  9.Rb1  Nbd7  10.Qd3  White completes development. Black is slightly better, being up two pawns, but his position is quite hard to play. White's threatening to take on b7 and infiltrate there. Rb3 is another move that is in the books. This requires more practical testing and will anyway make a good surprise weapon. }
5... Nd5
{ The only defence.   5...Na6?  6.a3  The standard response to ...Na6. The key thing to remember here is that White doesn't need to trap Black's Queen to get an advantage. Sometimes he can also play against b7 and the knight on a6.  6...Nd5  7.Rb1  Qa2  8.Rb3  d6  9.Ne2  Bf5  10.Nec3  Nxc3  11.Nxc3  Qxc2  12.Qxc2  Bxc2  13.Rxb7  Nb8  14.dxc5± }
6. a3
{ This Prie's idea, to give Black another chance to make a mistake, and then choose whether to take the draw on the 8th move or play this position for a win, intending to trap the Queen after Rb1, Ra1, and Qc1.   6.Rb1  White can make a draw already here, but this is not perhaps practically correct, unless one really just needs the draw. It's better to give Black one more chance to make a mistake.  6...Qxa2  7.Ra1  Qb2  8.Rb1= }
6... a6
{ The best move.   6...Nxf4?  7.exf4  Na6  8.Bc4  d5  9.Ra2   6...Nc3  Black tries to get creative and go on the counterattack. This does perhaps equalize, but only after very precise play.  7.Nc7+  Kd8  8.Qc1  Qxc1+  9.Rxc1  e5  10.Bxe5  d6  11.Nxa8  dxe5  12.dxe5  c4  13.Bxc4  For the rest, see the trainable line to follow. }
7. Rb1 Qa2 8. Qc1
{ This the moment White has a choice. He gave his opponent another chance to make a mistake and now has to decide whether to take the draw or play on with Qc1. The idea of this move is to control b2 and play for the win.   8.Ra1  Qb2  9.Rb1= }
8... axb5 9. Ra1 Qxa1 10. Qxa1
{ The dust has settled and White got a Queen for a piece, rook, and a pawn. This position has been reached in 109 games with both sides scoring about evenly. However, at master level it's been reached in 12 games and there Black scores slightly better. }
10... e5
{ Kamsky gives this as best for Black and it's hard to argue with him.   10...Nc6  This is what Prie and Romero&Prado used to consider critical.  11.Bxb5  cxd4  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.Qxd4  Rxa3  14.Nf3  e6  15.O-O  White gets the king to safety and should be slightly better, but it's not a position that is easy to play by any means. White threatens c4 which is probably met by ...Nxf4, exf4. After that White should probably play c5, Rc1, and try to get the knight into d6 with Nd2 to Ne4 to Nd6. }
11. dxe5 c4 12. Qd4 Nxf4 13. Qxf4 Bxa3 14. Ke2 { Stepping away from ...Bb4+. }
14... Bb4 15. Nf3 O-O 16. h4 Ra2 17. Nd4
{ The position is objectively equal, untested, and a complete mess. The practical likelihood of getting here is close to zero though, so I don't think this should necessarily put you off from playing this line, though, for several reasons 4. Nf3 seems like the objectively better move, overall. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Benoni"]
[Black "Plichta's 3...Nd5?!, 11...Rxb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nd5
{ This unprincipled knight jump is recommended by FM Kamil Plichta in his King's Indian course here on Chessable and by Andrew Martin in a YT video. It's been played ~1200 times and Black scores well. Our novelty should make this line practically unplayable for Black! }
4. Bg3 Qb6
{ This is the idea  4...cxd4  5.exd4  This is similar to main line if Black plays ...Qb6 next. }
5. c4
{ And this is the refutation. We just sacrifice the exchange for a development lead and a trapped Black Queen. }
5... Qxb2 6. cxd5 Qxa1 7. Qc2
{ This is the move, not Qb3, which can be met with a quick ...a5-a4. Engines already give this as much better for White who intends Nf3, Be2, O-O, and Nc3, trapping Black's Queen. }
7... Na6
{ The most common move. If Black would play the move order  7...d6  8.Nf3  Na6  now White should play  8.Bb5+  Bd7  9.Bxd7  Kxd7  10.O-O  and both Black's King and Queen are in big trouble. }
8. Bxa6 { Developing with a capture. } 8... bxa6 9. Nf3
{ White's idea is Nd2 to Nb3!, preventing Black from using the b-file and attacking the Queen. }
9... d6
{ Black has to close the diagonal first, before being able to play ...Rb8. }
10. Nd2 { This is the move that White players have usually missed. } 10... Rb8
11. Nb3 Rxb3 { The most logical and direct move. } 12. Qxb3 c4
{ The only move. If  12...cxd4  13.Qb8  and Black is in trouble. } 13. Qa4+ Bd7
14. Qc2 c3 { Again, the only move. } 15. O-O Qb2 16. Qxc3 Qxc3 17. Nxc3
{ Black was able to save his Queen by sacrificing a pawn. But despite material equality White is still a lot better due to his center and lead in development. It's very hard for Black to even start developing while White can continue with Rb8 and/or play for e4 to e5. }
