1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nd5 4. Bg3 Qb6 5. c4 Qxb2 6. cxd5 Qxa1 7. Qc2 Na6 8.
Bxa6 bxa6 9. Nf3 d6 10. Nd2 Rb8 11. Nb3 Bf5
{ This is a tricky move Black could try, in order to save the Queen. However, it doesn't work. }
12. Qxf5 { White can just take the bishop. } 12... Qxa2 13. N1d2 c4
{ The only move. Notice that  13...Rxb3??  14.Qc8# } 14. Nc5
{ Threatening mate in 1. } 14... Rd8 15. Ne6 { Threatening Nc7#. } 15... fxe6
{ If  15...Rd7  16.Ke2!  c3  17.Rb1!! } 16. dxe6
{ Threatening mate in 1 again. } 16... Rb8 { Making space for the king. } 17.
O-O { White just calmly castles, hanging the knight. Also good is  17.Qf3  . }
17... Kd8 18. Qd5 { White is down a whole rook, but completely winning. } 18...
Qa4 19. h3
{ Another calm move, taking away all back-rank threats and aiming to involve the minor pieces. }
19... Rc8
{ Black supports the passer. If  19...Qb5  20.Qe4  c3  21.Rb1!  cxd2  22.Rxb5  Rxb5  23.Qc6!  is an instructive line. Black has no way of exploiting the back rank and passed pawn.   If the direct  19...c3  20.Ne4  Rc8  21.Bh4  and White will take on  d6  with the knight sooner or later. }
20. Bh4 { Pinning the pawn. } 20... Qc6 21. Qa5+ Qb6 22. Qa2 c3 23. Ne4
{ A good place to stop. This will never occur in a non-correspondence game, but was instructive nevertheless. }
