1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4
{ The Caro-Kann capture is the second most common move here. } 4. exd4 Qb6
{ Everything else will sooner or later transpose to our Caro-Kann lines with the extra option of playing an early Bd3 for White. }
5. Na3 {  } 5... Qxb2
{ Black really shouldn't take the pawn, but there aren't that many good ideas here. If the computer suggestion  5...Nd5  6.Bc1  +/- with  Nc4  next   If  5...d6  6.Nc4 }
6. Nb5 Nd5
{ The typical defense. ...Na6 can be met with the thematic a3  6...Na6  7.a3  Nd5  8.Rb1  Qa2  9.Rb3  Nxf4  10.Nc3!  Qxb3  11.cxb3   If  6...Na6  7.a3  d6  8.Bc4  Be6  9.Rb1  Qxb1  10.Qxb1  Bxc4  11.Nxd6  exd6  12.Qxb7   If  6...Qb4+?  7.c3  . }
7. Rb1 { First, we lose the a-pawn to be able to control the whole a-file. }
7... Qxa2 8. Ra1 Qb2 9. Bd2
{ ~100 players have taken the draw here, not realizing that Bd2 just wins. White is threatening c4, followed by Bc3. Nc7+ always hangs in the air as well. }
9... a6 10. c4 {  } 10... Nb4 { If  10...axb5  10.Rxa8  is lights out. } 11.
Bc3 Nc2+ 12. Kd2 Nxa1+
{ If  12...Qb3  13.Qxc2  Qxc2  14.Kxc2  is even worse for Black since Nc7+ comes soon. }
13. Bxb2 axb5 14. Bxa1 *

