1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 4. Nc3 {  } 4... Qxb2 { The most common move. }
5. Nb5 { The typical response, played ~3200 times. } 5... Na6
{ This is most common, but this move never ever works! } 6. a3
{ The standard response to ...Na6. The key thing to remember here is that White doesn't need to trap Black's Queen to get an advantage. Sometimes he can also play against b7 and the knight on a6. }
6... Nd5
{ If  6...d6  7.Bc4  Be6  8.Rb1  Qxb1  9.Qxb1  Bxc4  10.dxc5  and White is winning. }
7. Rb1 Qa2 8. Rb3 { This is most straightforward, boxing in the Queen. } 8...
d6
{ The best try, closing the diagonal. If  8...cxd4  9.exd4  Nxf4  10.Nc3  Qxb3  11.cxb3  and White is winning. }
9. Ne2 { Nc3 is coming and Black can't stop it. } 9... Bf5 {  } 10. Nbc3
{ It's important to use this knight to unclog the b-file. } 10... Nxc3
{ Not the best, but humanly quite likely, making sure that taking on  c2  can't be met with ...Nxd5.   If  10...Bxc2?  11.Nxa2   If  10...Qxc2  11.Nxd5 }
11. Nxc3 Qxc2 12. Qxc2 Bxc2 13. Rxb7 Nb8 { The only way to save the piece. }
14. dxc5
{ An alternative is to try to get Black's light-squared bishop into trouble by starting with  14.g4  . }
