1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 4. Nc3 Qxb2 5. Nb5 Nd5
{ The best move, played ~1700 times. } 6. a3
{ This move enables us to play for a win, as 6.Rb1 leads to a draw. We simply take away the a3 square from the queen. }
6... Nxf4
{ This doesn't make a lot of sense and doesn't work, but it's best to have trained the refutation. }
7. exf4 Na6
{ The most natural move. If Black is bold enough to allow for Nc7+ he could also try   7...Nc6!?  8.Nf3!  White should improve first and only then go for the fork  8...cxd4  9.Rb1  Qa2  10.Nc7+  . }
8. Bc4 { White covers a2 first and now plans Rb1 or Ra2. } 8... d5
{ Aiming to get some material for the Queen. If   8...Nb4  9.axb4  Qxb4+  10.c3  Qxc4  11.Nc7+  Kd8  12.Nxa8  Qxc3+  13.Kf1  and White wins. }
9. Ra2
{ The important move, making sure that Black only gets a rook, not a rook and a bishop. }
