[Black "5...Nd5, 6...Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 4. Nc3 Qxb2 5. Nb5 Nd5
{ The best move, played ~1700 times. } 6. a3 Nc3
{ Black tries to get creative and go on the counterattack. This does perhaps equalize, but only after very precise play. }
7. Nc7+
{ Put your seatbelts on, as we are about to witness a very long forced sequence. }
7... Kd8 8. Qc1
{ This move is forced, as Black was threatening to take our Queen, and possibly our rook on a1, if we moved our Queen to any other square. }
8... Qxc1+ 9. Rxc1
{ Here, we have come to the first level for Black. Only one idea survives, and it is not super intuitive. }
9... e5
{ Exclam! Black sacrifices a pawn with the idea of ...d6 to try and disrupt the connection between the knight and bishop. }
10. Bxe5 d6 11. Nxa8 dxe5 12. dxe5
{ A good place to stop training. The rest is for illustration. } 12... c4
{ Another key move, opening the diagonal for the bishop. } 13. Bxc4 Bxa3
{ The point! Now, another long forced sequence will follow, but this time, White's rook will be the one running from danger. }
14. Ra1 Bb2 15. Rxa7 Nc6 16. Ra2 Nxa2 17. Bxa2 {  } 17... Bc3+
{ Another key idea, putting the bishop on a5 to stop the knight from escaping via b6. }
18. Ke2 Ba5 19. Nf3 Ke7 20. Rb1
{ Trying to save the knight. The engines keep giving White a small advantage, but practically it's quite difficult for both sides. }
20... b5
{ Tactics! The pawn on b5 is not en prise due to ...Ba6. But is the knight trapped for good? }
21. Bd5 { Taking advantage of a new diagonal that just opened. } 21... Bd7 22.
Nd4 Nxd4+ 23. exd4 Rc8 24. Be4
{ White has a slight pull. The practical likelihood of getting here in a non-correspondence game is not close to zero, it is ZERO. Black can only play this precisely if they've prepared it and it's hard to see someone voluntarily preparing this line just to end up here. }
