[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Benoni"]
[Black "6...a6, 10...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 4. Nc3 Qxb2 5. Nb5 Nd5 6. a3 a6
{ The most common and best move. } 7. Rb1
{ Driving the Queen to a2, to make possible Qc1. } 7... Qa2 8. Qc1
{ Controlling b2 and playing for the win. If White wants to make a draw immediately he should do it here with  8.Ra1  Qb2  9.Rb1 }
8... axb5 9. Ra1 Qxa1 10. Qxa1
{ The dust has settled and White got a Queen for a piece, rook, and a pawn. This position has been reached in 109 games with both sides scoring about evenly. However, at master level it's been reached in 12 games and there Black scores slightly better. }
10... Nc6
{ Developing and taking away the option of Bxb8, lessening the pressure on White's Queen by minors and misplacing Black's rook is what Prie and Romero&Prado considered best.   If  10...b4?  11.Bxb8!   10...c4  11.Bxb8!   10...Nxf4  11.exf4   However, Kamsky gives  10...e5!  which we'll look at next. }
11. Bxb5 {  } 11... cxd4
{ If  11...Nxf4  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.exf4  and White's better. } 12. Bxc6
{ In this position, White wants to exchange minor pieces. The more minors he gets off, the more space the Queen has to attack the remaining pieces and pawns. }
12... bxc6 13. Qxd4
{ This position has been reached in only 9 games and 3 master games  (which all ended as draws...) }
13... Rxa3
{ One of Black's two moves and the more common choice. For the other option   13...f6  14.c4!  see the sample game Prie vs Rivero, 2011. The key lines to know are   13...f6  14.c4!  e5?!  16.Bxe5  fxe5  17.Qxe5+  Ne7  18.Nf3  Rxa3  19.O-O   and  13...f6  14.c4!  Nxf4  15.exf4  Rxa3  16.Ne2 }
14. Nf3 e6 15. O-O
{ White gets the king to safety and should be slightly better, but it's not a position that is easy to play by any means. White threatens c4 which is probably met by ...Nxf4, exf4. After that White should probably play c5, Rc1, and try to get the knight into  d6  with Nd2-e4-d6. }
