1. d4 { This was a Classical game. Prie was rated 2490, Black was rated 2388. }
1... Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 4. Nc3 Qxb2 5. Nb5 Nd5 6. a3 a6 7. Rb1 Qa2 8. Qc1
axb5 9. Ra1 Qxa1 10. Qxa1 Nc6 11. Bxb5 cxd4 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Qxd4 f6 {  } 14.
c4
{ This is best, intending to meet ...e5 with Bxe5, when White has an advantage. }
14... Nxf4
{ If  14...e5!?  15.Bxe5  fxe5  16.Qxe5+  Ne7  17.Nf3  Rxa3  18.O-O  with an advantage, and plans like Ng5 to Ne4 to Nd6 or Rb1 to Rb8. }
15. exf4 { Best. } 15... e5
{ This is a mistake. Romero & Prado suggest  15...Rxa3  16.Ne2  e5  17.Qb2  exf4  18.Nxf4  Kf7  19.O-O  but current engines like this for White. }
16. fxe5 Bxa3 17. exf6 O-O {  } 18. Ne2
{ A mistake by White. It might've been hard to play, but 18. fxg7 was the move with a continuation like 18. fxg7 Rf7 19. Ne2 Bb4+ 20. Kd1 with an advantage in a messy position. }
18... Bb4+ 19. Kd1 Rxf6 20. c5 Rb8 21. Ng3
{ /Better was 21. Nf4 with the idea of Nh5. } 21... d5 22. Qe5 Rf8 23. f3 Rb7
24. Qd6 Rf6 25. Qd8+ { Prie goes for a repetition. } 25... Rf8 26. Qd6 Rf6 27.
Qd8+ Rf8 28. Qd6 Bd7
{ Black avoids the repetition. What follows are three mutual blunders and a draw. }
29. Nh5 { A blunder, after which Black could win with  29...Re8 } 29... Bc8
{ A blunder, now White could win with  30.Qxc6 } 30. Ng3
{ White repeats and a draw is agreed, even though he could've won with  30.Qxc6 }
