[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 4. Nc3 Qxb2 5. Nb5 Nd5 6. a3 a6 7. Rb1 Qa2 8. Qc1
axb5 9. Ra1 Qxa1 10. Qxa1 e5
{ Black sacrifices a pawn so as to open up the diagonal quickly. Kamsky gives this as best and thinks that this makes White's life pretty miserable. }
11. Bxe5
{ Better is  11.dxe5  which we'll look at next. The text move allows Black an easy repetition. However, beta testers for this course Flyingbishop97 and IronStone pushed the theory further, the former finding a continuation for Black that enables him to even play for a win and the latter finding a defense for White. }
11... c4 { Black is threatening ...Bb4+. } 12. Bxb8
{ White tries to distract the rook from the open a-file to buy time. } 12...
Rxa3 { Ouch. } 13. Qb2 Bb4+ { More ouch. } 14. Ke2 Ra2 { Even more ouch. } 15.
Qc1 b6
{ Flyingbishop's move, essentially asking White to find a good move. Kamsky gave the repetition with  15...Ba3  16.Qd2  Bb4 }
16. Kf3
{ If  16.Nf3  Nc3+  17.Kd2  Ne4+  18.Ke2  Ba3  traps the Queen.   If  16.f3  Ba3  17.Qd2  Nb4  threatens  ...Rxc2  . }
16... Bb7 17. Kg3 {  } 17... O-O 18. Be5 f6
{ Note how all of Black's moves have threats, meaning that White doesn't have any time to pursue his own goals. }
19. Ne2
{ Bf4 is natural, but then White is just worse after ...Rfa8. This is IronStone's proposed defense. }
19... fxe5 20. dxe5 Rfa8 21. c3 Bc5
{ Black is slightly better. In any case, none of this is practically relevant since White should play 11. dxe5 instead. }
