1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 4. Nc3 Qxb2 5. Nb5 Nd5 6. a3 a6
{ The best move. } 7. Rb1 Qa2 8. Qc1 axb5 9. Ra1 Qxa1 10. Qxa1 e5
{ Kamsky gives this as best for Black and it's hard to argue with him. } 11.
dxe5 { As we saw in the previous line, Bxe5 doesn't really work. } 11... c4
{ The Agadmator's Anti-London course gives the move order  11...Nxf4  12.exf4  c4  and now  13.Be2  Rxa3  14.Qb2  Nc6  and here White has an interesting idea  15.g4!?  not covered in the aforementioned course  15...Bc5  16.Nf3  with an equal position, again. }
12. Qd4
{ The queen gets away from the a-file and prepares to recapture on f4. } 12...
Nxf4 13. Qxf4 Bxa3 14. Ke2 { Stepping away from ...Bb4+. } 14... Bb4
{ Black controls a key diagonal and opens the a-file for his rook. } 15. Nf3
{ Developing. } 15... O-O 16. h4
{ Grabbing some kingside space and intending the typical h5 to h6. White can perhaps eventually even tuck away the king on h2 via f3-g3-h2. }
16... Ra2 17. Nd4
{ The position is objectively equal, untested, and a complete mess. The practical likelihood of getting here is close to zero though. }
