{ The most natural and common way to block the check.   If  5...Nbd7  6.a4  a6  7.a5  Qc7  8.Bd3   and if  5...Nc6  6.d5  a6  7.Ba4  Qc7!  8.Nge2  Rb8  9.dxc6  is a very hard line for Black to play without knowing all the moves ahead of time. }
6. a4 a6
{ Black doesn't ever want to play  6...Bxb5  7.axb5  giving White the open a-file. }
7. a5 Qc7 8. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 9. d5
{ White has a good version of a Benoni-esque position. } 9... g6
{ Most common and natural. } 10. e4 Bg7 11. Nf3 O-O 12. O-O
{ White has a good Benoni with the a-pawn in place, restricting the ...b5-break. In the long run, he should play for e5. We will see positions like this more in the next chapter on the Old Benoni. }
