[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 4. Nc3 Qxb2 5. Nge2
{ An interesting sideline. Played 53 times and 2 times at Master level, once by Grischuk against Adhiban and once by Aronian against Giri in Blitz. White won both games. Seehere andhere. }
5... Qa3
{ Probably the best move, but it's hard to say.   5...Qb6  Baskaran played this, perhaps on analogy with the Vaganian Gambit, but here White is already doing well after  6.Rb1  Qa5   6...Qd8  7.dxc5  7.Rb5  Qd8  8.dxc5   5...cxd4  Most common  6.exd4  Black plays all sorts of stuff here and White should always keep in mind Rb1 and the g4 idea. }
6. g4
{ A fun move, and it's never been played. The point is that Black can't really take it since then White can play Nd5. At the same time, White is intending g5 and Bg2. White can also play  6.Rb1  with about the same objective evaluation of equality. }
6... d6
{ 6...Nxg4?  7.Nd5  Qa5+  After this best play leads to a draw by repetition  8.Qd2  Qxd2+  9.Kxd2  Na6  10.Nec3  e6  11.Bxa6  exd5  12.Be2  Nxf2  13.Nxd5  Nxh1  14.Rxh1  Kd8  15.Bc7+  Ke8  16.Bg3  Kd8  17.Bc7+ }
7. Bg2 Nxg4 8. O-O Nf6 9. Rb1 Nbd7 10. Qd3
{ White completes development by connecting the rooks. Black is slightly better, being up two pawns, but his position is quite hard to play. White is threatening to take on b7 and infiltrate there. Rb3 is another move that is in the books. This requires more practical testing. }
