[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 {  } 4. Nf3
{ This is a very interesting option, gambiting the b-pawn for a development lead and play against the Queen. }
4... Qxb2
{ This is overwhelmingly most common, with 270 games  (compared to perhaps 80-90 games total for all the other options combined)  . As far as the rest,   4...a6  5.Nbd2   4...d6  5.Nbd2  lead to thematic play   while  4...d5  5.Nc3  transposes to the d5-lines   and  4...e6  5.Na3!  transposes to the QID-line   4...Nc6?!  5.Na3!   4...Na6?!  5.Nbd2  with  Bxa6  next are similar.  We will consider   4...cxd4   and  4...Nd5  separately. }
5. Nbd2 cxd4
{ Weirdly enough, overwhelmingly most common. Perhaps Black wants to prevent dxc5. }
6. exd4
{ One way to play is to just recapture the pawn and await further developments. As an alternative, you can also go for a line Kamsky considers from a different move order with   6.Rb1  Qc3  7.Rb3  Qa5  8.exd4  d5  9.Qb1!  b6  10.Rb5!  or Bb5+ followed by a4. }
6... Nc6
{ Most common move, with 67 games, but a blunder since now White can win immediately. If  6...Nd5?!  7.Rb1  Qa3  7.Rb3  Qa4  8.Bg3  and White is better. Other moves can be met with Rb1, with thematic play. }
7. Nc4 { Always the ideal square for the knight in these Queen trap lines. }
7... Qb4+ { If  7...Qc3+??  8.Bd2 } 8. c3
{ The key move, which most White players have missed. White wants to have the Queen control a4 before playing Bd2. }
8... Qxc3+ { ...Qb5 is obviously met with Nd6+ discovery:   8...Qb5??  9.Nd6+ }
9. Bd2 { The Queen is trapped and White is winning. } *

