1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 4. Nf3 Qxb2 5. Nbd2 Nc6
{ This developing move is not bad, and is the second most common. } 6. dxc5
{ We win our pawn back. This position is reminiscent of the sharp ...Qb6 lines. }
6... e6
{ This might be best. Most common is   6...e5?!  7.Rb1  Qc3  8.Rb3  Qxc5  9.Nxe5  when Black can't recapture the knight due to Rb5. }
7. Rb1 { Only 3 games have reached this position. } 7... Qc3
{ If   7...Qxa2  8.Bd3  can be handled similarly to the text. } 8. Bd3
{ White just aims to complete development and castle. } 8... Qxc5
{ If   8...Bxc5  9.Rb3  Qa5  10.Rb5  Qa3  11.Nb1!  and Black's bishop will be lost }
9. O-O { White just castles. Black's position is not easy to play at all. }
9... Be7 10. Rb5 Qa3 11. Nc4
{ White intends Nd6+, installing a piece on  d6  and hampering Black's development. }
11... Qa4
{ One option. If   11...Qxa2  12.Nd6+  and if   11...Qa6  12.Rb3  Qxa2  13.Bd6! }
12. Nd6+ Bxd6 13. Bxd6
{ White's winning. Black is in a lot of danger, for example, the tempting ...Ne4 fails to   13...Ne4  14.Rb4!  Nxb4  14.Bxe4  Nc6  15.Ng5  with Qh5 next, and it's over soon. }
