1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 4. Nf3 Qxb2 5. Nbd2 Qc3
{ This thematic Queen move might be the best, getting it out of potential trouble as fast as possible while keeping it in White's camp. }
6. Rb1 {  } 6... Nc6
{ Developing. If ...cxd4 we get a similar line as before after Rb3. For example, Kamsky gives the following idea   6...cxd4  7.Rb3  Qa5  8.exd4  d5  9.Qb1!  b6  10.Rb5!  or Bb5+ followed by a4. }
7. Rb3
{ White can also try moves like dxc5 and Bc4. In all of these positions, the pawn deficit really doesn’t matter. White’s development lead and active pieces give him great chances. }
7... Qa5 8. dxc5 { Taking the pressure off d4. } 8... Qxc5 9. Rb5
{ Forcing Black to decide between ...Qa3 and ...Qc3. } 9... Qa3
{ If  9...Qc3  10.Bd3  and White can castle next and then hope to play e4. }
10. Bd3
{ Objectively Black might have a slight 'engine advantage', but practically White has a lot of compensation and most Black moves can be met with Nc4 or O-O. For example:   10...Qxa2  11.Nc4   10...d6  11.Nc4   10...d6  11.O-O  are even Stockfish-equal.   10...e6  11.Nc4   10...g6  11.Nc4  .   If  10...d5  11.Qb1!  e6  12.Rxb7!  and Black is in trouble. }
