1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 4. Nf3 Nd5 {  } 5. dxc5 {  } 5... Qxb2
{ 5...Qxc5  6.Bg3  is just better for White due to his lead in development, Black's vulnerable Queen, and the pointless knight on d5. For example  6...d6  7.c4  Nf6  8.Nc3 }
6. Be5 { 6.Qxd5  Qxa1  7.Qb3  can be tried as well. } 6... Qb4+ 7. Nbd2 {  }
7... Qxc5
{ If   7...Nc3  8.Qc1  with Qb2 next and if something like   7...e6  8.Bd4  with c4 next. }
8. Nb3
{ Another typical idea in these positions. We are improving our pieces at the expense of the Black Queen. }
8... Qb4+
{ Quite likely. Another move is  8...Qc6  9.Na5  Qc5  10.Nb3  is a way to repeat.   8...Qc6  9.c4  Nf6  10.c5  e6  11.Rc1  Qd5  12.Qc2  Nc6  13.Bc4  Qe4  14.Bd3  Qg4  15.O-O  is a way to try for more when our development lead clearly compensates for our pawn deficit. }
9. c3 Nxc3 10. a3 { The point! The queen is overloaded. } 10... Nxd1+ 11. axb4
{ The contours of the position have been set. White is down two pawns, but more than likely will pick up the knight, leading to a very interesting endgame. }
11... d6 12. Rc1
{ The most testing move. Rxd1 doesn’t lead to much for White, hence why we play Rc1. }
12... Nc6 13. Ba1 Nxe3 { Black doesn't have anything better. } 14. fxe3 Nxb4
15. Kf2
{ Black has actually 4  (!)  pawns for the piece, but White's still better due to his lead in development. }
