[Black "3...g6!?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 g6 {  } 4. Nf3 {  } 4... Bg7
{ Most common. Notice that starting with ...d6 doesn't really change much  4...d6  5.c3   If  4...Qb6  5.Na3  is thematic.   If  4...Nh5  5.Be5  f6  6.Bxb8  Rxb8  7.g4!?  Ng7  8.Nc3  with a very interesting position.   A setup that doesn't make a ton of sense is  4...cxd4  5.exd4  Bg7  6.c3  to shut down the diagonal  6...O-O  7.Bc4  putting the bishop on a dangerous diagonal. See the model gameTsoi vs. Granados. }
5. c3 { White can also play Nbd2 first. } 5... O-O
{ Most common, but Black can also start with ...b6. If  5...Nh5?!  6.Be5!  f6??  7.Bxb8  Rxb8  8.g4! }
6. Nbd2 d6 { This prepares ...e5, but also takes away Be5 and Bxb8. } 7. h3
{ Hence, this is the moment to make an escape hole for the bishop. } 7... b6
{  } 8. Bc4
{ From this move order, White has a choice between playing Be2, Bd3, or Bc4. The text option is most interesting and was also the choice of Capablanca, see the model gameCapablanca vs. Reti.   The most common setup is  8.Be2  Bb7  9.O-O  Nbd7  10.a4  a6  11.Bh2  and now Black has several options like ...Qc7 or ...Ra7 & ...Qa8 and White can meet them with Re1, with an interesting game. }
8... Bb7 {  } 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Re1 { Aiming for e4. } 10... a6
{ Intending ...b5. } 11. a4
{ We've reached an interesting position where Black has to find a plan. } 11...
Qc7
{ The most common move. The other three moves are  11...Ne4  12.d5!   11...Rc8  12.Qe2   or  11...Ra7!?  12.Bf1!  Qa8  13.c4!  intending to just play  d5  and leave Black's pieces stranded on the Queenside.   The engine likes  11...d5  12.Bf1  but it's hard to see anyone playing this since it just shuts off the light-squared bishop. }
12. e4
{ A very rare move. White simply intends d5, shutting out Black's Queenside pieces. }
12... e5
{ Black should play this break while he can. If  12...cxd4  13.cxd4  Nxe4?!  14.Rc1!  Qd8  15.Rxe4!   and if  12...Rac8  13.d5  demonstrates White's idea. }
13. Bh2
{ Only two games have ever reached here and it's not clear what Black should do. White can play Rc1 and/or b4 or retreat the bishop and close the center with c4 and d5. }
