[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Benoni"]
[Black "Jose Raul Capablanca vs. Richard Reti, 1922"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was another game from the London 1922 tournament. Capablanca commented on this game in the Times:    @@StartBlockQuote@@I had a very interesting game with Reti, who adopted one of his new lines of defence. The position became very complicated in the middle game, and while I obtained the upper hand, I could not make much headway against the able defence of my opponent. Finally towards the end, when Queens were off - on the 27th move, in fact - Reti made a weak move, and I took advantage of it immediately to secure a win. Reti resigned on the 38th move.@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. h3
{ Capablanca intends to play Bf4 while having already created an escape square for the bishop. }
3... Bg7 4. Bf4 O-O 5. Nbd2 d6 6. e3 Nbd7 7. c3 c5 8. Bc4
{ Capablanca goes for Bc4 and that is our move as well. } 8... b6 9. O-O Bb7
10. Qe2 { 10.Re1  Is our move, but play is somewhat similar with e4. } 10...
Qc7 11. Bh2 { White steps away from the ...e5 break. } 11... Rae8 12. e4
{ The e4-push is one of White's main ideas here. } 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 e5
{ 13...Nxe4  14.Rac1  Qd8  15.Nxe4  d5  16.Bb5  dxe4  17.Ne5 } 14. Rac1 Qb8 15.
d5 Rc8 16. Bb5 { 16.Ng5  Followed by f4 was also an idea. } 16... Rxc1 17. Rxc1
Rc8 18. Bc6 { A very Capablancaish move. } 18... Bh6 19. b4 { Threatening b5. }
19... Bxd2 20. Nxd2 Bxc6 21. dxc6
{ This is probably what Capa was aiming for. } 21... b5 22. Nb3
{ The knight wants to go to a5. } 22... Nf8 23. Qd3 Ne6 24. Kf1 Qb6 25. Na5 Qd4
{ Capablanca commented: 'Reti made the right reply, 25...Qd4. If instead he had played 25...Nd4, then I would have won with f4! The continuation might have been 26...Nxc6 27.Bg1 Qa6 28.Qxd6 and Black must lose a piece.' Let's examine...   25...Nd4  26.f4  Nxc6  27.Bg1  Qa6  28.Qxd6  This is where Capablanca stopped. However, Black can try  28...Nxb4!  29.Rxc8+  Qxc8  30.Qxb4  Qc1+  31.Qe1  Qxf4+  32.Bf2  Nxe4  33.Qe3!  After this White's still better, but perhaps not clearly winning. }
26. Qxd4 Nxd4 27. f3 Rc7 { This is the move Capa called weak in his article. }
28. Bg1 Kf8 29. Bxd4
{ White exchanges the strong central knight and creates a target. } 29... exd4
30. Rd1 Ke7 31. Rxd4 Ke6 32. Ke2 Ng8 33. Nb7 Nf6 34. Rxd6+ Ke7 35. Ke3 Ne8 36.
e5 Ng7 37. f4 h5 38. g4 hxg4 39. hxg4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Old Benoni"]
[Black "Old Benoni: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ The Old Benoni. This is the 4th most frequent option with 900 000 games. } 2.
d5
{ Here I recommend you push on. It's worth learning these positions since, first, they will be relevant for all d-pawn games, second, it's the best training ground for learning how to play Benoni style positions. Furthermore, in this version, White gets an objective advantage in all lines which is why it's never seen at the top level. Black has three main setups: 1@@EndBracket@@ Czech: ... e5 & ...d6; 2@@EndBracket@@ Central break with ...e6; 3@@EndBracket@@ Modern: ...d6 & ...g6 }
2... Nf6
{ This is only the third most common move after ...d6 & ...e5, but it's the most flexible one, allowing for both ...e6 & ...g6 setups   2...b5  this doesn't work here  3.e4  a6  Most common  4.c4  a4 followed by f4 is also good  4...b4  5.a3  e5  6.axb4  cxb4  7.Be3   2...f5  the so-called Clarendon Court, played about 10 000x, but it's basically bad  3.e4  fxe4  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Nge2  g6  6.Ng3  d6   6...Bg7  7.d6  7.Ncxe4  Nxe4  8.Nxe4  Bg7  9.h4!?   2...e5  the Czech setup, closing the center and aiming to play for the ...b5 and ...f5 breaks. It's the second most common with ~100 000 games  3.e4  d6  4.Bb5+  The most forcing move, basically restricting Black's options to either ...Nd7 or ...Bd7. It's the third most common move.  4...Nd7  The more common move with ~2700 games   4...Bd7  The slightly less common move with ~2200 games  5.a4  a6  Kicking the bishop. The important point is Black doesn't want to take and give White the open a-file   5...Bxb5  6.axb5  6.Bd3  Be7  Second most common and most thematic, aiming to exchange the dark-squared bishops   6...Nf6  7.Nd2   6...g6  Most common, but quite bad since here the d-pawn is undefended and backwards  7.Nd2  The knight will go to c4  7.Nd2  Nf6   7...Bg5  8.Nc4  Bxc1  9.Qxc1  Bc8  10.f4  8.h3  5.a4  Easy to remember  5...a6  Most common, again, kicking the bishop  6.Bd3   6.Be2  Here engines, Plichta, and practice prefer Be2 probably because it prevents the maneuver ...Ngf6 to ...Nh5 to ...Nf4, but I like the rarer  text move which is common to both lines and poses novel problems  6...Be7  7.Nf3  Stopping ...Bg5  7...Ngf6  Black wants to castle and then play ...Ne8 and ...Bg5  8.Nc3  O-O  9.O-O  Ne8  10.Nd2  Bg5  11.Nc4  6...Be7  7.Nd2  Again, same move  7...Ngf6   7...Bg5  Most common and bad...  8.Nc4  Bxc1  9.Nxd6+  8.Ne2  The idea is to guard f4. Ngf3 is also fine.  8...Nh5  Black's main idea though it hasn't been played in practice   8...Nf8  9.a5  Followed by b3, Nc4 etc.  9.Nc4  The knight's going to e3   2...d6  The most common move, but it will transpose to the Tabiya after  3.e4  Nf6  4.Nc3   2...e6  We'll consider the e6-systems from this, earliest move order. This is the 4th most common move in the position with 67 000 games  3.Nc3  Only the 3rd most common, but best-scoring  3...Nf6   3...exd5  4.Nxd5  d6   4...Nf6  5.Bg5  Be7  6.Bxf6  Bxf6  7.c3  O-O  8.g3  Nc6  9.Bg2  5.g3  Nf6  6.Nxf6+  Qxf6  7.Nh3   3...d6  Another independent option  4.e4  exd5   4...a6  5.a4  Nf6  6.Bc4  exd5  7.Nxd5  Be7  8.Ne2  Offering the e-pawn. This position has not occurred in practice  8...Nxe4  9.Ra3  5.Nxd5  Nf6  6.Nxf6+  Qxf6  7.Ne2  The knight travels to d5  7...Nc6  8.Nc3  Qg6  9.h4  4.e4  d6   4...exd5  Believe it or not, this losing blunder is the most common move and has been played in over 11 000 games  5.e5  Even worse, White's responded with the correct move only in about 1/3 of the games. After this Black is losing in all variations  5.Bb5+  I like this move which I 'discovered' a year or so ago while studying these lines, pursuing the analogy with the Czech lines. It has also been recommended by Avrukh. It's not the engine's top choice, but nicest to play.  5...Bd7   5...Nbd7  Here this is clearly worse  6.dxe6  fxe6  7.Nf3  I prefer this over Avrukh's immediate e5  7...a6  8.Bc4  Nb6  9.Be2  Be7  10.a4  6.a4  Be7  7.Nf3  O-O  8.O-O  exd5  9.exd5  Here we take on d5 with a pawn. Black has to solve the problem of their knight and then we have a surprise in store  9...Na6  10.Bxa6  bxa6  11.Nd2  Rb8  The most common move  12.Nc4  Bf5  13.Re1  Re8  14.Bf4  Bf8  15.Qd2 }
3. Nc3 d6
{ 3...g6  4.e4  d6  Transposes   4...Bg7  5.e5  Ng8  6.Bf4   3...e6  Transposes to the 2...e6 lines after  4.e4 }
4. e4
{ Tabiya. From here Black can still choose between ...e6 and ...g6 setups. The latter is overwhelmingly more common. }
4... g6
{ The most common move with ~18 000 games. White can try a variety of moves here and he scores well after almost all of them, however, the main line is Nf3. We will also cover the more forcing and violent f4 as an alternative.   4...e6  Played only ~2500x. Transposes to the above. }
5. Nf3
{ 5.f4  The best move for faster time controls because of it's forcing nature. White tries to play a quick e5 and it's very easy for Black to go wrong here  5...Bg7   5...a6  Best move, but only the 4th most common and hard to play because of the e5 break  6.e5  Nfd7   6...dxe5  7.fxe5  Nfd7  8.Nf3  White already has a massive edge with the e6 break coming next  7.Qe2  A move which has never been played, but poses difficult problems due to the threat of exd6  6.Bb5+  Bd7  The only move   6...Nbd7  7.e5  After the knight moves e6 comes  7...Ng8  8.e6  7.e5  Ng8  8.Nf3  Bxb5  9.Nxb5  a6  Black thinks he gets ...b5 in and he does, but this is too slow  10.Nc3  b5  11.O-O  Nh6  12.e6  O-O  13.Ng5  White's a lot better. }
5... Bg7 { The main move.   5...Bg4  Second most common.  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Qxf3 }
6. Bc4 { The best move. } 6... O-O 7. O-O
{ Another tabiya. From here on it's not important to memorize everything, but to understand what both sides are aiming for, so you can find the best moves in live play.   7.h3  This is the second most common, but it doesn't work due to  7...b5  8.Bxb5   8.Nxb5  Nxe4  8...Nxe4  9.Nxe4  Qa5+ }
7... a6
{ Most common   7...Bg4  One of Black's main ideas in the Benoni structures is to exchange the light-squared bishop for White's knight. It's the second most common move here  8.h3  Bxf3  9.Qxf3  Nbd7  10.Be2  A rare move with the idea of prophylaxis against ...Nb6. White aims to put the Queen on g3 and play f4, for example  10...a6  11.a4  Ne5  12.Qg3  With f4 next   7...Na6  Third most common, aiming to reroute the knight to c7  8.h3  Squeeze...  8...Nc7  9.a4  All prophylactic moves, asking Black what his idea is   7...Nbd7  Fourth most common  8.a4  Ng4  Most played, with the idea of Ne5  9.Be2  Prophylaxis  9...Nge5  10.Ne1  Black doesn't have space so White should aim to keep as many pieces on the board as possible. Black has to find a very difficult maneuver to not lose a piece   10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.f4  Nd7  12.Qe1  This is fine too, intending f5 next  10...Qa5  11.f4  Nc4  12.Bxc4  Bxc3  13.Nf3  Bg7  14.Qe2  White is better   7...e6  Only the 5th most common and not a very good option  8.Re1  A simple solution and the best-scoring one. Sielecki gives dxe6, but it's a lot more to learn for such a sideline.  8...exd5  9.Nxd5  Nxd5  10.Bxd5  Nc6  11.Bf4  Ne5  12.Nxe5  dxe5  13.Be3  White has a comfortable edge due to his central presence. He can double or triple on the d-file. }
8. a4 { a6 is ALWAYS met by a4, stopping ...b5. } 8... Nbd7
{ Somewhat independent due to the inclusion of ...a6 and a4 since now it's White's move   8...Bg4  Equally as common as above, but play should transpose after.  9.h3 }
9. h3 { Prophylaxis. } 9... Rb8 { Preparing the ...b5 break. } 10. a5
{ Restricts Black the most since there is no ...Nb6. } 10... b5
{ 10...Ne8  11.Re1  Creating space for the bishop  11...b5  12.axb6  Nxb6 } 11.
axb6 Nxb6 12. Bd3
{ White holds all the trumps with the open a-file, center and more space. } *

