[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Old Benoni"]
[Black "2...b5?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 b5 { this Benko-style move doesn't work here. } 3. e4
{ Grabbing the center and attacking the b-pawn. } 3... a6
{ The most common move. If  3...Qa5+  4.Bd2   3...Qb6  4.a4! } 4. c4
{ Attacking Black's pawn formation further.  a4  followed by  f4  is also good as in  4.a4  b4  5.f4  d6  6.Nf3   For comparison, Avrukh prefers the plan of putting the knight on c4  4.a4  b4  5.Nd2  d6  6.Nc4  g6  7.Bd3  Bg7  8.a5! }
4... b4 { If  4...bxc4  5.Qa4 } 5. a3
{ White just keeps attacking Black's pawn wedge. } 5... e5
{ Black tries to get at least some foothold in the center before it is too late. If   5...bxa3?!  6.Rxa3  or   5...bxa3?!  6.f4  grabbing the whole center. }
6. axb4 cxb4 7. Be3
{ Preventing ...Bc5 and making Black's development a real problem. If   7...d6  8.Qa4+   7...Nf6  8.Nd2  .  White is in total control and will finish development and then seek to play in the center, aiming for the f4 break. }
