[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Old Benoni"]
[Black "2...f5?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 f5
{ the so-called Clarendon Court, mixing the Benoni and Dutch, has been played about 10 000x, but it's basically bad. }
3. e4
{ The key move to remember. This works because Black has weakened his king. }
3... fxe4
{ If  3...d6?  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.Bb5+  Bd7  6.exf5  Bxb5  7.Nxb5  Qd7  8.c4  a6  9.Qa4!  Nxd5  10.Nf3  and Black has a very hard time meeting the threat of  Nc7+  . }
4. Nc3 Nf6 { If  4...g6?!  5.h4! } 5. Nge2
{ Avrukh gives instead the g-pawn thrust with  5.g4  h6  6.Bg2  d6  7.Nxe4  Nxg4  8.Qe2  which is also good and White could also simply play 7. h3. }
5... g6
{ If Black tries something like  5...Qa5  6.d6!  exd6  7.Bg5   or  5...Qa5  6.d6  Nc6  7.h4! }
6. Ng3 { White could also try  6.d6!? } 6... d6 { If  6...Bg7  7.h4! } 7. Ncxe4
Nxe4 8. Nxe4 Bg7 9. h4
{ This is stronger than just Bd3 etc. White aims to push the h-pawn all the way to h6 if allowed. It's an unexplored line in practice, but here are some sample continuations   9...O-O  10.h5   9...h6  10.Bd3   9...Bf5  10.Ng3 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Old Benoni"]
[Black "Czech, 2... e5, 4...Bd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e5
{ the Czech-style setup, closing the center and aiming to play for the ...b5 and ...f5 breaks. It's the second most common with ~100 000 games.  However, here White is doing even better than in the Czech Benoni since they have  c4  available for their knight. }
3. e4 d6
{ One of Black's main plans is to exchange dark-squared bishops. This makes sense since his pawns are all on dark squares, meaning that his dark-squared bishop has less scope. }
4. Bb5+
{ The most forcing move, basically restricting Black's options to either ...Nd7 or ...Bd7. It's only the third most common move, but also the recommendation of FM Plichta in his Go for the Throat: Play 1. d4, and GM Avrukh. }
4... Bd7
{ The slightly less common move with ~2200 games.  The problem is that the bishop gets in the way of the knight on b8 and it doesn't really want to be on d7 anyway. }
5. a4
{ Keeping the tension and emphasizing that Black doesn't want to capture it and open the a-file for White. }
5... a6
{ Overwhelmingly the most common move is to kick the bishop. Again, Black doesn't want to take and give White the open a-file  5...Bxb5  6.axb5   Avrukh also considers  5...Be7  6.Nf3  Nf6  7.Nc3  O-O  8.Nd2!   and  5...g6  6.Nc3  Bg7  7.Nf3  Nf6  8.Be2 }
6. Bd3
{ I, like Plichta, prefer the retreat. Avrukh prefers  6.Bxd7+  Nxd7  7.a5! }
6... Be7
{ Second most common and most thematic, aiming to exchange the dark-squared bishops with ...Bg5   6...Nf6  7.Nd2   6...g6  Most common, but quite bad since here the d-pawn is undefended and backwards  7.Nd2  The knight will go to  c4 }
7. Nd2 Nf6
{ Note that if Black insists on exchanging here then Nc4 is strong because it attacks the weak d6-pawn.  7...Bg5  8.Nc4  Bxc1  9.Qxc1  Bc8  10.f4 }
8. h3
{ Plichta recommends  8.a5  which is also good. However, I like this move, emphasizing Black's lack of space even further.  White will play a5, Nc4, Ne2, O-O in due time and aim for the f4-break. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Old Benoni"]
[Black "Czech, 2... e5, 4...Nd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e5 3. e4 d6 4. Bb5+ Nd7
{ The more common move with ~2700 games. } 5. a4
{ Easy to remember. Like always, White prevents a future ...b5 if the bishop is ever kicked with ...a6. }
5... a6
{ Again, most common, kicking the bishop. If  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  Be7  8.Nf3  O-O  9.Nd2  when the knight heads to  c4  as usual.   Avrukh also considers the rarer  5...Be7  6.Nf3  Nf6  7.Nc3  O-O  8.O-O  Ne8  9.Nd2  again, going to  c4   and  5...g6  6.Nc3  Bg7  7.Nf3  Ne7  8.h4! }
6. Bd3
{ 6.Be2  Here engines, Avrukh, Plichta, and practice prefer this retreat, probably because it prevents the maneuver ...Ngf6 to ...Nh5 to ...Nf4, but I like the rarer text move which is common to both lines and poses novel problems.  6...Be7  7.Nf3  Stopping ...Bg5  7...Ngf6  Black wants to castle and then play ...Ne8 and ...Bg5  8.Nc3  O-O  9.O-O  Ne8  10.Nd2  Bg5  11.Nc4 }
6... Be7
{ If Black tries instead  6...g6  7.Ne2  is strong with the idea of putting this knight to  c3  and the other one directly to  c4  via  a3! }
7. Nd2 { Again, the same move, heading to c4. } 7... Ngf6
{ 7...Bg5  Most common and bad...  8.Nc4  Bxc1  9.Nxd6+ } 8. Ne2
{ The idea is to guard f4. Ngf3 is also fine. } 8... Nh5
{ Black's main idea though it hasn't been played in practice.   8...Nf8  9.a5  Followed by b3, Nc4 etc. }
9. Nc4
{ The knight's going to e3 and aim for f5. In the long run White can castle and play for f4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Old Benoni"]
[Black "e6 with 3...exd5, 4...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e6
{ Challenging the center and attempting to transpose back into a Modern Benoni after c4. We, of course, will not let this happen... }
3. Nc3 exd5 4. Nxd5
{ White has a nice central outpost.  REMEMBER: All of these ...e6 & ...dxe6 variations revolve around the d5-outpost. Most of the ensuing variations revolve around playing sometimes unintuitive moves to keep or put a piece there like Bg5-Bxf6 when we can exchange the bishop for knight; g3 & Bg2, Nh3-Nf4-Nd5 or Nge2-Nc3-Nd5. }
4... Nf6 { Slightly inaccurate since it allows for... } 5. Bg5
{ This is one way of playing it. Also good is  5.Nxf6  Qxf6  6.e4  Nc6  7.Ne2  with the typical idea of plonking the knight into  d5  . }
5... Be7 6. Bxf6 { We want to keep our strong central knight. } 6... Bxf6 7. c3
{ Restricting the bishop. } 7... O-O 8. g3
{ White aims to fianchetto the bishop to its best diagonal and support the strong central knight. }
8... Nc6 9. Bg2
{ White will complete his development with Nh3 to Nf4, to support our other knight and then O-O, with a nice edge. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Old Benoni"]
[Black "e6 with 3...exd5, 4...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e6 3. Nc3 exd5 4. Nxd5 d6
{ The main move. Black hopes to get into a normal Benoni structure with ...g6 and ...Bg7. However, this takes a lot of time and we can strike earlier. }
5. g3
{ This is our typical move in these Nxd5 positions. We simply develop our bishop to the long diagonal and support our prized central knight. }
5... Nf6 6. Nxf6+
{ White could also try  6.Bg5  with the same idea to exchange the bishop for knight, as before, but here Black has  6...Nbd7  , intending to recapture with the knight. }
6... Qxf6 7. Nh3
{ White adds extra control over d5 via Nh3 to Nf4 to Nd5 and Bg2, and is significantly better due to the weaknesses in Black's camp. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Old Benoni"]
[Black "e6 with 3...d6 & 4...exd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e6 3. Nc3 d6 { Another independent option. } 4. e4 exd5
{ If instead  4...Nf6  5.Bb5+  just transposes to a later line. } 5. Nxd5
{ Nxd5 is better than exd5 for a couple of reasons. First, we occupy the outpost on d5 with our knight, maximizing its potential, and secondly, by keeping the d-file open, we have a clear target in the form of the weak d6 pawn. }
5... Nf6
{ If  5...Nc6  6.Ne2   or  5...Be6  6.Ne2  Bxd5  7.Qxd5  and in both cases we're again trying to get the f-knight to  d5  , like in the main line. }
6. Nxf6+
{ Like in the previous variations, it's all about the d5-outpost. Here we capture since we have a specific maneuver in mind that gives us a better position. }
6... Qxf6 7. Ne2 { The knight travels to d5. } 7... Nc6 8. Nc3 Qg6
{ Stopping our bishop from developing for the moment, but the Queen is vulnerable here. }
9. h4
{ Again, this has never occurred in practice. The idea is to harass the queen with h4-h5 and thereby make the kingside inhabitable for Black's king. White will play Be3, Qd2, and O-O-O with a better position, as the d6-pawn is terminally weak. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
