[White "18. Old Benoni"]
[Black "e6 with 3...d6 & 4...a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e6 3. Nc3 d6 4. e4 a6
{ Another independent option, controlling b5. } 5. a4
{ The automatic reaction. } 5... Nf6 { If  5...Ne7  still  6.Bc4 } 6. Bc4
{ White strengthens the d5 square, which will make the Knight on d5  (after an eventual ...exd5 Nxd5)  much stronger. The Bishop on c4 also pressures the e6 square, meaning that dxe6 might be possible in the future, and White could very easily attack the weak pawns on d6 and e6. }
6... exd5
{ If  7...e5?!  8.Nf3  Be7  9.Nd2   or  7...Be7  8.Nge2  aiming to go to  c3 }
7. Nxd5 { Here White should try to exploit the d5 outpost. } 7... Be7
{ 7...Nxe4??  8.Qe2 } 8. Ne2
{ A fantastic and by now thematic idea, intending to go to c3 to fortify the knight on d5. At the same time, White offers the e-pawn which will be too much for some Black players to resist. Note that this position has not occurred in practice yet. }
8... Nxe4 9. Ra3
{ With the idea of Re3, when the knight will be pinned to the loose bishop on  e7  . Sample continuations are  9...O-O??  10.Re3   or  9...Nf6  10.Nxe7  Qxe7  11.Re3  Be6  12.Nf4  and Black is in trouble as Nxe6 is coming next with devastating effect. }
