[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Old Benoni"]
[Black "e6 with 4...d6, 5...Nbd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e4 d6 { The best move. } 5. Bb5+
{ Again, I like this disruptive check which is also the recommendation of Avrukh. }
5... Nbd7
{ Here this is clearly worse as it allows dxe6.  Even worse is   5...Nfd7  6.dxe6  fxe6  7.Qh5+  g6  8.Qh3 }
6. dxe6 { Creating a weakness on e6. } 6... fxe6 7. Nf3
{ I prefer this over Avrukh's immediate e5. Ng5 is always a threat Black needs to keep in mind. }
7... a6 { Notice that something like  7...Be7?  just loses to  8.Ng5 } 8. Bc4
{ Attacking the e-pawn and thereby temporarily preventing ...b5. } 8... Nb6
{ This is a natural way to defend the pawn while attacking the bishop. However, it also blocks the b-pawn. If  8...d5  9.exd5  Nb6  9.Bd3  exd5  10.a4 }
9. Be2
{ Now it's fine to retreat to e2 since Black can't play ...b5. White plans to play a4 and O-O. }
9... Be7 { If  9...d5  10.e5 } 10. a4
{ White will castle soon, develop the dark-squared bishop and enjoy his space advantage. Note that if Black tries ...d5 at any moment, White should respond with e5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Old Benoni"]
[Black "e6 with 4...d6, 5...Bd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e4 d6 5. Bb5+ Bd7 { The better way to block. }
6. a4 Be7
{ Notice that, again, Black shouldn't take the bishop and open the a-file for us  6...Bxb5?!  7.axb5   If  6...a6  7.Bd3  and White is a little better due to his space advantage   If  6...Na6?!  7.dxe6  fxe6  8.Nf3   If  6...e5  7.Nf3  transposes to a Czech structure.   and if  6...exd5  7.exd5  which should transpose to the main line. }
7. Nf3 O-O
{ Natural. Again, if  7...Na6?!  8.dxe6  fxe6  9.e5!   The only serious move is  7...exd5  8.exd5  but this will transpose to the text after both sides castle next. }
8. O-O exd5
{ Best move. If  8...Na6?  9.e5!  Nxd5  10.exd6  Bxd6  11.Ne4  Be7  12.c4 } 9.
exd5
{ Here we take on d5 with a pawn. Black has to solve the problem of their knight and if they do, we have a surprise in store. }
9... Na6
{ Both sides can also throw in the waiting moves ...Re8 & Re1 and ...h6 & h3. After that is done, Black will still have to play ...Na6. }
10. Bxa6 { Surprise. } 10... bxa6 11. Nd2
{ This should be a familiar idea by now. } 11... Rb8
{ The most common move, putting the rook on the open file. } 12. Nc4 Bf5 13.
Re1 Re8 14. Bf4 Bf8 15. Qd2
{ White has a nice safe edge with multiple targets. } *

