[White "18. Old Benoni"]
[Black "g6 5. f4, Bg7 6...Bd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 Nf6 3. Nc3 d6 4. e4 g6
{ The most common move with ~18 000 games. White can try a variety of moves here and he scores well after almost all of them, however the main line is Nf3. We will also cover the more forcing and violent f4 as an alternative. }
5. f4
{ The best move for faster time controls because of its forcing nature. White tries to play a quick e5 and it's very easy for Black to go wrong here. }
5... Bg7 { Most common. If  5...Nbd7  or  5...Nfd7  then just  6.Nf3  . } 6.
Bb5+ { The standard check! } 6... Bd7
{ Statistically most common in Lichess and also the best move, however, surprisingly, at master level the much worse ...Nfd7 is mostly played   6...Nbd7  7.e5  After the knight moves, e6 comes, winning a piece  7...Ng8  8.e6 }
7. e5 Ng8
{ 7...dxe5  8.fxe5  is obviously good for White and know the knight needs to return anyway. }
8. Nf3 Bxb5 9. Nxb5 a6
{ Black thinks he gets  ...b5  in and he does, but this is too slow. If  9...Nh6  10.O-O  . }
10. Nc3 b5 11. O-O { Our center matters more than Black's Queenside. } 11...
Nh6 12. e6 O-O 13. Ng5
{ White has a large advantage. Black can try to defend with 13  ...f5  but then  14.h3  stopping ...Ng4 and White is positionally dominant. }
