[White "18. Old Benoni"]
[Black "g6 5. f4, Bg7 6...Nfd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 Nf6 3. Nc3 d6 4. e4 g6 5. f4 Bg7 6. Bb5+ Nfd7
{ This is the most commonly played move at master level, probably on analogy with Modern Benoni  (imagine the c2- and e7-pawns are gone)  where it is indeed the main move. But here it isn't good and White gets an advantage after a4, Bd3, Be2 and a host of other moves. }
7. a4
{ The typical prophylactic move, to stop a quick ...b5 after the bishop gets kicked with ...a6. }
7... O-O
{ If  7...a6  8.Be2  Nf6  9.Nf3  O-O  10.O-O  and White is better due to his space advantage. }
8. Nf3 Na6
{ The most common move. Again, if  8...a6  9.Be2  .   Black's best might be to return the knight with  8...Nf6  9.O-O  but White has a definite advantage. }
9. O-O { Don't take the knight. } 9... Nc7
{ Black wants to play for  ...b5  . If  9...Nb4  10.Ne2  with the usual plan. }
10. Bc4
{ A good place to stop. Play is thematic and White has ideas of h3, stopping ...Bg4, and Qe2 followed by f5! starting the attack on the Black king.   White can meet  10...a6  11.h3   10...Nb6  11.Bb3  preparing for the eventual  ...e6  break   10...b6  11.f5!   10...Rb8  11.h3  a6  12.Qe2  In all of the above positions, White is better due to his extra space. }
