[Black "g6 5. f4, a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 Nf6 3. Nc3 d6 4. e4 g6 5. f4 a6
{ Apparently the best move, but only the 4th most common. Black is trying to orchestrate an early ...b5, but this move is hard to play because it allows the e5 break. }
6. e5 { More space? We take it! } 6... Nfd7
{ 6...dxe5  7.fxe5  Nfd7  8.Nf3  White already has a massive edge with the e6 break coming next }
7. Qe2
{ This hasn't been played, but poses difficult problems due to the threat of exd6. }
7... Qc7
{ The only move not to be considerably worse, but hard to find. What follows is the best line, the likelihood of which occurring is basically non-existent. If  7...dxe5  8.fxe5  Bg7  9.Nf3  followed by Bf4 with a nice edge due to the space advantage. }
8. g3 { The logical way to develop the bishop. } 8... dxe5 9. Bg2
{ White sacrifices the pawn with the idea of capturing on f4 with the bishop, increasing his lead of development even further. }
9... Bg7 10. Nf3 { Development! } 10... O-O 11. O-O
{ White would eventually like to take with fxe5, opening the f-file. } 11...
exf4 { If  11...Re8  12.Ng5  with the idea of Nxf7 and fxe5+. } 12. Bxf4 Qb6
{ The more nettlesome move. If  12...Qd8  13.Rae1  and White will get the pawn back and be much better. }
13. Rab1 { Protecting the b-pawn. } 13... Nf6
{ If Black keeps the knight on d7, his development will be stunted for even longer. }
14. Ne5
{ A good place to stop. White has a pretty clear dynamic edge despite being a pawn down. However, it's the backward e-pawn which is a target. White also has ideas of Nc4, Re1, followed by d6, pushing forward. }
