1. d4 c5 2. d5 Nf6 3. Nc3 d6 4. e4 g6
{ The most common move with ~18 000 games. White can try a variety of moves here and he scores well after almost all of them, however the main line is Nf3. We will also cover the more forcing and violent f4 as an alternative. }
5. Nf3 { The most natural move, developing. } 5... Bg7 { The main move. } 6.
Bc4 { The best move, supporting the d5-pawn. } 6... O-O 7. O-O
{ Another tabiya. From here on it's not important to memorize everything, but to understand what both sides are aiming for, so you can find the best moves in live play. }
7... e6 { Only the 5th most common and not a very good option. } 8. Re1
{ A simple solution and the best-scoring one. Sielecki gives dxe6, but it's a lot more to learn for a rare sideline. }
8... exd5 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxd5
{ After a couple of exchanges, the position has clarified. Black's main weakness is the d6-pawn and both sides try to keep this in mind in the ensuing play. }
10... Nc6 11. Bf4 Ne5
{ Black blocks the bishop's aim against d6.   If Black goes pawn-grabbing  11...Bxb2  12.Rb1  Bg7??  13.Bxd6!  and White wins, so Black should put the bishop on  e5  after which White will chop it off, with an advantage. }
12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Be3
{ White has a comfortable edge due to his central presence. He can double or triple on the d-file. }
