[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. 1...e6, Dutch, Modern etc."]
[Black "1...e6: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6
{ This move doesn't have a lot of independent significance. It is mostly used to transpose into either some d5-line or a QID. However, it can also be used to try trappy lines with 2...g5 or 2...c5 and 3... Qb6 and to enter the Delayed Dutch with 2... f5. }
2. Bf4 f5
{ This Delayed Dutch move has been played in ~18 000 games. We'll take a look at this position from the current move order since it's one you have to face even if you play something other than London against the Dutch   2...g5  ~800 games  3.Bg3  h5  4.h4  g4  5.Nc3  d5  6.e4  Nf6  7.f3   2...c5  ~16 000 games  3.e3  Qb6  This can be quite a tricky try, but we're just going to be bold and gambit the b-pawn!  4.Nf3  Qxb2  5.Nbd2  Good luck to any human who ventures into this as Black in a non-correspondence game. For more, see the trainable line. }
3. e3 { The main move. } 3... Nf6
{ Black can still opt for either a Stonewall or a Classical here and there's also the Christmas Tree setup with ...e6 & ...g6 }
4. Nf3
{ White has many moves, but I like the standard setup. Here Black has two ways of playing, either with the Nimzo-style ...b6 or with ...Be7 first. }
4... Be7
{ 4...b6  The Nimzo move is the second most common, but actually the most played move at master level. It's also the top engine choice.  5.Be2  I think it's practically best to start with this move, rather than the direct c4 which can also be played. The idea is that by playing Be2 and O-O first, we just take away all ...Bb4+ lines. Black already faces a choice here between continuing with ...Bb7 or moving the dark-squared bishop.  5...Bb7  6.O-O  Again, let's castle first, taking away the ...Bb4+ options.  6...Be7   6...Bd6  This is GingerGM's radical idea and it's been tried around 300 times. The best way to counter it is by aiming to push d5!  7.c4  Now White's threatening to take on d6 and push d5.  7...Bxf4  8.exf4  O-O  9.Nc3  Nc6  This was given by Simon, however...  10.Qc2  He didn't consider this move, controlling e4 and vacating d1 for the rook. For more, see the trainable line.  7.c4  O-O  8.Nc3  Ne4  9.Nxe4  Bxe4  10.Bg3  Prophylaxis against ...g5, played exactly once. White will continue with Rc1, Nd2, Bf3 with a nice edge due to the space advantage. For more, see the trainable line.   4...d5  Stonewall. Whenever you see this just play  5.c4  White has the perfect setup against the Stonewall with Nc3, Bd3 coming. For more, see Destroying the Dutch I   5.Bd6  GingerGM style, but here this gets hit with an even quicker d5  5...Bxd6 }
5. h3
{ Taking time to preserve the bishop. White can play in a variety of ways here, including with c4 }
5... O-O { Black completes the first Classical moves } 6. Nbd2
{ It's also possible to play with c4, but here I want to try a standard setup }
6... b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. c3 { White has made all the standard London moves } 8...
Ne4
{ The most common Nimzo-style move   8...c5  This looks to be the best move  9.O-O  Nc6  10.Qe2  d5  11.Ne5  For the rest, see the trainable line. }
9. Rg1 { White could also break immediately with g4, but this is even better }
9... d6 { 9...d5  10.g4  Nd7  11.gxf5  exf5  12.Qe2 } 10. g4 Nd7 11. gxf5 exf5
12. Qc2 { With a lot of kingside pressure. } *

