[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. 1...e6, Dutch, Modern etc."]
[Black "1...e6, 2...c5, 3...Qb6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Bf4 c5 { With this move Black aims for a quick ...Qb6. } 3. e3 Qb6
{ The interesting idea here is to meet Nc3 with ...exd4 to have available ...Bb4+. See the note to next move. However, we refuse to play ball, simply playing... }
4. Nf3
{ Yep, the b-pawn goes and we just get a line that is very similar to our line against the Sharp 5...Qb6 and against the Benoni.   4.Nc3  cxd4  5.exd4   5.Qxd4  Qxb2  6.Rb1  Qa3  7.Nb5  Nc6  Is not fun for White either.  Qxb2  6.Nb5  Bb4+  Is Black's idea, when White is forced to play  7.Ke2  With uncomfortable equality. }
4... Qxb2 { 4...Nf6  This just transposes to the QID lines after.  5.Na3 } 5.
Nbd2
{ Now, whatever Black plays, we'll have transposed into one of our lines against the Benoni. }
5... Nf6 6. Rb1 Qc3
{ 6...Qxa2  Greed isn't good.  7.Nc4  The Queen is in danger of getting trapped.  7...Qa4   7...Be7??  8.Ra1  It's a wrap.  8.Ra1  Qb4+  9.c3  Qxc3+  10.Nfd2  b5  11.Nb6!  Exploiting the pin.  11...Nd5  12.Nxa8  Nxf4  13.exf4 }
7. Rb3
{ I find this to be the most interesting move.   7.Be2  White has options here. Bd3 looks like the most natural move, except White really doesn't want to get hit with ...d5 and ...c4, so if you go Bd3, remember to meet ...d5 with dxc5. Be2 is better.  7...d5  8.O-O  Be7  9.Ne5  Nc6  10.Bb5  Bd7  11.Rb3  Qa5  12.c4=  Again, objectively this is equal, but White has the much easier game. }
7... Qa5 8. dxc5 Qxc5
{ 8...Bxc5??  Would probably claim lots of victims in bullet and blitz.  9.Rb5 }
9. e4 { White wants to push this pawn to e5 like always. } 9... Nc6
{ Not the easiest move to play. Most players would probably prefer developing the kingside to get castled quick.   9...Be7?!  10.e5!  White is already better.  10...Nd5  11.Ne4  Qc7  12.Nd6+  Bxd6  13.exd6  Qd8  14.Bg5  f6  15.Bd2  Black is a pawn up but his position is very very sad. White can play c4 next to kick the knight, develop the bishop and castle.   Another option is  9...d6  10.e5  dxe5  11.Nxe5  Nbd7  12.Bb5  Bd6  not easy to find  13.Ndc4  and the position is engine equal, but clearly much easier for White to play due to his superior activity. }
10. Bd3 Nb4
{ Again, Black has to move the same piece twice.   10...Be7  11.e5  Nd5  12.Ne4  Qa5+  13.Bd2  Ndb4  14.O-O  += }
11. O-O
{ Here we have to give up the bishop since Be2 would allow Black to take on c2. }
11... Nxd3 12. cxd3
{ However, we get a fixed structure and an extra central pawn in return. }
12... Be7 13. d4
{ Now White has two good pawn moves.   13.e5  Nd5  14.Bg5!  Keeping the tempo. Objectively Black might have a small edge, but his position is very hard to play.  14...O-O   14...f6  15.d4  Qc7  16.exf6  Bxf6  17.Ne4+=  15.d4  Qc7  16.Bxe7  Nxe7  17.Ne4=  Objectively perhaps equal, but practically White is preferable. }
13... Qa5 14. d5 { Scream with Freddy... 'Breakthruuuuuu....' } 14... b6
{ Again, not an easy move to play since it allows for d6 and dxe6.   14...exd5  Seems entirely natural.  15.e5!!  Nh5  16.Be3  d6  17.Nd4  dxe5  18.Qxh5  exd4  19.Bg5  Bxg5  20.Qxg5  White has a strong attack.   14...O-O  15.d6  Bd8  16.Ne5  Which side would you rather be :@@EndBracket@@ }
15. dxe6
{ 15.d6  Also an option.  15...Bd8  16.Re1  I don't think even Korhcnoi would choose Black here. }
15... fxe6
{ 15...dxe6  Very natural, but now White can pose Black even more problems with.  16.Nc4 }
16. Bd6 Bxd6 17. Nc4 Bxh2+
{ Not easy!   17...Qa6  18.Nxd6+  Here White just wins on the spot. } 18. Nxh2
