[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. 1...e6, Dutch, Modern etc."]
[Black "1...e6, 2...f5, 4...b6, 6...Bd6 - the GingerGM idea"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Bf4 f5 { This Dutch move has been played in ~18 000 games. } 3. e3
Nf6
{ Black can still opt for either a Stonewall or a Classical here and there's also the Christmas Tree setup with ...e6 & ...g6. }
4. Nf3
{ White has many moves, but I like the standard setup. Here Black has two ways of playing, either with the Nimzo-style ...b6 or with ...Be7 first. }
4... b6
{ The Nimzo move is the second most common, but actually the most played move at master level. It's also the top engine choice. }
5. Be2
{ I think it's practically best to start with this move, rather than the direct c4 which can also be played. The idea is that by playing Be2 and O-O first, we just take away all ...Bb4+ lines. Black already faces a choice here between continuing with ...Bb7 or moving the dark-squared bishop. Do note that if you know your opponent is going to go for GingerGM's radical idea of ...Bd6 then starting with c4 might actually be better as shown in the following variation   5.c4  Bb7  6.Be2  Bd6  From this move order this is quite bad since White can execute his threat immediately.   6...Bb4+  This is the downside of this move order. Not that it's very good for Black or bad for White, but it's at least somewhat tricky and common and it's better to just avoid it with the text.  7.Nfd2!  7.Bxd6  cxd6  8.d5  This is strong even as a pawn sacrifice. For example...  8...exd5   8...O-O  9.Nc3  9.cxd5  Nxd5?  10.Bc4  Nf6  11.Nc3  Black's position is in ruins. }
5... Bb7
{ This gives Black more options so let's take it as the main line.   5...Be7  As always, now ...Nh5 is threatened.  6.O-O  We can simply disregard the threat, like in the main line.  6...Nh5?!  Here this is even dubious because of...  7.d5!  Nxf4  8.exf4  Bf6   8...exd5  9.Qxd5  c6  10.Qb3  Is the idea. White is basically already winning since Black's king is stuck in the centre and the e-file is open.  9.Nc3 }
6. O-O { Again, let's castle first, taking away the ...Bb4+ options. } 6... Bd6
{ This is GingerGM's radical idea and it's been tried around 300 times. The best way to counter it is by aiming to push d5! }
7. c4 { Now White's threatening to take on d6 and push d5. } 7... Bxf4
{ 7...O-O  Allows White to demonstrate his idea.  8.Bxd6  cxd6  9.d5 } 8. exf4
{ White has an iron grip on the e5-square and is simply happy here. } 8... O-O
{ The most common move. 20 games have reached here. } 9. Nc3 Nc6
{ This was given by Simon.   9...Ne4  10.Rc1 } 10. Qc2
{ However, Simon didn't consider this move, steppipng off the d-file and controlling e4. }
10... Ne7 { 10...Nb4  11.Qb3 } 11. Rad1
{ White will play Rfe1 next, with an imposing center. He can then play g3 and start looking to expand on the Queenside with b4 etc. }
