[White "19. 1...e6, Dutch, Modern etc."]
[Black "Veselin Topalov vs. Thomas Paehtz Sr., 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a Classical game where White was the former World Championship contender Veselin Topalov, rated 2738 while Black was rated 2365. }
1... e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. Bf4
{ Topalov plays the London. You don't see this every day. } 3... Nf6 4. e3 b6
{ The Nimzo move. } 5. Be2 { Also our move order. } 5... Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. c4
Ne4 { Black jumps to e4 immediately. } 8. Nfd2
{ White challenges Black's knight with the f-knight, intending Bf3 next. That's why we developed the bishop to e2, after all. }
8... Nxd2 9. Nxd2 O-O 10. Bf3 d5
{ Black doesn't want to exchange his prized bishop.   10...Bxf3  11.Qxf3  Nc6  12.h3  Bf6  13.Bh2  Ne7  14.Rac1 }
11. cxd5 { 11.Rc1 } 11... exd5 12. Rc1 c6 13. Qa4
{ Topalov starts probing.   13.h3  First, was better, enabling to meet ...g5 with Bh2. }
13... b5 { 13...g5  Black had to play this move.  14.Bxb8  Rxb8  15.g3+= } 14.
Qb3 { Setting a trap. } 14... Nd7 { Black falls right into it. } 15. Bxd5+ cxd5
16. Rc7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. 1...e6, Dutch, Modern etc."]
[Black "4...Be7, 8...Ne4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Bf4 f5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7 { The most common move in Lichess. } 5.
h3
{ Taking time to preserve the bishop. White can play in a variety of ways here, including with c4. }
5... O-O 6. Nbd2
{ It's also possible to play with c4 or try the immediate 6. g4 followed by Rg1, but here we will look at the standard setup with Nbd2, Bd3, c3, and only then aiming to open the kingside. }
6... b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. c3
{ White has made all the standard London moves and now can think about where to put the Queen. }
8... Ne4
{ The most common, Nimzo-style move, but it's almost a mistake here due to. }
9. Rg1
{ White could also break immediately with g4, but this preparatory move is even better. }
9... d6
{ If  9...d5  10.g4  Nd7  11.gxf5  exf5  12.Qe2  . For more see the model game Kjetil Lie vs. Karl Oskar Hauge. }
10. g4 Nd7 11. gxf5 exf5 12. Qc2
{ White has a lot of kingside pressure and can hide the king away either by O-O-O or even on e2. }
