[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Bf4 f5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. h3 O-O 6. Nbd2 b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. c3
c5 { This break is Black's best move. } 9. O-O Nc6 10. Qe2 d5
{ Only 7 games have reached here... } 11. Ne5
{ White's best is to jump with the knight and focus on controlling e5, like always in the London. }
11... Nxe5
{ Nothing else is really played. If  11...Ne4  12.Ndf3  and White's knight is better than Black's. }
12. Bxe5 { Given the pawn structure, we obviously capture with the bishop. }
12... Ne4
{ This is the most common move here, so we'll take it as our main line, but it's a blunder.   If  12...Nd7  13.Bf4   If  12...Bd6  which seems best then  13.Ndf3  and White continues controlling  e5  . White has an edge due to his extra central control and it's time to play chess. }
13. Nxe4
{ Believe it or not, this obvious capture hasn't been played in a single game... }
13... fxe4
{ If  13...dxe4  14.Bc4  Bd5  15.dxc5  Bxc5  16.Rad1  and White has a clear edge. }
14. Qg4 Rf7 { Black defends, and now White's bishop is attacked. } 15. Bb5 a6
16. Be2 Bc8 { Defending e6, but now...   If  16...Qd7  stil  17.f3 } 17. f3
{ White opens things up. Remember that the rook is currently defending against mate. }
