[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. 1...e6, Dutch, Modern etc."]
[Black "1...f5, the Dutch: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 { The Dutch Defence. } 2. Bf4
{ My main recommendation is that you actually learn either 2. Nc3 or 2. Bg5. For the former check out my FREE course Destroying the Dutch I. For the latter you'll have to wait for the planned and also FREE Destroying the Dutch II. The London is also good, but perhaps not quite as forcing and straightforward as the above two. But that can also be a plus, in some cases. In any case, for completeness, sake, here we will take a look at the London lines which do not transpose to Delayed Dutch ones that we've already studied. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...g6  This is not good against Nc3 or Bf4 because it's simply an invitation for...  3.h4  Harry to go up the board. White can follow up with Nc3, e3, Qf3, Nge2, O-O-O etc. with usual play. For more, see the lines from the 3...g6 move order.   2...b6  an Accelerated QID-Dutch?  3.e4!  Now it's a Blackmar-Diemer Gambit! This has been played exactly once!  3...fxe4  4.f3  e3   4...exf3?  5.Qxf3!  d5  6.Qg3  White's already winning.  5.Nc3  Nf6  6.Bxe3  e6  7.Qd2  d5  8.g4  Bd6  9.O-O-O  O-O  10.Nh3  White first gets the knight to f4 and then continues with h4. }
3. e3 g6
{ e6 is most common here, but will transpose to our lines. This is second most common, with ~7400 games.   3...d6  ~3900 games.  4.Nf3  g6  Black can try entering the Leningrad setup from this move order, hoping to benefit from White's knight being on f3 already. This is by far the more common move.   4...e6  Second most common. The combination of d6 & e6 is rarely played from the ...e6 move order and we didn't consider it there, but will here.  5.c4  White can, but doesn't have to play h3. In fact, he does best to play c4 here and then continue with Nc3 not minding ...Nxf4.  5...Be7   5...Nh5?!  This immediate bishop-hunting move does nothing for Black here.  6.Nc3  Nxf4  7.exf4  Be7  8.g3  O-O  9.Bg2  6.Nc3  O-O   6...Nh5?!  This obsession is not justified.  7.Be2  Nxf4  8.exf4  O-O  9.O-O  Bf6  10.Re1  7.Be2  Qe8  The most played move in accordance with the Classical Dutch plan, but it doesn't do anything here. White hasn't even fianchettoed.   7...b6  8.O-O  8.O-O  White's got the perfect setup, completely stopping Black from playing ...e5. His long-term plan is a Queenside breakthrough with b4 and c5.  5.Bb5+  Bd7   5...c6  6.Bc4  d5  The Leningrad-Stonewall mongrel is not what Black wants here.  7.Be2  6.c4  Bg7  7.Nc3  O-O  8.c5  White starts with Queenside play and can involve the Queen with tempo after Qb3+. }
4. h4 { Harry goes up the board. } 4... h6
{ Black really has to stop h5, but this leaves behind a very weak pawn at g6.   4...Bg7  5.h5  White intends h6.  5...Nxh5??  You know what to do.  6.Rxh5  gxh5  7.Qxh5+  Kf8  8.Qxf5+  Kg8  9.Nc3 }
5. Nc3 d6
{ 5...d5?  After all the Grünfeld lines you should know the answer to this.  6.Nb5  Na6  7.c4   5...Bg7  A very common move.  6.Qf3  d6  7.Qg3  White hits the weak g-pawn and Black has to move his king to defend it.  7...Kf7  8.O-O-O  White's obviously doing great here. }
6. Qf3
{ The Queen always comes to f3 here. Sometimes it can go to g3 to attack the weak g6 pawn. GM Adrien Demuth who's made a video on the London and written a book about the Dutch considers this good for White in his Dutch book. }
6... Nc6 7. O-O-O
{ This exact position has been reached in only 5 games so the rest is "theoretical", but very interesting. }
7... e6 { 7...Bg7?  Black is oblivious to the danger.  8.Qg3 } 8. e4
{ The best move. White wants to play e5! } 8... Qe7
{ 8...Bg7  9.e5  Nh5  10.Nh3  Qxh4  11.exd6   8...Nxe4  This was played in the only game that reached here.  9.Nxe4  fxe4  10.Qxe4  White hits the g6 pawn and will play Bb5 and d5 next. }
9. exf5 gxf5 10. Bc4 Na5 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. d5 e5 14. Qe2
{ White has a serious advantage. } 14... b5
{ till's suggestion, to sacrifice a pawn for counterplay. } 15. Nxb5 Bg7 16.
Nc3 O-O 17. Bd2 Rab8 18. Qa6 Nb7 19. Be3 Ng4 20. Nge2 Nxe3 21. fxe3 Nc5
{ This is where till stopped. } 22. Qc4
{ White retreats to the natural square and is objectively better though the position is anything but simple and straightforward. }
