1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 d6 { ~3900 games. } 4. Nf3 g6
{ Black can try entering the Leningrad setup from this move order, hoping to benefit from White's knight being on f3 already. This is by far the more common move. }
5. Bb5+ Bd7
{ 5...c6  6.Bc4  d5  The Leningrad-Stonewall mongrel is not what Black wants here.  7.Be2 }
6. c4 Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. c5
{ White starts with Queenside play and can involve the Queen with tempo after Qb3+. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. 1...e6, Dutch, Modern etc."]
[Black "1...f5, 3...d6, 4...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 d6 4. Nf3 e6
{ Second most common. The combination of d6 & e6 is rarely played from the ...e6 move order and we didn't consider it there, but will here. }
5. c4
{ White can, but doesn't have to play h3. In fact, he does best to play c4 here and then continue with Nc3 not minding ...Nxf4. }
5... Be7
{ 5...Nh5?!  This immediate bishop-hunting move does nothing for Black here.  6.Nc3  Nxf4  7.exf4  Be7  8.g3  O-O  9.Bg2 }
6. Nc3 O-O
{ 6...Nh5?!  This obsession is not justified.  7.Be2  Nxf4  8.exf4  O-O  9.O-O  Bf6  10.Re1 }
7. Be2 Qe8
{ The most played move in accordance with the Classical Dutch plan, but it doesn't do anything here. White hasn't even fianchettoed.   7...b6  8.O-O }
8. O-O
{ White's got the perfect setup, completely stopping Black from playing ...e5. His long-term plan is a Queenside breakthrough with b4 and c5. }
*

