[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. 1...e6, Dutch, Modern etc."]
[Black "1...g6, the Modern: Roadmap"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6 { the Modern Defense. } 2. Bf4
{ This is an ambitious repertoire. If you want to be ambitious against the Modern you should really learn one of the main lines with 2. e4. For starters, you could play much like we do against the Pirc with Nc3, Be3, Qd2, O-O-O etc. I also very much like the Bc4 system with   2.e4  Bg7  3.Nf3  d6  4.Bc4  Nf6  5.Qe2  with the idea to force through e5. Another good system is the Austrian, covered by Chessforlife in his excellent anti-Pirc-Modern-Philidor course. However, for completeness sake, here we will see where one can get with sticking to the London, while angling for transpositions to our Pirc lines. }
2... Bg7
{ 2...Nf6  ,   3...d5  , and   3...f5  would all transpose to familiar territory. }
3. Nc3
{ Our typical setup against ...g6. This position has been reached in ~11 000 games. }
3... d6
{ The main move. From now on the fight will be over the  e5  square. White's aim is to prevent Black's ...e5 push at all costs and, if possible push e5 himself.   3...Nf6  and probably also   3...d5  transpose to earlier lines while   3...c5  can be met with either 4. dxc5 or 4. d5, depending on the sort of play you like. Of independent interest is   3...Nc6  4.Nf3  Nxd4  5.Nxd4  e5  6.Be3!  exd4  7.Bxd4 }
4. e4 Nd7
{ The typical Modern move, aiming for ...e5.   4...Nf6  is most common, but it transposes. If   4...Nc6  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.Bb5  a6  7.Bxc6  bxc6  8.e5   4...c6  5.e5   4...a6  5.Nf3  b5  6.Bd3 }
5. Nf3 e5
{ The most common move. If   5...Ngf6  6.Qd2  transposes to a Pirc-like line and if   5...c5  6.e5!  cxd4  7.Qxd4  dxe5  8.Nxe5!  Ngf6  9.O-O-O }
6. Nxe5 { What? For more, see the trainable line! } *

