[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. 1...e6, Dutch, Modern etc."]
[Black "1...Nf6 & 2...c6: Anti-London Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ 1...c6  Black can start with this move if they're a Caro player who prefers to get the Caro in every game. However, even if you don't play e4, they normally play ...d5 next. The only other thing that is sometimes tried is ...d6 with the idea of ...g5, aiming for Bxg5 and ...Qa5+, picking up the bishop.  2.Bf4  d6  3.Nd2!  This move just undercuts all ...Qb6 and ...g5 ideas and supports e4 next, taking the center. }
2. Bf4 c6
{ This sort of idea has been suggested by Lichess users SirDillyMoves and Water_Flame in a Lichess study called 'Anti-London Gambit'. Black wants to play ...g5 followed by ...Qb6. }
3. Nf3 { Just develop the knight and stop ...g5. } 3... d6
{ This is what the study recommends. Black wants to play ...Bg4 next.   3...Qb6  This would be like Colovic's Slav line without Black yet committing to d5. It's hard to see how much they can benefit from ...d6 though.  4.Qc1  d6  5.a4  Immediately going for the Queen, aiming to gain useful queenside space. This position has been reached exactly once.  5...a5   5...Bf5  6.a5  Qd8  7.Nbd2   5...Bg4  6.a5  Qc7  7.Nbd2 }
4. c4
{ The study authors don't consider this ambitious and principled move, overtaking the center. This has been played ~300 times. White will just play Nc3 and even e4, if allowed. }
4... Bg4
{ Most common. However, if Black wants to give up the bishop pair they're free to do so.   4...g6  Second most common.  5.Nc3  Bg7  6.e4  This is now like a weird King's Indian. White can continue with h3, Qc2, Be2 or Bd3, and choose which side to castle on.   4...Bf5  The engine favorite, stopping e4, but it's very rare.  5.Nc3  Nbd7  6.e3  Qb6  7.Qc1  h6  8.h3  e6  9.Be2  Be7  10.O-O  White hasa comfortable edge. }
5. Nc3 Nbd7 6. h3 Bxf3 7. exf3 e5
{ This is what Black mostly tries. If   7...g6  8.Be2  Bg7  9.O-O  O-O  10.Be3  and White has a safe edge. }
8. Be3 Be7 { If   8...exd4  9.Qxd4 } 9. Qc2
{ White keeps the bishop flexible and intends a quick Rd1. } 9... O-O
{ If   9...exd4  10.Bxd4 } 10. Rd1
{ White has a safe edge and will develop the bishop and castle next. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. 1...e6, Dutch, Modern etc."]
[Black "1...b6: Owen Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 b6 { The Owen Defense. } 2. e4
{ 2. Bf4 can be played, but here there is no reason not to simply take over the center. }
2... Bb7 3. Bd3 { The key starting move, defending the e-pawn. } 3... Nf6
{ The main move, attacking the e-pawn.   3...f5  This gambit doesn't work neither here nor in the Nimzo-Larsen. White has to just remember a few things.  4.exf5  Take the pawn.  4...Bxg2  5.Qh5+  Check.  5...g6  6.fxg6  Bg7  Black's only move.   6...Nf6  7.gxh7+  Nxh5  8.Bg6  7.gxh7+  Take the pawn with check.  7...Kf8  8.Nf3  The first non-obvious move. The point is to play Ne5. Nh3 works as well.  8...Nf6   8...Bxh1  9.Ne5  Bxe5  10.dxe5  Mate is coming soon.  9.Qg6  Bxf3  Black takes the knight, use your rook.   9...Bxh1  Black takes the rook.  10.Bh6  Meet Bxh1 with Bh6.  10...Rxh7  11.Ng5  Bxh6  12.Nxh7+  Nxh7  13.Qxh6+  Kf7  14.Qxh7+  Ke6  15.Qg6+  Kd5  16.Nc3+  Kxd4  17.Qg5  b5  18.Qe3  10.Rg1  Meet Bxf3 with Rg1 and Qg3.  10...Rxh7  11.Qg3  Be4  12.Bxe4  Nxe4  13.Qf3+   3...e6  4.Nf3  Will likely transpose.   3...g6  Double Fianchetto  4.c4  f4 can also be played, but I like this setup suggested by Chessforlife.  4...Bg7  5.Ne2!  Nc6   5...e6  Black plays the Hippo with ...e6, ...Ne7, ...d6, ...Nd7, ...a6, ...h6 etc.  6.Nbc3  Ne7  7.h4  Harry goes.  7...d6  8.h5  Nd7  9.Be3  c5  10.Bc2  White will continue with Qd2, O-O-O, and Ba4.  6.Be3  Nb4  7.Nbc3  Prioritizing development and center over the bishop pair.  7...Nxd3+  8.Qxd3  e6  9.O-O-O  d6  10.h4 }
4. Qe2
{ I've always liked this simple and logical system but White has several good options here. I'm going to give one line only. For the rest I refer you to my friend and co-author Chessforlife's excellent FREE course Beating ...b6 Defenses. }
4... e6
{ 4...Nc6  This prepares ...e5.  5.c3  We secure the center and prevent ...Nb4.  5...e5  6.Nf3  exd4   6...d6  7.O-O  Be7  8.d5  Nb8  9.c4  Nbd7  10.Nc3  O-O  11.Be3  a5  12.Nd2  7.O-O  White can sacrifice a pawn here.  7...dxc3  8.Nxc3  d6  9.Bb5  a6  10.Bxc6+  Bxc6  11.e5 }
5. Nf3 d5
{ 5...c5  6.d5!?  exd5  7.exd5+  Qe7  8.c4  Qxe2+  9.Kxe2  b5  10.b3 } 6. e5
Nfd7 { 6...Ne4  7.Nbd2  Nxd2  8.Bxd2  Nc6  9.O-O } 7. O-O
{ Simple chess. Ng5 can also be played here with the idea of following up with Qg4. }
7... c5 8. c4
{ Black's pieces are all on the back rank so this is a good moment for White to force matters.   8.c3  Is entirely natural and leads to less forcing play than c4. }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bc5 10. Nf3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Nc6 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Bf4
{ White can continue with Rfd1 and Ne4, targeting the d6 square. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. 1...e6, Dutch, Modern etc."]
[Black "1...Nc6?!: Dark Knight"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nc6 { Yeah, whatever. It's been played 189 000x though. } 2. d5
{ If Black wants us to give the whole center, we should just grab it. This is only the third most popular move, with ~37 000 games. White could also just aim for a transposition to London vs. Chigorin with Nf3, followed by Bf4.   2.Nf3  d5   2...d6  Independent, but not dangerous.  3.c4  3.Bf4  Just transposes. }
2... Ne5
{ ~34 000 games.   2...Nb4  What-eeeeeeeee-ver.  3.e4  Just disregaard the jumper.  3...c6   3...a5  4.Nc3  4.c4   2...Nb8  Even more whatever.  3.e4  d6  Most common.   3...e6  4.Nc3  4.c4  Just take the center and play chess. }
3. f4 { This is the correct move order, kicking the knight straight away. }
3... Ng6 4. e4 { The CENTER! 8200 games have reached here. } 4... e5
{ The engine choice and the most common move with ~6300 games.   4...e6  Avrukh's main line ~2100 games.  5.dxe6  dxe6   5...fxe6  6.h4!  Again, transposes to below.  6.Qxd8+  Kxd8  7.Bd2  Best move and an improvement over Avrukh's Nf3. It transposes to below so for more, see there. }
5. dxe6 dxe6
{ 5...fxe6  The more common, but worse move.  6.h4!  Going for the knight, immediately and improving on Avrukh's preparatory Nf3.  6...Nxh4  Most common.   6...Bc5  7.h5   6...Bb4+  7.Nc3  d5  8.h5  7.Qg4  Ng6  8.Rxh7  Qf6  9.Rxh8  Nxh8  10.Nc3  White is just winning. }
6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Bd2
{ Best move, but it's been played only twice. White simply avoids ...Bb4 and asks Black to find a move, intending to continue with Nc3 and O-O-O. }
7... Nf6
{ 7...Bd7  8.Nc3  Bd6  9.g3  e5  10.f5  N6e7  11.Nf3  White's clearly a lot better in this Queenless middlegame due to his space, development, and better king. }
8. Nc3 Bb4 { Natural.   8...Bc5  9.Nf3 } 9. O-O-O
{ This is actually best. Who cares about the pawn... } 9... Ke7
{ 9...Bd7  10.Nf3  Bxc3  11.Bxc3  Nxe4  12.Bxg7  Rg8  13.Bd4  Nxf4  14.g3  Ng6  15.Bd3  Nd6  16.Ng5   9...Bxc3  10.Bxc3+  Ke7  11.Bb4+  Ke8  12.Nh3 }
10. Bd3 Bxc3 11. bxc3 Ng4 12. Rf1 b6 13. Nf3 Bb7 14. Rhg1
{ A good place to stop. White's clearly better with his two bishops, center, and a safer king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. 1...e6, Dutch, Modern etc."]
[Black "1...b5?!: Polish Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 b5
{ The Polish Defense. This is even worse than the Owen. Still, it's been played ~39 000x. }
2. e4 Bb7 3. Nd2
{ The key move, defending the pawn and enabling us to play c3. The games have dropped to ~1450. }
3... a6 { Black defends the pawn. } 4. a4
{ The best move.   4.Ngf3  Fairly standard and also good.  4...e6  5.Bd3  is still best, but White can also play wtihout it.  5...c5  6.c3  Nf6   6...d6  7.O-O  Nf6  8.a4  7.e5  Nd5  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Ne4  Be7  10.O-O  ± }
4... b4
{ Black gains nothing by taking.   4...bxa4  5.Bd3  Starting with the bishop is more flexible since it always comes here and in some lines Nh3 is an idea.  5...e6  6.Qe2  d5  7.Ngf3  c5  8.exd5  Bxd5  9.c4  Bxf3  10.Nxf3  cxd4  11.O-O  Nf6  12.Bc2  White will play Ba4+ next with a winning advantage. }
5. Bd3 { Again, starting with the bishop. } 5... e6 6. Ngf3
{ The games have dropped to 80 and White scores massively from here. } 6... Nf6
{ Most common.   6...c5  Second most common.  7.O-O  cxd4  8.Nxd4  Nf6   8...Qc7  For some reason, this is the most frequently played move here.  9.Re1+-  9.e5  Nd5  10.Nc4  Nc6  11.Nb3  Avoiding trades.  11...Qc7  12.Re1  Nb6  No game has reached here.  13.Nd6+  Bxd6  14.exd6  Qxd6  15.Qg4 }
7. e5 { Attacking the knight and vacating e4. } 7... Nd5 8. Ne4
{ Only 13 games have reached here. We play Ne4 with the idea of continuing with c4 to have b3 protected after ...bxc3, bxc3. }
8... Be7 9. c4
{ This has been played only once. White opens the b-file to his benefit. } 9...
bxc3 10. bxc3 O-O
{ Natural move.   10...a5  Making room for ...Ba6. This will not be easy to find.  11.O-O  Ba6  12.Bxa6  Nxa6  13.Nfg5  h6  14.Nh3  d6  15.Qg4+- }
11. Rb1
{ Both this move and O-O are basically winning for White. The difference in central space and piece activity is immense and Black's king is basically devoid of any defenders. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. 1...e6, Dutch, Modern etc."]
[Black "1...e5?: Englund Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5
{ the Englund Gambit. This line is frequently played in Bullet @@StartBracket@@sometimes as a premove@@EndBracket@@, but is also frequent online at other time controls. White just needs to know a few things. I give one trainable line here and for the rest, you can check out InfiniteFlash's FREE Beat Bad & Pesky Openings or pick up my in-depth and super CHEAP  (1.99$)  Ending the Englund Gambit, from which the lines below are drawn. }
2. dxe5 Nc6
{ 2...d6  With these early pawn moves it's important to remember to not take and help Black develop, but just develop yourself.  3.Nf3  Nc6  4.Bg5  Qd7   4...Be7  5.Bxe7  Ngxe7  6.exd6  cxd6  5.exd6  Bxd6  6.Nc3  White's just a pawn up, but many people consider this good enough for Black in bullet etc.   2...f6  3.e4  Nc6  4.Nf3  fxe5  5.Bc4  Italian Game anyone. White will play Ng5 with an advantage. }
3. Nf3 Qe7
{ This is the actual Englund Gambit.   3...Nge7  This move is very rare, but perhaps best in the whole complex.  4.Bf4  Ng6  5.Bg3  Qe7  6.Nc3  Ncxe5  7.Nxe5  Nxe5  8.e4  d6  9.Nd5  Qd8  10.Qd4  f6  11.f4  Wherever Black puts the knight White will go O-O-O.   3...Bc5  Also very rare.  4.Bf4  Same move as above.  4...Nge7  5.e3  O-O  6.Nc3  Ng6  7.Bg3  Re8  8.Bd3  We can just give the pawn back.  8...Ngxe5  9.Nxe5  Nxe5  10.Bxh7+  Kxh7  11.Qh5+  Kg8  12.Bxe5  d6  13.O-O-O  White's up a pawn and the Black king is a target. }
4. Bg5
{ Instead of the standard Bf4 I prefer this move, attacking the Queen. Incidentally, this also prevents the bishop ever being taken after Qb4+. }
4... Qb4+ 5. Nc3 Qxb2 6. Bd2
{ The bishop drops back. Here Black mostly plays ...Bb4, but White should also know how to meet ...Nb4. }
6... Bb4
{ 6...Nb4  7.Nd4  If Black moves the same piece twice, so can White.  7...c6   7...c5  8.Rb1  Qa3  9.Ndb5  Qa5  10.a3  8.e4  Bc5  9.Rb1  Qa3  10.Rb3  Qa5  11.Nf5  Bf8  12.f4 }
7. Rb1 Qa3
{ 7...Qxc3  The so-called Aman Gambit after Aman Hambleton's ample use of it to troll people.  8.Bxc3  Bxc3+  9.Nd2  Bxe5  10.g3  Nf6  11.Bg2  O-O  12.c4  Black's just lost. }
8. Nd5 { Attacking both the bishop and c7. } 8... Bxd2+
{ 8...Ba5  9.Rb5  Rb8   9...Bb6  10.Rxb6  cxb6  11.Nc7+  10.Rxa5  Nxa5  11.Bb4  Qxa2  12.Nxc7+  Kd8  13.Nd5  Nc6  14.Bd6 }
9. Qxd2 Qxa2 10. Rd1 Kd8 11. Ng5 Nh6 12. e6 fxe6
{ An obvious way to go wrong.   12...d6  13.exf7  White's positionally winning. }
13. Nxe6+ dxe6 14. Nc3+ *

