[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Wei Yi vs. Vladimir Malakhov, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This game was played in the World Rapid Championship in Doha. White was rated 2713, Black 2707. }
1... d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nd2 cxd4 5. exd4 Bg4 6. Ngf3 Nc6 7. c3 e6 8. Qb3
Qc8 9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. Bxe5
{ This was all covered in our first trainable line in the Exchange Caro-Kann chapter. Seehere. However, our suggested move is  12.dxe5  . }
12... Nd7 { 12...Bh5  was perhaps better. } 13. Bf4 { White just retreats. }
13... Nb6
{ This is somewhat strange since it gets in the way of Black's main idea: the minority attack. }
14. a4
{ As always, knights on b3/b6 and g3/g6 are 'Rook-pawn-attractors'. White simply intends to kick the knight with a5 and then push a6 to weaken Black's queenside. }
14... Bf5
{ Black challenges White's bishop, but it's not sure what's to be gained from it. }
15. Bxf5 exf5 16. Rfe1
{ White just benefits from the opening of the e-file and now develops with tempo. }
16... Qd7
{ Defending the bishop and connecting rooks, but now a5 is coming.   16...Re8  17.a5  Nc4  18.Nxc4  dxc4  19.Qa4  White is increasing the pressure, since now any bishop-moves can be met with Rxe8 and Qxc4.  19...h6  20.d5  Aiming to make the bishop move and go for the aforementioned sequence. }
17. a5 Nc8 { Black gets pushed back since ...Nc4 here would just drop a pawn. }
18. Nf3 { The knight goes for e5. } 18... f6 { Controlling e5. } 19. c4
{ White pushes the action, but he could've also just doubled on the open e-file. }
19... Rd8
{ 19...dxc4  20.Qxc4+  Kh8  21.Rac1  White's just completely dominating } 20.
a6
{ Consistent, but c5 was also an option, completely locking down Black's b-pawn and then intending to exchange Queens via a4.   20.c5 }
20... b6 21. c5 g5
{ 21...bxc5  Black can't really take the pawn because now the a-pawn shines.  22.Qb7  Nd6  23.Qxd7  Rxd7  24.Rxe7  Rxe7  25.Bxd6 }
22. c6 { White continues pushing. } 22... Qxc6 23. Rac1 Qe8 24. Bc7 Rd7 25. Qb5
{ Black is completely tied up with several pins. } 25... Nd6
{ This drops the d-pawn. } 26. Qxd5+ Kg7 { 26...Nf7  27.Qxf5 } 27. Bxd6 Rad8
{ 27...Rxd6  28.Rxe7+  Qxe7  29.Qxa8 } 28. Qe6
{ White's a piece up and Black resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Daniel Naroditsky vs. Anton Smirnov, 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a rapid game in the PRO Chess League. White was rated 2616, Black was rated 2569. }
1... d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 cxd4 7. exd4 Nh5 8. Be3
Bd6 9. Ne5 g6 10. g4 Nf6
{ This was all covered in the first So System line in the Exchange Caro-Kann chapter. Seehere, where we consider the main retreat  10...Ng7  . The game retreat just gives White everything he wants after the natural... }
11. f4
{ ...clamping down on e5.   11.g5  The engines also like this push.  11...Bxe5  12.dxe5  Nh5  13.Be2  Ng7   13...Nxe5  14.f4  Nc6  15.Bxh5  gxh5  16.Qxh5  White has a serious advantage.  14.h4  Nf5  15.Bf4+= }
11... Nd7 12. Qf3
{ 12.Qe2  Also a good move, with the idea  12...f6  13.Nd3  e5  14.fxe5  fxe5  15.Bg2  e4  16.Bxe4  Obviously a good sacrifice.  16...dxe4  17.Nxe4  Hitting the bishop.  17...Nf6  18.Nxd6+  Qxd6  19.Bg5+  White will have a tremendous attacking position for essentially a pawn. Here's a sample continuation.  19...Ne7  20.O-O  O-O  21.Rae1  Ned5  22.Ne5  b5  23.Qg2  Rb8  24.Bh6  Re8  25.g5  Nh5  26.Nf7! }
12... f6 13. Nxd7 { 13.Nd3  Retreating was better. } 13... Bxd7 14. Bd3
{ The bishop could here get hit with ...e5-...e4   14.O-O-O } 14... Qe7
{ 14...Qc7= } 15. O-O-O O-O-O 16. Kb1
{ Completing castling, but this might've been too slow.   16.f5!?  gxf5  17.gxf5  e5  18.Qxd5 }
16... e5 17. fxe5 fxe5 18. Qxd5
{ Creating a mess on the board. Objectively Black might be better, but White's position is easier to play. }
18... Bxg4 19. Rde1 { 19.Rc1 } 19... Be6 20. Qg2 Qf7 21. a3
{ Defending the a-pawn and avoiding simplifications after ...Bxa2+, Ka1 and ...Qd5. }
21... exd4 22. cxd4 Bd5
{ This is the mistake, after which evaluation swings in White's favour. } 23.
Ne4 { Naroditsky grabs his chance. } 23... Kb8
{ Escapes the check, but walks into the pin.   23...Bc7   23...Bxe4  24.Bxe4  Kb8  25.Bxc6  bxc6  26.Qxc6  White just up a pawn and Black is forced to simplify so as not to be in trouble. }
24. Nxd6 Rxd6 25. Qg3 { Pin it and win it. } 25... Rd8 26. Rhf1 Qc7 27. Bf4 a6
28. Re8 { Ouchtown! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Eric Rosen vs. Simen Agdestein, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a Classical game. The famous Youtuber, Twitch streamer and London-fan IM Eric Rosen was rated 2361 while his opponent, the legendary Norwegian GM Simen Agdestein who was a one-time coach of Carlsen and also a professional footballer, was rated 2604. }
1... d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. exd4 Qb6
{ These sorts of lines were covered inChapter 5 where we learned that ...Qb6 before the 5th move is basically a mistake. }
6. Nc3
{ Rosen reacts well and thematically, but objectively strongest might be  6.Nbd2  sacrificing the b-pawn with a likely continuation like  6...Qxb2  7.Rb1  Qc3  8.Rb3  Qa5  9.Bb5+  Bd7  10.c4  with an edge to White. }
6... Bd7
{ 6...Qxb2  7.Nb5  Na6  8.Rb1  Qxa2  9.Ra1  Qb2  10.Bd3  The Black Queen can't survive this after O-O, Qe2 and Rfb1. }
7. Ne5 { 7.Bd3 } 7... a6 { 7...Nc6?!  8.Nxd7  Nxd7   8...Kxd7  9.Nb5  9.Nxd5 }
8. Qf3 e6 9. O-O-O Nc6 10. Nxc6 { 10.g4 } 10... Bxc6 11. g4 Qa5 12. Kb1
{ King safety! } 12... b5 13. Bd3 b4 14. Ne2 Ne4 15. Ng3 Nc3+
{ Agdestein sacrifices a piece, but it doesn't lead anywhere. } 16. bxc3 bxc3
17. Ka1 Ba3 18. Rb1 Bb2+ 19. Rxb2 cxb2+ 20. Kb1
{ Material is equal, but White's king is very safe behind the black b-pawn and the minor pieces are much stronger. }
20... O-O 21. g5 { 21.Nh5  Bb5  22.Bd6  Rfd8  23.Bxh7+  Kxh7  24.Qxf7 } 21...
f5
{ The decisive mistake, though White was much better anyway.   21...Bb5  22.Bd6  Rfc8  23.Bc5 }
22. gxf6 Rxf6 23. Nh5 Rf7 24. Rg1 Bb5 25. Nxg7 { 25.Bxh7+  Kxh7  26.Qh3 } 25...
Rxg7 26. Rxg7+ Kxg7 27. Be5+ Kg8 28. Bxh7+
{ White mates with the London bishop after ...Kxh7 and Qf7+, ... Kh6, Bf4# } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Arkadij Naiditsch vs. Peter Wells, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a Classical game between the super-GM Naiditsch, rated 2702, and the English GM and prolific author Peter Wells, rated 2447. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8.
Bb5 e6 9. O-O Qxc5 10. c4 Be7 11. Nb3 Qa3 12. Ne5
{ This was all covered in the Sharp 5...Qb6 chapter. Seehere. However, our recommendation and the better move is  12.Nbd4  . Still, even after the text, White is better. }
12... a6 { This is a mistake. } 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Nxc6
{ Naiditsch just grabs the pawn. } 14... Bd7 15. Nxe7
{ Getting rid of Black's bishop pair. White's activity makes it clear that he's already much better. }
15... Qxe7 16. Be5
{ 16.Qd4  O-O  17.c5  Is an interesting idea as well, simply using the passed pawn. }
16... O-O 17. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Another mistake that is swiftly punished by Naiditsch. White is threatening Bd6. }
18. e4 f6 { 18...Nf6  19.Bd6 } 19. Bd4
{ Now White is threatening Bc5, picking up the exchange. } 19... Nf4 20. Bc5
{ Naiditsch picks up the exchange. } 20... Qf7 21. Bxf8 Rxf8 22. Re1 e5 23. Nc5
{ White tries to simplify. } 23... Bh3
{ Black tries to drum up counterplay, but this is not going to work against a super GM. }
24. Rb7 Qxa2 25. gxh3 Nxh3+ 26. Kg2 Nf4+ { 26...Qxf2+  27.Kxh3 } 27. Kh1 Qxf2
28. Qb3+ { White is precise. } 28... Kh8 29. Qg3
{ Threatening mate in 1 and getting the Queens off, with a won game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Maaike Keetman vs. Rolf Corstjens, 2013"]
[Result "*"]

{ Annotations by WFM Maaike Keetman.  This game was played years ago, in a national youth championship. I had played my opponent many times before and, as I'm a 1.e4 player, we would usually end up in a theoretical battle in the French. I didn't have great results against him there, so I wanted to switch things up. At some point, I remembered that one of my club mates would always play 1. d4 and 2. Bf4 and then opponents would often be out of book already, when he would win with a quick mating attack. That seemed perfect, so I went for 1.d4 for the first time in my life! }
1. d4 e6
{ After 1. d4 my opponent looked at me very puzzled. Did I just pick up the wrong pawn? He decided to give me another chance to play e4 when we would transpose to the French again. }
2. Bf4
{ Of course I was not tempted to go e4 after all, and proceeded with my plan! This was when my opponent looked visibly upset already, as he would usually not play ...e6 against 1. d4 }
2... d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ IndrekR: We play Nd2 here, in order to counteract early ...e6-tricks by Black. }
4... Be7 5. Nbd2
{ I'll admit that my knowledge was very limited, so my move order is probably not optimal. All I knew was to put my pawns on e3 and c3, to develop my knights, put my bishop on d3 and then get a knight on e5 to start the attack. I assume his knowledge was equally limited, as he played quite timidly.  IndrekR: Nbd2 is exactly correct here. There is no need to play c3 before Black goes ...c5, and controlling e4 is important. }
5... O-O 6. Bd3 Nbd7
{ Continuing the timid path.   6...c5  7.c3  Nc6  This seems a more harmonious set-up for Black and would lead to a transposition to the lines in the Classical Setup with ...Be7 chapter. }
7. Ne5 c5 8. c3 Qb6
{ 8...Nxe5  9.dxe5  Nd7  10.h4  f5  11.g4  Qc7  12.Nf3  fxg4  13.Ng5  Bxg5  14.hxg5  g6  15.Qxg4  Nxe5  16.Bxe5  Qxe5  17.Rh6 }
9. Rb1 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7
{ Now there is a transposition to a course position after all, although the moves ...Qb6 and Rb1 are included. This is only to White's advantage, as the queen is further away from defending the king. }
11. h4
{ Launching the attack. Although it seems like Black has played normal moves, he is actually in trouble already. }
11... f6
{ 11...f5  Black could definitely have considered this defensive move.  12.Nf3!?  This seems best here, bringing a piece closer to the black king. g4 can be played next after all, when the pawn on e5 is not hanging.   12.g4  There is an important subtlety here: as the rook is on b1 already, White has lost the right to castle long! This means that it is not smart to play as in this variation, because there is no option to castle at the end:  12...Qc7  13.Nf3  fxg4  14.Ng5  Bxg5  15.hxg5  g6  16.Qxg4  Nxe5  17.Bxe5  Qxe5  18.Rh6  The same moves as before, but there is no O-O-O next, so it's not as strong here.  12...Rf7  A common way to defend: Black tries to get the knight to f8.   12...Qc7  Now 13. g4 would transpose to 12. g4 which is undesirable, but this push can be slowly prepared. Black lacks active plans so there is no need to rush.  13.h5  Rf7  14.Rg1  g4 is coming and White is doing well.  13.h5  The attack can be continued with h6 and for example Bg5, while Black can only sit and wait. }
12. Qh5
{ IndrekR: Other than the placement of Rb1 and ...Qb6, the position is the same as inthis line. }
12... g6
{ I'm not sure what my opponent missed here, as the refutation is not hard to find.   12...f5  The only move to stay in the game when it is not that easy for White. I could try  13.g4  But Black has some good defensive resources:  13...Rf7  14.gxf5  exf5  15.Bxf5  Nf8  White has won a pawn, but the game is not over. If the bishop takes on c8, Black recaptures and then suddenly all his pieces are working together, giving him compensation for the pawn.  16.Bd3  Keeping bishops seems best, but also here Black has some compensation. }
13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. Qxg6+ Kh8 15. Rh3 Nxe5 16. Qh5+
{ And my opponent resigned. My opening strategy worked to perfection! The London is definitely a good @@StartBracket@@surprise@@EndBracket@@ weapon for White and against unprepared opponents, you can score quick wins like this one. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Ray Robson vs. Alexander Onischuk, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 { This was a Classical game. White was rated 2663, Black 2664. } 1...
Nf6 2. d4 e6 3. Bf4
{ Only after ...e6 was played does Robson go for the London, here. } 3... d5 4.
e3 c5 5. c3 Nc6 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. Bg3 Qe7
{ Onischuk goes for an early ...Qe7. This is a move that is rarely seen at any level. }
8. Ne5
{ This was covered in Classical Setup 8...Bd6, Sidelines chapter. Our move is  8.Bb5  but play is quite similar. }
8... Bxe5 { Natural, but a mistake. } 9. dxe5 Nd7 10. Bb5
{ A practical choice. } 10... a6 11. Bxc6 { White creates doubled c-pawns. }
11... bxc6 12. Qa4 { This should look familiar. } 12... Bb7 13. Bh4 f6
{ Basically forced.   13...Qf8  14.Qa5   14.f4  Rc8   14...Nxe5?  15.Qc7  15.O-O }
14. exf6 gxf6 15. c4 Rg8 16. O-O h5 17. Qd1
{ This is not very logical.   17.f3  Creating space for the bishop and intending Bg3. }
17... Rg4 18. Bg3 Qh7 19. Rc1 a5 { 19...e5 } 20. Re1 Ba6 21. cxd5 cxd5 22. e4
d4
{ Another mistake and now Robson wins by attacking the light squares with the Queen. }
23. Qa4 { Threatening Qxa5 and Qc6. } 23... Bb7 24. Qb3
{ Hitting the bishop and the e-pawn. The game is over. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Anish Giri vs. Wesley So, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a 1+1 Bullet game, yes :@@EndBracket@@ However, both Super-GMs play the opening very accurately here and follow our course line. }
1... d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 c5 5. c3 Nc6 6. Nbd2 Nh5 7. Bg5 f6 8. Bh4 g6
9. Bd3 cxd4 10. cxd4 Be7
{ This is Black's main move at GM level and it was covered in the chapter Classical Setup with 6... Nh5!?. Seehere. }
11. O-O Bd7 12. a3 O-O 13. Rc1 Rc8 14. Nb1
{ An interesting idea of Giri's, aiming to relocate the knight to the more active square c3, where it belongs in the Exchange Slav structures. }
14... Qb6 15. Qe2 Na5 16. Nc3 { The knight completes its relocation. } 16...
Nc4 { Strong knights on c4/c5 and f4/f5 never survive long in GM games. } 17.
Bxc4 Rxc4 18. e4
{ This doesn't quote work.   18.Ne5!  This was the move that would've lead to an advantage. At the minimum, White picks up the bishop pair.  18...Rc7   18...fxe5  19.Bxe7  Re8  20.Bc5  19.Nxd7  Rxd7  20.Na4 }
18... dxe4
{ After this it's objectively better for Black, but White still comes out on top eventually. }
19. Qxc4 exf3 20. d5 fxg2 21. Rfe1 Rc8 22. Qe4 e5 23. d6 Bxd6 { 23...Qxd6 } 24.
Nd5 { Now White starts slowly getting back into the game. } 24... Qxb2 25.
Rxc8+ Bxc8 26. Nxf6+ { Here's a pawn and the engines show equality. } 26...
Nxf6 27. Bxf6 Be6
{ After this White's just better since he can exchange everything and then the rook will be strong and White can pick up the g-pawn. }
28. Bxe5 Bxe5 29. Qxe5 Qxe5 30. Rxe5 Kf7 31. Kxg2
{ Now White's  better and Giri converts without much difficulty by activating his king and creating a passed pawn on the kingside }
31... Kf6 32. f4 Bd7 33. Kf2 Bc6 34. Ke3 a6 35. h4 h6 36. Kd4 Bf3 37. Kc5 Bc6
38. Kd6 Kf7 39. f5 g5 40. hxg5 hxg5 41. Re6 g4 42. Rg6 g3 43. Ke5 g2 44. Rg5 b5
45. f6 a5 46. Rg7+ Kf8 47. Ke6 b4 48. axb4 axb4 49. Rf7+ Kg8 50. Rg7+ Kf8 51.
Rf7+ Ke8 52. Rg7 Kf8 53. Rg3 b3 54. f7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Akiba Rubinstein vs. Karel Treybal, 1912"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Nbd2
{ Rubinstein was one of the originators of this way of playing, allowing the doubling of the f-pawns. This was recommended in Chapter 11 against Black's move order with an early ...e6. }
5... O-O 6. Bd3
{ Our recommendation is to keep this bishop back to avoid losing a tempo after the exchange with ...b6 and ...Ba6! }
6... c5 7. c3 Bxf4 { Black captures on f4 slightly later. } 8. exf4 cxd4 9.
Nxd4
{ It's very thematic to capture on d4 with a piece so as not to get an isolated pawn. }
9... Nc6 10. N2f3 Qd6 11. Qd2
{ White develops the Queen and protects the f-pawn. } 11... a6
{ 11...Nxd4  12.Nxd4  e5  13.fxe5  Qxe5+ } 12. O-O Bd7 13. Rfe1 Rad8 14. Re2
{ Rubinstein just doubles and later triples on the half-open e-file. } 14...
Nh5 { This just wastes time. } 15. g3
{ The typical kingside structure is reached. } 15... g6 16. Kg2 Bc8
{ 16...Nf6 } 17. h4 { 17.Rae1 } 17... f6
{ Black really wants ...e5, but it's not going to happen. } 18. Rae1 Ng7 19.
Re3
{ 19.h5!  This was already possible since Black can't forsake the e6-pawn. }
19... Rfe8 20. Qe2 { Rubinstein has a gun of his own. } 20... Kf7 21. a3 Re7
22. Bb1
{ The bishop switches the diagonal.   22.h5  Nxh5  23.f5  gxf5  24.Ng5+ } 22...
Rde8 23. Ba2 Kf8 24. Qd2 { ! } 24... e5 { This just loses immediately. } 25.
Nxc6 bxc6 26. fxe5 fxe5 27. Rxe5 { White wins a pawn. } 27... Bf5
{ Black now realized he can't recapture with ...Rxe5 due to Qf4+.   27...Rxe5  28.Qf4+ }
28. Qf4 Rxe5 29. Rxe5 Rxe5 30. Qxe5 Qd7 31. Ng5
{ 31.Qf6+  Qf7  32.Qd6+  Qe7  33.Qxc6 } 31... Ne8 32. Qh8+ Ke7 33. Qxh7+ Kd6
34. Qxd7+ Kxd7 35. Kf3
{ White is up 2 pawns and has an easy kingside breakthrough so the game is over. }
35... Nf6 36. Kf4 c5 37. f3 Kc6 38. g4 Bc2 39. Ke3 c4 40. Kd2 Bd3 41. Ne6 Nd7
42. Nf4 Ne5 43. Nxd3 cxd3 { 43...Nxd3  44.h5 } 44. h5 { The h-pawn runs. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Magnus Carlsen vs. Ding Liren, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 { This was a Rapid game in the MC Chess Tour. } 1... Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4
c5 4. e3 e6 5. c3
{ With ...e6 played, it's fine to combine Nf3 with c3 since Black can't develop the light-squared bishop to f5 anymore. Still, I would probably prefer Nbd2 here. }
5... Bd6 6. Nbd2
{ Carlsen follows Rubinstein. However, the best move might be 6  Bb5+!  forcing  6...Nc6  and then White could calmly retreat with  7.Bg3  . These sorts of positions were covered in the Early ...e6: No Retreat! chapter and the current line is most similar to this one. }
6... cxd4 7. Bxd6
{ A complete surprise. Carlsen sacrifices a pawn for the two bishops. } 7...
dxe3 { Ding grabs another pawn, but now... } 8. Ba3
{ White gets a strong unopposed dark-squared bishop for a pawn and Black won't be able to castle kingside. }
8... exd2+ 9. Qxd2 Nc6 { Intending ...Ne7 and ...O-O. } 10. Qg5
{ Striking, while the iron is hot. } 10... Rg8
{ Ding avoids ...g6, weakening the dark squares, but now there's no chance of castling kingside ever. }
11. Bd3 h6 12. Qe3 Qb6 { Understandably, Ding wants to trade queens. } 13. Qe2
Bd7 14. O-O O-O-O 15. b4 { White wants to chase away the knight and play Ne5. }
15... Kb8 16. b5 Na5 17. Ne5 Be8 { The rooks get disconnected. } 18. Bb4
{ Improving the bishop, defending  c3  and enabling a4. } 18... Rc8 19. a4 Ne4
{ Desperation, giving the pawn back and intending to kick the knight with ...f6. }
20. Bxe4 dxe4 21. Qxe4 f6 22. Qh7
{ The rook is basically trapped since ...Bf7 is impossible due to Nd7+. } 22...
Nb3 { Ding tries a desperado, but... } 23. Qxg8 Nxa1 24. Qxe8
{ White wins a piece after something like   24...Rxe8  25.Nd7+  Kc7  26.Nxb6  Kxb6  27.Rxa1 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Boris Grachev vs. Rahman Mohammad Fahad, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a Classical game. The London specialist Boris Grachev was rated 2652 while Black was rated 2278. }
1... Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 Bf5 4. c4 e6 5. Nc3 c6 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. c5 Qxb3 8. axb3
Nbd7 9. h3
{ This was all covered in the Baltic/Slav chapter. Seehere. The text move is not necessary this early, but Grachev wants to keep it easy and thematic. Our move is  9.b4  . }
9... a6 10. b4 Rc8 11. Nf3 Be7 12. Nd2 { The knight starts its famous tour. }
12... Bd8
{ Black reroutes the bishop to d8, in order to be able to chop on a5. } 13. Nb3
Bc7
{ An instructive mistake. Grachev had also two games in the same tournament in 2010 when both of his opponents made the exact same mistake and lost more or less the same way. You'll find these in the notes below. }
14. Bxc7 Rxc7 15. b5 O-O
{ 15...Ke7  This was seen in Grachev-Kharitonov 2010.  16.b6  Rcc8  17.Na5  Rb8  18.Bxa6  bxa6  19.Nxc6+  Kf8  20.Rxa6  g5  21.Nxb8  Nxb8  22.Ra8  Kg7  23.Kd2  e5  24.b4  exd4  25.exd4  Rc8  26.b7  Rf8  27.b5  1-0.   15...axb5??  16.Ra8+   15...cxb5?  16.Nxb5 }
16. b6 Rcc8 17. Na5 Rb8 18. Bxa6 { Here it comes. } 18... bxa6 19. Nxc6 Rb7
{ 19...Ra8  This was seen in Grachev-Rychagov 2010, in fact, in the same tournament as the above game.  20.b7  Rab8  21.Nxb8  Nxb8  22.b4  Bd3  23.Kd2  Bc4  24.Rhb1  Ne4+  25.Nxe4  dxe4  26.b5  axb5  27.Ra8  Bd5  28.Rxb5  f5  29.Rb6  Kf7  30.Kc3  Ke7  31.Rd6  g5  32.Kb4  Kf6  33.Rxd5  Grachev simplifies to a win, showing the power of the connected passed pawns.  33...exd5  34.Rxb8  Rxb8  35.c6  Ke7  36.Kc5  1-0 }
20. Ne7+ Kh8 21. Nxf5 exf5 22. Rxa6
{ White now has 3 pawns for the piece and is completely winning. The rest is, as they always like to say, a matter of technique. }
22... Ne4 23. Nxe4 fxe4 24. Kd2 Nb8 25. Ra8 Kg8 26. Rha1 Nc6 27. Kc3 f5 28. b4
Kf7 29. Rxf8+ Kxf8 30. b5 Nd8 31. Ra7 Rb8 32. Kb4 Ke8 33. Rxg7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Matthieu Cornette vs. Olexandr Bortnyk, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was an online Rapid game in PRO Chess League. White was rated 2611, Black 2610. }
1... Nf6 2. Bf4 b6 3. Nc3 Bb7 4. f3 d5 5. e4 dxe4 6. fxe4 Nxe4 7. Bb5+
{ This was all covered in the Queen's Indian chapter. Seehere. However, our move is  7.Qf3  while the text is a good alternative. }
7... Nd7
{ Natural, blocking the check while developing, while also maintaining the protection of the knight, but this is not good.   7...c6  Was necessary.  8.Bd3  Nxc3  9.bxc3  The position might be objectively equalish, but is surely more fun for White with a development edge and half-open b- and f-files. }
8. Nxe4 Bxe4 9. Qe2 { Attacking the bishop and making possible O-O-O. } 9...
Bb7 10. Nf3 { Threatening Ne5. } 10... a6 11. Bc4
{ This position is already practically losing for Black due to White's numerous threats. }
11... e6 12. d5
{ This is fine, but a BDG player would've probably found Ng5!   12.Ng5!  White can start thinking of sacrifices on e6 and f7.  12...Qe7  13.O-O }
12... e5 13. Nxe5 Qe7
{ Black hopes to rely on a counterpin, but it's all over. } 14. O-O-O Nxe5 15.
Bxe5 O-O-O 16. Bxa6 { Boom! } 16... Qg5+ 17. Kb1 Re8 18. d6
{ A beautiful intermediate move, threatening d7+ and opening the long diagonal for White's Queen. }
18... Rxe5
{ If   18...cxd6  19.Qc4+  Kb8  20.Bxb7  Kxb7  21.Qd5+  Kb8  22.Bxd6  Bxd6  23.Qxg5 }
19. Qf3 { The idea. } 19... Bxd6
{ If   19...Bxa6?  20.d7+  Kb8  21.d8=Q  Qxd8  22.Rxd8+  Bc8  23.Rhd1  and White is completely winning. }
20. Rxd6 cxd6 21. Qxb7+ Kd8 22. Qc8+ Ke7 23. Qxh8
{ White's now just winning on material alone. } 23... Qxg2 24. Rc1 h5 25. a4
Qg4 26. Bb5 { Securing the pawn and the piece while making possible Qe8+. }
26... Qg2 27. Qe8+ Kf6 28. Qd8+ Kg6 29. Qxd6+ f6 30. Qxb6 Qxh2 31. a5
{ Now the a-pawn runs. } 31... h4 32. a6 h3 33. a7 Qg2 34. Bc6
{ White didn't really even need to use the rook. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Magnus Carlsen vs. Evgeny Tomashevsky, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This is a famous Classical game from Wijk an Zee. The world champion was rated 2844 and Black was rated 2728. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. h3 Be7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O c5 8. c3 Nc6
9. Nbd2 d5 10. Qe2 Bd6 11. Rfe1
{ This was all covered in the Queen's Indian chapter, though in an alternative line. See here. }
11... Ne7 { Tomashevsky wants to play ...Ng6. } 12. Rad1
{ Carlsen centralizes the other rook and has a concrete idea in mind to counter Tomashevsky's plan. }
12... Ng6 { In his commentary, Carlsen considered this move dubious. } 13. Bxg6
{ This starts an interesting sequence, getting an imbalance in the form of a damaged kingside structure + a strong knight on  e5  . }
13... hxg6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Ne5
{ Due to the pawn on  g6  it is hard for Black to ever evict White's knight with ...f6. Also, Black's bishop remains passive.  Carlsen said in commentary that his plan was simply f4, Queen to the h-file and Ng5. }
15... g5
{ Moving the pawn immediately. In the commentary, Robert Ris said that he and Yasser Seirawan were looking at ...Ne4. Carlsen said that in that case he wouldn't take immediately, but play f4 first and then take. Also possible was   15...a5  with the idea of activating the bishop with ...Ba6. }
16. f4
{ Carlsen said that here he got very excited about the possibility of an attack so he just went for it. Sedlak gives   16.Qf3  as enough for an edge. }
16... gxf4 17. Rf1 { White offers a pawn for an attack. } 17... Nd7
{ Tomashevsky declines the pawn, but it was necessary to go for the complications. If   17...fxe3  18.Rxf6!  gxf6?  19.Qg4+  Kh7  20.Rf1!!  exd2  21.Rf4  and mate soon. If   17...fxe3  18.Rxf6!  exd2!  20.Rf4  f6  21.Ng6  Rfe8  22.Qh5  with an attack, but Sedlak thinks Black should be able to hold this. }
18. Qh5 { Going for the attack. Safe edge was   18.Nxd7  Qxd7  19.Rxf4 } 18...
Nf6
{ Carlsen said that if   18...g6  19.Qh6  and White will meet ...fxe3 with Nf3 to Ng5 and ...Nxe5 with Rxf4. For example:   18...g6  19.Qh6  fxe3  20.Ndf3  Qe7  21.Ng5  f6  22.Qxg6  Qg7  23.Qxg7  Kxg7  24.Nxe6+  Kg8  25.Nxd7   18...g6  19.Qh6  Nxe5  20.Rxf4  g5!  21.Rf6! }
19. Qh4 Qd8
{ Trying to exchange Queens. However, Carlsen said that after this he thought Black was is just lost. The better move was   19...Nh7  20.Rxf4  g5!  21.Rg4  f6  or   19...Nh7  20.exf4 }
20. Rxf4 Ne4
{ Black should've played   20...cxd4  21.exd4  Ne4  so as not to have to face dxc5 }
21. Nxe4 Qxh4 22. Rxh4 dxe4 23. dxc5 { Opening the d-file. } 23... bxc5 24. Rd7
{ Simple and strong. } 24... Rab8
{ Black needs to defend the bishop which defends the  e5  pawn. If   24...Bd5  25.c4 }
25. b3
{ As GM Nielsen says: 'Black is basically in a zugzwang. Playing...f6 allows Ng6 and mate on h8. The f-rook defends  f7  , the other, the bishop on  b7  , which can't move, as then  a7  would fall. So what is left, is to move the a-pawn.' }
25... a5 26. Rc7 a4 27. bxa4 Ba8 28. a5 Rb7 29. Rxc5 Ra7 30. Nc4
{ White's up by 2 pawns, the knight is coming into  b6  and Black had seen enough. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Gata Kamsky vs. Sergei Tiviakov, 2007"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a Classical game. One of our heroes, Kamsky, was rated 2718 while Black was rated 2648. The annotations below rely on Kamsky's own in Chess Gamer, Vol. 2: Return. Kamsky writes that after his return to chess him and Tiviakov had played only once where Kamsky lost against Tiviakov's pet Scandinavian. Now he wanted to try his pet London and see how Tiviakov reacts. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 { Now we've transposed to our QID line. }
4... Be7 { A ha! Tiviakov goes for the tricky ...Be7. } 5. c3
{ Kamsky continues with standard play. However, from our point of view, this has several problems. First, here Black could try ...Nh5. Second, if Black chooses to enter the Hedgehog, White's already committed to c3 and can't play Kamsky's own improvement of c4 in one move. Therefore, in the Queen's Indian chapter we cover the modern 5. dxc5. Seehere. }
5... b6
{ Tiviakov is not interested in adventures and continues completing his setup. }
6. h3 Bb7 7. Nbd2 cxd4
{ Black exchanges only after White has committed their knight to d2. } 8. exd4
d6 { Tiviakov enters the Hedgehog and White is already commmitted to c3. } 9.
Bd3 Nbd7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Re8 12. a4
{ Quoting Kamsky:    @@StartBlockQuote@@The standard move that threatens to gain more space on the queenside by advancing the pawn to a5 and possibly a6. In addition it is important to note that in such structures, if Black manages to get his b-pawn to b5 and fix White’s c3 pawn, Black manages to solve all his problems because of the strong outpost on d5 for his minor pieces.@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
12... a6 13. Bh2 Qc7
{ Up until now both sides have made the standard Hedgehog moves. Black's idea is ...Bc6 and ...Qb7. }
14. c4
{ Kamsky:   @@StartBlockQuote@@The first critical moment of the game. White decides to proceed with brute force expansion on the queenside, instead of the more typical wait-and-see tactic of hopping around the center with his knight from d2–c4–e3 etc. Given my opponent’s classical chess upbringing I felt that it was psychologically important to force him to make an irrevocable decision with regard to his queenside pawn structure. Black must decide now whether he wants to allow White’s subsequent b2–b4, potentially followed by a4–a5 and c4–c5, or stop it at once.@@EndBlockQuote@@More standard is the Bronstein plan as coveredhere. }
14... a5
{ Black decides to stop b5, but this was an inaccuracy, allowing White to bring the d2-knight to c3 with tempo. Better was  14...Bf8  to prepare e5. }
15. Nb1 { The knight repositions itself. } 15... Qd8 16. Nc3 d5 17. b3 Bb4 18.
Rc1 Rc8 19. Re3
{ Escaping the pin. The following positional sacrifice was a fascinating possibility  19.Nb5  Bxe1  20.Nxe1  Re7  21.Nd6  Rc7  22.c5  bxc5  23.Nxb7  Rxb7  24.dxc5  and White has the bishop pair and a dangerous c-pawn. }
19... Nf8
{ This is solid but passive. Black missed  19...dxc4  20.bxc4  Bxf3!  21.Qxf3  Bxc3  22.Rxc3  Nb8!  with equality. }
20. Nb5 { White wants to invade on c7. } 20... Ne4
{ Kamsky:    @@StartBlockQuote@@Trying to make an active move is generally considered a standard psychological error when one is under pressure and in a passive situation. What is really needed is to find a way to activate one's least functioning piece. In this case, Black’s f8-knight clearly needs to be relocated.@@EndBlockQuote@@   Better was  20...Ng6 }
21. Rc2
{ White intends to double on the c-file and later actually ends up tripling... }
21... Re7 22. Qc1
{ Kamsky:    @@StartBlockQuote@@White prepares to play Re3–e2, connecting the rooks with the option of either opening the c-file or moving his knight from f3 to e5 and getting rid of Black’s e4-knight. If Black attempts to control the e5-square by playing ...f7–f6, his whole kingside and center become vulnerable on the light squares that his b7-bishop is unable to control.@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
22... Nd7 23. Na7
{ Kamsky:    @@StartBlockQuote@@White suddenly switches targets from the dark squares to the light squares!! Black’s b7-bishop is exchanged, after which the light squares, including the very important c6-square, will fall under White’s control, and from there the black queenside pawns will be under constant threat of capture.@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
23... Ra8 24. cxd5 exd5 25. Nc6 Bxc6 26. Rxc6
{ Kamsky:    @@StartBlockQuote@@At this point my opponent was looking very sad, as we both realized how unpleasant Black’s position is, with White controlling the c-file and his bishops criss-crossing the board with their X-rays. Technically, the position can be declared won, as the black pawns on b6 and d5 cannot expect to survive the attack.@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
26... Qf8 27. Re2 { Tripling coming up! } 27... Rae8 28. Rec2
{ Natural, but Kamsky considers it an inaccuracy, giving  28.Bb5  as much stronger. }
28... h6 29. Bf4 { White frees h2 for his king. } 29... g5 30. Bc7 Nef6 31. Bf5
Qg7 32. Bd6 { Eliminating Black's active piece. } 32... Bxd6 33. Rxd6 Nf8 34.
Rc8
{ Kamsky:    @@StartBlockQuote@@White exchanges one pair of rooks to both reduce Black’s central defenders and clear the way for the patiently waiting queen on c1 to decisively enter the battle.@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
34... Rxc8 35. Qxc8 Ne8 36. Rxb6 { The first pawn falls. } 36... h5 37. Qd8 Re2
38. Bd3 { Black will lose material and therefore resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Indrek Reiland vs. WFM Carey Groves, 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a Classical game at the Edinburgh Chess Congress and probably one of my best games to date. }
1... Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Qd2 c6 6. Bh6 O-O 7. O-O-O Qa5
{ This was all covered in the Pirc chapter. Seehere. However, here Black starts with ...Qa5 before ...b5. }
8. Kb1
{ I went for the old King safety move. Better options were  8.h4  or  8.Bxg7  . }
8... Re8
{ I figured she removed the rook from the pin and wants to preserve the bishop with Bh8. So I decided to take it off. The downside is that she has managed to unclog the h-file and can stop the march of my h-pawn with h5. }
9. Bxg7 Kxg7 10. f3 { Safe approach, preparing g4 & h4. } 10... Nbd7 11. g4 b5
12. h4 b4 13. Nce2
{ I'm happy I played Kb1 and can play Nc1, if needed. This knight turns out to be the key piece. }
13... h5
{ Black plays h5 to stop the march of my h-pawn. Now gxh5 will be met with Nxh5 and it's not easy to break through. I considered whether I can play Nh3, but was not very happy with hxg4. I very briefly thought about g5, kicking away the knight, but didn't look deep enough since it seemed to lock things up. In fact, that is the best move, putting the knight out of play, gaining some crucial tempos for a breakthrough with f5 and paralyzing the Black position. }
14. gxh5
{ Better was  14.g5!  Nh7  and White can break through with f4-f5   Perhaps strongest was  14.Ng3!  Nb6  15.gxh5  Nxh5  17.Nge2  and White is in total control }
14... Nxh5 15. Nh3 Ndf6
{ I considered Nc1 to Nb3 to kick away the Queen from the 5th rank so it can't participate laterally and then Be2. The problem is ...Ng3 which is annoying, since black can swap off my bishop and then put the other knight on h5. I decided it's time to focus on the g-file and use the open file I have. }
16. Rg1
{ Now the idea is to play for a  f4  to  f5  breakthrough, but perhaps better was  16.Ng5 }
16... Be6
{ I thought that this was a mistake since it blocks the e-pawn and makes the f4-f5 breakthrough even stronger. It seemed to me Black should instead break with ...e5. }
17. Nc1 { Always a fun defensive idea, made possible by Kb1. } 17... Bxh3 18.
Bxh3
{ My bishop develops with a free tempo, it's now on a different diagonal than originally intended, but this will lead to the win. }
18... Rab8
{ Black still doesn't break with ...e5. Now I noticed the attacking idea of Qg5, Bf5, Bxg6, Qxg6. To play this the Queen needs to be cut off laterally. }
19. Nb3
{ A multipurpose move. The knight hopes to kick the queen from the 5th rank so it can't participate in the defense laterally, it blocks the advance of the b-pawn and prevents the need to think about exchange sacs like after  ...b3  ,  Nxb3  ,  ...Rxb3  . Also good was  19.Rg5! }
19... Qc7
{ I thought she would play ...Qb5, attempting to keep the queen there and then something like ...a4 to ...a5. However, I figured my attack will be much faster. }
20. Qg5
{ This has the dual threats of the immediate e5, aiming to kick away the knight, then capture on h5 and, in case ...dxe5, dxe5, also play Rd7 with tempo and potentially sacrifice on f7. What followed was kind of a bolt in blue, I really didn't consider this defensive idea at all. Lesson learned.   The best move was the breakthrough with  20.d5! }
20... Rb5 { Annoying! It turns out Black's best was  20...e5  . } 21. d5
{ After this it's quite hard for Black to defend over the board. } 21... Rh8
{ Black has been under lots of pressure for the past few moves and finally crumbles. Again, she needed to play  20...e5  . }
22. Nd4
{ The knight threatens the rook and Ne6+ which wins the Queen or leads to a mate. }
22... Rc5 { Black misses the threat. } 23. Ne6+ { Game over. } 23... fxe6
{ Black checks for one more move whether I will take the g-pawn with check first. }
24. Qxg6+
{ She took a moment, then saw it and resigned. Mate would follow after  24...Kf8  25.Bxe6  Rh7  26.Qg8+  Nxg8  27.Rxg8#  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Kaido KÃ¼laots  vs. Yunguo Wan, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a Classical game between my compatriot and schoolmate Kaido Külaots, who caused quite a stir winning Aeroflot Open in 2019. He was rated 2577 at the time of this game while Black was rated 2482. }
1... Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. h4 O-O 6. h5 c5 7. hxg6 hxg6
{ Black takes with the h-pawn. } 8. Qd2 { White chose the plan with Qd2. } 8...
Nc6 9. O-O-O { Natural. } 9... c4
{ This was all covered in the Grünfeld chapter. Seehere. With the text Black deviates from our line preparing for a Queenside attack, but this takes off the pressure on the center. Making it a race is a definite mistake since White is much faster here. }
10. f3
{ Controlling e4 and preparing to play g5 and Qh2 to mate on the h-file. }
10... b5 { Black counterattacks. } 11. g4
{ Proceeding with the attack is strongest. However, the materialistic  11.Nxb5  is fine too. }
11... b4 12. Na4 { Slowing down Black's attack. } 12... b3
{ Trying to rip open lines. } 13. axb3 cxb3 14. cxb3 Bd7 15. Qh2
{ The most direct approach, but White can afford to be more patient here and improve the Queenside first with  15.Kb1!  Rc8  16.Ba6!   Or  15.Nc5   Or even develop with  15.Ne2 }
15... Nb4 16. Bh6 { Proceeding with the plan. } 16... Rc8+ 17. Kb1
{ Natural, but Nc5 was better, even though it requires calculation and leads to an exchange of Queens  17.Nc5  Qa5  18.Bxg7  Rxc5+  19.dxc5  Qa1+  20.Kd2  Qxb2+  21.Ke1  Qxh2  22.Rxh2  Kxg7  23.Ra1  and White should win because of his material superiority. }
17... Rc2 { Better was  17...Qc7  . } 18. Ne2
{ Developing and blocking the attack on the Queen. However, better was  18.Qh4  . }
18... Bxa4 { After this, White is objectively winning. } 19. Bxg7
{ The correct move. } 19... Nh5
{ Blocking the h-file. Obviously not  19...Kxg7  20.Qh6+  Kg8  21.Qh8# } 20.
bxa4 { Now recapturing the piece. The knight on  h5  isn't going anywhere. }
20... Qd7 { Black aims for a perpetual. } 21. Bxf8
{ In this highly tactical and complex situation White's best was  21.b3!  Rfc8  22.Bh3  with a complete mess on the board. However, Bxf8 objectively still wins. }
21... Qxa4 22. Nc3
{ This is the move that allows for the perpetual. White's only way to win was the completely insane and practically unlikely  22.Nc1!!  Rxh2  23.b3!  Rxh1  24.bxa4  Ng3  25.Bxe7  Nc6  26.Bb5  Nxe7  27.Rxh1  Nxh1  28.Nd3  . }
22... Rxc3 23. bxc3 Qb3+ 24. Kc1 Qxc3+ 25. Kb1 Qb3+ 26. Kc1 Qc3+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Alexander Grischuk  vs. Baskaran Adhiban, 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 { This was a Rapid game. White was rated 2774, Black 2674. } 1... Nf6 2.
Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 4. Nc3 Qxb2 5. Nge2
{ This is one of our alternative lines in the Benoni chapter. Seehere. This is one of the few games in this line at the master level. }
5... Qb6
{ Natural, but perhaps too complacent. After this, it's already at best equal, with White's position the easier to play.  Black should instead try to keep the Queen in White's camp, disturbing his development with ...Qa3. }
6. Rb1 Qd8 { Again, ...Qa5 was better. } 7. dxc5 g6 8. g3 Na6 9. Qd4
{ Protecting the pawn, keeping the knight on the rim, and not minding stepping into the pin. }
9... Bg7 10. Bg2 Nh5 { Black should've probably castled here. } 11. Be5 f6 12.
Bf4 e5 13. Qc4 exf4 14. exf4 { Stockfish likes  14.g4  much better. } 14... Bf8
15. O-O Nxc5
{ Black is a full piece up, but his king is in the center and his pieces don't coordinate at all. }
16. Nd4 Ng7 { Making possible meeting checks on e1 with ...Nce6. } 17. Rfe1+
Nce6 18. Nd5
{ White goes for the fork on  c7  , but apparently, this is a blunder. Stockfish prefers  18.Bxb7  Bxb7  19.Nxe6  Nxe6  20.Rxb7  Be7  21.Nd5  with a winning advantage. }
18... Rb8 { Better was  18...Kf7  stepping out of both the fork and the pin. }
19. Rbd1 { Better was  19.Qa4  pinning the d-pawn. } 19... Be7
{ This loses. Better was, again  19...Kf7  . } 20. Nxe6 Nxe6 21. Rxe6
{ White goes for the Queen, but better was, again  21.Qa4  . } 21... dxe6 22.
Nc7+ Kf7 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. Bf3
{ Now, material is almost equal, but Stockfish slightly prefers Black. However, one could argue that White's position is practically easier to play. }
24... a6 { Necessary was  24...f5  . } 25. f5
{ After this White has a winning advantage. } 25... b5 26. Qb3 Rb6 27. Qe3
{ Intending to penetrate behind the king. Now it's all over. } 27... Rbd6 28.
Qh6 exf5 29. Qxh7+ Kf8 30. Qxg6 Be6 31. Nxe6+ Rxe6 32. Bh5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
