[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "LevonAronian vs. AnishGiri, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a Blitz game from their match in the Chess.com Speed Chess championships. }
1... Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Qb6 4. Nc3 Qxb2 5. Nge2
{ Again, this is one of our alternative lines in the Benoni chapter. Seehere. This is the second of the few games in this line at the master level. }
5... Qa3 { Better than Adhiban's move. } 6. Rb1 Qa5
{ Not clear why this was needed. Better was  6...d6  7.Rb3  Qa5  8.Rb5  Qd8  9.dxc5  a6  10.Rb1  . }
7. Rb5 Qd8 8. dxc5 b6
{ This is dubious. Better was  8...Nc6  intending ...e5. } 9. e4 Ba6 10. e5
{ This is also dubious, but Black misses the best response. Better was  10.Ng3  . }
10... Nh5 { Black would've been better after  10...Ne4!  . } 11. Be3 Bxb5 12.
Nxb5 g6 13. Nec3 bxc5 14. Nd5 Na6 15. g4 { Removing the defender of f6. } 15...
Ng7 16. Nd6+ { Boom! } 16... exd6 17. Nf6+ Ke7 18. Qxd6# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Nicole Tsoi vs. Maria Granados, 2014"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a Classical game played at the Tromso Olympiad in 2014. White was a WFM rated 1787, Black was rated 1899. }
1... Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 { Granados exchanges immediately on d4. } 4. exd4
g6 5. c3
{ This has now transposed into a minor sideline mentioned in the Benoni chapter. Seehere. }
5... Bg7 6. Nf3
{ With the e-pawn gone, White doesn't have to worry about ...Nh5. } 6... O-O 7.
Bc4 { The bishop takes up its most aggressive post. } 7... a6
{ Intending ...b5. } 8. a4 d6
{ Black plays in a KID fashion, refusing to commit to ...d5. } 9. O-O Nbd7 10.
Re1 { Rook on the open file. } 10... b6 11. Qe2
{ White was probably already thinking about the coming sacrifice... } 11... Re8
{ Black plays a typical move, oblivious to the danger. } 12. Bxf7+
{ A devastating sacrifice. } 12... Kxf7 13. Ng5+
{ Black resigned since  13...Kf8  14.Ne6+  picks up the Queen   while  13...Kg8  leads to a nice smothered mate after  14.Qe6+  Kh8  15.Nf7+  Kg8  16.Nh6+  Kh8  17.Qg8+  Rxg8  18.Nf7#  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Nino Batsiashvili vs. Alina Kashlinskaya, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was played at the World Blitz Championship 2016. The Georgian GM playing White was rated 2482, while IM Kashlinskaya of later IM not a GM Speed Chess Championship fame was rated 2452. }
1... Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. e3
{ This is not our move order, but we'll soon transpose to a line which we will face. }
3... Bg7 4. h3
{ Strictly speaking this is unnecessary, but it's Blitz so it's an easy and thematic move to make just to prevent any shenanigans. }
4... O-O 5. Nf3 c5
{ After this break we're in a line which we face from the Benoni move order. }
6. Nbd2 { 6.c3  is more standard. } 6... b6 7. Bd3
{ This was all more-or-less covered in the Benoni chapter. Seehere. However, we put the bishop on c4. }
7... Bb7 8. O-O d6 { Black completes the Reversed Reti setup. } 9. Qe2
{ Here  9.c3  made more sense. } 9... a6 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Bh2
{ Stepping away from the ...e5 break to make sure Black can't play ...e5 with tempo and then ...e4. }
11... cxd4 12. exd4 Nd5 13. c3 Bh6 14. Rfe1
{ Hitting the e-pawn and thereby indirectly preventing ...Nf4. } 14... N7f6 15.
Ne4 Re8 { The rook goes to the e-file, but leaves f7 undefended. } 16. Neg5 Bg7
{ A somewhat inexplicable move. } 17. Nxf7
{ A similar tactic as in the last game, but this time with a knight sacrifice. }
17... Kxf7 { 17...Qd7  had to be tried. } 18. Qe6+ Kf8 19. Ng5
{ Black resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Gata Kamsky vs. Ivan Rozum, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This was a highly instructional Blitz game by one of our Heroes, Kamsky. White was rated 2666 and Black was rated 2573. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 d6 6. Bc4
{ We've now transposed to our main line against the Old Benoni. } 6... O-O 7.
O-O Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Na6
{ This was all covered in the Old Benoni chapter. Seehere. However, in this game Black puts the knight on a6 not on d7. }
10. Qe2 { Kamsky threatens to win a pawn. } 10... Nc7 11. a4
{ Clamping down on b5. } 11... Nd7 12. Bg5 Re8 13. Kh1
{ Hiding the king away in the corner so as not to have to worry about it afterwards. Smart blitz strategy and White could afford it here, he's in no rush really since Black lacks play.   13.f4  This central move was perhaps objectively stronger. }
13... b6 14. f4 Qc8 15. Rad1
{ White brings the last piece to the center and is now fully prepared to play the e5 and f5 breakthrough. }
15... a6 16. e5 { Here it comes. } 16... dxe5 17. f5
{ 17.d6!  exd6  This opens the diagonal for the bishop.  18.f5  gxf5  19.Rxf5  Rf8  20.Qh5  White can just pile up on the poor f-pawn with Rdf1 or take on d6 with Rxd6. }
17... Nf6 18. d6 { Same move, different order. } 18... exd6 19. fxg6 hxg6 20.
Bxf6 { White wins a piece. } 20... Ne6 21. Rxd6 Nf4 22. Qf3 Qf5 23. Ne4
{ 23.Bxf7+!!  Kxf7  24.Qb7+  Leads to mate. } 23... b5 24. Bxg7 { 24.Bxf7+!! }
24... Kxg7 25. Rf6 { Goodbye Queen. } 25... Qxf6 26. Nxf6 Kxf6 27. Bd5 Rad8 28.
g3 { and goodbye Knight. } *

